window.BALLOT_DATA = [{"state":"Alabama","sigs":"AL: 5,000 valid signatures (fixed statutory, independent presidential)","deadline":"AL: 74 days before general election (Aug 23, 2024) — NOT Sept 6 (draft is WRONG)","risk":"Signature count is solid (5,000 confirmed in §17-14-31(a)); the draft DEADLINE is materially wrong — it cites Sept 6 (a repealed pre-2012 date / a party convention-certificate date Ballotpedia conflated), but the enacted law (SB324, eff. 2024) sets the independent presidential petition deadline at 74 days before the election = Aug 23, 2024. Treat the deadline as Aug 23, 2024 and verify the exact 2028 date with the SOS before relying.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT PRESIDENTIAL candidate filing a §17-14-31 petition of 5,000 qualified voters, please confirm the exact filing deadline for the next general election: is it 74 days before Election Day (as amended by SB324, 2024), and what is that calendar date?","Please confirm there are NO circulator qualification requirements (age, residency, voter-registration) for an independent presidential petition under Alabama law, and that no circulator affidavit, witness, or notarization is required on petition pages beyond Rule 820-2-4-.05's per-signer information."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Alabama's candidate-petition law (Ala. Code 17-9-3) and the Secretary of State's independent-candidacy administrative rules (Ala. Admin. Code ch. 820-2-4) are entirely signer-centric: they govern petition format, the information requested of each signer, and random-sample signature verification, but say NOTHING about circulators — neither their compensation (per-signature or otherwise), nor whether circulators may be paid at all, nor any circulator residency/registration requirement. Compensation of circulators on a candidate petition is therefore UNADDRESSED in Alabama's election code and SOS rules; Alabama has no statewide initiative process, so no initiative pay-per-signature rule carries over.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition under Ala. Code 17-9-3, may a campaign pay signature circulators on a per-signature basis; may circulators be paid at all (hourly/salary); and must a circulator be an Alabama resident or registered Alabama voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/alabama/Ala-Admin-Code-r-820-2-4-.05","quote":"An election petition shall request the following information for each person signing said petition: name, residential address, date of birth, and signature. A signature shall not be deemed invalid for lacking any portion of the requested information if the disclosed information is sufficient for determining the validity of a signature."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Alabama","quote":"All petition signatures must be gathered in person, but the code does not specify requirements for petition circulators."},{"url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/alabama/title-820/chapter-820-2-4","quote":"§ 820-2-4-.05 - Petition Requirements § 820-2-4-.06 - Random Sample Of Signatures § 820-2-4-.07 - Random Sampling Formula For Verification Of Elections Petitions § 820-2-4-.08 - Certification Of Election Petition"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Alabama","quote":"An independent presidential candidate must petition for placement on the general election ballot. At least 5,000 qualified state voters must sign this petition."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.alabamainteractive.org/sos/voter/voterWelcome.action","official":true,"dom":"alabamainteractive.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/alabama/Ala-Admin-Code-r-820-2-4-.05","official":false,"dom":"law.cornell.edu"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Alabama","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/alabama/title-820/chapter-820-2-4","official":false,"dom":"law.cornell.edu"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Alabama","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.al.com/news/2026/04/alabama-just-slashed-the-price-of-its-statewide-voter-list.html","official":false,"dom":"al.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.alreporter.com/2025/11/18/wes-allen-backs-bill-to-protect-voter-data-and-lower-the-cost-of-alabamas-voter-list/","official":false,"dom":"alreporter.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 valid signatures of qualified Alabama voters — a FIXED statutory number for an independent presidential candidate under Ala. Code §17-14-31(a). This is distinct from the 3%-of-last-gubernatorial-vote rule (42,458 statewide for 2024) that governs OTHER independent candidates under §17-9-3.","note":"Both Ballotpedia quotes verified verbatim (page line 232). Independently confirmed against the primary source: enacted SB324 §17-14-31(a) — presidential candidates may be nominated 'by written petition signed by at least 5,000 qualified voters of this state.' The draft correctly separates this from the §17-9-3 3%/42,458 general-independent rule (SOS PDF quote also verified verbatim, lines 11-18).","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"74 days before the general election. For 2024 this was August 23, 2024 (election day Nov 5, 2024). DO NOT rely on September 6 — that is the WRONG date for an independent presidential petition.","note":"Citation quotes verified verbatim, BUT the asserted VALUE (Sept 6) is wrong. The Sept 6 Ballotpedia quote describes the party national-convention certificate-of-nomination deadline (Ballotpedia line 226) and Ballotpedia conflated it onto the independent petition (line 232); Ballot Access News notes Sept 6 was Alabama's old deadline pre-2012. Enacted SB324 (LegiScan: Passed/Enacted 2024-05-03), amending §17-14-31(b), sets the deadline for presidential certificates AND petitions at '74 days before the date of the election' (strikethrough shows change from the prior '82nd day' = Aug 15). 74 days before Nov 5, 2024 = Aug 23, 2024 — independently corroborated by Ballot Access News, WVUA23, and 1819News reporting RFK Jr.'s Aug 23 deadline. Strictest-defensible value set to the earliest applicable deadline (Aug 23, 2024) to never risk a missed filing; exact 2028 date must be re-derived (74 days before that Election Day) and confirmed with the SOS.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 5,000-signature independent presidential petition is a single statewide total with no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement.","note":"Ballotpedia quote verified verbatim (line 232). Confirmed against §17-14-31(a): 'petition signed by at least 5,000 qualified voters of this state' — a flat statewide count with no geographic allocation. No distribution language anywhere in the presidential petition statute.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"UNKNOWN / no circulator-specific qualifications are specified in Alabama law. Signatures must be gathered in person; signers must be registered Alabama voters. (Conservative posture: do not assume circulators are unrestricted — verify with SOS.)","note":"Ballotpedia quote ('All petition signatures must be gathered in person, but the code does not specify requirements for petition circulators') verified verbatim (line 398). SOS PDF 'signatures of registered Alabama voters' verified verbatim (line 11). Reviewed full Rule 820-2-4-.05 (Cornell) and enacted SB324 — neither imposes circulator age/residency requirements. The draft's UNKNOWN/no-specified-requirement framing is itself the strict, safe statement, so it is left AUTO-LIVE; an SOS inquiry is queued to close the gap.","conf":0.85,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Petition pages require only a per-page identifying statement, pagination, and per-signer information (name, residential address, date of birth, signature) under Rule 820-2-4-.05. No circulator affidavit, witness, or notarization is required.","note":"SOS PDF quote (Rule 820-2-4-.05(3) per-signer info) verified verbatim (lines 63-66). Cornell LII text of Rule 820-2-4-.05 verified verbatim and read in full (subsections 1-3) — contains no notary/affidavit/witness requirement. Enacted SB324 likewise imposes none for the presidential petition.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be gathered in person on paper petitions; a photocopiable sample form is provided by the SOS. No digital/remote-online signature system exists for an Alabama independent presidential petition.","note":"Ballotpedia 'gathered in person' quote verified verbatim (line 398); SOS PDF 'sample petition form, which may be photo copied' verified verbatim (lines 70-72). No source indicates any electronic submission path; in-person paper is confirmed.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing/qualifying fee for an independent candidate and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative; the 5,000-signature petition is the sole ballot-access mechanism.","note":"SOS PDF 'There is no qualifying fee' verified verbatim (line 4). §17-14-31(a) provides the petition as the only independent path (no fee alternative mentioned). Note: the draft's quote attributes 'There is no qualifying fee' to a sentence about choosing not to run as a party candidate — the exact phrase appears verbatim at line 4 of the SOS PDF, so grounding holds.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Alaska","sigs":"HOLD: packet self-contradicts (3,409 narrative vs 3,614 dates page) — rely on the higher 3,614","deadline":"HOLD: rule is 90th day before general; controlling 2028 packet date = Aug 16, 2028 (draft mis-anchored on expired Aug 7, 2024)","risk":"Same official packet states two different signature counts (3,409 vs 3,614) and the draft's headline deadline is an expired 2024 date; both need DOE confirmation, so default to strictest (collect to 3,614, treat Aug 16, 2028 as the deadline) until resolved.","sos":["For the 2028 cycle, the B05P presidential candidate packet states two different signature minimums for an independent presidential petition: the narrative text says 'at least 3,409' (1% of the 340,981 ballots cast for President in 2024), while the Election Law Dates page says 'at least 3,614 signatures.' Which figure is controlling, and what total of valid signatures must an independent presidential candidate collect to be certified for the November 14, 2028 ballot?","Please confirm the exact filing deadline for an independent presidential candidate petition for the 2028 general election: is it 5:00 p.m. prevailing time on August 16, 2028 (the 90th day before the November 14, 2028 general election), and does registered/certified mail postmarked on or before that date satisfy the deadline if received within 15 days?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Alaska's independent-presidential petition lives in AS 15.30.026 (National Elections), which sets only the signer/qualified-voter requirement and a resident \"state campaign chair\" — it is entirely SILENT on petition circulators: no compensation rule (no per-signature cap and no prohibition), and no circulator residency/registration requirement. The familiar \"$1 a signature\" cap and pay-to-sign prohibition sit in a different chapter (AS 15.45.110, Initiative/Referendum/Recall) and do not by their terms reach candidate petitions, so candidate-petition circulator compensation is unaddressed.","sosInquiry":"For an independent U.S. presidential candidate's nominating petition under AS 15.30.026, does any Alaska statute or regulation restrict how petition circulators may be compensated (e.g., may a campaign pay circulators per signature), and must a circulator be an Alaska resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/ak-st-sect-15-30-026/","quote":"A person who desires to be an independent candidate for President of the United States must file with the director ... a petition signed by qualified voters of the state equal in number to at least one percent of the number of voters who cast ballots in an election under this chapter for President of the United States at the last presidential general election. ... (b)(3) the name, Alaska mailing address, and signature of the candidate's state campaign chair, who must be a state resident."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/ak-st-sect-15-45-110/","quote":"(c) A circulator may not receive payment or agree to receive payment that is greater than $1 a signature, and a person or an organization may not pay or agree to pay an amount that is greater than $1 a signature, for the collection of signatures on a petition. ... (e) A person or organization that violates (c) or (d) of this section is guilty of a class B misdemeanor."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/","quote":"Chapter 30. National Elections ... Chapter 45. Initiative, Referendum, and Recall"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.eac.gov/sites/default/files/voters/Available_Voter_File_Information.pdf","official":true,"dom":"eac.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.elections.alaska.gov/research/","official":true,"dom":"elections.alaska.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/ak-st-sect-15-30-026/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/ak-st-sect-15-45-110/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Availability_of_state_voter_files","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ak/title-15-elections/ak-st-sect-15-07-195/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 3,614 valid signatures of qualified Alaska voters (the higher of the two conflicting figures the official B05P packet publishes). The statutory formula is 1% of the ballots cast for President at the last presidential general election; 1% of the certified 2024 total (340,981) computes to 3,409.81, which the packet narrative rounds to 'at least 3,409.' However, the same packet's Election Law Dates page states the petition must have 'at least 3,614 signatures.' Until the Division resolves the contradiction, collect to the higher 3,614 floor to avoid any risk of falling short.","note":"Both quotes verbatim-confirmed in B05P.pdf (downloaded and text-extracted; narrative at lines 67-72, dates page at lines 119-123). 340,981 confirmed as the certified 2024 AK presidential total. The draft picks 3,409 as the value and labels 3,614 a mere 'packet inconsistency' to be overridden by the formula. Adversarially, 3,614 implies a base of ~361,400, not 2024's 340,981, so it looks erroneous/stale — BUT it is published by the same controlling official source. Strict, never-risk-ballot-access posture requires relying on the HIGHER figure (3,614) pending DOE confirmation, not silently overriding it down to 3,409. Note also the 'at least one percent' floor arguably rounds UP to 3,410, not down to 3,409. Interpretation (which figure governs) cannot be settled by retrieval.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"File not earlier than January 1 of the presidential election year and not later than the 90th day before the presidential general election (AS 15.30.026(a)); by 6 AAC 25.074(a) the cutoff is 5:00 p.m. prevailing time on that 90th day, in person or by registered/certified mail (return receipt requested) postmarked on or before the 90th day and received within 15 days. For the upcoming (2028) cycle, the controlling B05P packet states this date is August 16, 2028 (90 days before the November 14, 2028 general election). Treat August 16, 2028, 5:00 p.m. prevailing time as the operative deadline.","note":"Statute + regulation quotes verbatim-confirmed (B05P lines 64-67/482-487; Cornell LII 6 AAC 25.074(a)). The statutory rule is correct. BUT the draft's headline value anchors on 'August 7, 2024' — the 90th day before the Nov 5, 2024 general, an EXPIRED date for the wrong (already-completed) cycle — while burying the actual controlling date (August 16, 2028, stated twice in the packet, lines 44/67/113/119) as a parenthetical 'for reference.' Arithmetic verified: Nov 14, 2028 minus 90 days = Aug 16, 2028. For a forward-looking 2028 ballot rule, relying on a past 2024 date is unsafe; relied value corrected to the 2028 packet date. Which cycle/date governs is an interpretation retrieval alone shouldn't decide.","conf":0.92,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The statute requires only a statewide signature total (1% of the last presidential vote); there is no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement. Alaska has a single at-large U.S. House district.","note":"Quote verbatim-confirmed in B05P.pdf (line 68). Independently re-derived: AS 15.30.026(a) and 6 AAC 25.074 impose a single statewide 1% requirement with no geographic distribution language anywhere in the statute, regulation, or subscriber pages. Alaska is a single at-large district, so a distribution requirement would be structurally meaningless. No adversarial counter found.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No separate circulator requirement is found in AS 15.30.026, AS 15.30.025, or 6 AAC 25.074. The only confirmed person-eligibility requirement is that each SIGNER (subscriber) must be a qualified voter of the State of Alaska and must provide a printed name, Alaska residence address, an identifier (last 4 SSN, voter #, DOB, ADL #, or AK State ID #), signature, and date. Treat the existence/absence of a distinct circulator rule as UNCONFIRMED and verify with the Division before relying on it.","note":"Both quotes verbatim-confirmed in B05P.pdf (subscriber petition text line 366-367; subscriber-provide line 92-94). The signer requirement is solidly grounded. However, the field's core claim is a NEGATIVE/absence inference ('no separate circulator rule exists anywhere'), which two cited sources cannot conclusively establish — a separate signature-verification or petition-circulation regulation could exist outside these two documents. Under strict posture this absence is interpretation-required and should be confirmed, not asserted as settled. Strictest defensible framing: rely only on the affirmatively-grounded signer requirement; treat circulator rules as unconfirmed.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarized affidavit and no per-signature circulator/witness certification is required. The only required certification is a written statement signed by the submitting candidate or party, filed at submission, acknowledging the number of petition booklets or subscriber pages included (6 AAC 25.074(b)). Individual subscriber signatures are not separately notarized or witnessed.","note":"Both quotes verbatim-confirmed (B05P signed-statement text line 97-99; Cornell LII 6 AAC 25.074(b)). Independently re-derived from the regulation: 25.074(b) requires only the single 'written statement signed by the submitting candidate or party.' The subscriber pages and statute contain no notary or per-signature witness/circulator-affidavit field. The receipt form (B05P lines 221-222/346-347) likewise asks only for the candidate/party signature. No adversarial counter found. Correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"paper. The petition is circulated on paper subscriber pages/booklets and filed as a single paper instrument, delivered either in person (by 5:00 p.m. prevailing time on the deadline) or by registered/certified mail (return receipt requested) postmarked on or before the 90th-day deadline and received within 15 days. Assume paper-only for this independent presidential petition.","note":"Core paper claim is grounded: Cornell LII 6 AAC 25.074(a) (registered/certified mail) and B05P 'mailed to the Division of Elections Director's Office' both verbatim-confirmed. 6 AAC 25.074 plus the physical subscriber pages clearly contemplate a paper instrument. HOWEVER, the draft's added NEGATIVE assertion — 'there is NO digital/remote-online system' and 'Alaska's e-signature system is limited to initiative/referendum measures, not candidate petitions' — is NOT supported by either cited quote and is an interpretive inference about scope. Strict posture: rely only on the grounded paper requirement (which is the safe operational answer); flag the no-digital-system claim as unverified by the citations.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures for ballot access via the independent presidential petition; signatures are the sole qualification mechanism under AS 15.30.026. The separate 'appropriate fee' in the Division's calendar relates only to placement in the Official Election Pamphlet under AS 15.58.030(a), not to getting on the ballot.","note":"Pamphlet-fee quote verbatim-confirmed in B05P.pdf (Election Law Dates page, lines 125-129). Independently re-derived: AS 15.30.026 conditions ballot access solely on the petition signatures; no filing fee or fee-in-lieu appears anywhere in the statute, regulation, or packet for the petition itself. The packet's only fee reference is expressly tied to the Official Election Pamphlet (AS 15.58.030(a)), a distinct downstream step. The value correctly distinguishes the two. No adversarial counter found.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Arizona","sigs":"AZ indep pres: ~42,303 (2024 only) — RECOMPUTES each cycle, do not hardcode","deadline":"AZ pres-elector filing: 80-100 days before general (Aug 17, 2024); date recomputes","risk":"Six of seven fields verified live; signaturesRequired held because the number is cycle-specific (3% of non-affiliated registrants as of Jan 2) and the draft's new-party comparison misreads its own Ballot Access News citation (34,116=Full Party, 41,090=Candidate, neither equals 42,303).","sos":["For an independent (non-party) presidential-elector nomination petition under A.R.S. 16-341(E)-(F), what is the exact certified minimum signature count for the upcoming general-election cycle, computed as 3% of registered voters who are not members of a qualified party as of January 2 of the election year, and where is that official figure published?","Does A.R.S. 16-341(N)'s authorization of electronic petitions 'for statewide and legislative offices' extend to independent presidential-elector petitions, or are such petitions required to be collected on paper because E-Qual under A.R.S. 16-318 is limited to U.S. Senate and U.S. House candidates?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; per-signature ban (ARS 19-118.01) limited to statewide initiative/referendum","note":"Arizona's candidate-petition statutes (Title 16, Article 2/3, including the independent/presidential path at ARS 16-341 and the circulator rules at ARS 16-315 and 16-321) do NOT address circulator compensation at all — neither permitting nor prohibiting per-signature pay. Arizona's only per-signature ban, ARS 19-118.01, by its own terms applies solely to \"a statewide initiative or referendum petition\" (Title 19) and does not reach candidate nomination petitions, so candidate-petition per-signature compensation is unaddressed rather than authorized; circulators need not be Arizona residents but must be eligible to register to vote here and (if non-resident) register with the Secretary of State.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nomination petition under ARS 16-341, may a campaign legally pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, or is per-signature compensation prohibited or restricted for candidate (as opposed to initiative/referendum) petitions under Arizona law?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/19/00118-01.htm","quote":"A. A person shall not pay or receive money or any other thing of value based on the number of signatures collected on a statewide initiative or referendum petition. Signatures that are obtained by a paid circulator who violates this section are void and shall not be counted in determining the legal sufficiency of the petition. B. A violation of this section is a class 1 misdemeanor."},{"url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00341.htm","quote":"G. A nomination petition for any candidate may be circulated by a person who is not a resident of this state but who is otherwise eligible to register to vote in this state if that person registers as a circulator with the secretary of state before circulating petitions."},{"url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00315.htm","quote":"2. Circulator is not required to be a resident of this state but otherwise must be qualified to register to vote in this state and, if not a resident of this state, shall register as a circulator with the secretary of state."},{"url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00321.htm","quote":"D. The person before whom the signatures were written on the signature sheet is not required to be a resident of this state but otherwise shall be qualified to register to vote in this state pursuant to section 16-101 and, if not a resident of this state, shall register as a circulator with the secretary of state."},{"url":"https://law.justia.com/cases/arizona/supreme-court/2023/cr-22-0154-pr.html","quote":"The Supreme Court held that Ariz. Rev. Stat. 19-118.01 does not facially violate the First Amendment where it only prohibits per-signature compensation to petition circulators."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/19/00118-01.htm","official":true,"dom":"azleg.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00341.htm","official":true,"dom":"azleg.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00315.htm","official":true,"dom":"azleg.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00321.htm","official":true,"dom":"azleg.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.azleg.gov/ars/16/00168.htm","official":true,"dom":"azleg.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://law.justia.com/cases/arizona/supreme-court/2023/cr-22-0154-pr.html","official":false,"dom":"law.justia.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat 42,303 as the 2024-cycle figure ONLY. For any live cycle the requirement must be recomputed as 3% of Arizona registered voters who are NOT members of a qualified party, measured as of January 2 of the general-election year (A.R.S. 16-341(E)-(F)), and verified against the Secretary of State's official signature-requirement table for that cycle. Any registered AZ voter may sign regardless of party. Do NOT rely on the draft's new-party comparison.","note":"All four quotes verified verbatim. 42,303 for 2024 is double-corroborated by azcentral (Aug 16 + Aug 19, 2024) as the SoS-reported independent statewide presidential figure. HOLD reasons: (1) the value is explicitly cycle-recomputed (3% of non-affiliated registrants as of Jan 2) and must not be hardcoded for a future cycle; (2) the draft's NOTE misreads its own Ballot Access News citation: in that table 34,116 is the 'Full Party' column and *41,090 is the 'Candidate' column for Arizona; neither is 42,303, and the draft's claim that the new-party 'Candidate' figure (34,116) is lower than the independent figure inverts the table headers. The headline number is right; the surrounding interpretation is not reliable.","conf":0.86,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A nomination petition for the office of presidential elector must be filed with the Arizona Secretary of State not less than 80 nor more than 100 days before the general election (A.R.S. 16-341(G)). For 2024 (general election Nov 5) this was August 17, 2024 (exactly 80 days prior). The 120-150-days-before-primary window in 16-341(C) does NOT apply to presidential-elector filings. NOTE: the specific calendar date recomputes from the general-election date each cycle.","note":"Both quotes verified verbatim. The 80-100-day rule is a bright-line statute, correctly excluding presidential-elector petitions from the primary-tied window. Aug 17, 2024 derives correctly (80 days before Nov 5, 2024) and is independently confirmed by Ballot Access News. The rule is durable and non-interpretive; only the calendar date is cycle-dependent.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. A single statewide threshold (3% of statewide non-affiliated registered voters) applies; there is no geographic/congressional-district/county distribution requirement for an independent presidential-elector petition. The petition is a single group petition naming all elector candidates, and a valid signature counts for each elector candidate (A.R.S. 16-341(G)).","note":"Quote verified verbatim in 16-341(G). Nothing in 16-341 imposes a distribution requirement; the threshold in 16-341(E)-(F) is a flat statewide percentage. Confirmed correct and non-interpretive.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A circulator need NOT be an Arizona resident but must otherwise be eligible/qualified to register to vote in Arizona (U.S. citizen, 18+, etc., per A.R.S. 16-101). A non-resident circulator must register as a circulator with the Secretary of State before circulating petitions (A.R.S. 16-341(G), 16-321(D)). The circulator need not be a registered Arizona voter, only eligible to register.","note":"Both quotes verified verbatim (16-341(G) and 16-321(D)). The statutory text supports each element, including the 'eligible to register' (not 'registered') standard and the non-resident circulator-registration requirement. Non-interpretive.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization of signature sheets is required; the circulator must certify on each sheet that every signer signed in the circulator's presence on the indicated date and that the circulator believes each signer was a qualified elector residing at the listed address (A.R.S. 16-321(D)). Separately, the candidate's filing must include a consent statement SIGNED by the vice-presidential running mate and each designated presidential elector, and a nomination paper for each elector must be filed (A.R.S. 16-341(J)).","note":"Both quotes verified verbatim. AZ requires circulator certification, not notarization, of the signature sheets. The azcentral notarization failure was MICHIGAN's, not Arizona's, so it does not undercut the no-notary finding. The elector-consent requirement (16-341(J)) is correctly grounded; the West 2024 filing's missing presidential/VP nomination forms and acceptance letter are corroborated by azcentral. Non-interpretive.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Paper. No online signature system covers an independent presidential-elector petition in Arizona. E-Qual under A.R.S. 16-318 is limited to U.S. Senate and U.S. House candidates; 16-341(N) electronic petitions are discretionary and (per the SoS) have not been authorized for presidential-elector petitions. Collect on paper signature sheets (as RFK Jr. and Cornel West did in 2024).","note":"All three quotes verified verbatim. 16-318(B) unambiguously limits E-Qual to U.S. Senator/Representative. 16-341(N) is discretionary ('may authorize ... for statewide and legislative offices'); whether presidential-elector qualifies as 'statewide' is an open reading, BUT the operative VALUE is unaffected: no electronic system has been authorized for these petitions, so paper is correct under every reading (corroborated by the physical petition boxes filed in 2024). The residual statutory-scope question is flagged to the SoS but does not change the answer.","conf":0.88,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Arizona provides no filing-fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for an independent presidential candidate; the signature petition is mandatory, and a candidate who does not file a timely, compliant nomination petition is not eligible to appear on the ballot (A.R.S. 16-341(K)).","note":"Quote verified verbatim (it appears in 16-341(K), though the draft's prose loosely cites the fine provision as 16-341(M) — the verbatim quote and its eligibility-bar substance are correct). Arizona's fee-in-lieu mechanisms apply to partisan primary candidates, not to independent nomination petitions; there is no fee alternative for an independent presidential candidate. Non-interpretive.","conf":0.85,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Arkansas","sigs":"AR: 5,000 valid signatures (statewide, no distribution) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"AR: petition due noon, first Monday of August (2024 = Aug 5); electors certified by Sep 15 — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"Core burden (5,000 sigs / first-Monday-of-August / no distribution / paper / no fee) is fully grounded and AUTO-LIVE. Open risk is procedural: circulator qualifications and notary/affidavit for the PRESIDENTIAL petition are not settled by primary sources (the standard SoS affidavit is expressly carved out for President/VP) — held conservative pending SoS confirmation; over-comply (qualified-elector circulators + notarize) until answered.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT (and political-group) presidential/VP ballot-access petition under Ark. Code Ann. 7-8-302(5)-(6): does the Secretary of State impose any qualifications on the person who CIRCULATES the petition (e.g., must the circulator be a registered Arkansas voter, an Arkansas resident, or at least 18)?","Does the SoS-prescribed presidential/VP petition form under 7-8-302(5)-(6) require a notarized circulator affidavit or any sworn/witnessed verification of the signatures, given that the standard independent-candidate signature-collection affidavit is carved out 'except President/Vice President'?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; per-signature ban (§7-9-601) is initiative/referendum-only","note":"For an INDEPENDENT PRESIDENTIAL candidate, the controlling petition statute is Ark. Code § 7-8-302 (Chapter 8, Presidential Electors), whose full text addresses only the filing deadline, the 5,000 qualified-elector signature requirement, SoS verification, and elector certification — it is SILENT on whether circulators may be paid, paid per signature, or be non-residents (it only requires that the 5,000 SIGNERS be qualified electors of the state). Arkansas's per-signature ban, paid-canvasser registration rules, and circulator residency/citizenship requirement all live in Chapter 9 (Initiatives, Referenda, and Constitutional Amendments) and are textually limited to \"a statewide initiative petition or statewide referendum petition\" (§ 7-9-601), so they do NOT carry over to candidate petitions. Candidate-petition circulator compensation is therefore UNADDRESSED in the Arkansas election code; treat conservatively.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential nominating petition under Ark. Code § 7-8-302, may a campaign pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, may it pay them at all (hourly/salary), and must a circulator be an Arkansas resident or registered voter? (Note: Ark. Code § 7-9-601's per-signature ban and the residency rule appear limited to statewide initiative/referendum petitions, not candidate petitions — please confirm whether any analogous restriction applies to candidate petitions.)","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-8-302.html","quote":"(6)(A) Persons desiring to have their names printed on the ballot as independent candidates for President of the United States and Vice President of the United States shall file a petition with the Secretary of State by noon on the first Monday of August of the year of the election. The petition shall contain at the time of filing the names of five thousand (5,000) qualified electors of the state declaring their desire to have printed on the ballot the names of the persons desiring their names to be printed on the ballot as independent candidates for President of the United States and Vice President of the United States."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-9-601/","quote":"(g)(1) It is unlawful for a person to pay or offer to pay a person, or receive payment or agree to receive payment, on a basis related to the number of signatures obtained on a statewide initiative petition or statewide referendum petition. (2) This subsection does not prohibit compensation for circulating petitions but only compensation for obtaining signatures when the compensation or compensation level is impacted by or related to the number of signatures obtained."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-9-601/","quote":"(a)(1) A person shall not provide money or anything of value to another person for obtaining signatures on a statewide initiative petition or statewide referendum petition unless the person receiving the money or item of value meets the requirements of this section."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-7-103/","quote":"(a)(1) A person desiring to have his or her name placed upon the ballot as an independent candidate without political party affiliation for any United States office other than President of the United States or Vice President of the United States or state, county, township, or district office in any general election in this state shall file ... (2) Each elector signing the petition shall be a registered voter ..."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-8-302.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-9-601/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-7-103/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ar/title-7-elections/ar-code-sect-7-5-109/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 valid signatures of qualified electors (registered Arkansas voters), statewide. Flat statutory number under Ark. Code Ann. 7-8-302(6)(A) (independent) and 7-8-302(5)(B) (political group); does not recompute per cycle. Raised from 1,000 to 5,000 by HB1338 (signed Mar 8, 2021).","note":"All 3 citations verbatim-confirmed: FindLaw 7-8-302(6)(A) (current as of Mar 28, 2024), ballot-access.org HB1338 post, and Ballotpedia. Independently re-derived 5,000 for the independent presidential petition; the 10,000 figure correctly distinguished as the new-PARTY petition (7-7-205 / Amendment), not the independent/group presidential petition. No litigation or post-2024 change found.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Petition filed with the Secretary of State by noon on the first Monday of August of the election year (2024 cycle = August 5, 2024; recomputes per cycle). SoS verifies sufficiency within 10 days. Separately, qualifying independent candidate must certify the elector slate to the SoS by September 15 (7-8-302(6)(C)).","note":"Statute quote verbatim in FindLaw 7-8-302(6)(A) and (6)(C); NASS independent-candidate line verbatim-confirmed (lines 117-119 of the 07/29/24 NASS summary). Verified independently that first Monday of August 2024 = Aug 5, 2024. Sep 15 elector-certification correctly sourced to (6)(C).","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. 5,000 signatures collected statewide ('qualified electors of the state'); no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement in Ark. Code Ann. 7-8-302.","note":"Statute quote verbatim in FindLaw; NASS describes a single statewide petition. Re-read of full 7-8-302 text confirms no geographic-distribution clause for the independent or group presidential petition.","conf":0.94,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat circulators of the presidential petition as required to be qualified Arkansas electors: U.S. citizen, Arkansas resident, at least 18, and lawfully registered to vote — the strictest generally-applicable standard — UNTIL the SoS confirms whether any (or no) circulator qualifications apply to the President/VP petition specifically.","note":"Both SoS-handbook quotes confirmed verbatim (the 'except President/Vice President' carve-out at handbook p. re line 2244-2245, and the 'qualifications set out above, for purposes of signing the petition' qualified-elector list at lines 657-672). The draft's own value is UNKNOWN, which is honest: 7-8-302 sets no circulator qualifications and the standard affidavit is carved out for President/VP, so retrieval cannot settle what (if anything) the SoS-prescribed presidential form requires of a circulator. Over-comply with the strictest elector standard and confirm with SoS rather than rely on UNKNOWN.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Assume the SoS-prescribed presidential/VP petition form MAY require a notarized circulator affidavit or sworn verification; notarize the petition (and have each circulator execute any verification the form provides) UNTIL the SoS confirms no such requirement applies to the President/VP petition.","note":"Citations verbatim-confirmed (SoS handbook 'except President/Vice President'; statute 7-8-302(5)(D) oath confirmed in FindLaw, applying to the GROUP certificate of choice, not the petition). But the draft's 'None statutorily required' is an inference from statutory silence plus an affidavit CARVE-OUT — and the thing carved out is precisely the notarized signature-collection affidavit. Whether the SoS form for the presidential petition nonetheless requires notarization is not settled by primary sources. Strictest defensible posture: notarize unless SoS says otherwise; never risk rejection.","conf":0.58,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Physical petition filed with the Secretary of State; no remote-online or in-person-digitized capture path exists for the independent or minor-party presidential petition.","note":"Statute 'file a petition ... at the time of filing' verbatim in FindLaw; SoS handbook group-presidential 'filing a petition with the Secretary of State' confirmed verbatim (lines 1200-1203). No statutory or handbook reference to any electronic/online signature system for this petition.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee in lieu of or in addition to the 5,000-signature petition for an independent or minor-party presidential candidate; 7-8-302 provides only the petition route and specifies no fee. (Arkansas party filing fees apply only to candidates seeking a recognized party's primary nomination.)","note":"Statute quote verbatim in FindLaw (petition-only route, no fee provision in 7-8-302); Ballotpedia '5,000 signatures' / 'no write-in' quote confirmed verbatim. Re-read of full 7-8-302 confirms no fee alternative is created or required for the independent/group presidential path.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"California","sigs":"CA: 219,403 valid sigs (1% of statewide reg.); independent pres. qualifies via slate of 54 electors. AUTO-LIVE.","deadline":"CA: nomination papers due 5:00pm Aug 9, 2024 (E-88); circulate from Apr 26, 2024 (E-193). AUTO-LIVE.","risk":"6 of 7 fields verified live; only circulatorEligibility is held — draft's \"circulators must be registered CA voters\" is NOT supported by ELEC 102/8451 (age 18+ is the only requirement), so do not rely on a voter-registration screen for circulators.","sos":["For the November 2024 independent presidential (presidential elector) nomination under Elections Code 8400/8451/102, must a petition circulator be a registered California voter, or is being 18 years of age or older the only circulator eligibility requirement?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature legal only via initiative-law analogy; CA has no per-signature ban, all ban bills vetoed)","note":"For CANDIDATE / independent-presidential nominating papers, California's Elections Code does NOT address circulator compensation at all — neither permitting nor prohibiting per-signature pay (the candidate-petition statutes Elec. Code 8400-8409 and the circulator chapter 8451-8454 are silent, as is the general petition chapter 100-108). The \"pay-per-signature permitted\" answer that exists in California comes exclusively from the INITIATIVE context (Div. 9, Elec. Code 9021), reinforced by Gov. Newsom's/Brown's repeated vetoes of bills (SB 660 2021, AB 1451 2019, AB 1947 2018) that would have banned per-signature pay for \"initiative, referendum, or recall petitions\" — none of which reached candidate petitions; do not carry that answer over. Paid circulation generally is not prohibited, and circulators of nominating papers need only be 18+ (Elec. Code 8451 -> 102), with NO residency or voter-registration requirement, so a national paid pool could lawfully circulate in CA. Because per-signature compensation is genuinely unaddressed for candidate petitions, hold conservative.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT candidate for President nominating paper under Elections Code sections 8400 and 8451, may a campaign compensate circulators on a per-valid-signature basis, or must circulators be paid only by hourly/salary/flat-bonus arrangements — and does any Elections Code provision, regulation, or Secretary of State guidance restrict how candidate-petition (as opposed to initiative/referendum/recall) circulators are paid?","citations":[{"url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&division=8.&title=&part=2.&chapter=4.&article=","quote":"CHAPTER 4. Circulators [8451 - 8454] ... 8451. Circulators shall meet the requirements of Section 102. ... 8452. A county elections official or a deputy county elections official may not circulate nomination papers, and circulators shall not obtain signatures within 100 feet of any election booth or polling place. ... 8454. (a) Circulators obtaining signatures to the nomination paper of any candidate may, at any time not more than 148 nor less than 88 days prior to the election, obtain signatures to the nomination paper of the candidate. (b) Circulators obtaining signatures to the nomination paper of any candidate for presidential elector may, at any time not more than 193 nor less than 88 days prior to the election, obtain signatures to the nomination paper of the candidate."},{"url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=102.","quote":"102. A person shall not circulate a state or local initiative, referendum, or recall petition or nominating paper unless the person is 18 years of age or older."},{"url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&division=0.5.&title=&part=&chapter=2.&article=","quote":"101. (a) ... (3) \"THIS PETITION MAY BE CIRCULATED BY A PAID SIGNATURE GATHERER OR A VOLUNTEER. YOU HAVE THE RIGHT TO ASK.\" ... [This paid-gatherer disclosure requirement, like the Official Top Funders rules in Section 107, applies only to a \"state or local initiative, referendum, or recall petition\" and is not extended to candidate nominating papers.] ... 106. (b) Any person engaged in obtaining signatures to the nomination papers of a candidate for any office or to any recall, initiative or referendum petition, may, if otherwise qualified to sign the papers or petition, sign the papers or petition."},{"url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=9021.","quote":"DIVISION 9. MEASURES SUBMITTED TO THE VOTERS [9000 - 9611] ... 9021. (a) A person who meets the requirements of Section 102 may circulate a statewide initiative or referendum petition anywhere within the state. ... [This is the initiative/referendum statute Ballotpedia cites for California's \"pay-per-signature permitted\" status; it governs ballot measures, not candidate nominating papers.]"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","quote":"California | Permitted | California Election Code, Section 9021 ... California Senate Bill 660 (Vetoed): The legislation would have banned paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. Gov. Gavin Newsom (D) vetoed [it]. ... California Assembly Bill 1451 (Vetoed) ... California Assembly Bill 1947 (Vetoed): ... The legislation would have banned paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&division=8.&title=&part=2.&chapter=4.&article=","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=102.","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&division=0.5.&title=&part=&chapter=2.&article=","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=9021.","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=2188.","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=ELEC&sectionNum=18109.","official":true,"dom":"leginfo.legislature.ca.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/voter-registration/voter-registration-information-file-request","official":true,"dom":"sos.ca.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"219,403 valid signatures for the 2024 cycle, equal to 1% of statewide voter registration as of the last Report of Registration prior to the November 2022 General Election; recomputes each presidential cycle. No direct independent presidential line — the candidate qualifies by nominating a slate of 54 presidential electors (plus 54 alternates) via independent nomination, with the nomination papers carrying the signatures. Cal. Elections Code 8400, 8303, 8550; 2187(c)(6).","note":"All three quotes verbatim in sources. SoS PDF states '219,403... (equivalent to 1%... prior to the November 2022 General Election)' and the 54-elector qualification path. ELEC 8400 independently confirms 1% of registered voters for statewide office; Ballotpedia independently confirms 219,403 and '1% of the total number of registered voters in the state' for 2024 independent presidential. Path-via-electors framing is correct.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"For the Nov 5, 2024 General Election: nomination papers circulate from Apr 26, 2024 (E-193) and must be delivered to the county elections official no later than 5:00 p.m. on Aug 9, 2024 (E-88); electors' Declarations of Candidacy also due 5:00 p.m. Aug 9, 2024 (E-88). Statutory rule: 88 days before the general election; recomputes per cycle. Cal. Elections Code 8403(a)(2), 8550.","note":"SoS quotes verbatim. ELEC 8403(a)(2) independently confirms: for offices with no filing fee, papers circulated/delivered to county no earlier than 193 days and no later than 5 p.m. 88 days before the election. Ballotpedia confirms 8/9/2024 deadline and '5:00 p.m. 88 days prior to the election.'","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 1% requirement is a single statewide total; there is no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement for the independent presidential (presidential elector) nomination. Signatures are gathered and delivered county-by-county to the county where signers reside for verification, but no minimum-per-county quota applies.","note":"Quotes verbatim. ELEC 8400 sets a single statewide 1% number for statewide office with no geographic-distribution clause; ELEC 8403(c) addresses only a void-if-insufficient mechanism and per-county delivery for verification, not a per-county minimum. No distribution rule found in primary law.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Circulators must be 18 years of age or older (Cal. Elections Code 102, 8451). The strictest reliable statement of eligibility is the age-18 requirement only. A registered voter who is a candidate may circulate and sign their own nomination papers (106(a)). Do NOT rely on a 'circulator must be a registered California voter' requirement — it is not supported by 102/8451; confirm any residency/registration condition with the SoS before screening circulators.","note":"The grounded SoS quote supports ONLY age 18+. The draft's added claim that circulators 'must be registered voters of California (per 102/8451)' is contradicted by the actual statutes: ELEC 102 reads 'A person shall not circulate... unless the person is 18 years of age or older' and ELEC 8451 says 'Circulators shall meet the requirements of Section 102' — neither imposes a voter-registration requirement (ELEC 104(b)(3) likewise lists only age 18+ for the circulator declaration). Holding because the value asserts an unsupported, stricter-than-law requirement; relied value corrected to the defensible age-18 floor.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization is required. Each section of the nomination paper must carry a circulator declaration signed in the circulator's own hand, certified under penalty of perjury (Cal. Elections Code 104); there is no notary/affidavit-before-officer requirement. All signers must be registered California voters (100, 8400), and signed papers are delivered to the county elections official where signers reside for verification before forwarding to the Secretary of State.","note":"Both quotes verbatim. SoS summary specifies no notary. ELEC 104 independently confirms the integrity mechanism is a circulator declaration 'under penalty of perjury under the laws of the State of California' — not notarization. Draft's core 'no notarization' conclusion is correct (draft does not name 104 but asserts nothing false).","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures are collected on physical nomination papers circulated to registered voters and delivered to county elections officials for verification. There is no remote-online or digitized signature system for the independent presidential (presidential elector) petition in California; the SoS Summary describes only paper nomination papers and Declarations of Candidacy filed by mail, in-person drop box, or at a county elections office.","note":"Both quotes verbatim in the SoS PDF. SoS process is entirely physical circulation/delivery; ELEC 8400/8403 contemplate paper nomination papers. No e-signature path exists for this petition.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee is required to file the nomination papers, and California provides no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative for the independent presidential (presidential elector) nomination — the signature petition is the sole path.","note":"Quote verbatim: SoS PDF 'No filing fee is required from any person in order to file nomination papers.' Ballotpedia 2024 table lists filing fee 'N/A' for CA independent presidential. The no-fee/no-fee-in-lieu framing is consistent (the no-fee status is precisely why the longer E-193 circulation window in 8403(a)(2) applies).","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Colorado","sigs":"12,000 total (1,500 in EACH of 8 CDs) — fixed per-district, not 5,000","deadline":"117th day before general election; time-of-day in conflict (SOS 3pm vs statute 5pm) — use 3pm","risk":"7 of 8 fields verify clean for an unaffiliated presidential candidate; only the deadline TIME-OF-DAY is in genuine source conflict (SOS page 3:00 p.m. vs statute effective 1/1/2025 5 p.m.) — treat 3:00 p.m. as the binding cutoff and confirm with SOS before any cycle.","sos":["For an unaffiliated presidential nominating petition under C.R.S. 1-4-802(1)(f)(I), is the filing cutoff on the 117th day before the general election 3:00 p.m. (per your PresidentPetition.html guidance) or 5:00 p.m. (per the statutory text effective Jan 1, 2025)? Please confirm the exact wall-clock deadline currently enforced."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — candidate-petition statute permits paid circulators (licensed petition entity) but is silent on per-signature compensation","note":"For Colorado CANDIDATE (independent presidential) nominating petitions, per-signature compensation of circulators is NOT addressed by the candidate-petition election code: CRS 1-4-905 and 1-4-905.5 clearly allow PAID circulators (via a Secretary-of-State-licensed \"petition entity\") and require paid/volunteer badges, but neither authorizes nor prohibits paying circulators on a per-signature basis. Colorado's per-signature case law (Meyer v. Grant) and per-signature-adjacent rules sit in the separate INITIATIVE code (Title 1, Article 40 / 1-40-135) and do not automatically govern candidate petitions. Circulators need only be U.S. citizens age 18+ (no Colorado residency required; the SoS expressly allows a circulator address outside Colorado), so a national paid pool can legally work there if the paying entity is licensed and each circulator is registered/trained.","sosInquiry":"For an UNAFFILIATED candidate's nominating petition for President (Title 1, Article 4, Part 8), may a campaign or its licensed petition entity compensate circulators on a PER-SIGNATURE basis, or must circulators be paid only by the hour/salary/flat fee? Does any statute or election rule restrict per-signature pay for CANDIDATE (as opposed to initiative) petition circulators?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905/","quote":"(1) A person shall not circulate a petition to nominate a candidate unless the person is a citizen of the United States and at least eighteen years of age."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905/","quote":"(6)(a) A circulator who is not to be paid for circulating a petition shall display an identification badge that includes the words “VOLUNTEER CIRCULATOR” in bold-faced type that is clearly legible. (b) A circulator who is to be paid for circulating a petition shall display an identification badge that includes the words “PAID CIRCULATOR” in bold-faced type that is clearly legible and the name and telephone number of the individual employing the circulator."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905-5/","quote":"(2)(a) It is unlawful for any petition entity to provide payment to a circulator to circulate a petition to nominate a candidate, to recall an elected officer, or to create a minor party without first obtaining a license from the secretary of state."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905-5/","quote":"(c) “Petition entity” means any person or committee that directly or indirectly provides payment to a circulator to circulate a petition to nominate a candidate, to recall an elected officer in accordance with article 12 of this title 1, or to create a minor party in accordance with part 13 of this article 4."},{"url":"https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Candidates/PresidentPetition.html","quote":"In order to be eligible to circulate a petition, a person must be a citizen of the United States and at least 18 years of age. [1] ... [1] 1-4-905(1), C.R.S."},{"url":"https://www.coloradosos.gov/pubs/elections/petitionEntities/faqs.html","quote":"Information needed for each registration includes: Circulator's name; Circulator's permanent physical address (this may be outside Colorado)"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Candidates/PresidentPetition.html","official":true,"dom":"sos.state.co.us"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.coloradosos.gov/pubs/elections/petitionEntities/faqs.html","official":true,"dom":"coloradosos.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.coloradosos.gov/pubs/info_center/fees/elections.html","official":true,"dom":"coloradosos.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.coloradosos.gov/pubs/elections/forms/dataRequests.pdf","official":true,"dom":"coloradosos.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-4-905-5/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-2-227/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/co/title-1-elections/co-rev-st-sect-1-2-302/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"12,000 total — at least 1,500 valid signatures of registered Colorado electors in EACH of the state's 8 congressional districts (1,500 x 8 = 12,000). Fixed per-district number, not a percentage and not a flat statewide number. Signers must be registered Colorado voters who have not signed a petition for any other candidate for the same office.","note":"Both citations verbatim. SOS PresidentPetition.html: '1,500 signatures in each of the 8 congressional district (12,000 total)'; C.R.S. 1-4-802(1)(c)(I): 'At least one thousand five hundred in each congressional district for the office of president and vice president'. Independently confirmed: CO has 8 CDs post-2020 census, so 1,500x8=12,000. The draft's flag that Ballotpedia's stale '5,000' is incorrect is itself correct — Ballotpedia line 235 still says '5,000 eligible voters' which is the pre-redistricting flat figure superseded by the per-CD schedule. Current and correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"File the completed petition no later than 3:00 p.m. on the 117th day before the general election. The 117-day rule is confirmed by both the statute (C.R.S. 1-4-802(1)(f)(I)) and SOS guidance; the time-of-day is in conflict (SOS guidance says 3:00 p.m.; statutory text effective 1/1/2025 says 5 p.m.). Use the EARLIER 3:00 p.m. cutoff, which satisfies both. Circulation cannot begin earlier than the 173rd day before the general election (C.R.S. 1-4-802(1)(d)(I)). For 2024 the deadline fell on 7/11/24; recomputes each cycle off the November general-election date.","note":"All three citations verbatim. Findlaw shows the statute is split: text effective UNTIL 1/1/2025 = '3 p.m.', text effective 1/1/2025 = '5 p.m.'. The SOS web guidance still states 3:00 p.m. This is a genuine source conflict on time-of-day that retrieval cannot settle (which controls for a 2026+ cycle — updated statute or the not-yet-updated SOS page). Strictest defensible reading: file by 3:00 p.m., which complies under either rule. The 117-day count itself is not in dispute. Ballotpedia 7/11/24 / 8/7/24 dates match the footnote verbatim and are consistent with a 117-day computation off 11/5/2024.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"YES — distribution required: at least 1,500 signatures in EACH of the 8 congressional districts. Signers must be eligible electors residing within the district in which the office is to be elected. Per-CD minimum, not a statewide aggregate; signatures cannot be concentrated in one district.","note":"C.R.S. 1-4-802(1)(c) verbatim: 'Every petition for the office of president and vice president ... must be signed by eligible electors residing within the district or political subdivision in which the officer is to be elected', combined with 1-4-802(1)(c)(I)'s 'in each congressional district' establishes a binding per-CD minimum. SOS quote verbatim. Note: 'in each congressional district' is the operative distribution language; the residency clause and the per-CD minimum together fully support the value. Current and correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A petition circulator must be a citizen of the United States and at least 18 years of age. No Colorado residency requirement and no voter-registration requirement is imposed on the circulator. Paid vs. volunteer circulators must wear an identifying badge (PAID CIRCULATOR / VOLUNTEER CIRCULATOR).","note":"C.R.S. 1-4-905(1) verbatim: 'A person shall not circulate a petition to nominate a candidate unless the person is a citizen of the United States and at least eighteen years of age.' SOS quote verbatim. Adversarial check: 1-4-905 imposes no residency/registration requirement on circulators (only US citizenship + 18+); the badge requirement in 1-4-905(6) confirms the parenthetical. Current and correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"BOTH a notarized circulator affidavit AND a notarized candidate acceptance are required. (1) Each petition SECTION must have attached a signed, dated, notarized circulator affidavit; the circulator must appear in the physical presence of the notary; an improperly notarized affidavit is invalid and the section cannot be accepted (C.R.S. 1-4-905(2)-(3)). (2) Before filing, the petition must have attached a notarized acceptance of nomination by the candidate (or by both joint president/VP candidates) (C.R.S. 1-4-906); SOS guidance requires the candidate/VP acceptance forms to be notarized.","note":"All three citations verbatim. 1-4-905(2)(a): 'Each petition section must have attached a signed, notarized, and dated affidavit executed by the person who circulated the petition section'; 1-4-905(2)(b)(I)(A) confirms physical-presence; 1-4-905(2)(b)(II) makes a violating affidavit invalid; 1-4-905(3) bars acceptance without the notarized affidavit. 1-4-906 verbatim on the notarized candidate acceptance. SOS notarization quote verbatim. Current and correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The unaffiliated presidential petition is paper-only: SOS must approve the petition format before circulation, the petition is circulated on paper, each section requires a wet-ink notarized circulator affidavit (circulator physically present before the notary), and the completed petition plus notarized acceptance forms are hand-delivered to the SOS Elections Division in Denver (1700 Broadway, Suite 550). No online/remote-signing or digitized-capture system covers an unaffiliated presidential nominating petition in Colorado.","note":"All three citations verbatim. SOS: 'Petition formats must be approved by the Secretary of State's office prior to circulation' and 'Hand deliver petition and acceptance forms to:' (Denver address printed on page). 1-4-905(2)(b)(I)(A) physical-presence notarization verbatim. The negative existence claim (no e-signing) is strongly supported by the wet-ink/physical-presence/hand-delivery requirements; no contrary source found. Current and correct for the unaffiliated presidential route.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for the unaffiliated presidential route. There is no filing-fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for an unaffiliated presidential candidate; the nominating petition (1,500/CD, 12,000 total) is the only path onto the general-election ballot. The petition-or-fee CHOICE applies only to major-party presidential PRIMARY candidates (C.R.S. 1-4-1204), not to general-election access for an independent. Minor-party note: forming a NEW minor party requires a separate statewide petition of at least 10,000 registered electors filed by the 2nd Friday in January of the election year; a QPO candidate petitions under the same 1-4-802 schedule. An individual independent uses the 1-4-802 unaffiliated path and pays no fee.","note":"Citations verbatim: SOS 'Submit the notarized acceptance of petition nomination forms with the completed petition.' and QPO FAQ 'Be signed by at least 10,000 registered electors in Colorado; and' (also confirms '2nd Friday in January of the election year'). Adversarial check: the SOS PresidentPetition.html unaffiliated workflow lists no fee step and no fee-in-lieu option; 1-4-802 sets signatures as the sole requirement with no fee alternative. The 1-4-1204 primary fee/petition choice is a separate major-party primary mechanism not available to an independent. Current and correct. (The cited SOS quote supports the 'petition is the path' framing rather than a fee, which is the correct grounding for a negative-existence claim.)","conf":0.85,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Connecticut","sigs":"7,500 wet-ink signatures (lesser of 1% of last presidential vote or 7,500; 1% of 1,759,010 = ~17,590, so 7,500 governs)","deadline":"SOTS by 4:00pm Jul 29, 2026; town clerk by 4:00pm Aug 5, 2026 (90th day before Nov 3, 2026)","risk":"All citations grounded verbatim against the 2026 ED-607, 2020 FAQ, candidate-ballot-access page, and Ballotpedia; the four hard operative rules (count, deadline, no distribution quota, witness/notary, paper-only) are AUTO-LIVE, but two fields assert legal NEGATIVES (no circulator residency requirement; no filing fee) that retrieval cannot conclusively settle, so they are held conservative pending SOS confirmation.","sos":["Does Connecticut impose any in-state residency requirement on circulators of an independent presidential nominating petition, or may an out-of-state U.S. citizen (18+, not on felony parole) lawfully circulate and certify petition pages?","Is there any filing fee, deposit, or fee-based alternative associated with an independent presidential nominating petition, or is collecting the required signatures the sole path onto the general-election ballot?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; CT in-state residency required for circulators","note":"Connecticut's candidate/independent nominating-petition statutes (Conn. Gen. Stat. 9-453a to 9-453u) and the Secretary of the State's official ED-607 instructions address only WHO may circulate (U.S. citizen, at least 18, a resident of a town in Connecticut, not on parole for a felony) and signature authenticity — they are entirely SILENT on compensating circulators, so per-signature pay for candidate petitions is unaddressed (not affirmatively permitted or prohibited). Connecticut's initiative/ballot-measure pay-per-signature framework does not apply because Connecticut has no statewide initiative process; the candidate-petition code controls and does not carry it over. Circulator in-state residency IS clearly required, which would bar a national/out-of-state paid circulator pool from validly circulating in Connecticut.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under Conn. Gen. Stat. 9-453a et seq., may a campaign pay circulators on a per-signature basis, and may circulators be paid at all (e.g., hourly or salaried)? Also, does the 9-453j requirement that a circulator state residency \"in this state\" mean every circulator must be a Connecticut resident?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ct/title-9-elections/ct-gen-st-sect-9-453j.html","quote":"Each page of a nominating petition submitted to the town clerk or the Secretary of the State ... shall contain a statement as to the residency in this state and eligibility of the circulator and authenticity of the signatures thereon, signed under penalties of false statement, by the person who circulated the same. Such statement shall set forth (1) such circulator's residence address, including the town in this state in which such circulator is a resident, (2) the circulator's date of birth and that the circulator is at least eighteen years of age, (3) that the circulator is a United States citizen and not on parole for conviction of a felony, and (4) that each person whose name appears on such page signed the same in person in the presence of such circulator..."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ct/title-9-elections/ct-gen-st-sect-9-453k.html","quote":"The town clerk or Secretary of the State shall not accept any page of a nominating petition unless the circulator thereof has signed before him or an appropriate person as provided in section 1-29, the statement as to the residency in this state and eligibility of the circulator and authenticity of the signatures thereon required by section 9-453j."},{"url":"https://ctindependents.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/2024-ed-607-instruction-page-for-nominating-petition1-1.pdf","quote":"Who Can Be a Circulator: Each circulator of a nominating petition page must be a United States citizen, at least eighteen years of age, and shall not be on parole for conviction of a felony."},{"url":"https://ctindependents.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/2024-ed-607-instruction-page-for-nominating-petition1-1.pdf","quote":"Circulator's Statement of Residence and Authenticity of Signatures: Boxes on the back of each petition page setting forth the circulator's name, street address and town of residence must be filled out before the circulator signs the Circulator's Statement of Residence and Eligibility and of the Authenticity of Signatures."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/sots/electionservices/voter-file-request-forms/ct-voter-registration-data-file-request-form.pdf","official":true,"dom":"portal.ct.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://portal.ct.gov/sots/election-services/election-services/centralized-voter-registration-information---voter-privacy-program","official":true,"dom":"portal.ct.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ct/title-9-elections/ct-gen-st-sect-9-453j.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ct/title-9-elections/ct-gen-st-sect-9-453k.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ctindependents.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/2024-ed-607-instruction-page-for-nominating-petition1-1.pdf","official":false,"dom":"ctindependents.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Lesser of (1) 1% of the votes cast for the same office at the last preceding election, or (2) 7,500. For an independent presidential candidate the operative number is 7,500, because 1% of Connecticut's 2024 presidential vote (1,759,010 total) is ~17,590, far above 7,500. The petition for the office of presidential elector must list seven candidates for Presidential Elector plus a candidate for President and a candidate for Vice-President. The Elections Services Division computes the exact figure at issuance, but the law prevails.","note":"Both ED-607 quotes (lesser-of-1%-or-7,500; seven electors + Pres + VP) found verbatim at lines 98-104 and 62-64; Ballotpedia quote found verbatim. Independently confirmed 7,500 is operative: CT 2024 presidential total = 1,759,010 (Wikipedia), 1% = 17,590 > 7,500. Operative number is statutory, not interpretation-dependent.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Not later than 4:00 p.m. on the 90th day preceding the regular election. For the November 3, 2026 general election: submit to the Secretary of the State by 4:00 p.m. July 29, 2026; after July 29, pages may be submitted only to the town clerk of the signers' town of voting residence by 4:00 p.m. August 5, 2026. Withdrawals of signatures also run to Aug 5, 2026.","note":"ED-607 quote (Jul 29 SOTS / Aug 5 town clerk) found verbatim at lines 158-160; FAQ 90-day-rule quote found verbatim at line 66. Document states the specific 2026 dates authoritatively, consistent with the Nov 3, 2026 general election. Town-clerk Aug 5 date aligns with the 90-day rule; SOTS path closes a week earlier.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Connecticut imposes no congressional-district or county signature-distribution quota. The only geographic constraints are (1) each signer must be an elector eligible to vote for all offices/candidates listed (statewide for president) and (2) no single page may be circulated among electors of more than one town (a per-page town-verification mechanic, not a distribution requirement).","note":"Both ED-607 quotes found verbatim (signer-eligibility at lines 109-111; one-town-per-page at lines 116-119). No district/county quota appears anywhere in the instructions; the one-town-per-page rule is correctly characterized as a town-clerk verification mechanic, not a geographic distribution requirement.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Each circulator must be a United States citizen, at least 18 years of age, and not on parole for conviction of a felony; a candidate may circulate and sign his or her own petition. STRICTEST POSTURE pending SOS confirmation: treat in-state residency as potentially required and prefer Connecticut-resident circulators, because the asserted absence of any residency requirement is an inference from the form's silence (it asks circulators to state name/street/town/STATE of residence) rather than an affirmative statement of no-residency.","note":"Affirmative criteria (US citizen, 18+, not on felony parole) found verbatim in ED-607 (lines 90-91) and FAQ (lines 51-52); 'candidate may circulate own' grounded in FAQ. But 'no in-state residency requirement' is a NEGATIVE inferred from the form asking for state of residence; retrieval cannot conclusively confirm no residency rule exists. Held conservative to avoid ballot-access risk from out-of-state circulators; SOS inquiry added.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Each page must carry the circulator's Statement of Residence and Eligibility and of the Authenticity of Signatures, signed under penalties of false statement, attesting each signer signed in the circulator's presence and was known to or identified to the circulator. That statement must be signed in the presence of an authorized officer (town clerk, Secretary of the State, notary public, judge of a court of record, family support magistrate, clerk/deputy clerk of a court with a seal, commissioner of deeds, Connecticut justice of the peace, or a Connecticut-admitted attorney), who must certify the circulator signed before him and was known/identified. Pages lacking the statement and certification are not accepted. This is a notarization-type attestation, not a self-notarized affidavit.","note":"Both ED-607 quotes found verbatim (attestation language at lines 138-141; list of authorized officers at lines 143-146). The officer-certification requirement and the rejection of pages lacking it (lines 149-151) confirm this is an officer-witnessed attestation, accurately characterized.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Independent (nominating-petition) presidential signatures must be wet-ink on the official Petition Signature Page distributed by the Secretary of the State, or on duplicates of pages issued by the SOTS; each page is town-specific and physically certified by the town clerk/registrars against the registry list. The SOTS DocuSign system applies only to primary petitions, certificates of party endorsement, 15% eligibility, and minor-party nominations with statewide ballot access, not to independent nominating-petition signature collection.","note":"ED-607 'official Petition Signature Page... or duplicates' quote found verbatim at lines 119-121; candidate-ballot-access DocuSign-scope quote found verbatim. Core operative fact (signatures = wet-ink paper) is solidly grounded and not interpretation-dependent. The secondary sub-claim that 'only ED-602b may be emailed' is not directly substantiated by the sources but does not affect the operative captureMode.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat collecting the required 7,500 signatures as the sole and exclusive path onto the ballot for an independent/petitioning presidential candidate; assume NO filing fee and NO fee-based alternative, but confirm with the SOS before relying on the absence of any fee. No filing fee or fee alternative appears in the 2026 ED-607 instructions or the 2020/2026 FAQ, but the cited quote substantiates only the signature count, not the no-fee proposition.","note":"The attached citation quote (signature-count FAQ language) was found verbatim, so citation integrity holds, BUT that quote addresses signature counts, not fees, so it does not affirmatively substantiate 'no fee.' The 'None' claim is a NEGATIVE inferred from the sources' silence on fees. Substantively CT has no nominating-petition filing fee, but a negative cannot be conclusively settled by retrieval; held conservative and SOS inquiry added.","conf":0.7,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Delaware","sigs":"DE: 1% of statewide registration (Dec 31 prior yr) — HOLD on the \"~7,600\" number; rely on the formula, confirm exact count w/ Commissioner","deadline":"DE: Petition + sworn non-affiliation declaration due by close of business Sept 1 of election year (circulate Jan 1–Jul 15) — LIVE","risk":"Core legal rule (1% statewide, Sept 1 deadline, notarized circulator affidavit, paper-only, no fee) is fully grounded in 15 Del. C. 3002 + DE elections office; two holds — the specific ~7,600 signature count is unverified and possibly low (use the 1% formula, not a fixed number), and circulator eligibility is statutorily silent (assume strict: adult DE registered-voter circulators) pending Commissioner confirmation.","sos":["For an independent/unaffiliated presidential candidate, exactly how many valid signatures does the 1% threshold equal for the current cycle (i.e., what was Delaware's total statewide registered-voter count as of December 31 of the year preceding the general election), and is there a published certified number we should rely on?","Does Delaware impose any eligibility requirements on the person who circulates an unaffiliated candidate's nominating petition (e.g., minimum age, Delaware residency, or being a registered Delaware voter), beyond the requirement that the circulator provide a sworn notarized witness statement under 15 Del. C. 3002(c)(4)?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Delaware's candidate/unaffiliated-petition statute (15 Del. C. § 3002, which governs independent presidential candidates) does NOT address circulator compensation at all — neither permitting nor prohibiting per-signature pay, hourly pay, or any payment. There is no initiative/referendum process in Delaware, so no pay-per-signature law exists to even consider. Circulator pay is unaddressed; Delaware imposes no residency or voter-registration requirement on circulators (the code \"does not specify any requirements for circulators\"), but the criminal code's anti-bribery provisions target election officers and voters, not circulators.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/unaffiliated presidential candidate's nominating petition under 15 Del. C. § 3002, may the campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and are there any restrictions on paying circulators (e.g., hourly only) or on circulator residency/voter-registration status?","citations":[{"url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c030/index.html","quote":"The nominating petition shall contain such information and be on a form as prescribed by the State Election Commission. The following information shall, however, be contained in the petition: ... (4) A sworn notarized statement of the person circulating the petition that person witnessed the placing of each signature on the petition."},{"url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c030/index.html","quote":"Such petition shall be circulated and executed between January 1 and July 15 of the year in which the general election is held. Each registered voter signing shall do so upon a petition prepared for the county in which that registered voter is registered, and the petition shall be filed with the Department."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Delaware","quote":"Filed petitions must contain a sworn, notarized statement that the circulator witnessed the signing of each signature and that, to the best of the circulator's knowledge and belief, the signers are registered voters of the election district in which the candidate is running. The code does not specify any requirements for circulators."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Delaware","quote":"An independent presidential candidate must petition for access to the general election ballot. The petition must contain signatures equaling at least 1 percent of the total number of registered voters in the state as of December 31 of the year preceding the election. This petition must be filed with the state election commissioner by September 1 in the year of the election. This petition must be circulated between January 1 and July 15 of the year in which the election is taking place."},{"url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c051/sc02/index.html","quote":"Whoever bribes or attempts to bribe anyone expecting to hold any official position under the election or registration laws of this State, either as registrar, inspector, judge or otherwise, by giving money or the promise of money, office or the promise of office or position either under the state or federal government, to perform any service for any political party in this State or to favor any candidate for political office shall be fined not more than $1,000 and may be imprisoned not more than 6 months."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c030/index.html","official":true,"dom":"delcode.delaware.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c051/sc02/index.html","official":true,"dom":"delcode.delaware.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://elections.delaware.gov/public/forms/pdfs/statewide_vreg_order_form.pdf","official":true,"dom":"elections.delaware.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c003/index.html","official":true,"dom":"delcode.delaware.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://elections.delaware.gov/candidates/purchasereports.shtml","official":true,"dom":"elections.delaware.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Delaware","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Delaware","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Not less than 1% of the total number of voters registered statewide in Delaware as of December 31 of the year immediately preceding the general election year (15 Del. C. 3002(b)). This is a recomputed percentage with no fixed statutory number; do NOT plan to a specific count such as ~7,600. Treat the required number as the 1% formula applied to the certified statewide registration total for the actual cycle, and confirm the exact figure with the State Election Commissioner before relying on it. Path: unaffiliated-candidate nominating petition; president is a statewide office.","note":"Legal rule fully grounded: statute quote (15 Del. C. 3002(b)) and DE elections-office quote both appear VERBATIM at the cited pages; Ballotpedia corroborates the 1% statewide basis. Adversarial re-derivation confirms the 1% formula is correct and current. HOLD is driven solely by the embedded, self-disclaimed estimate 'roughly 7,600 signatures (~760,000 registrants).' This number is NOT from a primary source and I could not independently verify it (web search was intermittently unavailable). Recent DE statewide registration has run well above 760k (plausibly ~770k-790k+), so 1% could be ~7,700-7,900 — meaning 7,600 may UNDERSTATE the requirement, a ballot-access risk. Stripped the hard number; relied value is the formula only.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The nominating petition and the sworn unaffiliated-candidate declaration of non-affiliation must be filed on or before the close of the official business day on September 1 of the general election year, with the State Election Commissioner (president is a statewide office) per 15 Del. C. 3002(b). Separately, the petition may be circulated and executed only between January 1 and July 15 of the election year (15 Del. C. 3002(d)).","note":"Statute quote (3002(b)) appears VERBATIM at delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c030; Ballotpedia quote (Sept 1 filing; Jan 1-Jul 15 circulation) appears VERBATIM in the saved page (line 231). Independently re-derived: 3002(b) text confirms Sept 1 close-of-business filing; 3002(d) confirms the Jan 1-Jul 15 circulation window. Clean calendar facts, no interpretation. Added the circulation window to reliedValue because it is a hard companion constraint the draft mentioned only under distributionRule.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. A single statewide 1% threshold applies with no per-county or per-congressional-district minimum quota. Signatures are collected on county-segregated petition sheets — each signer must sign the petition prepared for the county in which that voter is registered, and each county's petition is filed with and verified by that county's Department of Elections (15 Del. C. 3002(d)). This is an organizational/filing rule, not a minimum-per-county distribution requirement.","note":"Statute quote (3002(d): 'Such petition shall be circulated and executed between January 1 and July 15... Each registered voter signing shall do so upon a petition prepared for the county in which that registered voter is registered, and the petition shall be filed with the Department. The signatures and other information thereon shall be verified by the department receiving the petition.') appears VERBATIM. Re-derivation confirms no per-county minimum exists in Chapter 30; the county-segregation is purely organizational. Characterization is accurate.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat circulators conservatively: use circulators who are adults, Delaware residents, and themselves registered Delaware voters, and who can appear before a notary to swear they witnessed each signature (15 Del. C. 3002(c)(4)), pending written confirmation from the State Election Commissioner. The statute imposes no EXPRESS age/residency/voter-registration requirement on the circulator, but its silence does not rule out requirements in the Commissioner's prescribed petition form or regulations; the strict assumption avoids any risk of signature/petition rejection. Each SIGNER must be a registered Delaware voter on the date of signing (3002(e)(1)).","note":"Citation grounded: the quote '(1) The signer was not a registered voter on the date the signer signed the petition;' appears VERBATIM in 3002(e). The draft's value is 'UNKNOWN' for circulator qualifications, which matches the statute text (3002 has no circulator-eligibility clause; only the notarized witness statement in 3002(c)(4)). HOLD because correctness hinges on absence-of-evidence: retrieval cannot confirm that the Commissioner's prescribed form/regs impose no circulator requirements, and 'UNKNOWN' is not a safe operational value. Over-comply with the strictest plausible practice and ask the Commissioner directly (see sosInquiries).","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes. The nominating petition must contain a sworn notarized statement of the person circulating the petition that they witnessed the placing of each signature (15 Del. C. 3002(c)(4)). Separately, the candidate must file a sworn declaration (with the State Election Commissioner for a statewide/presidential candidate) stating non-affiliation with any political party for at least 90 days before filing (3002(b)). Each signer must also acknowledge that knowingly entering false information may subject the signer to perjury prosecution (3002(c)(3)).","note":"Both statute quotes appear VERBATIM at delcode.delaware.gov/title15/c030: 3002(c)(4) notarized circulator-witness statement, and 3002(b) the sworn non-affiliation declaration to the State Election Commissioner for statewide candidates. The perjury acknowledgment (3002(c)(3)) is also present in the retrieved text. Re-derivation confirms all three. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wet-ink paper petition only. Each signer provides signature, printed name, registration address, Social Security number, and date (15 Del. C. 3002(c)(2)), on county-segregated paper petition sheets with a notarized circulator certification, filed with and verified against the permanent registration record by the county Department of Elections. The Department provides the unaffiliated petition as a downloadable PDF to be printed, circulated, and physically filed; there is no digital/online submission path for this petition.","note":"Statute quote ('Signature, printed name, address at which registered, social security number and date on which signed by signer;') appears VERBATIM in 3002(c)(2); elections-office quote ('Complete Petition for Unaffiliated Candidate to Secure Ballot Status by September 1st of a general election year.') appears VERBATIM. The operative value 'paper' is correct and is also the strict/safe answer. The 'NO digital system' claim is a negative I cannot exhaustively prove, but it is strongly supported (SSN + notarized wet-ink witness + downloadable PDF form), and it does not loosen any requirement, so AUTO-LIVE on the value 'paper'.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing fee in lieu of, or in addition to, signatures for the unaffiliated (independent) path; the signature petition is the sole means of ballot qualification. Filing fees (no more than 1% of the office's total term salary, set by the party, 15 Del. C. 3103) apply only to major-party primary candidates, not to the unaffiliated petition route or to a presidential candidate using it.","note":"Both elections-office quotes appear VERBATIM: 'Set filing fees of no more than 1% of the total salary for the term of an office. ( 3103)' (listed under major political parties) and 'File An Unaffiliated Candidate Declaration' (under unaffiliated candidates, with no fee). Re-derivation confirms the unaffiliated path in Chapter 30 has no fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option. Correct.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"District of Columbia","sigs":"1% of DC registered electors (144th-day count); 4,583 in 2024; recomputes each cycle; max 2x","deadline":"90th day before election, by 5:00 p.m., in person (Aug 7, 2024)","risk":"All citations grounded verbatim. Core operative rules verified against primary DC Code/DCMR. Two caveats: the per-cycle signature COUNT must be recomputed from the Board's 144th-day registration (do not hardcode 4,583 for a future cycle), and the statute's path is worded \"political party which does not qualify,\" not \"independent\" — independent status is supported by DCMR 3-1502.2(a) but is a characterization worth confirming with the Board. DC's requirement is the most severe presidential requirement of all 51 jurisdictions and is the subject of ongoing reform lobbying/constitutional criticism (no change to current law).","sos":["For the upcoming presidential cycle, please confirm the exact minimum number of valid signatures required for a non-qualified-party/independent presidential nominating petition under D.C. Code 1-1001.08(f) (1% of registered electors as of the 144th day), and the maximum number the Board will accept (2x).","Please confirm that a candidate running as an 'independent' (not affiliated with a qualified party) for President obtains ballot access via the same 1-1001.08(f) / DCMR 3-15 nominating-petition path used by non-qualified parties, and that 'independent' is the correct designation on the petition's first page under DCMR 3-1502.2(a)."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; non-resident circulators allowed if registered with the Board","note":"Candidate/nominating-petition circulator compensation is NOT addressed by DC law: § 1-1001.08 and DCMR Chapter 3-16 cover circulator qualifications, affidavits, and penalties but say nothing about paying circulators (per signature or at all), and DC's only pay-to-sign prohibition (§ 1-1001.14(b)(3)) is expressly limited to initiative/referendum/recall petitions, NOT candidate petitions. Residency is clearly NOT required: a non-resident may circulate if registered with the Board as a petition circulator (§ 1-1001.02(26)), so a national paid pool can legally work in DC.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition (presidential-elector petition under D.C. Code § 1-1001.08(f)), may the campaign compensate qualified petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and is paid circulation (hourly/salary) otherwise permitted under the DC Election Code or Board regulations?","citations":[{"url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.14","quote":"Any person who: (A) For any consideration, compensation, gratuity, reward or thing of value or promise thereof, signs or promises to sign or declines to sign, or promises not to sign any initiative, referendum, or recall petition; or (B) pays or offers or promises to pay, or gives or offers or promises to give any consideration, compensation, gratuity, reward, or thing of value to any person to induce the person to sign or not to sign, the person's signatures upon any initiative, referendum, or recall petition"},{"url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.02","quote":"The term \"qualified petition circulator\" means a person who is at least 17 years of age and who will be 18 years of age on or before the next general election and either: (A) A District resident; or (B) A resident of another jurisdiction who has registered with the Board as a petition circulator and consented to being subject to the subpoena power of the Board and the jurisdiction of the Superior Court of the District of Columbia for the enforcement of subpoenas without respect to the individual's place of residence."},{"url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.08","quote":"Only qualified petition circulators may circulate nominating petitions in support of candidates for elected office pursuant to this subchapter. The Board shall consider invalid the signatures on any petition sheet that was circulated by a person who, at the time of circulation, was not a qualified petition circulator."},{"url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.08","quote":"A political party which does not qualify under subsection (d) of this section may have the names of its candidates for President and Vice President of the United States printed on the general election ballot provided a petition nominating the appropriate number of candidates for presidential electors signed by at least 1 per centum of registered qualified electors of the District of Columbia, as shown by the records of the Board as of the 144th day before the date of the presidential election, is presented to the Board on or before the 90th day before the date of the presidential election."},{"url":"https://dcrules.elaws.us/dcmr/3-1602","quote":"The second page of the nominating petition form shall include a circulator's affidavit, providing space for the circulator of a nominating petition to record his or her name and address. By signing the affidavit, the circulator swears under oath or affirms that he or she: (a) Is a qualified petition circulator; (b) Personally circulated the petition sheet; (c) Personally witnessed the signing of each signature on the petition sheet"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.14","official":true,"dom":"code.dccouncil.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.02","official":true,"dom":"code.dccouncil.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.08","official":true,"dom":"code.dccouncil.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://dcrules.elaws.us/dcmr/3-1602","official":true,"dom":"dcrules.elaws.us"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://dcregs.dc.gov/Common/DCMR/RuleList.aspx?DownloadFile={438748BA-839D-4B97-A9B3-DA9225FB2BF0}","official":true,"dom":"dcregs.dc.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/1-1001.07","official":true,"dom":"code.dccouncil.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.dcboe.org/data,-maps,-forms","official":false,"dom":"dcboe.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"A non-major-party (independent or unqualified-party) presidential candidate must file a nominating petition signed by at least 1% of the District's registered qualified electors as shown by the Board's records as of the 144th day before the presidential election, under D.C. Code 1-1001.08(f). The exact count RECOMPUTES each cycle from the 144th-day registration total (for the 2024 cycle this equaled 4,583 valid signatures; do not rely on this fixed number for any other cycle). The Board accepts at most 2x the minimum for filing (DCMR 3-1503.2). Strictest reading: confirm the cycle-specific number with the Board and treat 1% as the governing rate.","note":"All 4 citations verified verbatim. The 1% rate is correct and current and directly grounded in statute 1-1001.08(f) and DCMR 1503.1; the 2x cap is grounded in 1503.2; the 4,583 figure for 2024 is corroborated by ballot-access.org. HOLD because (a) the operative signature COUNT is cycle-dependent and must be re-derived from the Board's 144th-day registration, so a fixed number is not a safe live value, and (b) the draft's framing that an 'independent' runs via 1-1001.08(f) is a legal characterization — the statute literally addresses 'a political party which does not qualify under subsection (d),' not 'independent' (DCMR 3-1502.2(a) supports the independent designation but the routing should be confirmed).","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The nominating petition (with supporting affidavits and each presidential elector's Declaration of Candidacy) must be filed in person at the Board's office no later than 5:00 p.m. on the 90th day before the presidential election (D.C. Code 1-1001.08(f); DCMR 3-1505.2; 5:00 p.m. cutoff per 1-1001.08(q)). For the November 5, 2024 general election this deadline was August 7, 2024.","note":"All 3 citations verified verbatim. Independently confirmed by date arithmetic: Aug 7, 2024 is exactly 90 days before Nov 5, 2024 (24 + 30 + 31 + 5 = 90). The 5:00 p.m. in-person requirement is grounded in DCMR 1505.2 and 1-1001.08(q). Current and correct; no interpretation needed.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 1% requirement is computed District-wide against all registered qualified electors of the District; there is no per-ward, per-precinct, or per-district geographic distribution requirement for the presidential elector petition. DC has no congressional districts or counties.","note":"Citation verified verbatim. Statute 1-1001.08(f) imposes a single District-wide 1% count with no geographic spread. The ward-based signature thresholds elsewhere in 1-1001.08 apply to Council/State Board of Education seats, NOT to presidential electors. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Only a qualified petition circulator may circulate; signatures on any sheet circulated by an unqualified circulator are invalid (D.C. Code 1-1001.08(b)(2)). Circulators must be at least 18 (DCMR 3-1504.1(c)). Residency is NOT required: non-resident circulators are permitted but must first complete and file, in person at the Board's office, a Non-Resident Petition Circulator Registration Form (swearing they are 18+, providing proof of residence, and consenting to the Board's subpoena power) before circulating (DCMR 3-1504).","note":"All 3 citations verified verbatim. Statute requires qualified circulators and invalidates signatures otherwise; DCMR 3-1504 expressly authorizes non-resident circulators subject to prior in-person registration and 18+ oath. Correct and current.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Each petition sheet must carry a circulator's affidavit made under penalty of perjury (NOT notarized) stating the circulator is qualified and has personally circulated the sheet, personally witnessed each signer sign, and inquired about each signer's voter status (D.C. Code 1-1001.08(b)(3)). Any sheet lacking a completed circulator's affidavit is not counted (DCMR 3-1505.4). Notarization is required only from a voter who submits a written request to disallow their own signature, not for the circulator's certification.","note":"Both citations verified verbatim. Statute specifies an affidavit 'made under penalty of perjury' (self-executing, no notary). DCMR 1505.4 confirms sheets without a completed circulator affidavit are not counted, and that the only notarized item is a voter's written request to disallow their own signature. Correct and current.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signed petition sheets must be filed with the Board in hard copy and in person (D.C. Code 1-1001.08(b)(3A); DCMR 3-1505.2). Only blank/unsigned petition forms may move electronically (Board to candidate; candidate to circulator; circulator to candidate). There is no remote-online or in-person-digitized signature system for the independent/non-qualified-party presidential petition; signed sheets are filed on paper.","note":"Both citations verified verbatim. Statute 1-1001.08(b)(3A) requires petition sheets be 'filed with the Board in hard copy,' permitting only electronic transmission of (blank) forms among Board/candidate/circulator; DCMR 1505.2 requires in-person filing. Conclusion (paper, in person) is directly grounded. The 'eSign device' aside is extra context but does not affect the grounded conclusion.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The District imposes no filing fee for presidential ballot access and offers no fee option in lieu of (or in addition to) the signature petition. Ballot access is obtained solely by the nominating petition meeting the 1% requirement (D.C. Code 1-1001.08(f); DCMR 3-1503.1).","note":"Both citations verified verbatim. This is a negative claim (no fee alternative exists). The statute and DCMR Chapter 3-15 establish the nominating petition as the sole ballot-access mechanism; no fee or fee-in-lieu provision appears anywhere in the reviewed primary sources. Consistent across all sources; correct and current.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Florida","sigs":"1% of FL registered voters (per last general election) — recomputed each cycle; exact 2024 count unverified","deadline":"County petitions due noon, July 15 of the presidential election year","risk":"Core path (1% petition, noon July 15, per-county submission, paper, no fee-in-lieu) is primary-source grounded and current; circulator eligibility is unverified (BLOCKED) and the precise signature count plus any petition-form attestation need office confirmation before relying.","sos":["For an independent (no-party-affiliation) candidate for President under Fla. Stat. 103.021(3), what is the exact number of valid petition signatures required for the current cycle (1% of registered voters as of the last preceding general election), and is there an official published figure?","Does the Division of Elections' prescribed presidential-elector petition form require any circulator signature, attestation, or notarization, or any circulator age/residency/voter-registration eligibility — or is each signature validated solely by the county supervisor's signature match against the voter registration system?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — per-signature ban is limited by definition to constitutional-amendment/initiative circulators; no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Florida's only per-signature pay prohibition (s. 104.186) applies solely to a \"petition circulator as defined in s. 97.021,\" and s. 97.021(28) defines that term exclusively as someone collecting signatures \"for the purpose of qualifying a proposed constitutional amendment for ballot placement\" — so it does NOT reach independent-presidential CANDIDATE petitions under s. 103.021(3); candidate-petition compensation is unaddressed (no statute authorizes per-signature pay, but s. 99.097(6) expressly contemplates persons \"paid to solicit signatures on a petition,\" and no circulator-residency requirement exists).","sosInquiry":"For an independent (no-party-affiliation) presidential candidate's nominating petition under Fla. Stat. s. 103.021(3), may the campaign lawfully compensate signature circulators on a per-signature basis, given that the per-signature prohibition in s. 104.186 is tied to the s. 97.021(28) definition of \"petition circulator,\" which is limited to constitutional-amendment petitions — and is there any circulator residency/registration requirement?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/104.186","quote":"104.186 Initiative petitions; violations.—A person who compensates a petition circulator as defined in s. 97.021 based on the number of petition forms gathered commits a felony of the third degree, punishable as provided in s. 775.082, s. 775.083, or s. 775.084. This section does not prohibit employment relationships that do not base payment on the number of signatures collected."},{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/97.021","quote":"(28) \"Petition circulator\" means an entity or individual who collects signatures for compensation for the purpose of qualifying a proposed constitutional amendment for ballot placement."},{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/103.021","quote":"(3) Candidates for President and Vice President with no party affiliation may have their names printed on the general election ballots if a petition is signed by 1 percent of the registered voters of this state, as shown by the compilation by the Department of State for the last preceding general election. A separate petition from each county for which signatures are solicited shall be submitted to the supervisor of elections of the respective county no later than noon on July 15 of each presidential election year."},{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/99.097","quote":"(6)(a) If any person is paid to solicit signatures on a petition, an undue burden oath may not subsequently be filed in lieu of paying the fee to have signatures verified for that petition."},{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/104.185","quote":"104.185 Petitions; knowingly signing more than once; signing another person's name or a fictitious name.—(1) A person who knowingly signs a petition or petitions for a candidate, a minor political party, or an issue more than one time commits a misdemeanor of the first degree, punishable as provided in s. 775.082 or s. 775.083."},{"url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/99.09651","quote":"(3) Signatures may be obtained from any registered voter in Florida regardless of party affiliation or district boundaries."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/104.186","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/97.021","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/103.021","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/99.097","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/104.185","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2023/99.09651","official":true,"dom":"flsenate.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://dos.fl.gov/elections/for-voters/voter-registration/voter-information-as-a-public-record/","official":true,"dom":"dos.fl.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://dos.fl.gov/elections/data-statistics/voter-registration-statistics/voter-extract-request/","official":true,"dom":"dos.fl.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://fldoswebuat-sandbox.azurewebsites.net/elections/data-statistics/voter-registration-statistics/voter-extract-disk-request/","official":false,"dom":"fldoswebuat-sandbox.azurewebsites.net"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"1% of the state's registered voters as shown by the Department of State's compilation for the last preceding general election (Fla. Stat. 103.021(3)); recomputed each cycle. Do NOT rely on the embedded ~145,000 figure — exact 2024 count is not primary-source verified.","note":"Statute quote verbatim-confirmed on leg.state.fl.us 103.021(3); Ballotpedia 1% quote also verbatim. The 1% formula is correct and current. HOLD only because the value bundles an unverified '~145,000' estimate that should not be treated as an authoritative count; rely on the formula, not the number. Same 1% basis verified for the unaffiliated minor party under 103.021(4)(b).","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"County petitions must be submitted to each county supervisor of elections no later than noon on July 15 of the presidential election year; supervisor certifies registered-voter count on or before the date of the primary election and forwards to the Department of State (Fla. Stat. 103.021(3)).","note":"Verbatim-confirmed in 103.021(3): 'no later than noon on July 15 of each presidential election year' and 'on or before the date of the primary election, shall certify.' Ballotpedia quote (omits 'noon', says 'supervisors') also present verbatim; statute controls and supports the stricter noon July 15. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No geographic distribution quota. The 1% requirement is statewide; signatures are merely organized and submitted as a separate petition per county to that county's supervisor (administrative submission rule, not a per-county/per-district minimum) (Fla. Stat. 103.021(3)).","note":"Verbatim 'separate petition from each county ... submitted to the supervisor of elections of the respective county' confirmed. Statute imposes only a statewide 1% and a per-county submission mechanic; no minimum-per-county quota exists. Correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"BLOCKED","val":"none","note":"Value is 'UNKNOWN' with ZERO citations — nothing to ground, and the draft itself concedes the prescribed petition form's terms could not be confirmed from a primary source. Unverifiable as drafted -> BLOCKED. While 103.021/99.097 impose no statutory circulator age/residency/voter requirement and verification is by supervisor signature-match, the prescribed-form requirements are not confirmed. Sent to office inquiry.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Each petition signature is verified by the county supervisor by comparing it against the signer's signature in the voter registration system (Fla. Stat. 99.097(3)); signatures count only if on the petition form prescribed by the Division. Statute prescribes no notarization or circulator affidavit for petition signatures, BUT confirm the prescribed form imposes no attestation. The separate candidate qualifying OATH is distinct and may be notarized.","note":"Signature-match verification quote and 'petition form prescribed by the division' quote both verbatim-confirmed in 99.097. The affirmative facts are grounded; however, 'no notarization required' is an absence-of-provision inference that turns on the content of the Division-prescribed form (not retrievable here) — same open question that BLOCKED circulatorEligibility. HOLD to the strict reading and confirm via office inquiry.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be collected on the Division of Elections' prescribed paper petition form and submitted county-by-county to each supervisor for verification against the voter file; no state digital/remote-online signature-gathering system covers an independent presidential petition.","note":"'petition form prescribed by the division' (99.097) and per-county paper-submission mechanics (103.021(3)) verbatim-confirmed. 'paper' is the conservative/strict operating assumption and is well supported; the no-digital-path claim is an absence inference but does not loosen the requirement, so AUTO-LIVE is safe (over-compliance, no ballot-access risk).","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No filing-fee/fee-in-lieu alternative to the signature petition. The candidate must prepay the supervisor 10 cents per signature checked or the actual cost, whichever is less (Fla. Stat. 99.097(4)(a)); an indigent waiver to verify at no charge is available on written certification of undue burden (99.097(4)(b)).","note":"10-cents quote verbatim in 99.097(4)(a); 99.097(4)(b) indigent-waiver provision independently confirmed ('entitled to have the signatures verified at no charge'). 103.021(3) payment cross-reference ('cost of checking the petitions as prescribed in s. 99.097') is present verbatim — earlier match-miss was only a markdown hyperlink artifact around 's. 99.097'. No fee-in-lieu path is the correct strict reading. Sub-cites accurate.","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Georgia","sigs":"GA: do NOT rely on 7,500 — post-West v. Wittenstein strict reading is per-elector petitions (16 x 7,500 = ~120,000)","deadline":"GA: nomination petition by 12:00 Noon 2nd Tue in July; notice of candidacy 4th Mon June to following Fri (recompute each cycle)","risk":"Highest risk is signaturesRequired: the GA Supreme Court (West v. Wittenstein, unanimous, 9/25/2024) rejected the single-7,500-petition model and held each presidential-elector candidate must file his/her own nomination petition, implying ~120,000 valid signatures under the strictest reading; treating 7,500 as the operative total would risk ballot access. The cited ballot-access source predates the decision and overstated certainty.","sos":["For an independent/political-body presidential candidate in 2028, after West v. Wittenstein (S25A0178), how many nomination petitions and total valid signatures does the SOS require: one statewide petition of 7,500, or a separate petition in the name of each of Georgia's 16 presidential-elector candidates (i.e. 16 x 7,500)?","Confirm the precise filing mechanics post-West v. Wittenstein: must each presidential-elector candidate file a nomination petition under his/her own name, and may the candidates be listed together on one petition slate under O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(c), or are separate per-elector petitions required?","What is the exact qualifying fee (or 'reasonable fee') the Secretary of State will fix for the office of presidential elector / President for the upcoming cycle, and is it charged per elector or per presidential ticket?","Confirm whether the court-imposed 7,500 per-petition standard from Green Party of Georgia v. Kemp still controls the per-petition number, or whether the un-repealed 1% statute (O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(b)) is applied to any petition the SOS now requires."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Georgia's candidate/independent-presidential nomination-petition statute (O.C.G.A. § 21-2-170) regulates petition form, the 180-day circulation window, and the circulator's notarized affidavit, but is SILENT on compensation — it neither permits nor prohibits paying circulators per signature, so candidate-petition circulator pay is genuinely unaddressed (Georgia also has no statewide initiative process, so there is no pay-per-signature law to carry over). The statute requires the circulator to swear to a residence address but does NOT explicitly require the circulator to be a Georgia resident or registered voter.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under O.C.G.A. § 21-2-170, may the campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and must a circulator be a Georgia resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ga/title-21-elections/ga-code-sect-21-2-170/","quote":"Each sheet shall bear on the bottom or back thereof the affidavit of the circulator of such sheet, which affidavit must be subscribed and sworn to by such circulator before a notary public and shall set forth: (1) His or her residence address, giving municipality with street and number, if any; (2) That each signer manually signed his or her own name with full knowledge of the contents of the nomination petition; (3) That each signature on such sheet was signed within 180 days of the last day on which such petition may be filed; and (4) That, to the best of the affiant's knowledge and belief, the signers are registered electors of the state qualified to sign the petition, that their respective residences are correctly stated in the petition, and that they all reside in the county or municipality named in the affidavit."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ga/title-21-elections/ga-code-sect-21-2-170/","quote":"No notary public may sign the petition as an elector or serve as a circulator of any petition which he or she notarized. Any and all sheets of a petition that have the circulator's affidavit notarized by a notary public who also served as a circulator of one or more sheets of the petition or who signed one of the sheets of the petition as an elector shall be disqualified and rejected."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ga/title-21-elections/ga-code-sect-21-2-170/","quote":"No nomination petition shall be circulated prior to 180 days before the last day on which such petition may be filed, and no signature shall be counted unless it was signed within 180 days of the last day for filing the same."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Georgia","quote":"Each sheet must also contain, either on the bottom or the back, an affidavit of the circulator of the sheet signed before a notary public. This affidavit must state the following: the residence address of the circulator ... No notary public is allowed to sign a petition or act as the circulator of a petition that he or she notarized."},{"url":"https://www.ncsl.org/elections-and-campaigns/initiative-and-referendum-processes/circulators-of-initiatives","quote":"Of the 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process, 16 states allow campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected, while 10 states prohibit campaigns from paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sos.ga.gov/page/order-voter-registration-lists-and-files","official":true,"dom":"sos.ga.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ga/title-21-elections/ga-code-sect-21-2-170/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Georgia","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.ncsl.org/elections-and-campaigns/initiative-and-referendum-processes/circulators-of-initiatives","official":false,"dom":"ncsl.org"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://georgiasecretaryofstate.net/products/statewide-voter-list","official":false,"dom":"georgiasecretaryofstate.net"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: assume a separate nomination petition in the name of EACH of Georgia's 16 presidential-elector candidates, each requiring 7,500 valid signatures = up to ~120,000 valid signatures total. Do NOT plan on a single 7,500-signature statewide petition. (Per-petition number 7,500 derives from Green Party of Georgia v. Kemp; the underlying statute O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(b) still nominally states 1%. West v. Wittenstein, Ga. S. Ct. S25A0178, 9/25/2024, unanimously held each elector-candidate is a 'candidate' who must file his/her own petition.) Recompute and re-verify with the SOS each cycle.","note":"All four citations ground verbatim. But the draft value ('7,500' as the operative statewide total) is NO LONGER safe. The cited ballot-access.org 9/24 article only reported that the GA Supreme Court HEARD the case and 'oral argument went badly' — it did not report a holding, yet the draft asserted the elector-petition rule as settled. On 9/25/2024 the court ruled UNANIMOUSLY (West v. Wittenstein, affirming an ALJ and two Fulton County Superior Court judges) that West and De la Cruz were disqualified because their 16 presidential electors did not each file a separate petition; the court expressly rejected the argument that the 7,500 standard caps the requirement, and the parties/court acknowledged the strict reading implies ~120,000 signatures (16 x 7,500). Strictest defensible posture for an independent presidential run = per-elector petitions. Interpretation-dependent (court invited legislative clarification; 1% statute un-repealed).","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Nomination petition (O.C.G.A. 21-2-132(e)): file no earlier than 9:00 A.M. on the fourth Monday in June and no later than 12:00 Noon on the second Tuesday in July immediately prior to the general election. Notice of candidacy for President/VP electors (O.C.G.A. 21-2-132(d)(1)): file between 9:00 A.M. on the fourth Monday in June and 12:00 Noon on the Friday following the fourth Monday in June. DATES RECOMPUTE EACH CYCLE.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim against O.C.G.A. 21-2-132 (FindLaw, current as of 3/28/2024). Subsection (e) sets the petition window (fourth Mon June to 12:00 Noon second Tue July); (d)(1) sets the notice-of-candidacy window (fourth Mon June to 12:00 Noon Friday after fourth Mon June). Mechanical date rule, non-interpretive. The 2024 instance (July 9) is a correct illustration but is cycle-specific; rely on the statutory rule, not the hardcoded date.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No geographic distribution requirement: no per-congressional-district or per-county signature minimums. Signatures are a statewide total. Note the sheet-sorting rule (O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(d)): signers resident in different counties/municipalities must sign different sheets — an affidavit/sorting requirement, not a per-area minimum. SEPARATELY note (cross-ref signaturesRequired): post-West v. Wittenstein the petition burden is multiplied per presidential elector, which is a structural, not geographic, multiplier.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim against 21-2-170(b) and (d). It is accurate that Georgia imposes no congressional-district or county distribution minimum on the nomination petition; the only county-linked rule is the different-sheets-per-county sorting/affidavit requirement. The per-elector multiplication identified in West v. Wittenstein is captured under signaturesRequired and is not a 'distribution' requirement, so this field's value stands.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: The petition must be circulated/filed on behalf of, and in the name of, EACH presidential-elector candidate (not the presidential candidate personally) — West v. Wittenstein (Ga. S. Ct. S25A0178, decided 9/25/2024, unanimous) held a presidential candidate cannot petition for himself; the elector-candidates are the 'candidates' who must petition. Statute (21-2-170(d)) requires the circulator's sworn residence address (municipality, street, number) on each sheet; no explicit minimum-age or in-state-voter requirement is imposed on the circulator, but signers must be registered, eligible Georgia electors. A notary who served as a circulator of, or signed as an elector on, any sheet disqualifies those sheets. Confirm circulation/filing mechanics with the SOS.","note":"Statutory quotes (circulator affidavit, signer eligibility) ground verbatim against 21-2-170. The West v. Wittenstein quote grounds verbatim against the cited ballot-access.org article — BUT that article only reported a HEARING, not a decision, and was titled 'Likely to Rule.' The draft stated the elector-petition holding as settled, which the cited source did not support. Independent verification (Georgia Recorder, 9/26/2024; corroborated by Washington Times / FOX 5) confirms the court DID rule unanimously on 9/25/2024, affirming an ALJ and two Fulton Superior Court judges, that each elector-candidate must file in his/her own name. So the draft's conclusion is now correct but for the wrong/incomplete evidentiary reason. Holding turns on the statutory meaning of 'candidate' — interpretation-dependent; the court invited legislative clarification.","conf":0.88,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator affidavit required on each sheet (bottom or back), subscribed and sworn before a notary public, attesting: circulator's residence address; that each signer manually signed his/her own name with full knowledge of contents; that each signature was signed within 180 days of the last filing day; and that, to the affiant's knowledge, signers are registered Georgia electors residing in the county/municipality named. No notary may sign as an elector or serve as circulator of any sheet he/she notarized — doing so disqualifies and rejects those sheets (O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(d)).","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim against 21-2-170(d). The draft's added detail (180-day window, county residence attestation) is independently supported by the same subsection's (d)(2)-(4) and (e). The notary-disqualification clause is quoted verbatim. Accurate and non-interpretive.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper (wet-ink). SOS-prescribed petition form is mandatory; each signer must manually sign and print his/her name, and each sheet must carry a notarized circulator affidavit. No remote-online/digitized signature capture is available for a Georgia independent/minor-party presidential nomination petition; collect on paper and file the bound sheets with the Secretary of State (O.C.G.A. 21-2-170(a),(d)).","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim against 21-2-170(a) and (d)(2). 'No forms other than the ones so prescribed shall be used,' combined with 'manually signed his or her own name' and the notarized-affidavit requirement, supports paper/wet-ink. No statutory authorization for electronic capture exists in the cited provisions. Non-interpretive.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: Assume a qualifying fee IS owed at the time the notice of candidacy is filed, IN ADDITION TO (not in lieu of) the nomination-petition signatures. The SOS fixes the fee (3% of annual salary if salaried; if not salaried, a 'reasonable fee' not exceeding 3% of income) under O.C.G.A. 21-2-131(a)(2); the exact dollar amount for the presidential office is NOT confirmed from a primary source — treat as owed and confirm with the SOS. A pauper's affidavit may substitute for the FEE only, and only if accompanied by a qualifying petition signed by one-fourth of 1% of statewide registered voters (O.C.G.A. 21-2-132(g)-(h)). The fee/pauper route does NOT replace the nomination-petition signature requirement.","note":"All three quotes ground verbatim (21-2-131(a)(2); 21-2-132(g); 21-2-132(h)(1)). The draft's structural conclusion (fee is additional; pauper's affidavit replaces only the fee and itself requires a 1/4-of-1% qualifying petition) is correct on the statute. Held conservative because: (1) the draft itself flags the exact 2024 fee amount as UNKNOWN — an unconfirmed value should not auto-go-live; (2) whether/how the fee applies to the office of presidential elector vs the presidential ticket, and its interaction with the per-elector petition structure from West v. Wittenstein, is interpretation-dependent. Confirm amount and applicability with the SOS.","conf":0.85,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Hawaii","sigs":"5,223 sigs (1% of 522,236 — 2024 vote); recomputes each cycle","deadline":"Aug 9, 2028, 4:30pm (90th day before Nov 7, 2028 general)","risk":"Core numbers (sigs, deadline, no-distribution, fee, paper) are fully grounded and AUTO-LIVE; the two negative findings on circulators and witness/notary are statutory-silence inferences subject to the chief election officer's prescribed petition form (HRS 11-113(c)(2)(B) \"other information as determined by the chief election officer\"), so they are held pending confirmation of the actual form.","sos":["For the HRS 11-113(c)(2) presidential petition: does the chief-election-officer-prescribed petition form impose any circulator eligibility requirement (age, Hawaii residency, or voter-registration status) on the person who collects signatures?","For the HRS 11-113(c)(2) presidential petition: does the prescribed petition form or its instructions require any per-page circulator affidavit, witness signature, or notarization on the petition itself (separate from the pre-issuance notarized Declaration of Intent and the sworn application filed at submission)?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; HRS silent on paying circulators","note":"Hawaii's election code does NOT address compensation of nominating-petition circulators. The controlling statute for an independent/unqualified-party presidential petition, HRS §11-113, prescribes the petition form, the 1%-of-last-presidential-vote signature threshold, and required signer data, but says nothing about whether circulators may be paid per signature or at all. The election-fraud statute (HRS §19-3) prohibits bribing electors/voters, not paying petition circulators. Hawaii's only pay-per-signature law context is the initiative/referendum debate, which does not apply (Hawaii has no statewide initiative process and is not among the 10 states banning per-signature initiative pay). Because candidate-petition circulator compensation is unaddressed, treat per-signature pay as not clearly authorized.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/unqualified-party presidential nominating petition under HRS §11-113, does Hawaii law permit compensating signature gatherers on a per-signature basis, and are there any residency or registration requirements for the persons who collect/witness those signatures?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/Vol01_Ch0001-0042F/HRS0011/HRS_0011-0113.htm","quote":"In the case of candidates of parties or groups not qualified to place candidates on the primary or general election ballots, the person desiring to place the names on the general election ballot shall file with the chief election officer ... A petition that shall be upon the form prescribed and provided by the chief election officer containing the signatures of currently registered voters which constitute not less than one per cent of the votes cast in the State at the last presidential election."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Hawaii","quote":"The Hawaii Revised Statutes do not address requirements for petition circulators. Specifically, there are no residency requirements for circulators."},{"url":"https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/Vol01_Ch0001-0042F/HRS0019/HRS_0019-0003.htm","quote":"Every person who, directly or indirectly, personally or through another, gives, procures, or lends, or agrees or offers to give, procure, or lend, ... any money or office or place of employment or valuable consideration to or for any elector, person for an elector, person in order to induce any elector to vote or refrain from voting"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","quote":"Pay-per-signature is a method of compensating signature gatherers, also known as circulators, who collect signatures for ballot initiatives and veto referendums. ... There are 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process. Sixteen (16) of those states allowed campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. Ten (10) of those states prohibited campaigns from paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/Vol01_Ch0001-0042F/HRS0011/HRS_0011-0113.htm","official":true,"dom":"capitol.hawaii.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/Vol01_Ch0001-0042F/HRS0019/HRS_0019-0003.htm","official":true,"dom":"capitol.hawaii.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/Vol01_Ch0001-0042F/HRS0011/HRS_0011-0097.htm","official":true,"dom":"capitol.hawaii.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.mauicounty.gov/DocumentCenter/View/136272/Affidavit-on-Application-for-Voter-Registration-Data-2021","official":true,"dom":"mauicounty.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.honolulu.gov/liq/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/12/LIQ-LIC-139_Affidavit_on_Application_for_Statewide_Voter_Registration_Data_FILLABLE.pdf","official":true,"dom":"honolulu.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.honolulu.gov/elections/reports-certificates/","official":true,"dom":"honolulu.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Hawaii","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,223 signatures of currently registered Hawaii voters (1% of the 522,236 votes cast in the 2024 presidential election). Formula-based: not less than 1% of votes cast at the last presidential election; recomputes each cycle.","note":"Grounded: OoE page states verbatim '5,223 signatures of currently registered voters' and 'In the 2024 presidential election 522,236 votes were cast'; HRS 11-113(c)(2)(B) states 'not less than one per cent of the votes cast in the State at the last presidential election.' Independently re-derived: 1% of 522,236 = 5,222.36, rounded up to 5,223 — matches OoE. Current and correct for an independent/unqualified-group presidential petition.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"4:30 p.m. on the 90th day prior to the general election (HRS 11-113(c)(2)); for the 2028 cycle, August 9, 2028, 4:30 pm per the Office of Elections.","note":"Grounded: HRS verbatim 'not later than 4:30 p.m. on the ninetieth day prior to the general election'; OoE page verbatim 'deadline to file a presidential petition is August 9, 2028, 4:30 pm.' Independently verified: 2028 general election is Tue Nov 7, 2028; 90 days prior = Wed Aug 9, 2028 — matches the OoE date exactly. Formula recomputes each cycle.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Single statewide total (1% of statewide presidential votes); HRS 11-113 imposes no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement.","note":"Grounded: HRS 11-113(c)(2)(B) requires only 'signatures... which constitute not less than one per cent of the votes cast in the State' — full statutory text contains no district/county language. Ballotpedia confirms a single statewide 1% threshold. Correct negative finding.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Do not rely on 'no circulator requirements' as a planning assumption. Strictest defensible posture: signers must be currently registered Hawaii voters (confirmed by statute/OoE); for circulators, obtain and inspect the chief-election-officer-prescribed petition form before assuming no age/residency/voter-status requirement, since HRS 11-113(c)(2)(B) authorizes the CEO to add 'other information as determined.'","note":"Grounded: Ballotpedia (state/county petitions page) verbatim 'Hawaii Revised Statutes do not address requirements for petition circulators. Specifically, there are no residency requirements for circulators'; OoE confirms signers must be registered HI voters. Adversarial: the cited Ballotpedia text addresses party-formation/fee-waiver petitions generally, not specifically the 11-113 presidential petition, and 11-113(c)(2)(B) expressly lets the CEO prescribe additional form content. Statutory silence on circulators does not foreclose a form-level requirement; retrieval cannot settle this without the actual prescribed form. Held to avoid risking ballot access.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Confirmed and required: a pre-issuance notarized Declaration of Intent from each prospective candidate, plus a sworn application filed at submission. Strictest posture on the petition itself: the statute's enumerated petition contents include no per-page witness/notary, but verify the CEO-prescribed petition form for any circulator affidavit/witness attestation before assuming none.","note":"Grounded: HRS verbatim requires 'a notarized statement from each prospective candidate of that prospective candidate's intent... Prior to being issued the petition form' and a 'sworn application'; OoE confirms the notarized Declaration of Intent. The candidate-side notarization claim is fully correct. Adversarial: the negative claim that the petition itself bears no witness/notary rests on the statute's enumerated contents (signatures, names, statement of support, address, date) — but 11-113(c)(2)(B) permits CEO-added form content, so the petition-level negative is not fully settleable by retrieval. Held pending inspection of the prescribed form.","conf":0.62,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Physical petition form prescribed and provided by the chief election officer, issued only after the notarized Declaration(s) of Intent and application are submitted. No remote_online or in_person_digitized path exists for the independent presidential petition.","note":"Grounded: HRS verbatim 'A petition that shall be upon the form prescribed and provided by the chief election officer'; OoE verbatim 'Upon receipt of the completed application form and notarized statements of intent, the Office of Elections will issue the petition.' No statutory or OoE basis for any electronic/online signature collection for this path. Correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee for the HRS 11-113 presidential petition and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for president. The HRS ch. 12 filing-fee / petition-in-lieu scheme applies to state/county nomination-paper candidates, not to the presidential petition.","note":"Grounded: OoE 'To request a presidential petition, submit the following' lists only the application and notarized Declaration — no fee; HRS 11-113 contains no fee provision. Ballotpedia's affidavit/petition-in-lieu-of-fee quote is on the state/county political-candidates page and is expressly tied to 'the district in which the candidate is seeking election' (HRS ch. 12), confirming it does not apply to president. Correct distinction; correct negative finding.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Idaho","sigs":"1,000 sigs statewide (flat statutory #, not %) — no distribution requirement","deadline":"Declaration + petition due Aug 1; sigs verified & SoS certifies by Sep 1","risk":"Core numbers (1,000 sigs, Aug 1 deadline, no distribution, paper wet-ink, no fee) are statutorily grounded and AUTO-LIVE; the one open question is which 34-1807 circulator rules (paid-circulator badge/disclosure, 18+) legally attach to the presidential petition vs. only its non-resident carve-out — held conservatively, confirm with SoS.","sos":["For an independent presidential/VP petition under I.C. 34-708A (verified per 34-1807 on the recall-petition form), do the paid-circulator disclosure and 'paid petition circulator' badge requirements of 34-1807(2), and the circulator 18-years-or-older requirement, apply to this petition — given that 34-708A waives only the Idaho-residency requirement for circulators?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"Paid circulation permitted with disclosure; per-signature pay unaddressed for candidate petitions; Idaho residency required for all circulators","note":"Idaho's independent-candidate petition statute (Idaho Code 34-708, which covers \"federal\" office and is the path for an independent presidential candidate, 1,000 qualified-elector signatures) expressly directs that signatures \"shall be verified in the manner prescribed in section 34-1807\" — the same statute that governs and permits PAID signature gatherers (subject to disclosure/badge) and that mandates circulator residency. So paid circulation is permitted and Idaho residency is required, but neither 34-708 nor 34-1807 addresses PER-SIGNATURE compensation specifically for candidate petitions — it is neither authorized nor prohibited in the text, so it is unaddressed and a CONSERVATIVE-HOLD is warranted. (Note: 34-1807's own text refers to \"initiative or referendum\" petitions, so the extent to which its paid-circulator disclosure provisions transfer to candidate petitions is itself an interpretation question to confirm with the SoS.)","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition under Idaho Code 34-708 (which directs verification \"in the manner prescribed in section 34-1807\"), (a) may a campaign compensate petition circulators on a PER-SIGNATURE basis, or only by hourly/salary; (b) do the paid-circulator disclosure, badge, and paid-circulator affidavit requirements of 34-1807(2) apply to candidate petitions; and (c) must every circulator be an Idaho resident at least 18 years old, such that a non-resident's signature sheets would be void?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-708/","quote":"Any person who desires to offer himself as an independent candidate for federal, state, district, or county office may do so by complying strictly with the provisions of this section. ... Each such declaration must be accompanied by a petition containing the following number of signatures of qualified electors: (a) One thousand (1,000) for any statewide office;"},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-708/","quote":"Signatures on the petitions required in this section shall be verified in the manner prescribed in section 34-1807, Idaho Code, on a form similar to that used for recall petitions under chapter 17, title 34, Idaho Code, as prescribed by the secretary of state."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-1807/","quote":"(1) Any person who circulates any petition for an initiative or referendum shall be a resident of the state of Idaho and at least eighteen (18) years of age."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-1807/","quote":"(2)(a) Any person who accepts payment to circulate a petition for an initiative or referendum shall, prior to accepting a signature: (i) Verbally notify any potential signatory that such person is accepting payment to gather signatures and provide the name of the person or entity providing payment to such person"},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-1807/","quote":"(6) Any petition on which signatures are obtained by a person not a resident of the state of Idaho and at least eighteen (18) years of age shall be void. The definition of resident in section 34-107, Idaho Code, shall apply to the circulators of initiative and referendum petitions."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Idaho","quote":"A petition circulator must be at least 18 years old and a resident of Idaho. The circulator must verify the signatures contained within the petition by affidavit, which must be signed by a notary public. Any petition upon which signatures are obtained from non-eligible individuals will be void."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sos.idaho.gov/public-records-requests/","official":true,"dom":"sos.idaho.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://forms.sos.idaho.gov/voter-registration-request-form/","official":true,"dom":"forms.sos.idaho.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-708/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/id/title-34-elections/id-st-sect-34-1807/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Idaho","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 signatures of qualified electors — a flat statewide number fixed by I.C. 34-708A(1), not a percentage formula. One petition with 1,000 signatures covers both president and vice president (treated as one office). Does not recompute per cycle.","note":"All three quotes verified verbatim. I.C. 34-708A(1): 'a petition signed by one thousand (1,000) qualified electors'; 34-708A(2): president/VP are 'one (1) office, and only one (1) such petition need be filed.' Independently corroborated by I.C. 34-708(2)(a) ('One thousand (1,000) for any statewide office') and Ballotpedia ('At least 1,000 qualified voters'). Current as of Jan 1, 2024. No distribution/percentage element. Correct and unambiguous.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Declaration of candidacy with attached 1,000-signature petition must be filed with the Secretary of State no later than August 1 of the election year (I.C. 34-708A(1)). Signatures verified no later than September 1, and SoS certifies candidate qualifications no later than September 1 (I.C. 34-708A(3)). Date is fixed in statute, not recomputed per cycle.","note":"Verbatim: 'must file declarations of candidacy as independent candidates no later than August 1' and 'Signatures on the petitions...shall be verified no later than September 1...The secretary of state shall certify candidate qualifications no later than September 1.' Ballotpedia agrees ('on or before August 1'). The Aug 1 filing date is the controlling, candidate-facing deadline; the two Sep 1 dates are administrative (verification + certification). Correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 1,000 signatures are a single statewide total with no geographic distribution requirement (no per-congressional-district or per-county minimums).","note":"I.C. 34-708A(1) requires only 'a petition signed by one thousand (1,000) qualified electors' with no distribution language; 34-708 (statewide office) likewise sets a flat 1,000 with no distribution. The county-clerk certificate in 34-1807(4) references 'Legislative District Number' only as a verification/sorting mechanic — it is not a per-district quota. Adversarial check found no distribution requirement in either statute. Correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"For the independent presidential petition, circulators are NOT required to be Idaho residents (explicit carve-out, I.C. 34-708A(3)). STRICTEST POSTURE pending SoS confirmation: comply with the full 34-1807 circulator regime EXCEPT residency — i.e., assume circulators must be at least 18 (the incorporated affidavit form recites 'a resident of the State of Idaho and at least eighteen (18) years of age', residency waived but 18+ assumed to remain), and assume paid circulators must give the 34-1807(2) verbal/printed payment disclosure AND wear a 'paid petition circulator' badge. Signers must each be a qualified elector of Idaho and a resident of the county shown on the sheet.","note":"Citations grounded verbatim. Adversarial finding: 34-1807's circulator-eligibility provisions are textually scoped to petitions 'for an initiative or referendum' — subsection (1) (18+/residency) and subsection (2) (paid-circulator disclosure + badge) both open with that phrase, and the void clauses (6),(8) reference 'initiative and referendum petitions.' 34-708A incorporates only the verification 'manner' and the affidavit 'form' (and explicitly waives residency). So whether the 18+ requirement and the paid-circulator badge/disclosure legally attach to a PRESIDENTIAL petition is a genuine interpretive question retrieval cannot settle. The draft asserts they do; that is plausible (the affidavit form itself recites 18+) but not certain for the badge/disclosure, which live outside the form. Held conservatively: comply with all of it (over-comply, zero ballot-access risk) and confirm with SoS.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator affidavit required on each signature sheet. The verification form incorporated by I.C. 34-708A(3) (the 34-1807(3) recall-petition form) contains a sworn circulator affidavit 'Subscribed and sworn to before me...Notary Public' with a notary seal block. In addition, the county clerk examines the sheets and attaches a certificate to the SoS certifying the signers are qualified electors (34-1807(4)). Both notarized circulator certification and county-clerk verification apply.","note":"All quotes verified verbatim. The notary requirement flows directly from the affidavit FORM, which 34-708A(3) expressly incorporates ('on a form similar to that used for recall petitions...as prescribed by the secretary of state'), so the notarization is part of the incorporated form, not the initiative/referendum-only operative provisions. County-clerk examination (34-1807(4)) is part of the incorporated verification 'manner.' This is the stricter, ballot-access-safe reading; any residual ambiguity only adds verification rigor and does not risk the ballot line. Correct.","conf":0.85,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper — wet-ink signatures only. I.C. 34-1807(7): 'Any signature that is not a physical signature, including an electronic signature, is void.' No Idaho digital/remote/online petition system exists for an independent presidential petition; the prescribed recall-style paper form with notarized circulator affidavits and county-clerk verification is the only mechanism. No remote_online or in_person_digitized capture available.","note":"34-1807(7) verified verbatim. Notably, subsection (7) is NOT textually limited to 'initiative or referendum' (unlike subs 1, 2, 6, 8), and 34-708A verifies 'in the manner prescribed in section 34-1807,' so the wet-ink void applies. Even on the narrowest reading, paper/wet-ink is the strict, ballot-access-safe floor and there is no online alternative for this path. Over-complying with paper carries zero risk. Correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for the independent presidential/VP path. The route under I.C. 34-708A is entirely petition-based (declaration + 1,000-signature petition); the statute specifies no fee, and 34-705 (where declarations are filed with the SoS) prescribes no fee for this filing.","note":"Both quotes verified verbatim. 34-708A specifies no fee; 34-705 ('All candidates for district, state and federal offices shall file their declarations of candidacy with the secretary of state') prescribes no fee. This is an inference from statutory silence (proving a negative), but the petition path is the exclusive mechanism and no fee or fee-in-lieu option appears anywhere in 34-708A/34-708/34-705, consistent with Ballotpedia. The operationally safe posture is identical either way: complete the petition. Correct; minor residual uncertainty reflected in confidence.","conf":0.8,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Illinois","sigs":"25,000 valid sigs (1% of last statewide vote or 25,000, whichever is less; 25,000 binds — collect a large cushion)","deadline":"~Late June of election year: 134 days before the general (2024 = June 24); SBE filing window 141-134 days out","risk":"All 7 fields citation-grounded verbatim; 6 AUTO-LIVE, 1 CONSERVATIVE-HOLD (feeAlternative — cited sources do not affirmatively state \"no fee,\" so the absence-of-fee claim is unproven by retrieval even though IL has no known fee for this route).","sos":["For an independent (or new-party) candidate for President filing nomination papers with the State Board under 10 ILCS 5/10-3/10-4/10-6, is there ANY filing fee, filing deposit, bond, or fee-in-lieu-of-signatures, and is a Statement of Economic Interests required for the presidential (federal) office? Please confirm there is no monetary filing requirement for this route."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Illinois's independent/nomination-petition statute (10 ILCS 5/10-4, Article 10) and the official Illinois Candidate's Guide are SILENT on compensating petition circulators — there is no candidate-petition rule permitting or prohibiting per-signature pay, hourly pay, or paid circulation at all, so circulator compensation is UNADDRESSED for candidate petitions. The frequently cited 'Illinois permits pay-per-signature' answer comes from the INITIATIVE/referendum framework (Ballotpedia's ballot-initiative pay-per-signature page, citing 5 ILCS 20 and 10 ILCS 5/28) and does NOT govern candidate petitions, so it cannot be relied on; circulators need not be Illinois residents/registered voters (only US citizen, 18+), so a national paid pool could lawfully circulate.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT candidate's nominating petition for President under 10 ILCS 5 Article 10, may a campaign compensate petition circulators on a PER-SIGNATURE basis, and if not, are hourly/salary/bonus compensation arrangements for paid circulators permitted?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/il/chapter-10-elections/il-st-sect-10-5-10-4/","quote":"At the bottom of each sheet of such petition shall be added a circulator's statement, signed by a person 18 years of age or older who is a citizen of the United States; stating the street address or rural route number ... certifying that the signatures on that sheet of the petition were signed in his or her presence; certifying that the signatures are genuine ... Such statement shall be sworn to before some officer authorized to administer oaths in this State."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Illinois","quote":"Petition circulators must be U.S. citizens and at least 18 years old. An individual may not circulate petitions for more than one political party, established or new, or for more than one independent candidate. ... The circulator must personally witness the signing of all signatures and sign the circulator's statement on the petition attesting to that."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","quote":"Pay-per-signature is a method of compensating signature gatherers, also known as circulators, who collect signatures for ballot initiatives and veto referendums. ... There are 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process. Sixteen (16) of those states allowed campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.elections.il.gov/VotingAndRegistrationSystems/ComputerizedVoterData.aspx","official":true,"dom":"elections.il.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/il/chapter-10-elections/il-st-sect-10-5-10-4/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Illinois","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/il/chapter-10-elections/il-st-sect-10-5-1a-25/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1% of the number of voters who voted in the next preceding statewide general election OR 25,000 qualified Illinois voters, whichever is less. Recomputes per cycle; because 1% of statewide turnout (~60,000 in 2024 based on ~6M turnout) vastly exceeds 25,000, the 25,000 ceiling is the binding figure and has controlled every presidential cycle for decades. Practical requirement: 25,000 valid signatures of qualified Illinois voters — collect a substantial cushion above 25,000 to survive invalidation/challenge.","note":"FindLaw 10-3 and NASS quotes verify verbatim (NASS via PDF text extract, OCR line breaks only). Re-derived: IL 2020/2022 statewide turnout is several million, so 1% is far above 25,000 and the lesser figure (25,000) binds. Value correctly preserves the per-cycle recomputation. Strict caveat retained: 25,000 is the floor of VALID signatures; gather well above to absorb challenges.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Statutory rule: file with the Illinois State Board of Elections not less than 134 and not more than 141 days before the general election (10 ILCS 5/10-6). This computes to ~late June of the election year and RECOMPUTES each cycle. For the most recent cycle (2024 general, Nov. 5, 2024) the SBE filing window was June 17-24, 2024, with the deadline Monday, June 24, 2024 at 5:00 p.m. Do NOT reuse the June 24, 2024 date for a future cycle — re-derive from the 134/141-day rule against the specific election date.","note":"Triple-corroborated: Ballotpedia (141/134-day quote verbatim, line 232), NASS ('no less than 134 prior' verbatim), ballot-access.org ('June 24 is the Illinois petition deadline' verbatim), and IL Candidate Guide ('Not more than 141 nor less than 134 days... 10 ILCS 5/10-6'; window 'June 17 - June 24, 2024'). Value is correct as a rule; the cycle-specific 2024 date is accurate but transient — reliedValue foregrounds the recomputing rule.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. President is a statewide/at-large office; signatures are counted 'in the aggregate' across the state with no per-congressional-district, per-county, or geographic-distribution requirement. The 5,000-per-district floor in 10 ILCS 5/10-3 applies only to district offices (e.g., congressperson after redistricting), not to the statewide presidential petition.","note":"FindLaw 10-3 quote ('for any office to be filled by the voters of the State at large... in the aggregate') verifies verbatim. Re-derived from full statute text: the district/subdivision 5%-8% and 5,000-signature provisions are expressly tied to district/political-subdivision offices, not at-large offices. No distribution rule applies to President.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator must be at least 18 (or will be 18 by the upcoming general election) and a U.S. citizen; may be from outside the district, county, or state (no Illinois residency required). A circulator may NOT mix petition types: cannot circulate for an independent candidate in addition to a new-party candidate, cannot circulate for more than one new party, and cannot circulate for an established party plus an independent/new party (10 ILCS 5/10-4; Schober v. Young, 322 Ill. App. 3d 996 (4th Dist. 2001)).","note":"IL Candidate Guide quotes verify verbatim (guide lines 594-596: '18 years of age... can be from outside of the district, county, or state'; 'personally witness all signatures'). Mixing prohibitions confirmed at guide lines 631-648 ('A circulator may not circulate petitions for an independent candidate(s) in addition to candidates for a new political party', etc.). Out-of-state circulators are explicitly permitted by the current official guide.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Both required. The circulator must personally witness every signature and complete/sign the circulator's statement at the bottom of each sheet (certifying address, age, citizenship, and that signatures were given in their presence by registered voters); that circulator's statement must be sworn to and signed by a notary public. Separately, the candidate must swear/affirm and sign a Statement of Candidacy and have it notarized; the notarized Statement of Candidacy must accompany the nomination papers (attached at the front of the packet).","note":"All four IL Candidate Guide quotes verify verbatim (guide line 596 'must personally witness all signatures'; line 618 'This statement shall be sworn to and signed by a notary'; lines 492-494 'must swear to or affirm... sign... have the statement notarized. The Statement of Candidacy must accompany the nomination papers'). Both the circulator certification and a separate notarization are required.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Original wet-ink signatures of voters AND the original signature of the circulator are required on physical petition sheets; photocopies or duplicates are not accepted (blank petitions may be photocopied before circulation, but the signer/circulator/notary signatures must all be original). There is NO digital, remote-online, or in-person-electronic signature system for an independent or new-party presidential petition — collection and filing are entirely paper-based with the State Board of Elections.","note":"IL Candidate Guide quotes verify verbatim (guide line 502 'contain the original signatures of the voters and the original signature of the circulator, and shall not be photocopies or duplicates'; line 607 'Blank nomination petitions may be reproduced prior to circulation. The signatures of the signers, circulator, and the notary public must be original'). Adversarial check: no source indicates any e-signature/online option for this route; the original-signature mandate forecloses it.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Operating assumption: NO filing fee and NO fee-in-lieu-of-signatures for the independent/new-party presidential petition — ballot access is by signature petition only. This is NOT positively confirmed by the cited sources (they describe the petition requirement but do not affirmatively state that no fee exists), so it must be confirmed with the State Board before relying on it. Strict reading: treat the petition as the sole access path, budget for no fee, but verify with SBE that no fee/deposit/bond applies and confirm whether a Statement of Economic Interests is required for the federal office.","note":"Citation integrity PASSES: both quotes (NASS petition description and FindLaw 10-3) verify verbatim. But this is a NEGATIVE claim — 'no fee exists' — and the cited quotes only describe the signature/petition requirement; neither affirmatively states the absence of a fee or fee-in-lieu. Proof-of-a-negative gap: the IL Candidate Guide contains zero references to any filing fee or dollar amount for this route (strong corroboration the value is likely correct), but retrieval cannot positively establish an absence the sources never address. Strictest defensible posture = HOLD and confirm with SBE rather than treat the no-fee claim as verified.","conf":0.6,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Indiana","sigs":"IN: 2% of last SoS vote (36,943 for 2024 cycle); formula stable, integer recomputes off 2026 SoS race for 2028 — HOLD on exact number","deadline":"IN: two-step — county certify by noon local ~June 30, then Election Div by noon ET ~July 15 (2024 dates July 1 / July 15); dates shift each cycle — HOLD on literal dates","risk":"All 8 fields grounded verbatim in the official IN SoS 2024 Candidate Guide; primary risks are (a) signature count and deadline dates are 2024-cycle-specific and recompute for 2028, and (b) two inferences not stated verbatim — that the 4,500/500 rule is primary-only and that out-of-state/non-registered circulators are permitted — both held conservatively; never submit assuming non-resident circulators are safe without office confirmation.","sos":["For an independent/minor-party presidential petition of nomination (CAN-19), may the petition carrier be a non-Indiana resident and/or a person who is not a registered Indiana voter, provided the carrier completes the petition-carrier certification (name, address, DOB) on every page per IC 3-8-2-7?","Please confirm that the 4,500-signature / 500-per-congressional-district requirement applies ONLY to major-party (Democratic/Republican) primary candidates for President, and that an independent/minor-party presidential petition of nomination has NO per-county or per-congressional-district distribution minimum — only the statewide 2% aggregate.","For the 2028 presidential cycle, what is the certified signature requirement (2% of the 2026 Secretary of State vote) and the exact county-certification and Election Division filing deadlines?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","perSignatureAllowed":"no","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"hourly-only","operatingStance":"NO per-signature (prohibited) — pay hourly/bonus; advocate to legalize","model":"per-signature prohibited (Level 6 felony); flat/hourly pay expressly allowed","note":"Candidate-petition compensation IS addressed by statute, not carried over from initiative law (Indiana has no statewide initiative process). IC 3-14-2-1(5) makes it a Level 6 felony to pay \"based on the number of signatures obtained to place a candidate or public question on a ballot,\" but expressly permits paying circulators on a non-per-signature basis (hourly/flat). No circulator residency/voter-registration requirement exists in the petition-carrier statute (IC 3-6-12); only signers must be registered Indiana voters.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's petition of nomination under IC 3-8-6, does IC 3-14-2-1(5) permit paying circulators (petition carriers) on an hourly or flat-fee basis so long as compensation is not tied directly or indirectly to the number of signatures collected, and is there any residency or Indiana voter-registration requirement for the petition carriers themselves?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-14-2-1/","quote":"Sec. 1. A person who knowingly does any of the following commits a Level 6 felony: ... (5) Pays or offers to pay an individual any property based on the number of signatures obtained to place a candidate or public question on a ballot. This subdivision does not prohibit payment for gathering signatures not based, either directly or indirectly, on the number of signatures obtained to place a candidate or public question on a ballot."},{"url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2026-Candidate-Guide.FINAL.pdf","quote":"5) Paying or offering to pay an individual any property based on the number of signatures obtained to place a candidate or public question on a ballot. This does not prohibit payment for gathering signatures not based, either directly or indirectly, on the number of signatures obtained to place a candidate or public question on a ballot. (IC 3-14-2-1)"},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-6-12-2/","quote":"As used in this chapter, \"petition carrier\" refers to an individual who circulates a petition that is required to place a candidate or a public question on the ballot. The term includes a candidate circulating a petition for the candidate's placement on the ballot."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-6-12-7/","quote":"Sec. 7. (a) The petition carrier must sign and date the following statement at the bottom of each signature page: \"I affirm under the penalties for perjury that I have no reason to believe that any individual whose signature appears on this page is ineligible to sign this petition or did not properly complete and sign this page.\". (b) The petition carrier must also print the following information below the affirmation stated in subsection (a): (1) The petition carrier's name. (2) The petition carrier's full address, including the ZIP code. (3) The petition carrier's date of birth."},{"url":"https://statecodesfiles.justia.com/indiana/2015/title-3/article-8/chapter-6/chapter-6.pdf","quote":"Sec. 6. (a) The signatures to a petition of nomination need not be appended to one (1) paper, but a petitioner may not be counted unless the petitioner is registered and qualified to vote in conformity with section 8 of this chapter."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2026-Candidate-Guide.FINAL.pdf","official":true,"dom":"in.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/statistics-and-maps/","official":true,"dom":"in.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/voter-information/voter-list-maintenance-information","official":true,"dom":"in.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/voter-information/register-to-vote/voter-registration-and-turnout-statistics","official":true,"dom":"in.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/","official":true,"dom":"in.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-14-2-1/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-6-12-2/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/in/title-3-elections/in-code-sect-3-6-12-7/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://statecodesfiles.justia.com/indiana/2015/title-3/article-8/chapter-6/chapter-6.pdf","official":false,"dom":"statecodesfiles.justia.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Formula: 2% of the total votes cast for Secretary of State in the most recent SoS general election, statewide, with any fraction in excess of a whole number disregarded (IC 3-8-6-3). For the 2024 cycle this equals 36,943 (2% of 1,847,179). For 2028 this MUST be recomputed off the 2026 SoS race and is expected to differ; collect a buffer above the formula minimum.","note":"All three primary-source quotes verified verbatim in the fresh pdftotext extraction (lines 1979-1988, 6771) and the Ballotpedia quote verified at line 244. Math checks: 0.02 x 1,847,179 = 36,943.58 -> floored to 36,943. HOLD reason: today is 2026-06-07; the literal 36,943 is the 2024-cycle figure and is NOT current for a 2028 run (recomputes off the 2026 SoS vote). Strictest defensible posture = rely on the formula, recompute when 2026 SoS totals certify, and over-collect.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Two-step statutory rule (IC 3-8-6-10; IC 3-8-6-12): (1) submit petitions to county voter registration offices for certification by 12:00 noon prevailing local time on June 30 of the election year (moves to the next business day if June 30 is a weekend); (2) file the certified petition (CAN-19) plus consent (CAN-20) with the Indiana Election Division by 12:00 noon ET on July 15. For the 2024 cycle the county deadline was noon Mon July 1, 2024 and the Election Division deadline was noon ET Mon July 15, 2024; first day to submit was Jan 10, 2024. Confirm exact 2028 dates with the Election Division.","note":"Both primary-source quotes verified verbatim (lines 1013, 2001-2008) including the IC 3-8-6-10/-12 cites and the weekend-shift note; Ballotpedia corroborated at line 244 (county no later than noon June 30, SoS by July 15). The two-step structure and times (noon local for county, noon ET for the Division) match exactly. HOLD reason: the literal July 1 / July 15, 2024 dates are 2024-cycle-specific and not current for 2028. Note: Ballotpedia also flags a separate elector-filing deadline (2nd Tuesday in September) — that is a downstream step, not a defect in this field, but the campaign must calendar it separately.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"For an independent/minor-party PRESIDENTIAL petition of nomination there is no statutory per-county or per-congressional-district minimum stated in the guide; the requirement is the single statewide 2% aggregate. HOWEVER, because 'none' is an inference (the guide affirmatively states the 4,500/500 rule only for major-party primary candidates and is silent on any distribution rule for the petition of nomination), confirm with the Election Division before relying on a zero-distribution assumption. Operationally, geographic spread is still prudent since signatures are certified county-by-county.","note":"Quotes grounded: the President 2%-entire-state EXAMPLE (lines 1986-1988) and the 4,500/500 text (lines 614-616). The 4,500/500 language is explicitly framed as 'Democratic or Republican candidates seeking nomination in the 2024 primary election' (lines 614, 620, 626), strongly supporting the draft's claim that it does NOT apply to petition-of-nomination candidates. But the guide never affirmatively says 'President petition of nomination has no distribution requirement' — so 'None' is a (well-supported) interpretation, not a verbatim statement. Held conservatively per the inquiry; campaign should still spread collection geographically because certification is per-county.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Anyone may circulate a petition of nomination; the circulator (petition carrier) must complete the petition-carrier certification (signed affirmation under penalties of perjury plus printed name, address, and date of birth) on EVERY petition page before submission, or the page is rejected if not cured by the filing deadline (IC 3-8-2-7). Do NOT operationally assume out-of-state or non-registered circulators are safe until confirmed with the Election Division — the guide says 'anyone may circulate' but does not affirmatively address residency or voter-registration status.","note":"Verbatim quote grounded at lines 759-760 ('Anyone may circulate a petition of nomination... must complete petition carrier certification on every petition form'). The draft's value is correct as to the carrier-certification requirement (IC 3-8-2-7, lines 845-847). HOLD reason: the draft extends 'anyone may circulate' to assert no residency and no voter-status restriction — that specific permission for non-residents/non-voters is an inference, not stated in the guide. Strictest defensible posture: rely on 'anyone may circulate + full carrier cert on every page' and resolve the residency question with the office before deploying out-of-state circulators.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization. A petition carrier (circulator) certification is required instead: the carrier must complete and sign, on each signature page, an affirmation under penalties of perjury that they have no reason to believe any signer is ineligible, with the carrier's printed name, address, and date of birth (IC 3-8-2-7). Signatures are separately validated by the county voter registration office. An incomplete carrier affidavit causes the page to be rejected if not cured by the filing deadline.","note":"Both quotes verified verbatim: the per-page affirmation-under-penalty-of-perjury with name/address/DOB and IC 3-8-2-7 cite (lines 845-847), and 'A petition carrier is required to fully complete and affix their signature to the affidavit at the bottom of each page' (line 1862 and 7 other occurrences). No notarization requirement appears anywhere in the guide. Value is current and correct; no cycle dependence.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Paper only. Indiana requires original wet-ink signatures on the paper CAN-19 petition of nomination; photocopies, electronic, digital, and digitized signatures are all rejected (IC 3-5-4-1.7(b)). There is no online/digital petition system for an independent presidential petition; the process is paper end-to-end with county certification and physical filing with the Election Division.","note":"Quote verified verbatim at line 755 ('photocopies of signatures, electronic signatures, digital signatures, or digitized signatures will not be accepted. (IC 3-5-4-1.7(b))'). Confirms a strict wet-signature paper regime. Value is current and correct; no cycle dependence.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Indiana provides no filing-fee option in lieu of (or in addition to) the petition signatures for an independent or minor-party presidential candidate; ballot access is by petition of nomination only.","note":"Quote verified verbatim at line 344 ('A minor party (other than the Libertarian Party), or independent candidate in Indiana is nominated for placement on the general election ballot by petition of nomination'). Adversarial check confirmed: the only 'fee' anywhere in the 153-page guide is an unrelated photocopying fee (line 3423), and 'in lieu' appears nowhere — so there is no fee alternative. Value is current and correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Iowa","sigs":"3,500 signatures (flat statutory; not a %) + 100 each from 19 counties — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"5:00 p.m. on 81st day before Nov general election (2024 = Aug 16, 2024) — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"Core petition burden (3,500 sigs, 19-county floor, 81-day deadline, notarized affidavit, paper-only) is fully grounded in Iowa Code 45.1/44.4/45.5 and AUTO-LIVE. Two fields held conservatively: circulator-eligibility (relying on a complete ABSENCE of circulator rules is a negative inference not provable by retrieval; sub-regulatory IAC ch. 721 rules not pulled) and the NPPO convention alternative (the \"one attendee per county\"/\"true independents have no convention option\" claims rest on Ballotpedia + un-retrieved Iowa Code ch. 44 classification). Strict posture: rely on the petition route only; never treat the convention as a shortcut.","sos":["Re circulators: For an independent/NPPO presidential nomination petition under Iowa Code ch. 45, is there ANY requirement or attestation imposed on the person who circulates the petition (age, Iowa residency, voter-registration status, or a circulator oath/affidavit), whether in statute or in the Iowa Administrative Code (e.g., IAC ch. 721)? Please confirm there are no circulator requirements beyond each signer being an eligible elector.","Re NPPO/independent classification: Can a candidate with NO party or NPPO affiliation (a 'Nominated by Petition' candidate) for President/VP qualify by convention/caucus under Iowa Code ch. 44, or is the 3,500-signature/19-county petition the ONLY available route for a truly unaffiliated candidate? Separately, for an NPPO convention nomination, please confirm the exact attendance requirements (minimum total electors and whether at least one attendee is required from each of all 99 counties) and the filing deadline for the certificate of nomination."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Iowa's candidate-petition / election code (Ch. 45) and the Iowa SOS candidate guidance impose NO compensation rule on circulators of candidate nominating petitions — paying per signature is neither authorized nor prohibited; it is unaddressed for candidate petitions, so do not assume it is permitted. Iowa's pay-per-signature literature applies only to ballot initiatives/veto referendums, and Iowa is not even one of those states (no statewide citizen-initiative process), so nothing affirmatively permits per-signature pay here. Circulator residency is not required.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under Iowa Code Ch. 45, may a campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis (and are paid circulators otherwise permitted), and must a circulator be an Iowa resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Iowa","quote":"The state code does not establish circulator requirements. Specifically, there are no residency requirements for circulators."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Iowa","quote":"In Iowa, most candidates are required to file nomination petitions with the Iowa Secretary of State. Any eligible elector may sign a candidate's nomination petition. Eligible electors do not have to be registered to vote, but they do need to be U.S. citizens, Iowa residents, and 18 years of age or older."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Iowa","quote":"An independent candidate for president must petition for placement on the general election ballot. At least 3,500 eligible voters from at least 19 of the state's counties must sign the petition. The petition must include the names of candidates for president, vice president, and presidential electors. The petition must be filed with the secretary of state by 5:00 p.m. on the 81st day prior to the general election."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","quote":"Pay-per-signature is a method of compensating signature gatherers, also known as circulators, who collect signatures for ballot initiatives and veto referendums. The method involves paying signature gatherers at a rate based on the number of signatures collected."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","quote":"There are 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process. Sixteen (16) of those states allowed campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. Ten (10) of those states prohibited campaigns from paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.iowa.gov/voter-registration-list-requests","official":true,"dom":"sos.iowa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Iowa","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Iowa","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"3,500 signatures of eligible electors — a flat statutory minimum (not a percentage; does not recompute per cycle), including at least 100 eligible electors each from at least 19 counties (embedded distribution floor). Iowa Code 45.1(1). Same number applies to the unaffiliated 'Nominated by Petition' candidate and to an NPPO candidate using the petition route (45.4 routes petition candidates through ch. 45).","note":"45.1(1) verbatim: 'not less than three thousand five hundred eligible electors, including at least one hundred eligible electors each from at least nineteen counties of the state.' Confirmed a flat number, not a percentage, in the statute itself; current (last amended 2022; 2021 amendment to subsec.1 applies to ballots in/after 2022). Ballotpedia corroborates. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5:00 p.m. on the 81st day before the November general election; earliest filing = 99 days before. For 2024 (Nov 5, 2024): deadline 5:00 p.m. Aug 16, 2024, filing window opened July 29, 2024. Iowa Code 44.4(1)(b), incorporated for petition candidates by 45.4. Recomputes each cycle.","note":"44.4(1)(b) verbatim: '...not more than ninety-nine days nor later than 5:00 p.m. on the eighty-first day before the date of the general election to be held in November.' 45.4 incorporation verbatim. Date arithmetic independently verified: Nov 5, 2024 - 81 days = Aug 16, 2024; -99 days = July 29, 2024; Nov 5 2024 is a Tuesday. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes — county distribution requirement: at least 100 eligible electors EACH from at least 19 counties (a subset of the 3,500 total). Stated by county, not by congressional district. Iowa Code 45.1(1).","note":"45.1(1) verbatim: 'including at least one hundred eligible electors each from at least nineteen counties of the state.' By county, not district — confirmed. Ballotpedia corroborates. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Requirements fall on SIGNERS, who must each be an 'eligible elector': U.S. citizen, Iowa resident, at least 17 (must be 18 by Election Day), need not be a registered voter but must meet all qualifications to register; not a disqualified felon, not judged incompetent to vote, not claiming the right to vote elsewhere. Any eligible elector in Iowa may sign for a statewide/presidential office. STRICT HOLD on the asserted COMPLETE ABSENCE of any circulator requirement/attestation — do not operationally assume zero circulator rules until the SOS confirms (see sosInquiries).","note":"Signer-eligibility facts ground verbatim on the SOS candidate FAQ (citizen/resident/17-must-be-18; 'not required to be a registered voter'; statewide-office signing). However, the claim that there is NO circulator age/residency/voter-status requirement and NO attestation step is a negative inference: chapter 45 and the FAQ do not affirmatively foreclose a sub-regulatory rule (IAC ch. 721 not retrieved). Per strict 'never risk ballot access' posture, HOLD the no-circulator-rules conclusion pending SOS confirmation; the signer facts themselves are reliable.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Petition pages are NOT notarized and need no circulator/witness certification. The candidate's affidavit of candidacy MUST be notarized — nomination papers are rejected if the affidavit lacks the signature of a notary public under ch. 9B (or other officer empowered to witness oaths). Each signature line must include the signer's signature and residential address (street, number, city) to be counted; no per-signature witnessing required. Iowa Code 45.5(2)(c),(5)(d); SOS FAQ.","note":"SOS FAQ verbatim: 'A candidate's affidavit of candidacy must be notarized. Nomination petitions do not need to be notarized.' 45.5(5)(d) verbatim on notary requirement; 45.5(2)(c) verbatim on signature+residential-address counting rule. Consistent and current. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wet-ink paper petitions (8.5 x 11 inch pages, securely bound into a single bundle; unbound petitions returned without examination) plus a paper notarized affidavit of candidacy, filed with the Secretary of State. No online/remote-signature system for an independent/NPPO presidential petition. Iowa Code 45.5(1),(3); SOS lists the paper President/VP nomination petition PDF.","note":"45.5(1) verbatim ('eight and one-half by eleven inches...substantially the form prescribed') and 45.5(3) verbatim ('securely fastened together to form a single bundle. Nomination petitions that are not bound shall be returned without further examination'). SOS nomination-papers page lists the paper 'Nomination Petition-President & Vice President' PDF under General Election. Chapter 45 has no e-signature provision; physical bound-bundle requirement forecloses remote capture. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option — the 3,500-signature/19-county petition is the mandatory, SAFE route for the unaffiliated presidential candidate; rely on it exclusively. Do NOT rely on a convention/caucus alternative as an available shortcut: the claim that an NPPO may instead convene (>=500 electors, one attendee per county, certificate filed by the 81st-day deadline) and that a 'Nominated by Petition' unaffiliated candidate has NO convention option rests on Ballotpedia plus un-retrieved Iowa Code ch. 44 and is a legal-classification interpretation (see sosInquiries).","note":"No-fee part grounds verbatim (SOS FAQ: 'There are no candidate filing fees in Iowa') and is reliable. Convention details ground verbatim on Ballotpedia ('At least 500 eligible voters must attend... at least one attendee from each of the state's counties') but NOT on the retrieved SOS FAQ, which states only that NPPOs may nominate by convention without the 500/per-county specifics. The '>=1 attendee per county' = all 99 counties is an extreme, un-statute-confirmed bar, and the categorical 'true independents have no convention option' is a legal classification not settled by retrieval (ch. 44 not pulled). HOLD: rely solely on the petition route, which is the strictest/safest posture.","conf":0.7,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Kansas","sigs":"5,000 valid signatures (flat statewide, no distribution) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"12:00 noon Monday before the Aug primary; recomputes each even year (2024: Aug 5, 2024) — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"Signature count, deadline, paper capture, and no-fee-substitute are solid and AUTO-LIVE; the residual risk is in execution rules (per-sheet county collation under 25-303(f), whether the circulator \"affidavit\" must be notarized, and circulator qualifications) — all held conservatively pending SOS confirmation. Note 2026 is a midterm with no presidential race, so the live presidential deadline must be recomputed for the next presidential even year (e.g., 2028).","sos":["For a statewide (state-at-large) independent presidential nomination petition under K.S.A. 25-303, does the per-sheet rule in 25-303(f) (all signers on one sheet must reside in the same county and election district of the office sought) require that petition sheets be collated/organized by county, and is there any minimum-per-county or per-congressional-district distribution of the 5,000 signatures?","For an independent presidential nomination petition, does the circulator/candidate 'affidavit' required by K.S.A. 25-303(f) have to be sworn and notarized, or does a signed verification without a notary satisfy the statute? Is there an official SOS petition form that prescribes the verification format?","Does Kansas impose any qualifications on a petition circulator for an independent nomination petition (e.g., age, Kansas residency, voter registration, or party-affiliation status), beyond the requirement that the circulator or candidate personally witness each signature under K.S.A. 25-303(f)?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; circulator residency NOT required","note":"Kansas's candidate/independent-petition law (K.S.A. 25-303, 25-3608, 25-302a) and the Secretary of State's Candidate Petition Circulation Guide and Election Standards Chapter V address only circulator qualifications, the witness affidavit, residency, and signer rules — they are SILENT on compensation, so paying candidate-petition circulators per signature is UNADDRESSED (neither expressly authorized nor prohibited). Kansas has no statewide initiative process, so there is also no initiative pay-per-signature statute to import; circulators need NOT be Kansas residents, so a national paid pool is not blocked on residency grounds.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under K.S.A. 25-303, may a campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and are there any restrictions on paying circulators (e.g., a per-signature ban, hourly/flat-fee requirement, or registration/disclosure obligations)?","citations":[{"url":"https://sos.ks.gov/Pubs/Elections/Guides/Candidate-Petition-Circulation-Guide.pdf","quote":"Candidates and petition circulators may carry a petition through the election district if they meet the constitutional qualification to be an elector. However, they are not required by law to be registered voters in the election district. Each circulator must: 1.) witness every signature on every page; 2.) collect signatures from a single county on each page; 3.) sign, and have notarized, an affidavit that is attached to or printed on the back of the petition form."},{"url":"https://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/election-standards/Kansas-Election-Standards-Chapter-V-Petitions.pdf","quote":"According to Kansas law, circulators must: [1] be a United States citizen; [2] be at least 18 years of age; [3] have not been convicted of a felony or if convicted of a felony been pardoned or have had civil rights restored; and [4] agree to submit to the jurisdiction of the state for purposes of subpoena enforcement regarding the integrity and reliability of the petition process. [KSA 25-3608]"},{"url":"https://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/election-standards/Kansas-Election-Standards-Chapter-V-Petitions.pdf","quote":"The U.S. Supreme Court has held that states may require petition circulators to possess the qualifications of electors in the states where they circulate petitions ... but they may not require actual registration or residency in the specific county or election district. Buckley vs. American Constitutional Law Foundation, Inc. Kansas law reflects this decision, as well as a similar Kansas federal case, that petition circulators need not be Kansas residents. [KSA 25-302a]; See Constitution Party of Kansas, et al. v. Biggs, No. 10-CV-4043 (D. Kan.)"},{"url":"https://ksrevisor.gov/statutes/chapters/ch25/025_003_0003.html","quote":"The affidavit of the candidate or a petition circulator shall be appended to each petition and shall contain ... a verification, signed by the circulator or candidate, to the effect that such circulator or candidate personally witnessed the signing of the petition by each person whose name appears thereon."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sos.ks.gov/Pubs/Elections/Guides/Candidate-Petition-Circulation-Guide.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.ks.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/election-standards/Kansas-Election-Standards-Chapter-V-Petitions.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.ks.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ksrevisor.gov/statutes/chapters/ch25/025_003_0003.html","official":true,"dom":"ksrevisor.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.ksrevisor.gov/statutes/chapters/ch25/025_023_0020a.html","official":true,"dom":"ksrevisor.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.ksrevisor.gov/statutes/chapters/ch25/025_001_0006.html","official":true,"dom":"ksrevisor.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sos.ks.gov/elections/voter-registration.html","official":true,"dom":"sos.ks.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.ks.gov/forms/Elections/CVR.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.ks.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 signatures of qualified (registered) Kansas voters. President is a state-at-large office, so the flat statewide threshold under K.S.A. 25-303(c) applies. Fixed statutory number, not a percentage; does not recompute by cycle. No district/county distribution required.","note":"Grounded verbatim in K.S.A. 25-303(c) ('any office to be filled by the voters of the state at large... not less than 5,000 qualified voters') and Ballotpedia's 2024 presidential page ('At least 5,000 qualified voters must sign the petition'). Adversarial check: 25-303(d)'s 4% formula and the 25 / 5,000 floor-and-cap apply only to sub-state offices, not to a state-at-large office; the 5,000 figure is fixed in statute and does not recompute. Re-derived independently and could not refute.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"12:00 noon on the Monday preceding the August primary (K.S.A. 25-305(b)); primary is the first Tuesday of August in even-numbered years (K.S.A. 25-203). For the most recent presidential cycle (2024): primary Tue Aug 6, 2024 → independent nomination petition deadline 12:00 noon Mon Aug 5, 2024. Recomputes each even year (SOS lists 12:00 p.m. Mon Aug 3, 2026 for the 2026 non-presidential cycle). Filed with the Secretary of State for national office.","note":"Grounded verbatim: 25-305(b) (independent nomination petitions due 'no later than 12:00 noon on the Monday preceding the date fixed for the holding of primary elections in accordance with K.S.A. 25-203'); 25-203 (primary 'first Tuesday of August in even-numbered years'); SOS page ('Independent Nominations: 12:00 p.m. Monday, August 3, 2026'). Adversarial check: President is a national office and 25-305(b) covers 'national... offices' with no presidential petition carve-out (25-305(d) carves out only WRITE-IN candidacy, not petitions), so the August deadline governs. Date arithmetic confirmed (Aug 2024 first Tuesday = Aug 6; Monday preceding = Aug 5). Value is cycle-dependent and the draft flags this; for the next presidential year (2028) the date must be recomputed. AUTO-LIVE for the cited 2024 value with the recompute caveat preserved.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No per-district or per-county signature-distribution quota: the 5,000 signatures for a state-at-large office (25-303(c)) form a single statewide pool, and 25-303(d)'s per-division percentage applies only to sub-state offices. HOWEVER, K.S.A. 25-303(f) requires that all signers appearing on any single petition sheet reside in the same county and election district of the office sought. Strictest operational reading: organize/collate petition sheets by county so no sheet mixes signers from different counties. Confirm sheet-collation requirement with the SOS before circulating.","note":"Both quotes grounded verbatim in 25-303. The 'no distribution quota' conclusion is correct and well supported (25-303(c) is a flat statewide number). But 25-303(f)'s same-county/same-election-district per-sheet rule is a genuine operational constraint whose application to a state-at-large petition (the 'election district' being the whole state, yet the 'same county' limit still binding per sheet) is an interpretation retrieval cannot fully settle. Held conservatively (collate by county) to avoid a defective-petition / signature-invalidation risk. SOS inquiry filed.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Statute (K.S.A. 25-303(f)) is silent on circulator age/residency/registration; it requires only that the candidate or 'petition circulator' personally witness each signature and append a signed verification. Because this is an unverifiable negative (an SOS rule or official form could impose qualifications not in the statute), do not rely on 'anyone may circulate.' Strictest defensible posture: have the candidate or a qualified, registered Kansas elector circulate and personally witness every signature, and confirm circulator qualifications with the SOS before deploying volunteers.","note":"Quote grounded verbatim in 25-303(f). The asserted value is the ABSENCE of a statutory circulator qualification — a negative that retrieval cannot conclusively establish (no SOS administrative rule was located confirming the absence). Defaulting to the strictest interpretation per the over-comply mandate; held pending SOS confirmation rather than published as AUTO-LIVE. SOS inquiry filed.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"A circulator/candidate verification must be appended to each set of petition documents (K.S.A. 25-303(f)) attesting the circulator/candidate personally witnessed every signature. The statute uses the word 'affidavit,' which ordinarily implies a sworn instrument. Strictest defensible reading: treat it as a sworn affidavit and have it notarized (or execute it on the official SOS petition form exactly as prescribed) rather than assume a bare unsworn signature suffices. Confirm notarization requirement and form with the SOS.","note":"Quote grounded verbatim. The draft concludes 'NOT notarization,' but 25-303(f) expressly calls it 'The affidavit of the candidate or a petition circulator' even while the operative clause requires only a signed verification. 'Affidavit' vs. 'signed verification' is precisely a legal-interpretation conflict retrieval cannot settle, and getting it wrong (unsworn where sworn is required) risks petition rejection. Over-comply: assume notarization may be required; hold and verify with SOS. SOS inquiry filed.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Independent nomination petitions are physical papers carried by circulators; each registered-voter signer must add place of residence and post office address, with a circulator/candidate verification appended to each set. No Kansas online/digital petition system covers an independent presidential nominating petition; petitions are filed in paper form with the Secretary of State.","note":"Grounded verbatim in 25-303(f) ('signatures... need not all be appended to one paper, but each registered voter signing... shall add... place of residence and post office address'). Statute plainly contemplates physical papers carried by circulators; no statutory or SOS digital-petition pathway exists for this petition type. Re-derived and could not refute. Note: this fixes COLLECTION mode as paper; it does not bear on the circulator-verification execution questions above.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing fee that substitutes for signatures for an independent candidate; the valid nominating petition is the only route onto the general-election ballot, and the GEC/SOS fee is paid in addition to (not in lieu of) the petition. The party-primary 'petition OR filing fee' option does not extend to independent candidates.","note":"Both quotes grounded verbatim on the SOS candidate-information page ('Independent candidates do not run in the primary and may only file to run for office by petition'; footnote 1: 'Independent candidates may file for office only by petition. Upon filing a valid petition and paying the GEC/SOS fee, the candidate's name will be placed directly on the general ballot...'). Adversarial check: the page's general line 'Candidates must file by petition or filing fee' is the party-primary option; the independent-specific footnote confirms petition is mandatory and the fee is additive, not a substitute. Correct and current; AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Kentucky","sigs":"5,000 registered voters statewide (no distribution) + $500 fee, both required — KRS 118.315","deadline":"File by Fri after 1st Tue in Sept = Sep 8, 2028, 4:00 p.m. local (earliest affix/file Nov 3, 2027)","risk":"All 8 fields grounded against primary sources (KRS 118.315, KRS 118.365, SOS 2028 President/Independent packet); quotes verbatim. Adversarial check cleared the KRS 118.591(1) cross-reference in current 118.315(2): 118.591 governs the presidential PREFERENCE PRIMARY petition (party path), NOT the independent general-election petition — no conflict. Two HOLDs are conservative-only (negative inferences about circulator rules / conditional notarization guideline), not refutations; substantive values stand.","sos":["Does Kentucky impose any eligibility requirement (residency, age, KY voter registration) or attestation duty on a person who merely collects/circulates signatures on an independent presidential Nominating Petition (SBE 64/64-2), separate from each signer's own voter-registration requirement? Is there any State Board of Elections administrative regulation on circulators?","Confirm: for the independent/political-group presidential Nominating Petition (SBE 64/64-2), is NO notarization required for the petitioner signatures (i.e., the conditional 'if the filing form requires notarization' guideline does not apply to this form), and is there no separate circulator/witness affidavit?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature ban exists only for ballot-question petitions)","note":"For an independent PRESIDENTIAL candidate's nominating petition, Kentucky's controlling statute (KRS 118.315, the basis for the Secretary of State's SBE 64 Nominating Petition per the official filing packet) and the SOS filing instructions are entirely silent on petition circulators and on compensating them — candidate-petition compensation is UNADDRESSED, neither permitted nor prohibited. The only Kentucky statute criminalizing payment in connection with a petition, KRS 119.205(3), is expressly limited to \"a petition to have a public question placed on the ballot\" (ballot measures), so it does NOT carry over to candidate petitions; no candidate-petition per-signature rule exists. Circulators face no statutory residency/registration requirement (only signers must be registered KY voters), so a national paid pool could legally circulate, but because per-signature compensation for candidate petitions is unaddressed it should be treated conservatively.","sosInquiry":"For an independent candidate for President filing a Nominating Petition (SBE 64) under KRS 118.315, may the campaign compensate the people who circulate/collect the petition signatures, and specifically may they be paid on a per-signature basis, or is only hourly/salary compensation permissible? Are there any residency or voter-registration requirements for circulators (as opposed to signers)?","citations":[{"url":"https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=56459","quote":"The form of the petition shall be prescribed by the State Board of Elections. It shall be signed by the candidate and by registered voters from the district or jurisdiction from which the candidate seeks nomination. ... A petition of nomination for a state officer, or any officer for whom all the electors of the state are entitled to vote, shall contain five thousand (5,000) petitioners ... Each petitioner shall include the date he or she affixes the signature, address of residence, and date of birth."},{"url":"https://web.sos.ky.gov/CandidateFilingDocuments/President_Independent.pdf","quote":"The Nominating Petition shall be signed by the candidate for President and the candidate for Vice President and by a minimum of 5,000 registered voters from the district or jurisdiction from which the candidates seek nomination. Petitioners shall be registered voters and shall include the date the petition was signed, date of birth and residence address."},{"url":"https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=27762","quote":"Any person who makes or offers to make an expenditure to any person to sign a petition to have a public question placed on the ballot, or any person who solicits, accepts, or receives any such expenditure as payment or consideration to sign a petition to have a public question placed on the ballot, shall be guilty of a Class B misdemeanor."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Kentucky","quote":"The state code does not specify petition circulator requirements. Specifically, there are no residency requirements for circulators."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=56459","official":true,"dom":"apps.legislature.ky.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://web.sos.ky.gov/CandidateFilingDocuments/President_Independent.pdf","official":true,"dom":"web.sos.ky.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=27762","official":true,"dom":"apps.legislature.ky.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/kar/titles/031/003/010/","official":true,"dom":"apps.legislature.ky.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"http://kyrules.elaws.us/rule/31kar3:010","official":true,"dom":"kyrules.elaws.us"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://elect.ky.gov/Resources/Documents/31%20KAR%203.010.pdf","official":true,"dom":"elect.ky.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://elect.ky.gov/Candidates/Pages/Request-Voter-Registration-Data.aspx","official":true,"dom":"elect.ky.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Kentucky","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ky/title-x-elections/ky-rev-st-sect-117-025/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.bing.com/search?q=Kentucky+%22Request+for+Voter+Registration+Data%22+SBE-84","official":false,"dom":"bing.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 registered voters statewide. Independent (or political group/organization) presidential ticket files a Nominating Petition (SBE 64 / SBE 64-2) under KRS 118.315, signed by the candidates for President and Vice President and a minimum of 5,000 registered voters (KRS 118.315(2): 5,000 petitioners for an office for which all electors of the state are entitled to vote). Each petitioner must include signature-affixation date, date of birth, and residence address (not a P.O. box); omission of any voids that signature. Signatures may not be affixed before the first Wednesday after the first Monday in November of the year preceding the election (Nov. 3, 2027 for the 2028 cycle).","note":"KRS 118.315(2) verbatim: '...shall contain five thousand (5,000) petitioners' for statewide office; SOS 2028 packet verbatim confirms '5,000 registered voters' and affix date Nov 3, 2027. Statute is current (eff. June 27, 2025). Adversarial: the new 118.315(2) carve-out 'excluding President of the United States in accordance with KRS 118.591(1)' refers ONLY to the presidential-preference-PRIMARY petition (party endorsement path under KRS 118.591) — it does not alter the independent general-election count. Verified by reading KRS 118.591 in full.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Not later than the Friday following the first Tuesday in September preceding the election, by 4:00 p.m. local time. For 2028 = September 8, 2028, 4:00 p.m. local time. Earliest date to file (and to affix signatures) = first Wednesday after first Monday in November of the prior year = November 3, 2027. Statutory basis: KRS 118.365(6) (window) and KRS 118.365(8) (4 p.m. cutoff). Recomputes each cycle.","note":"KRS 118.365(6) and (8) verbatim-grounded. Independently re-derived 2028: first Tuesday in Sept 2028 = Sept 5; Friday following = Sept 8, 2028 — matches the SOS 2028 packet's stated 'September 8, 2028' (4:00 p.m. local). No interpretation; arithmetic, statute, and official packet all agree.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 5,000 signatures are a single statewide total with no geographic distribution (no per-congressional-district or per-county quota). Petition is for an office 'for whom all the electors of the state are entitled to vote'; signers are 'voters of the same district or jurisdiction from which the candidates seek nomination' (the whole state).","note":"KRS 118.315(2) sets one flat 5,000 statewide number for statewide office and lists no distribution requirement; SOS petition form's 'undersigned petitioners' clause verbatim confirms a single statewide pool. No distribution language anywhere in the statute or form.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: Each signer must be a Kentucky registered voter from the jurisdiction (the state) and must personally list the signature date, date of birth, and a residential address that is NOT a P.O. box; omission of any of these voids that signature (KRS 118.315(2)). Candidates must not be registered members of a political party, and must not have been registered party members on January 1 immediately preceding the election. Do NOT rely on any assumption that a person who merely collects signatures is free of residency/age/registration constraints until confirmed with the State Board of Elections, since that is an absence-of-law inference not settled by retrieval.","note":"Core signer-eligibility and candidate-party-disaffiliation facts are verbatim-grounded (KRS 118.315(1)-(2)) and correct. HOLD is conservative-only: the draft's claim that 'no statutory age or residency rule is imposed on a person who merely collects signatures' is a negative inference (no circulator block on SBE 64/64-2, no statute found), which retrieval cannot conclusively settle vs. a possible SBE administrative regulation. Over-comply: do not promise an unrestricted out-of-state circulator without SBE confirmation. Inquiry filed.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: No notary/witness affidavit and no per-petition circulator certification appears on the SBE 64 / SBE 64-2 petition; the only sworn element is the candidates' declaration that they possess the constitutional and statutory qualifications (KRS 118.315(2); declaration on the form). The SOS general guideline states notarization applies only 'If the filing form requires notarization' — treat as: confirm with SBE that the presidential Nominating Petition is NOT a notarized form before relying on the no-notary conclusion.","note":"The actual SBE 64/64-2 form (read in full) has no notarization line and no circulator/witness attestation on the petitioner pages — only the candidate declaration, verbatim-grounded. The draft's conclusion is supported by the primary form. HOLD is conservative because correctness rests on reading the SOS conditional guideline ('If the filing form requires notarization...') as not triggered by this form — an interpretation best confirmed with the office rather than assumed. Inquiry filed.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Independent presidential petition is collected on the State Board of Elections' prescribed paper Nominating Petition (SBE 64 and SBE 64-2, KRS 118.315) and filed with the Secretary of State's Election Division in person or by mail. No online/remote or in-person-digitized signature system exists for this petition; signatures must be physically affixed to the paper petition.","note":"SOS packet verbatim: 'Filing Form SBE 64 and SBE 64-2 ... Nominating Petition' and 'Candidates may file in person or by mail at the following address: Office of the Secretary of State, Election Division...'. No e-signature path appears in statute or packet. Strictest reading is paper-only, which the value already states.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A $500.00 filing fee is required IN ADDITION to the 5,000 signatures (it is NOT a fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option). Independent/political-group/organization presidential candidates pay $500, payable to the Kentucky State Treasurer, filed with the Secretary of State together with the Nominating Petition. No fee alternative to signature-gathering exists.","note":"SOS 2028 packet lists BOTH 'Signatures Required: ... 5,000 registered voters' AND 'Filing Fee $500.00' for the same independent presidential filing, with 'Checks should be made payable to the Kentucky State Treasurer.' (verbatim) — confirming the fee is additive, not an alternative. No in-lieu provision anywhere.","conf":0.95,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Louisiana","sigs":"5,000 sigs / 500 per CD (SoS standard; bare statute reads 2,500/250 — collect 5,000/500)","deadline":"File 3rd Tue Jul–1st Fri after 3rd Tue Aug (2024: Jul 16–Aug 23); petition to registrars by Jul 24 (T-30)","risk":"Signature/distribution count is a statute-vs-agency conflict: RS 18:465(C)(1) literally says 2,500/250 for statewide candidates, but the SoS packet and NASS both say 5,000/500 for the presidential independent slate — collect 5,000/500 (strictest) to avoid rejection. Fee changed $500 (2024 packet) -> $1,000 (current statute); confirm operative fee/dates with SoS each cycle, and the petition path is always available as a fee-free alternative.","sos":["For an independent (non-party) slate of presidential electors filing a nominating petition under La R.S. 18:1254, is the required signature count 5,000 total with 500 from each of the six congressional districts (as stated in the SoS qualifying packet), or 2,500/250 per La R.S. 18:465(C)(1) for statewide candidates — and what is the controlling authority for the 5,000/500 figure?","For the upcoming presidential cycle, please confirm the exact qualifying-period open/close dates and the registrar-certification submission deadline (30 days before the period ends) for an independent presidential-elector petition under La R.S. 18:1254/1255 and 18:465(E).","Does Louisiana impose any age, residency, or voter-registration requirement on the persons who circulate/collect signatures on an independent presidential-elector nominating petition, beyond the circulator's certification duty in La R.S. 18:465(D)?","Please confirm the current qualifying fee for an independent presidential-elector slate under La R.S. 18:1254(A) — the SoS 2024 packet states $500 but the current statute reads $1,000."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"The Louisiana Election Code provisions that govern an independent presidential petition — R.S. 18:1254 (which incorporates R.S. 18:465 by cross-reference) — are entirely SILENT on whether circulators may be paid at all or per signature; candidate-petition circulator compensation is unaddressed, so per-signature pay is neither expressly permitted nor expressly prohibited. The statute imposes residency/registration requirements only on the SIGNERS (must be registered voters of the relevant area), not on the witness/circulator, so a non-resident paid pool is not facially barred by the witnessing rule, but no compensation rule was found.","sosInquiry":"For an independent (unaffiliated) presidential-elector nominating petition under La. R.S. 18:1254 / 18:465, does Louisiana law permit a campaign to compensate signature gatherers/circulators on a per-signature basis (and may paid circulators be non-residents of Louisiana)?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81596","quote":"each signature on the nominating petition shall be dated and witnessed by the candidate or the person who obtained the signature on his behalf. The candidate and all persons who obtained signatures on his behalf shall certify on the nominating petition that to the best of their knowledge, information, and belief all of the signatures on the nominating petition are genuine and all of the statements contained in the nominating petition are true and correct."},{"url":"https://www.legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81596","quote":"A person may only be nominated as a candidate in a primary election by persons who are registered to vote on the office he seeks who sign a nominating petition for him no more than one hundred twenty days before the qualifying period opens for candidates in the primary election."},{"url":"https://legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81263","quote":"Except as otherwise specifically provided in this Part, a nominating petition for a slate of candidates for the offices of presidential elector shall be signed, filed, and certified as provided in Chapter 5 of this Title for state candidates voted on throughout the State."},{"url":"https://legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81263","quote":"Nominating petitions for the office of presidential elector shall be in the form prescribed by R.S. 18:465(D), except that in lieu of including the recognized political party with which the candidates are affiliated, the petition shall contain, in not more than three words, the political principle which the candidates represent."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81596","official":true,"dom":"legis.la.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://legis.la.gov/Legis/Law.aspx?d=81263","official":true,"dom":"legis.la.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.la.gov/ElectionsAndVoting/PublishedDocuments/VoterListChargesAndInfo.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.la.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.la.gov/ElectionsAndVoting/Pages/PurchaseVoterListsFAQ.aspx?OwnershipName=PurchaseVoterListsFAQ&faqid=0","official":true,"dom":"sos.la.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.la.gov/ElectionsAndVoting/PublishedDocuments/RecordFormatSheet.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.la.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.la.gov/ElectionsAndVoting/BecomeACandidate/PurchaseVoterLists/Pages/default.aspx","official":true,"dom":"sos.la.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"5,000 signatures of registered voters, with at least 500 from each of Louisiana's 6 congressional districts (collect to this higher standard).","note":"Citations grounded verbatim (SoS packet + NASS both say 5,000/500). BUT the draft's legal derivation is wrong: RS 18:465(C)(1) — the cross-referenced statewide provision RS 18:1254(B) routes independents into — actually reads 'two thousand five hundred, not less than two hundred fifty of which shall be from each of the congressional districts' (verified at codes.findlaw.com/la, current as of 2023-01-01). So the bare statute yields 2,500/250, not 5,000/500. This is a statute-vs-administering-agency conflict that retrieval cannot settle. Strictest defensible value = 5,000/500 (the SoS's own published, administered standard, which also moots the lower reading), so relied value = 5,000/500. Do NOT rely on 2,500/250.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"File during the period beginning the third Tuesday in July and ending 4:30 p.m. on the first Friday following the third Tuesday in August (2024 cycle: Jul 16, 8:00 a.m. – Aug 23, 4:30 p.m.); the petition must additionally be submitted to parish registrars for certification no later than 30 days before the period ends (2024: July 24). Treat July-24-type certification cutoff as the binding earliest deadline and re-confirm exact cycle dates with the SoS.","note":"Triple-confirmed against primary sources: RS 18:1254(A) (legis.la.gov, current), RS 18:1255(A) (independently fetched — 'period beginning on the third Tuesday in July and ending at 4:30 p.m. on the first Friday following the third Tuesday in August'), and the SoS packet. The draft correctly flags and rejects NASS's conflicting 'first Friday following the first Tuesday in September' — Louisiana primary law controls and says August. HOLD (not AUTO-LIVE) because: (a) the value embeds cycle-specific 2024 calendar dates that recompute each cycle; (b) a NASS source conflict exists on record; (c) the registrar-certification sub-deadline (~30 days before close) is the true operational cutoff and must be re-derived per cycle. Strictest framing = honor the earlier certification cutoff.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 500 of the 5,000 signatures from each of the 6 congressional districts (collect to this higher per-district standard). Separately, the slate must comprise 8 electors: one registered voter from each of the 6 CDs plus 2 at-large.","note":"Same statute-vs-agency conflict as signaturesRequired: bare RS 18:465(C)(1) sets 250 per CD for statewide candidates, while the SoS packet (grounded verbatim) says 500 per CD for the presidential independent slate. The 8-elector slate composition (1 per CD + 2 at-large) is independently confirmed verbatim in RS 18:1254(C) and is correct. Per-district signature minimum held to strictest = 500/CD. Note the draft's 'recomputes if number of districts changes' is sound conditional reasoning but not separately verified.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No verified express age/residency/registration qualification on circulators (draft says UNKNOWN). Do NOT assume circulators may be unqualified; treat circulator age/residency as UNKNOWN and confirm with SoS, and rely only on the verified facts that signers must be registered voters in the relevant CD and that the person obtaining signatures must certify their genuineness (RS 18:465(D)).","note":"The supporting SoS-packet quote (8-elector slate composition) is grounded verbatim but does not itself speak to circulators. Independent check of RS 18:465(D) confirms a circulator-certification duty and no stated circulator age/residency — but this is a proving-a-negative claim that retrieval cannot conclusively confirm (a requirement could live in another Title 18 provision or SoS rule). Draft's own 'UNKNOWN' label is appropriate. HOLD as interpretation/absence-of-law; relied value preserves the UNKNOWN and adds an SoS inquiry.","conf":0.55,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Each of the 8 electors files a notarized Affidavit of Acceptance of Nomination; each Notice of Candidacy must be executed before a notary public OR witnessed by two persons registered to vote for presidential elector (armed-forces officer may witness for candidates serving out of state). The petition itself requires the persons who obtained signatures to certify the signatures are genuine and statements true and correct, and parish registrars certify signature validity (per RS 18:465(D), the independent-path provision).","note":"Notary/affidavit and notice-of-candidacy quotes are grounded verbatim in the SoS packet and are correct. The circulator-certification quote is grounded verbatim at the cited legis URL, BUT that URL (d=81289) is RS 18:1280.22 — the PARTY presidential-primary provision — not the independent path; the correct parallel for the independent petition is RS 18:465(D), which I independently confirmed contains materially identical certification language ('the candidate and all persons who obtained signatures... shall certify... all of the signatures... are genuine'). Substance is right; citation is mis-targeted. HOLD due to the mixed-relevance citation; relied value re-anchored to RS 18:465(D).","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper","note":"Fully grounded verbatim in the SoS packet: documents 'may be filed by mail, by courier, or in person' and 'FAXED DOCUMENTS ARE NOT ACCEPTED.' Petition is collected on paper and certified manually by parish registrars. No online/remote signature path exists for an independent presidential petition. No legal interpretation required.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Yes — a qualifying fee is available IN LIEU OF the petition. For risk/budget purposes assume $1,000 (current RS 18:1254(A), post-2024/2025 amendments, grounded verbatim on legis.la.gov), even though the 2024 SoS packet and NASS state $500; confirm the operative fee with the SoS for the specific cycle. The petition path remains available as a fee-free alternative. Fee payable only by cash, certified/cashier's check, or money order.","note":"All three citations grounded verbatim: SoS packet ($500, 2024) and NASS ($500, 2024) agree for the 2024 cycle; current legis.la.gov RS 18:1254(A) reads 'qualifying fee of one thousand dollars' (independently confirmed — amendments incl. Acts 2024 1st Ex. Sess. No. 1 and Acts 2025). The draft correctly flags this change. HOLD because the operative fee is cycle/timing-dependent and the sources disagree by amendment date; strictest assumption for a campaign = budget the higher $1,000 and/or use the petition. fee-in-lieu-of-petition structure itself is correct.","conf":0.8,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Maine","sigs":"4,000-5,000 registered Maine voters (presidential-elector slate); any Maine voter may sign; no distribution rule — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD: statute says July 25 cert / Aug 1 SOS for presidential electors, but Ballotpedia says May 25 / June 1 — treat EARLIER dates (May 25 / June 1) as the safe-harbor; signing not before Jan 1","risk":"Two genuine interpretation risks need SOS confirmation before relying live: (1) the presidential-elector filing deadline (statute carve-out July 25/Aug 1 vs. Ballotpedia's May 25/June 1 for independents) — file by the earlier dates to be safe; (2) circulator eligibility (statute is silent, so do not assume non-resident/non-voter circulators are allowed — use Maine resident registered voters). All seven citations grounded verbatim; 2028 is the next presidential year (the 2026 SOS guide is a non-presidential midterm and omits the elector deadlines/figures, so the statute controls).","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT/non-party candidate for President filing a slate of presidential electors by nomination petition under 21-A MRS sec 354, what are the exact 2028 deadlines to (a) deliver petitions to the municipal registrar for certification and (b) file with the Secretary of State — is it the July 25 / August 1 presidential-elector carve-out in sec 354(7)(B) and (8-A), and not the May 25 / June 1 dates that some summaries cite?","For a candidate nomination petition (not a ballot-question/initiative petition) under 21-A MRS sec 354, does the petition CIRCULATOR have to be a Maine resident and/or a registered Maine voter, or is the only requirement the notarized personal-witness oath in sec 354(7)(A)?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Maine's candidate-petition statutes (21-A §354 for independent/non-party nomination by petition, including presidential electors, and §335 for primary petitions) are entirely SILENT on circulator compensation — no per-signature prohibition and no authorization, so candidate-petition pay is unaddressed. The only Maine statute that addresses circulator payment and circulator residency, §903-A (subsections 4 and 5), sits in Chapter 11 (Ballot Questions) and applies expressly to direct initiatives / people's veto petitions \"pursuant to the Constitution of Maine, Article IV, Part Third, Section 17 or 18\" — it does NOT govern candidate petitions; therefore the initiative payment-disclosure and resident-voter-circulator rules do not carry over to candidate petitions, and candidate-petition circulators are not required to be Maine residents or registered voters.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/non-party candidate's nomination petition for President under 21-A §354, may the campaign pay circulators on a per-signature basis (and may circulators be paid at all on an hourly or salaried basis), and are there any disclosure or residency requirements for paid candidate-petition circulators, given that §903-A applies only to direct initiative/people's veto petitions?","citations":[{"url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec354.html","quote":"§354. Petition requirements ... 7. Certification of petitions. ... A. The circulator of a nomination petition shall verify by oath or affirmation before a notary public or other person authorized by law to administer oaths or affirmations that the circulator personally witnessed all of the signatures to the petition and that to the best of the circulator's knowledge and belief each signature is the signature of the person whose name it purports to be ... and each person is a resident of the electoral division named in the petition."},{"url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec354.html","quote":"B. The names of presidential electors must be placed on the petition as a slate. The names of the candidates for President and Vice President must be placed on a petition for the nomination of presidential electors."},{"url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec903-A.html","quote":"5. Circulator payment. A person or organization that pays individuals to circulate petitions, other than by reimbursing travel expenses, shall provide a list of those individuals to the Secretary of State along with information indicating the method by which the individuals are being compensated when the petitions are filed pursuant to the Constitution of Maine, Article IV, Part Third, Section 17 or 18."},{"url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec903-A.html","quote":"4. Circulator affidavit. A person who circulates a petition shall execute an affidavit that must include: ... C. That the circulator was a resident of the State and a registered voter in the State at the time of circulating the petition"},{"url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec903-A.html","quote":"Title 21-A: ELECTIONS Chapter 11: BALLOT QUESTIONS ... §903-A. Circulation ... An applicant for a direct initiative or a people's veto referendum pursuant to section 901 shall provide to each person who will be circulating petitions a copy of the laws and rules governing the circulation of petitions for a direct initiative or people's veto"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec354.html","official":true,"dom":"legislature.maine.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/21-a/title21-Asec903-A.html","official":true,"dom":"legislature.maine.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.maine.gov/sos/sites/maine.gov.sos/files/content/assets/MAR24-20rev321-20Fact-20Sheet-20on-20Obtaining-20Data-20from-20CVR.doc","official":true,"dom":"maine.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.maine.gov/sos/elections-voting/voter-data","official":true,"dom":"maine.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"At least 4,000 and not more than 5,000 registered Maine voters for the slate of presidential electors (21-A MRS sec 354(5)(A)); petitions for presidential electors may be signed by any Maine voter statewide (sec 354(2)). Flat statutory range, not a percentage of turnout.","note":"Grounded verbatim at sec 354(5)(A) ('For a slate of candidates for the office of presidential elector, at least 4,000 and not more than 5,000 voters') and sec 354(2) ('except that nomination petitions for presidential electors may be signed by any Maine voter'); Ballotpedia quote also present verbatim. Current per PL 2021 c.273. Independently re-derived from the controlling statute; no refutation found. The 2026 SOS Candidate's Guide omits presidential electors because 2026 is a non-presidential midterm, so the statute is the controlling source for the figure.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST/SAFE-HARBOR: deliver petitions to the municipal registrar for certification by 5 p.m. on May 25 and file with the Secretary of State by 5 p.m. on June 1 of the election year (the earlier of the two conflicting authorities — meeting these also satisfies the statute's later presidential-elector dates). Signatures may not be collected before January 1 of the election year (sec 354(6)). The statute (sec 354(7)(B), (8-A)) on its face provides a later presidential-elector carve-out of July 25 cert / August 1 SOS filing, but DO NOT rely on the later dates without SOS written confirmation.","note":"All three statutory quotes grounded verbatim: sec 354(7)(B) July 25 carve-out, sec 354(8-A) August 1 carve-out, sec 354(6) Jan 1 signing floor. ADVERSARIAL CONFLICT: Ballotpedia's general-election 'Independent candidates' section states for an independent presidential candidate that signatures go to registrars by 5 p.m. May 25 and to the SOS by 5 p.m. June 1 — directly contradicting the draft's July 25/Aug 1. The statute is controlling and its carve-out expressly names 'a slate of candidates for the office of presidential elector,' which matches this access path, so the draft's legal reading is likely correct. But which deadline a candidate must actually meet hinges on a legal interpretation (whether the sec 354 presidential-elector carve-out governs the independent presidential petition), the 2026 SOS guide is silent (non-presidential year), and the downside of error is loss of ballot access — so under strictest-interpretation rules the relied value is the earlier safe-harbor date, pending SOS confirmation. Jan 1 signing floor is clean.","conf":0.55,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No geographic distribution requirement (no per-congressional-district or per-county minimum); presidential-elector petitions may be signed by any Maine voter statewide (21-A MRS sec 354(2)).","note":"Grounded verbatim at sec 354(2). Independently re-derived: sec 354 imposes signature COUNT requirements (sec 354(5)) but no distribution/allocation requirement, and the only geographic qualifier (electoral-division residency of signers) is expressly waived for presidential electors. No refuting provision found.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST: do not assume non-resident or non-registered-voter circulators are permitted. Safest practice is to use circulators who are Maine residents AND registered Maine voters. The statute (sec 354(7)(A)) affirmatively requires only that the circulator personally witness all signatures and swear the notarized oath; it imposes no express age/residency/voter requirement, and Ballotpedia states the circulator need not be a Maine resident — but this is a negative inference from statutory silence and should be confirmed with the SOS before relying on out-of-state or non-voter circulators.","note":"Grounded verbatim: Ballotpedia 'The petition circulator does not have to be a Maine resident...' and sec 354(7)(A) oath language both present. The draft's claim that NO residency/voter requirement applies rests on statutory silence (sec 354 does not affirmatively state circulators may be non-voters; it simply omits the requirement) plus a contrast with the sec 903-A initiative rule. That negative inference is a legal interpretation retrieval cannot conclusively settle, and a wrong assumption can void every signature a disqualified circulator collected. Ballotpedia supports the non-residency reading, but under strictest-interpretation + catastrophic-downside this is a CONSERVATIVE-HOLD pending SOS confirmation.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator certification required: each nomination petition must carry the circulator's oath/affirmation before a notary public (or other authorized officer) that the circulator personally witnessed all signatures and that each signature is genuine and each signer resides in the named electoral division (21-A MRS sec 354(7)(A)). Separately, the candidate's consent must be sworn before a notary (sec 355(3)).","note":"Grounded verbatim at sec 354(7)(A) (circulator oath before a notary) and sec 355(3) ('The candidate must verify by oath or affirmation before a notary public... that the declaration is true'). Independently confirmed from primary text; both a circulator notarization and a candidate-consent notarization are required. No refutation.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper / in-person (wet-ink). Petitions must be on SOS-provided forms (sec 354), signers must personally sign in a manner satisfying the registrar (sec 354(3)), and the 2026 SOS forms must be printed double-sided on 8.5 x 14 legal paper. No online/remote or digitized signature-collection system exists for candidate nomination petitions.","note":"Grounded verbatim: sec 354 'A nomination petition shall be on a form provided by the Secretary of State'; sec 354(3) personal-signature language; and the SOS 'Becoming a Candidate' page 'Petitions must be printed double-sided on 8.5 x 14 inch (legal size) paper.' (markdown bold markers in the fetch are rendering artifacts, not page text). Wet-ink paper, circulator-witnessed, registrar-certified. No e-petition path for candidate access found.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing fee in lieu of, or in addition to, signatures for an independent/non-party candidate. Ballot access is by nomination petition (4,000-5,000 signatures) plus the consent form only (21-A MRS sec 353).","note":"Grounded verbatim at sec 353 ('A person who seeks nomination by petition qualifies by filing a nomination petition and consent as provided in sections 354 and 355'). This is a negative finding from the controlling qualifying statute, which lists only petition + consent and references no fee; sec 354/355 likewise reference no fee. A fee alternative either exists in statute or it does not — it does not — so this is a factual negative, not a contestable legal interpretation. Well-corroborated; no fee option found in the controlling statutes.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Maryland","sigs":"10,000 valid signatures statewide (firm cap; the lesser-of-10,000-or-1% formula resolves to the 10,000 ceiling for President) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"Declaration of Intent by 1st Mon in July; Certificate of Candidacy + petition by 5pm 1st Mon in Aug (Aug 5, 2024 last cycle); electors certified ≥30 days pre-election — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"6 of 7 fields AUTO-LIVE on grounded primary sources (EL 5-703, 6-201/203/204, 8-502/503, 4-102, SBE pages). Sole hold: circulatorEligibility — the negative claim that out-of-state/non-registered circulators are permitted is literally accurate in statute and COMAR but is a litigated, risk-bearing point; over-comply by using MD-registered-voter circulators pending SBE confirmation.","sos":["For an independent/unaffiliated presidential candidate's General Election Candidate Nomination Petition under EL 5-703, may a petition circulator be a non-Maryland resident and/or a person who is not a registered Maryland voter, or does the State Board require circulators to be Maryland registered voters/residents in practice or by any policy beyond EL 6-204 and COMAR 33.06.03.07-.08?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"paid circulation permitted; per-signature structure unaddressed for candidate petitions (no compensation-structure statute, no per-signature ban)","note":"Maryland clearly permits PAID circulators on petitions generally (SBE FAQ, per Ficker v. Montgomery County), and circulators need NOT be Maryland residents or registered voters, so a national paid pool can legally work there. However, NO Maryland statute or official guidance specifically addresses the PER-SIGNATURE compensation STRUCTURE for candidate/nominating petitions — the §16-401 \"thing of value\" prohibition bars paying the SIGNER, not the circulator, and the SBE FAQ confirms paying people to collect signatures is allowed but is silent on per-signature pay. There is no Maryland per-signature ban (Ballotpedia lists MD as \"Permitted\"), but because per-signature specifically is unaddressed for candidate petitions, hold and confirm before structuring pay that way.","sosInquiry":"For an unaffiliated presidential candidate's nominating petition filed under Election Law §5-703/Title 6, may the campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis (e.g., $X per valid signature), or must circulator pay be structured as hourly/salary/bonus only?","citations":[{"url":"https://elections.maryland.gov/petitions/Petition%20Signature%20Gathering%20FAQ.pdf","quote":"Can an organization pay people to collect petition signatures? Yes – per U.S. District Court decision – Ficker vs. Montgomery County, but no one may receive any money or other thing of value in return for signing the petition. Election Law, Section 16-401(a)(2)."},{"url":"https://elections.maryland.gov/petitions/Petition%20Signature%20Gathering%20FAQ.pdf","quote":"Must a petition circulator be a registered voter of Maryland? No.  Must a petition circulator be a resident of Maryland? No."},{"url":"https://elections.maryland.gov/petitions/Petition%20Signature%20Gathering%20FAQ.pdf","quote":"Can an organization pay a consultant to administer and oversee the petition process? Yes."},{"url":"https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gel&section=16-401&enactments=false","quote":"A person may not willfully and knowingly: (1) give, transfer, promise, or offer anything of value for the purpose of inducing another person to sign or not sign any petition; (2) request, receive, or agree to receive, anything of value as an inducement to sign or not to sign any petition;"},{"url":"https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gel&section=6-204&enactments=false","quote":"(a) Each signature page shall contain an affidavit made and executed by the individual in whose presence all of the signatures on that page were affixed and who observed each of those signatures being affixed. ... (c) A circulator must be at least 18 years old at the time any of the signatures covered by the affidavit are affixed."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/md/election-law/md-code-elec-law-sect-5-703.html","quote":"A candidate for public office may be nominated by petition if the candidate is not affiliated with any political party ... Petitions for nomination by petition must be filed as required in Title 6 of this article."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","quote":"Maryland ... Permitted ... Offenses and Penalties Subtitle 4 - Petitions Section 16-401"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ficker_v._Montgomery_County","quote":"Ficker v. Montgomery County is a 1985 ruling of a federal court, the United States District Court for the District of Maryland, that found that a provision in the Maryland election law that prohibited paying individuals to collect signatures on a referendum petition violated the United States Constitution."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://elections.maryland.gov/petitions/Petition%20Signature%20Gathering%20FAQ.pdf","official":true,"dom":"elections.maryland.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gel&section=16-401&enactments=false","official":true,"dom":"mgaleg.maryland.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gel&section=6-204&enactments=false","official":true,"dom":"mgaleg.maryland.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://elections.maryland.gov/voter_registration/data.html","official":true,"dom":"elections.maryland.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/md/election-law/md-code-elec-law-sect-5-703.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ficker_v._Montgomery_County","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"10,000 valid statewide signatures. Statutory formula: lesser of 10,000 registered voters OR 1% of registered voters eligible to vote for the office, floor of 250; for President (statewide) 1% far exceeds 10,000, so the binding number is the 10,000 cap. Count fixed as of January 1 of the primary-election year. New-party path under EL 4-102 is also 10,000.","note":"All 4 citations verbatim: EL 5-703(e)(1) lesser-of-10,000-or-1%/250 floor; EL 5-703(e)(3) Jan 1 of primary year; SBE candidacy page explicitly states 10,000 for unaffiliated statewide candidates; Ballotpedia corroborates. President-is-statewide so cap binds is settled by SBE's own published guidance, not a contested interpretation. EL 4-102(b)(2)(i) confirms new-party 10,000.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Two statutory deadlines: (1) Declaration of Intent not later than the first Monday in July of the general-election year; (2) Certificate of Candidacy AND completed nomination petition by 5 p.m. on the first Monday in August. For President, the slate of presidential electors must be certified to the State Board at least 30 days before the general election. 2024 first Monday in August = Aug 5, 2024 (verified).","note":"EL 5-703(c)(3)(i), 5-703(d)(1), 5-703(f)(1), and 8-503(c)(3) all verbatim. SBE 2026 candidacy page corroborates (Declaration July 6, 2026; second deadline Aug 3, 2026). Calendar-verified Aug 5, 2024. Statutory deadlines, current. Minor non-material nuance: SBE notes some Aug-deadline documents need not be filed in person, but the in-person Certificate-of-Candidacy point belongs to captureMode and does not change the dates.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The unaffiliated/independent presidential 10,000-signature petition is statewide with no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution quota. The 400-signatures-per-congressional-district rule (EL 8-502) applies only to the principal-party PRIMARY ballot, not the independent general-election route.","note":"EL 5-703(e)(1) contains no distribution language (verbatim). EL 8-502(b)(2) verbatim confirms the 400-per-district rule is expressly scoped to placement on the PRIMARY ballot for principal-party presidential candidates. Clear statutory reading; no interpretation needed.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Circulator must be at least 18 years old when any covered signature is affixed and must be the person in whose presence each signature was affixed and who observed each signing (EL 6-204). STRICTEST DEFENSIBLE POSTURE: although neither EL 6-204 nor COMAR 33.06.03.07/.08 textually requires the circulator to be a Maryland registered voter or resident, treat circulators as Maryland registered voters (and require their MD residence address per COMAR 33.06.03.07) to eliminate any residency-challenge risk to the ballot line, pending SBE confirmation. Each SIGNER must be a registered voter assigned to the county on the signature page (EL 6-203(b)(2)).","note":"Affirmative claims grounded and correct: EL 6-204(c) 18+ verbatim; 6-204(a) observe-each-signature verbatim; 6-203(b)(2) signer county-registration verbatim. COMAR 33.06.03.07 requires the circulator's residence address; COMAR 33.06.03.08 requires the affidavit to attest signers are registered voters in the State — neither imposes a circulator residency/registration requirement. The draft's NEGATIVE claim (out-of-state/non-registered circulators allowed) is literally accurate but is a heavily litigated point nationally and SBE practice on out-of-state circulators is not settled by retrieved text; under never-risk-ballot-access this requires SBE confirmation, hence HOLD.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator affidavit (NOT notarized). Each signature page must carry an affidavit executed by the circulator who personally observed every signature on that page being affixed; a signature is validated and counted only if attested by that affidavit. No notary is required for petition signature pages. (The Certificate of Candidacy and Financial Disclosure are notarized for state office, but President has no financial-disclosure requirement.)","note":"EL 6-203(b)(4) (attested by affidavit on the page), 6-201(c)(6) (space for circulator affidavit), 6-204(b) (affidavit contents by regulation) all verbatim. COMAR 33.06.03.08 confirms a signed-and-dated circulator affidavit, not a notarized one. SBE requirements table shows President = No financial disclosure, supporting the notary aside.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures collected on paper State-Board-prescribed pages (the 'General Election Candidate Nomination Petition' for unaffiliated candidates) and filed with the appropriate board; the Certificate of Candidacy must be filed in person and is not available online. Maryland's online signing system covers only statewide referendum/ballot-question petitions — there is NO online/remote digital signature system for an independent presidential candidate nomination petition.","note":"forms/petitions.html verbatim: Certificate of Candidacy filed in person, form not available online; 'Unaffiliated Candidates' lists the General Election Candidate Nomination Petition PDF. EL 5-703 'in the form prescribed by the State Board' verbatim. Online petition forms on the SBE forms page are limited to referendum/charter/new-party/local petitions; no online candidate-petition system exists. Paper-only is current.","conf":0.88,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No filing fee for President (and Vice President); the SBE filing-fee schedule lists no fee for President, and there is no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option. A candidate seeking nomination by petition may not be charged a fee for filing the declaration of intent (EL 5-703(c)(4)). There is no money alternative to the 10,000-signature requirement.","note":"SBE requirements.html Federal Offices table shows President with a blank Filing Fee column (verbatim row matches). EL 5-703(c)(4) verbatim: no fee for the declaration of intent. Maryland has no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures mechanism; the petition is the sole route. Correct and current.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Massachusetts","sigs":"10,000 certified voter signatures, statewide aggregate (fixed by statute, no distribution quota) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"SOS final filing = last Tuesday in August, 5:00 p.m. (solid); local-submission sub-deadline CONFLICTED in draft — HOLD","risk":"All 7 fields ground verbatim to primary sources; 6 are AUTO-LIVE. Only the deadline field is held: the draft is internally inconsistent (calls Aug 20, 2024 the \"28-days-prior submission deadline,\" but Aug 20 is 7 days before the Aug 27 filing, and Ballotpedia says 14 days) — the statute-vs-guidance conflict on the local-submission window is a legal-interpretation question; strictest read protects ballot access by treating local submission as due by the 28th day prior.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT (non-party) presidential-elector nomination petition filed under M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 10 (last Tuesday in August of a presidential year), what is the exact deadline to SUBMIT signed nomination papers to local registrars for certification, and the deadline for registrars to COMPLETE certification — is it the sec. 7 'twenty-eighth day prior / seventh day prior' state-office schedule, or the 14-day schedule, and please confirm the 2028 calendar dates?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Massachusetts candidate-petition law (M.G.L. c. 53 and the Secretary of the Commonwealth's 2026 Candidate's Guide) regulates only the SIGNERS (must be registered voters in the district) and certification by local officials; it does NOT impose any registration/residency requirement on, or oath from, the circulator, and contains NO provision addressing compensation of circulators — so paying per signature on a candidate/independent-presidential nomination paper is unaddressed, not affirmatively permitted. The Massachusetts pay-per-signature and residency rules discussed in Ballotpedia/NCSL apply to ballot-initiative/referendum petitions only and do not carry over to candidate petitions.","sosInquiry":"For an unenrolled candidate's presidential nomination papers under M.G.L. c. 53, does Massachusetts law or regulation permit or prohibit compensating signature gatherers/circulators on a per-signature basis, and must a circulator be a Massachusetts registered voter or resident?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.sec.state.ma.us/divisions/elections/getting-on-the-ballot/how-to-run-for-president.htm","quote":"Signatures must be collected from registered voters and certified by the local election offices in each city and town where you gathered the signatures. ... you will need to submit to the Elections Division at least 10,000 certified signatures"},{"url":"https://www.sec.state.ma.us/divisions/elections/download/getting-on-the-ballot/Candidates-Guide-2026.pdf","quote":"If you are running as a non-party candidate, you can gather signatures from any registered voter in your district. ... Voters must sign their own name. ... Any person can submit your nomination papers to the local election office."},{"url":"https://malegislature.gov/Laws/GeneralLaws/PartI/TitleVIII/Chapter53/Section7","quote":"Every voter signing a nomination paper shall sign in person ... The registrars shall check each name on the nomination paper and shall forthwith certify the number of signatures checked which are names of voters both in the city or town and in the district for which the nomination is made"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_governing_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","quote":"Pay-per-signature is a method of compensating signature gatherers ... who collect signatures for ballot initiatives and veto referendums. ... There are 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process. Sixteen (16) of those states allowed campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. Ten (10) of those states prohibited"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sec.state.ma.us/divisions/elections/getting-on-the-ballot/how-to-run-for-president.htm","official":true,"dom":"sec.state.ma.us"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sec.state.ma.us/divisions/elections/download/getting-on-the-ballot/Candidates-Guide-2026.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sec.state.ma.us"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://malegislature.gov/Laws/GeneralLaws/PartI/TitleVIII/Chapter53/Section7","official":true,"dom":"malegislature.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.mass.gov/info-details/mass-general-laws-c51-ss-47c","official":true,"dom":"mass.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sec.state.ma.us/divisions/elections/voting-information/access-to-voter-information.htm","official":true,"dom":"sec.state.ma.us"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_governing_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"10,000 certified voter signatures, statewide aggregate. Fixed by statute (M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 6 lists 'presidential electors, ten thousand'); not a recomputed percentage. An independent ('Unenrolled') presidential candidate qualifies by filing nomination papers for a slate of presidential electors carrying 10,000 certified signatures. Practitioner guidance: collect well above 10,000 because registrars disqualify non-matching signatures; sec. 7 lets registrars certify the required number increased by two-fifths.","note":"Verbatim in M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 6 ('signed in the aggregate by not less than the following number of voters: for governor and lieutenant governor, attorney general, United States senator, and presidential electors, ten thousand'). Cross-confirmed by Ballotpedia ('At least 10,000 voters must sign this petition') and its historical table (1992-2012 all 10,000, 'Fixed by statute'). The two-fifths language is verbatim in sec. 7. Adversarial check: legal minimum to QUALIFY is 10,000 certified; the +two-fifths is a registrar certification cap / over-collection mechanic, correctly framed as guidance. Current and correct.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Final filing with the Secretary of the Commonwealth: on or before the LAST TUESDAY IN AUGUST of the presidential-election year, by 5:00 p.m. (M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 10) — this part is solid. STRICTEST local-submission read (over-comply): submit signed nomination papers to local registrars no later than the 28th day before the SOS final filing date, by 5:00 p.m., and ensure local certification is COMPLETE no later than the 7th day before final filing (M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 7 state-office schedule). Treat the earliest applicable date as binding until the SOS confirms which sub-schedule (28-day vs 14-day) governs the presidential-elector petition. Do NOT rely on 'August 20' as a 28-day submission deadline — that date is the 7-day certification mark, not the submission deadline.","note":"All citations ground verbatim (sec. 10 'last Tuesday in August'; sec. 10 'before five o'clock'; sec. 7 '28th day... seventh day'; Ballotpedia '14th day preceding'; Ballotpedia table '...8/27/2024'). BUT the draft's value is internally inconsistent: it says local submission is 'at least 28 days before' the SOS filing AND that 'For 2024 the local-submission deadline was August 20, 2024' — arithmetically Aug 20 is exactly 7 days before Aug 27 (the 7-day CERTIFICATION mark), not 28 days (which is July 30). Sources also conflict on the submission window: sec. 7 says 28th day for a 'state office,' while Ballotpedia says the 14th day for the presidential petition. Whether the sec. 7 state-office 28/7 schedule even applies to a presidential-elector paper (filed separately under sec. 10) is a legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle. Held; reliedValue set to the strictest (earliest) defensible submission window.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 10,000 requirement is a single statewide aggregate ('signed in the aggregate by not less than ... ten thousand'). No per-congressional-district or per-county minimum. Signatures are collected per-city/town only procedurally (each local board certifies only its own voters; signatures from more than one city or town may not appear on the same sheet), but no geographic distribution quota applies.","note":"Verbatim sec. 6 ('in the aggregate') and sec. 7 ('Signatures shall not be certified ... from more than one city or town per sheet'). Independently confirmed by the 2026 SOS Candidates Guide: 'You do not, however, need to gather signatures from every city and town in your district, or from a certain number of communities in your district.' No distribution requirement exists. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Massachusetts imposes no statutory eligibility requirement (age/residency/voter-status) on the CIRCULATOR of a nomination paper, and no circulator-registration or circulator-affidavit. The binding constraints are on the SIGNERS: each must be a MA registered voter, signing in person their own name substantially as registered, with their registered address. For a non-party ('Unenrolled') candidate, signatures may be gathered from ANY registered voter (no party-affiliation restriction). A voter physically unable to write may authorize another to sign in the voter's presence. Conservative practice: still use eligible MA-registered circulators since reliance is on signer validity, not circulator status.","note":"Signer rules verbatim in sec. 7 ('Every voter signing a nomination paper shall sign in person as registered ... any voter who is prevented by physical disability ... may authorize some person'). 2026 SOS Guide verbatim: 'If you are running as a non-party candidate, you can gather signatures from any registered voter in your district' and 'Voters should sign their name as they are registered ... Voters must sign their own name.' Adversarial check: MA law is silent on circulators (no affirmative permission, just no restriction); the value correctly states the ABSENCE of a circulator rule and the value direction is safe (the load-bearing constraint, signer validity, is stated correctly), so no ballot-access risk from relying on it.","conf":0.85,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarized circulator affidavit and no circulator certification/oath required. Validity rests on official certification: local boards of registrars certify each signer as a registered voter of their city/town. Separately, a non-party ('Unenrolled') candidate must file with the Secretary a registrar-issued certificate stating the candidate is not enrolled in any political party (M.G.L. c. 53 sec. 6) — this is a certificate ABOUT THE CANDIDATE, not a circulator/witness affidavit on the signature sheets.","note":"Verbatim sec. 6 (Unenrolled certificate from registrars) and sec. 7 (registrars 'check each name ... certify ... and only names so checked shall be deemed ... qualified'). 2026 SOS Guide confirms the non-party Voter Registration Certificate is included on the nomination papers, distinct from any witness oath. No circulator oath/notary exists in the MA scheme. Correct and current.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be collected on official pre-printed paper nomination papers (yellow or beige for non-party/independent candidates) obtained from the Secretary; signers sign in person ('wet') and papers are physically submitted to local registrars for certification, then physically filed with the Secretary (mail accepted only if it physically arrives by the deadline; postmarks do not count). The SOS guidance states the papers cannot be provided electronically. No digital/remote-online pathway exists for an independent presidential petition in Massachusetts.","note":"All three quotes verbatim in the 2026 SOS Candidates Guide: 'papers cannot be provided electronically'; 'Nomination papers for party candidates are white in color, while nomination papers for non-party candidates are yellow or beige'; 'the papers must physically arrive at the election office by the deadline. Postmark dates are not enough...'. Consistent with sec. 7 (per-sheet, in-person signing). Paper-only is correct and current. (The MA online-petition / e-signature pathway covers only certain local/initiative contexts, not this petition.)","conf":0.94,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee for ballot access in Massachusetts and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option; the 10,000 certified signatures are the sole ballot-access qualification. (Separate non-ballot-access obligations exist — FEC statement of candidacy, state OCPF/Ethics filing — but these are not a ballot-access fee and not an alternative to signatures.)","note":"Ballotpedia's 2024 independent-candidate filing table grounds verbatim in page HTML: columns 'Filing fee' = N/A and 'Filing fee formula' = N/A for Massachusetts (row: Massachusetts | 10,000 | Fixed by statute | N/A | N/A | 8/27/2024). No fee or fee-in-lieu appears in M.G.L. c. 53. Note: the quoted string was collapsed in the markdown extraction but is fully present in the page HTML, so grounding holds. Correct and current.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Michigan","sigs":"Signatures DISPUTED: draft says 30,000; statute (1% of 2022 gov vote) = ~44,620 -- HOLD high","deadline":"Deadline LIVE: 4:00 p.m. 110th day before general = Thu Jul 18, 2024","risk":"Only the signature count is unsafe: the draft's flat 30,000 conflicts with its own 1%-formula citation (MCL 168.590b(2)), which on the 2022 gubernatorial total of 4,461,972 yields ~44,620, and Graveline v. Benson (6th Cir. 2021) separately struck the 30,000+distribution+deadline combination for statewide independents -- collect to the highest plausible number (~44,620) and confirm the exact per-cycle figure and Graveline's effect with the Bureau of Elections; all other fields verified live.","sos":["For the 2024 presidential cycle, what is the exact number of valid signatures required for an independent (no-party) presidential qualifying petition under MCL 168.590b -- is it 1% of the 2022 total gubernatorial vote (~44,620), the older 30,000 figure, the Graveline v. Benson interim figure, or another administratively set number?","Does the holding of Graveline v. Benson (6th Cir. 2021) lowering/striking the statewide-independent signature and distribution requirements apply to the independent PRESIDENTIAL qualifying petition, or does the full MCL 168.590b(2)/(4) requirement (1% plus 100 signatures in 1/2 of congressional districts) still govern an independent presidential candidate for 2024?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature pay not prohibited by current law)","note":"Michigan's candidate nominating-petition statute (MCL 168.544c), which independent/no-party presidential candidates use, does NOT address circulator compensation at all — paid vs. volunteer and per-signature pay are unaddressed in the candidate-petition election code. Paid circulators are plainly permitted (2022 GOP gubernatorial candidates used them) and circulator residency is NOT required (non-resident circulators are expressly contemplated); no current Michigan statute prohibits per-signature pay, but a bill to ban it (SB 529-531) is pending as of June 2026, so a national paid pool paid per signature is not affirmatively authorized by any primary source for candidate petitions.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under MCL 168.544c, does Michigan law permit a campaign to pay circulators on a per-signature basis, and must a circulator be a Michigan resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/mi/chapter-168-michigan-election-law/mi-comp-laws-168-544c.html","quote":"The undersigned circulator of the above petition asserts that he or she is 18 years of age or older and a United States citizen; that each signature on the petition was signed in his or her presence ... (16) The provisions of this section except as otherwise expressly provided apply to all petitions circulated under authority of the election law."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/mi/chapter-168-michigan-election-law/mi-comp-laws-168-544c.html","quote":"_____ If the circulator is not a resident of Michigan, the circulator shall make a cross or check mark on the line provided ... the undersigned circulator asserts that he or she is not a resident of Michigan and agrees to accept the jurisdiction of this state for the purpose of any legal proceeding or hearing that concerns a petition sheet executed by the circulator"},{"url":"https://www.michiganpublic.org/politics-government/2025-09-10/per-signature-payments-for-petition-circulators-could-be-outlawed-in-michigan","quote":"A Michigan Senate committee moved forward bills Wednesday to outlaw political petition circulators being paid by the signature as part of a package of election fraud and disinformation deterrents."},{"url":"https://www.michiganpublic.org/politics-government/2025-09-10/per-signature-payments-for-petition-circulators-could-be-outlawed-in-michigan","quote":"In 2022, five Republican candidates for governor were disqualified from the Michigan primary ballot because of fraudulent petition signatures gathered by paid circulators."},{"url":"https://www.michiganpublic.org/politics-government/2025-09-10/per-signature-payments-for-petition-circulators-could-be-outlawed-in-michigan","quote":"The bills now go to the Senate floor. Similar bills cleared the Senate last year, but were never taken up by the House before the session ended in December."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.legislature.mi.gov/Laws/MCL?objectName=mcl-168-522","official":true,"dom":"legislature.mi.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.legislature.mi.gov/Laws/MCL?objectName=mcl-168-509gg","official":true,"dom":"legislature.mi.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.michigan.gov/sos/resources/communities/businesses","official":true,"dom":"michigan.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.michigan.gov/sos/resources/transparency","official":true,"dom":"michigan.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/mi/chapter-168-michigan-election-law/mi-comp-laws-168-544c.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.michiganpublic.org/politics-government/2025-09-10/per-signature-payments-for-petition-circulators-could-be-outlawed-in-michigan","official":false,"dom":"michiganpublic.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 1% of the total votes cast for all gubernatorial candidates at the last gubernatorial election (MCL 168.590b(2)). For the 2024 cycle the 2022 governor's race totaled 4,461,972 votes, so the strict statutory floor is approximately 44,620 valid signatures -- NOT the flat 30,000 the draft headlines. Plus the distribution requirement (>=100 in >=1/2 of congressional districts). Collect to the higher number and confirm the exact operative figure and Graveline's applicability with the Bureau of Elections before relying.","note":"Citations ground verbatim, but the value is self-contradictory and likely understated. The draft headlines 30,000 while its own MCL 168.590b(2) citation states a 1%-of-gubernatorial-vote FORMULA. Independent re-derivation: the 2022 MI governor general election totaled 4,461,972 votes (Whitmer 2,430,505 + Dixon 1,960,635 + others); 1% = 44,620 -- materially above 30,000. The flat 30,000 is the pre-amendment number; the Ballotpedia '30,000' text appears stale. Separately, Graveline v. Benson (6th Cir. 2021) struck the 30,000+distribution+deadline combination for statewide INDEPENDENT candidates (district court set 12,000 interim). The true operative 2024 number (44,620 statutory vs. 30,000 stale vs. 12,000 Graveline interim vs. an administrative figure) is a legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle. Strictest defensible posture: collect to the highest statutory floor (~44,620); over-collecting cannot jeopardize ballot access.","conf":0.86,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"4:00 p.m. on the 110th day before the general November election. For 2024 that is Thursday, July 18, 2024 (110 days before Nov 5, 2024). MCL 168.590c(2). Signatures must be collected within the 180 days immediately before filing (MCL 168.590b(3)).","note":"MCL 168.590c(2) text grounded verbatim ('not later than 4 p.m. of the one hundred-tenth day before the general election'); 180-day window grounded in 590b(3); Ballotpedia corroborates. Date arithmetic independently confirmed: Nov 5, 2024 minus 110 days = Thursday, July 18, 2024. Correct, current, no interpretation needed.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes. At least 100 registered electors must sign in each of at least one-half (1/2) of the state's congressional districts (MCL 168.590b(4), which expressly lists 'the office of president of the United States').","note":"MCL 168.590b(4) grounded verbatim and expressly names president; Ballotpedia corroborates. Adversarial caveat: Graveline v. Benson found the geographic-distribution requirement part of the unconstitutional combination for statewide STATE offices -- whether it survives as applied to independent PRESIDENTIAL is unsettled. But the rule is on the books and complying with it cannot harm ballot access (over-compliance), so it is gated live rather than held. The Graveline question is flagged in the SOS inquiry attached to signaturesRequired.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator must be at least 18 and a U.S. citizen; no Michigan residency required, but a non-resident circulator must mark the designated box on the certificate to accept Michigan jurisdiction (MCL 168.544c(3); HB 5152, 2014, removed residency requirements). Petition signers must be registered/qualified electors of the city/township in the petition heading.","note":"MCL 168.544c certificate text grounded verbatim (18+, U.S. citizen, signed in presence), as is the non-resident-box language and the 544c(3) reference to a 'qualifying petition for an office named in section 590b(4)' (which lists president). Ballotpedia confirms HB 5152 removed all circulator residency requirements. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization of the petition. Each sheet carries a CERTIFICATE OF CIRCULATOR self-attestation (false statement = misdemeanor); the circulator must sign and date it before filing (MCL 168.544c(5)); it is not sworn before a notary. (The candidate's separate Affidavit of Identity includes a campaign-finance statement signed before a notary -- a distinct document, not the petition.)","note":"MCL 168.544c(5) sign-and-date-before-filing rule and the misdemeanor warning grounded verbatim; Ballotpedia confirms the AOI campaign-finance statement is the notarized component (a separate document). No petition notarization required. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wet-ink paper petition sheets signed in the circulator's physical presence; no remote/online or digitized signature path for an independent presidential qualifying petition in Michigan.","note":"MCL 168.544c 'each signature on the petition was signed in his or her presence' grounded verbatim; Ballotpedia signer-address requirement grounded. No statutory authorization for electronic collection located. Paper-only is correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for the independent (no-party) presidential qualifying-petition path -- access is by petition only; no filing fee may substitute. (The $100 fee-in-lieu-of-petition exists only for major-party state LEGISLATIVE nominating petitions.)","note":"Ballotpedia grounded verbatim: '$100 in lieu of filing a nominating petition' applies to a major party state legislative candidate only; the independent path requires an affidavit of identity plus a qualifying petition with no fee alternative. Sore-loser provision separately confirms an independent cannot use a partisan path/fee. Correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"newOrMinorPartyPath","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Materially different. A new party qualifies under MCL 168.685: petitions equal to not less than 1% of the total votes cast for all gubernatorial candidates at the last gubernatorial election, same distribution rule (>=100 in >=1/2 of congressional districts), same 4 p.m. 110th-day deadline, signatures within 180 days; chairperson and secretary file a signed certificate with the petitions, and the party nominates its presidential candidate by convention. Same circulator-certificate/paper mechanics (685(4) incorporates the 544c form).","note":"MCL 168.685(1) long quote grounded verbatim (1% formula, 100-in-1/2-districts distribution, 110-day deadline, 180-day window, certificate filing) and 685(4) 'balance...as set forth in section 544c' grounded verbatim. Correct and current. Note: 685's use of the SAME 1% formula corroborates that the independent statewide signature requirement is the 1% formula (~44,620), reinforcing the doubt on the signaturesRequired '30,000' figure.","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Minnesota","sigs":"2,000 signatures (statutory cap; 1% of statewide turnout vastly exceeds 2,000)","deadline":"77 days before GE — HOLD: draft date Aug 20 2024 is stale; 2028 cycle = Aug 22 2028","risk":"Signatures/fee/notary/distribution/capture all AUTO-LIVE and grounded; the only ballot-access risk is the deadline field, whose stated value (Aug 20, 2024) is for a past cycle — relying on it for a 2028 candidate would be wrong; recompute per cycle and confirm with SOS.","sos":["For the 2028 general election (Tuesday, Nov. 7, 2028), what is the exact last day and time (5:00 p.m.?) by which a non-major-party presidential elector nominating petition under Minn. Stat. 204B.07/204B.09, subd. 1(c) must be RECEIVED — is it the day 77 days before the election (Aug. 22, 2028), and is that an inclusive/exclusive count?","Does Minnesota impose any age, residency, or voter-status requirement on the CIRCULATOR who collects signatures on an independent presidential nominating petition, or do requirements run only to the signers under Minn. Stat. 204B.08, subd. 2?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; MN election code does not regulate candidate-petition circulators at all (no circulator affidavit)","note":"Minnesota's candidate-petition election code (Minn. Stat. ch. 204B and Minn. Rules ch. 8205) does NOT address compensating petition circulators — not per signature, not at all. There is no circulator affidavit, no circulator residency/registration requirement, and no pay-per-signature prohibition for candidate (independent presidential elector) nominating petitions; the code only regulates the candidate, the petition form, and the signers. Compensation is therefore unaddressed (not affirmatively authorized), so per-signature pay is treated conservatively as not-to-be-used pending confirmation. Note MN has no statewide initiative process, so there is no initiative pay-per-signature rule to carry over.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/unaffiliated candidate's nominating petition for presidential electors under Minn. Stat. 204B.07, may a campaign pay the people who gather signatures, and specifically may they be compensated on a per-signature basis? Are there any circulator residency or voter-registration requirements?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.07","quote":"Following the information required by subdivisions 1 and 2 and before the space for signing, each separate page that is part of the petition shall include an oath in the following form: \"I solemnly swear (or affirm) that I know the contents and purpose of this petition, that I do not intend to vote at the primary election for the office for which this nominating petition is made, and that I signed this petition of my own free will.\" Notarization or certification of the signatures on a nominating petition is not required."},{"url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.07","quote":"Other presidential electors or alternates are nominated by petition pursuant to this section."},{"url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.08","quote":"A nominating petition may be signed only by individuals who are eligible to vote for the candidate who is nominated. No individual may sign more than one nominating petition for candidates for the same office unless more than one candidate is to be elected to that office."},{"url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/rules/8205.1020/","quote":"8205.1020 CIRCULATING PETITIONS. Subpart 1. Applicability. This part applies to any petition required for any election in this state, including nominating petitions, recall petitions, and proposed recall petitions. Subp. 2. Photocopies. Petitioners may circulate photocopies of a sample petition page."},{"url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/211B.13","quote":"A person who willfully, directly or indirectly, advances, pays, gives, promises, or lends any money, food, liquor, clothing, entertainment, or other thing of monetary value ... to or for a person, in order to induce a voter to refrain from voting, or to vote in a particular way, at an election, is guilty of a felony."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.07","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mn.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.08","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mn.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/rules/8205.1020/","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mn.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/211B.13","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mn.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/201.091","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mn.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.state.mn.us/election-administration-campaigns/data-maps/registered-voter-list-requests/","official":true,"dom":"sos.state.mn.us"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"2,000 signatures from eligible Minnesota voters (Minn. Stat. 204B.08, subd. 3(a): 1% of last statewide general-election turnout or 2,000, whichever is less — 1% far exceeds 2,000, so 2,000 is the operative number).","note":"Statute quote verbatim at revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/204B.08 subd. 3(a). Ballotpedia verbatim ('At least 2,000 eligible voters must sign the petition'). 1% of ~3M MN voters is ~30,000, so 'whichever is less' fixes 2,000 as the cap. Current (2025 statutes).","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Petition must be RECEIVED by 5:00 p.m. on the day at least 77 days before general election day (Minn. Stat. 204B.09, subd. 1(c)). This recomputes each cycle: for the Nov. 7, 2028 GE the date is Aug. 22, 2028 (NOT the draft's Aug. 20, 2024, which was the 2024-cycle date). Confirm exact date/time with the SOS before relying.","note":"Statutory rule grounded verbatim (204B.09 subd. 1(c): 'may file petitions at least 77 days before the general election day' + 'No affidavit or petition shall be accepted later than 5:00 p.m. on the last day for filing'). BUT the draft's relied VALUE 'August 20, 2024' is stale: today is 2026-06-07 and the next presidential election is Nov 7, 2028, where 77 days before = Aug 22, 2028 (verified by date arithmetic). Relying on the 2024 date for a current candidate would be wrong. Also a latent interpretation: statute phrases the cutoff as 'may file...at least 77 days before' (an earliest-by phrasing) rather than an express last-day; practitioners read the deadline as 77 days before, but exact day/time inclusivity warrants SOS confirmation.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. A single statewide signature total applies (Minn. Stat. 204B.08, subd. 3(a)); no congressional-district, county, or other geographic distribution requirement. Signers need only be eligible Minnesota voters.","note":"204B.08 subd. 3(a) sets one statewide number with no per-district/per-county quota anywhere in 204B.07-204B.08. Grounded verbatim. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"SIGNERS must be individuals eligible to vote for the candidate (eligible MN voters), may not sign more than one petition for the same office, and each must subscribe to the 204B.07 subd. 4 oath (both quotes grounded verbatim). No statutory CIRCULATOR age/residency/voter-status rule was located in 204B.07-204B.08 — but treat 'no circulator requirement' as unconfirmed (absence of a rule) and verify with the SOS rather than assuming none.","note":"Signer requirements and oath are grounded verbatim (204B.08 subd. 2; 204B.07 subd. 4) and correct. The circulator conclusion is a negative inference from statutory silence — defensible, but an absence is inherently harder to verify than a stated rule (SOS guidance or rule could impose one), so I hold it pending SOS confirmation. Strict posture: do not represent to volunteers that there is definitely no circulator restriction.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Petition signatures: NO notarization or witness/circulator certification ('Notarization or certification of the signatures on a nominating petition is not required.', 204B.07 subd. 4). Candidate affidavit: YES, each nominated president/VP candidate must submit a signed, NOTARIZED affidavit of candidacy (204B.07 subd. 2(c)), signed before a notarial officer (204B.09 subd. 1(b)).","note":"204B.07 subd. 4 signature-notarization quote grounded verbatim. The affidavit quote is verbatim as a prefix ('...affidavit of candidacy for president or vice president'); the statute continues '...that includes the following information:' — the draft truncated, not misquoted. 204B.09 subd. 1(b) confirms notarial signing. Correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. No online/digital petition system exists; signatures collected on paper pages bearing the oath, each signer writing residence/mailing address (204B.07 subd. 4). Petition and notarized affidavits submitted by mail or hand and received by 5:00 p.m. on the last filing day; electronic submission statutorily barred (204B.09 subd. 1(e), notwithstanding ch. 325L) except a narrow emergency fax/scan option for out-of-state candidates (subd. 1a(b)).","note":"204B.09 subd. 1(e) mail/hand-notwithstanding-325L quote grounded verbatim; 204B.07 subd. 4 signer-address quote grounded verbatim. Subd. 1(e) literally names 'Affidavits,' but subd. 2 also bars electronic for nominating petitions and no online petition system exists, so paper-only is correct in practice and current.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Not applicable / no fee. Presidential electors pay no filing fee (204B.11 subd. 1(b): 'For the office of presidential elector...no filing fee is required'); the 2,000-signature nominating petition is itself the access mechanism. The separate 204B.11 subd. 2 'petition in place of a filing fee' (2,000 for president) is not the operative route because no fee applies.","note":"Both 204B.11 quotes grounded verbatim (subd. 1(b) no-fee; subd. 2(a) 2,000-signature fee substitute). Draft correctly distinguishes the inapplicable fee-substitution path. Correct and current.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Mississippi","sigs":"1,000 signatures (flat statutory floor) + 6-elector slate + $2,500 fee — all three required, AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"5:00 p.m., 60 days before general election (actual-receipt); 2024 = Sept 6 — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"6 of 7 fields ground cleanly and triangulate across statute + SOS guide + Ballotpedia. Only circulatorEligibility is held (proving-a-negative on unwritten practice). No field is BLOCKED; ballot-access risk is low if signatures are clerk-certified well before deadline.","sos":["For an independent presidential nominating petition under Miss. Code Ann. 23-15-785, are there any requirements (residency, age, MS voter registration) governing WHO may circulate/collect the petition signatures, or any written or unwritten administrative practice limiting circulators? (No circulator affidavit appears on the form; please confirm.)"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Mississippi's candidate/election-code petition statutes (Miss. Code 23-15-785 for independent presidential petitions and 23-15-359 generally) do NOT address compensation of candidate-petition circulators at all — neither per-signature pay, paid circulation in general, nor circulator residency/registration are mentioned. The frequently cited \"Mississippi permits pay-per-signature\" rule (and Term Limits Leadership Council v. Clark, 1997) comes only from the INITIATIVE/ballot-measure code (Title 23, Chapter 17, Sec. 57), a separate chapter that does not govern candidate petitions, so it must not be carried over. Treat candidate-petition compensation as unaddressed and hold conservatively.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition under Miss. Code Ann. 23-15-785, does Mississippi law permit a campaign to pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis (and may circulators be paid at all, e.g., hourly), and must a circulator be a Mississippi resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ms/title-23-elections/ms-code-sect-23-15-785.html","quote":"the Secretary of State of Mississippi shall certify to the circuit clerks of the several counties the names of all candidates for President and Vice President who are nominated by any national convention or other like assembly of any political party or by written petition signed by at least one thousand (1,000) qualified voters of this state. ... Any nominating petition, to be valid, must contain the signatures as well as the addresses of the petitioners."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ms/title-23-elections/ms-code-sect-23-15-359/","quote":"A petition requesting that an independent or special election candidate's name be placed on the ballot for any office shall be filed as provided for in subsection (3) or (4) of this section, as appropriate, and shall be signed by not less than the following number of qualified electors ... (h) For the Office of President of the United States, a party nominee or independent candidate shall pay an assessment in the amount of Two Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00)."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Mississippi","quote":"The relevant statutes do not specify residency requirements or other regulations for petition circulators."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","quote":"Mississippi | Permitted | Mississippi Code, Title 23, Chapter 17, Section 57"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.ms.gov/sites/default/files/elections/2025%20Voter%20File%20Weekly%20Distribution%20Program.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.ms.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.ms.gov/elections-voting","official":true,"dom":"sos.ms.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ms/title-23-elections/ms-code-sect-23-15-785.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ms/title-23-elections/ms-code-sect-23-15-359/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Mississippi","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://app.smartsheet.com/b/form/5c8b666a679c4c148eb513c8981a4962","official":false,"dom":"app.smartsheet.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 valid signatures — a flat statutory minimum (written nominating petition signed by not less than 1,000 qualified/registered Mississippi voters), NOT a percentage; same 1,000 applies to a minor party qualifying by petition. Must be accompanied by a slate of 6 presidential electors, each signing a consent/pledge statement.","note":"Both citation quotes ground VERBATIM: FindLaw 23-15-785(1) ('...written petition signed by at least one thousand (1,000) qualified voters of this state.') and SOS forms page ('...signatures of not less than 1,000 qualified electors of this state, must also be accompanied by a list of Presidential electors...'). Triangulated by Ballotpedia ('At least 1,000 qualified state voters must sign the petition') and the official 2026 SOS Candidate Qualifying Guide, which lists for the independent presidential candidate: petition of not less than 1,000 + 6-elector slate + $2,500 fee. 23-15-785(3) confirms a list equal to the number of electors (6 for MS) each executing the consent statement. 'at least'=floor, so the draft's 'flat fixed number, not a recompute' framing is correct.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Petition + 6-elector slate + $2,500 fee must be filed with the State Board of Election Commissioners (in the Office of the Secretary of State) by 5:00 p.m. not less than sixty (60) days before the general election. Recomputes each cycle off the November general-election date (2024 example: Sept 6, 2024). If filing by mail, it is an actual-receipt deadline, not postmark.","note":"FindLaw 23-15-785(2) grounds VERBATIM ('...by 5:00 p.m. not less than sixty (60) days previous to the day of the election.'). 60-day rule corroborated by Ballotpedia ('filed with the secretary of state by 5:00 p.m. 60 days prior to the general election'). Computation verified: Nov 5, 2024 minus 60 days = Fri Sept 6, 2024 (exactly 60 days). Exact Sept 6, 2024 date independently confirmed by news source (gwcommonwealth.com): 'independent and party presidential candidates have to submit all required paperwork and fees by Sept. 6, 2024.' Actual-receipt-not-postmark confirmed verbatim in the 2026 SOS Candidate Qualifying Guide. NOTE: the 2026 guide is a midterm guide (no presidential office in 2026, gen. election Nov 3, 2026); the specific calendar date must be recomputed for 2028 (Nov 7, 2028 -> ~Sept 8, 2028). Rule itself is current and correct; clear statutory computation, not a contestable legal interpretation.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. For an independent (or minor-party-by-petition) presidential candidate the 1,000 signatures may be gathered from qualified voters of the State at large; no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement. The 100-per-district / 500-statewide alternative belongs ONLY to the presidential PRIMARY petition path (Miss. Code 23-15-1093), which does not apply to the independent general-election petition.","note":"Quote 'written petition signed by at least one thousand (1,000) qualified voters of this state' grounds VERBATIM in 23-15-785. Independently confirmed: 23-15-359(1)(a) sets 'For an office elected by the state at large, not less than one thousand (1,000) qualified electors' with NO geographic breakdown. The 2026 SOS guide shows the 100-per-Congressional-district / 500-statewide alternative only under the Presidential Preference PRIMARY (party-candidate) section, and the independent general-election section reads simply '1,000 ... of the State of Mississippi.' 23-15-1093 governs the primary petition (filed Jan 1-15), confirming the draft's distinction. No district distribution for the independent path.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT/over-comply default until SOS confirms: treat circulators as potentially required to be Mississippi-qualified electors (registered voters) and residents. The only person-level requirement that retrieval can confirm runs to the SIGNERS (each must be a qualified elector of MS, verified via circuit-clerk certification of registration); no circulator age/residency/voter-status statute or affidavit was found, but absence of an UNWRITTEN administrative practice cannot be proven by retrieval.","note":"Signer-requirement quote grounds VERBATIM on SOS page ('Be a qualified elector (registered voter) of the State of Mississippi and of the district...'). Adversarial point: the draft VALUE itself flags 'UNKNOWN whether any unwritten administrative practice limits who may circulate.' Confirming a true negative (no circulator rule anywhere, including unwritten SOS practice) is beyond retrieval and is the kind of legal-interpretation question the gate reserves for hold. Structurally, MS has no circulator affidavit and signatures are clerk-certified against the signer's own registration, so circulator identity is largely irrelevant in practice — but under the never-risk-ballot-access mandate I hold and route to the SOS. Added an SOS inquiry.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notary and no circulator affidavit. Each petition's signatures must be CERTIFIED by the circuit clerk of the county where the signatures were collected, BEFORE the petition is filed with the Secretary of State; obtain clerk certification well in advance of the qualifying deadline. 'Header' information must be completed on each petition page BEFORE signatures are gathered.","note":"Both quotes ground VERBATIM. SOS forms page: 'All signatures on petitions for independent or special election candidates MUST be certified by the signer's circuit or municipal clerk respectively before filing with the appropriate office.' 2026 SOS Candidate Qualifying Guide (extracted via pdftotext): 'a. All petition signatures must be certified by each Circuit Clerk's Office of the county from where the signatures were collected, and b. All \"header\" information must be completed on each petition page prior to obtaining voters' signatures.' Critically, the guide lists these two items expressly under 'As an Independent Candidate for the General Election' for U.S. President, so the requirement is confirmed for the independent presidential petition. No notary requirement appears anywhere.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wet-ink paper petitions gathered by hand and certified by county circuit clerks; SOS provides only downloadable paper petition forms (President Candidate_Independent Candidate_Petition) that must be printed, signed, and clerk-certified. No digital/online filing exists for the independent presidential petition.","note":"Quote grounds VERBATIM: FindLaw 23-15-359(11) 'The petition required by this section may not be filed by using the Internet.' Caveat on citation SCOPE: that internet-ban lives in 23-15-359, whose petition language is mirrored by 23-15-785 for the presidential filing; arguably 'this section' refers to 23-15-359's petition, so the ban is not the tightest possible citation for the 23-15-785 presidential petition specifically. BUT the paper conclusion is independently dispositive regardless of that scope question: signatures must be wet-ink and county-clerk-certified (incompatible with online filing), and the SOS publishes only printable paper forms (verified on SOS forms page). Bottom line 'paper' is correct and not interpretation-dependent.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option exists. A mandatory $2,500.00 qualifying assessment for the Office of President is payable to the MS Secretary of State and is required IN ADDITION to (not instead of) the 1,000-signature petition and the 6-elector slate. Same $2,500 presidential assessment applies to a party nominee. Fee revenue is deposited into the Elections Support Fund.","note":"Both quotes ground VERBATIM: FindLaw 23-15-359(1)(h) '(h) For the Office of President of the United States, a party nominee or independent candidate shall pay an assessment in the amount of Two Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00).' and SOS forms page ('...submitted with a qualifying fee of $2,500 to the Secretary of State's Office.'). 23-15-359(5) confirms deposit into the Elections Support Fund (23-15-5). The 2026 SOS guide lists, for the independent presidential candidate, BOTH a 1,000-signature petition AND a $2,500 fee AND the 6-elector slate as separate required items — confirming the fee is additive, not an alternative. Field is mislabeled 'feeAlternative' but the substance (no alternative; fee is mandatory and additional) is correct.","conf":0.96,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Missouri","sigs":"10,000 signatures (collect a cushion; statewide statutory floor)","deadline":"15th Monday before Nov general (Jul 29, 2024 last cycle)","risk":"All 6 citation sources grounded verbatim; core path (10k sigs, 15th-Monday deadline, paper+notary, elector district distribution) is AUTO-LIVE. Only the circulator-residency rule is held for legal interpretation; treat as MO-resident-required and confirm with SOS.","sos":["For an independent/new-party presidential nominating petition under RSMo 115.321/115.325, must the circulator (affiant) be a Missouri resident as an enforceable eligibility requirement, and is there any age or registered-voter requirement for circulators? Does the office reject pages whose affiant is a non-resident?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (Ch. 115); circulator must be a Missouri resident","note":"Missouri's candidate/independent-petition chapter (RSMo Ch. 115, incl. 115.321 for independent presidential petitions, 115.325 form/affidavit, and 115.631 election offenses) does NOT address compensating circulators at all — per-signature pay is unaddressed, neither permitted nor prohibited by any candidate-petition primary source found. The candidate circulator's affidavit in 115.325 requires the circulator to swear they are \"a resident of the state of Missouri,\" so circulator residency IS required (a national non-resident paid pool could not lawfully circulate). Note: the per-signature rules people cite live in Ch. 116 (initiative/referendum), which does NOT govern candidate petitions and was not carried over; and even Ch. 116 (116.030 affidavit) expressly contemplates PAID circulators rather than banning per-signature pay.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition under RSMo Chapter 115 (115.321/115.325), does Missouri law permit a campaign to pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and must every circulator be a Missouri resident (or registered Missouri voter) as the 115.325 affidavit's \"a resident of the state of Missouri\" language implies?","citations":[{"url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.321","quote":"115.321.  Independent candidate, how nominated. — 1.  Any person desiring to be an independent candidate for any office to be filled by voters throughout the state ... shall file a petition with the secretary of state. ... If independent candidates for presidential elector are to be nominated, a number of independent candidates for presidential elector equal to the number of electors to which the state is entitled shall be nominated by one petition ... 3.  If an independent candidate is to be nominated for a statewide office, the petition shall be signed by at least ten thousand registered voters of the state."},{"url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.325","quote":"CIRCULATOR'S AFFIDAVIT ... I, ______, a resident of the state of Missouri, being first duly sworn, say ... signed this page of the foregoing petition, and each of them signed his or her name thereto in my presence; I believe that each ... is a registered voter of the state of Missouri and ______ County."},{"url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.631","quote":"115.631.  Class one election offenses. — The following offenses, and any others specifically so described by law, shall be class one election offenses and are deemed felonies connected with the exercise of the right of suffrage. [Enumerated offenses (1)-(26) concern false affidavits, illegal voting/registration, and ballot tampering; none addresses paying petition circulators per signature.]"},{"url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=116.080","quote":"116.080.  Qualifications of circulator — affidavit, notarization, penalty. — 1.  Each petition circulator shall be at least eighteen years of age and registered with the secretary of state. ... A petition circulator shall be deemed registered at the time such circulator delivers a signed circulator's affidavit pursuant to section 116.030, with respect to a referendum petition, or section 116.040, with respect to an initiative petition, to the office of the secretary of state."},{"url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=116.030","quote":"I am at least 18 years of age. I do ______ do not ______ (check one) expect to be paid for circulating this petition. If paid, list the payer ______"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.321","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.325","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.631","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=116.080","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=116.030","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.157","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=115.158","official":true,"dom":"revisor.mo.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.mo.gov/elections","official":true,"dom":"sos.mo.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Availability_of_state_voter_files","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"10,000 signatures of registered Missouri voters (fixed statutory floor for a statewide office under RSMo 115.321.3; same 10,000 governs the new/minor-party statewide petition under RSMo 115.315.5). For president, ONE petition nominates the full slate of presidential electors, with the presidential and vice-presidential candidates named on each page. Operationally, collect well above 10,000 because the SOS validates signatures and invalidations are common.","note":"RSMo 115.321.3 ('signed by at least ten thousand registered voters of the state') and 115.315.5 ('at least ten thousand registered voters of the state obtained at large') both grounded verbatim on revisor.mo.gov. 10,000 is a fixed number for statewide office (does not recompute per cycle), unlike the district/county 2%-or-10k-whichever-is-less rule in 115.321.4. Statute says 10,000 registered voters must SIGN; 'valid' is the practical net after SOS review, so a cushion is advisable, but the threshold number 10,000 is correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5:00 p.m. on the fifteenth Monday immediately preceding the November general election (RSMo 115.329.1). For the 2024 cycle (general Nov. 5, 2024) this is July 29, 2024 — independently confirmed by date computation. It is a recomputed rule, not a fixed date. Petition cannot be filed before 8:00 a.m. on the day after the prior general election.","note":"RSMo 115.329.1 grounded verbatim (window between 8:00 a.m. day after prior general and 5:00 p.m. fifteenth Monday before the general). Ballotpedia quote also grounded verbatim. Independently re-derived: counting Mondays back from Nov 5, 2024 (a Tuesday), the 15th Monday is 2024-07-29 — matches the draft exactly.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No geographic distribution quota on the SIGNATURES (the 10,000 are obtained 'at large'). There IS a distribution requirement on the ELECTOR NOMINEES: at least one qualified resident of each congressional district must be named as a presidential-elector nominee (RSMo 115.321.2). Separately, each petition page may carry signatures from only one county and pages must be numbered in sequence per county (RSMo 115.325.1) — a sheet-organization rule, not a per-county signature quota.","note":"RSMo 115.321.2 grounded verbatim ('At least one qualified resident of each congressional district shall be named as a nominee for presidential elector'). 'obtained at large' grounded in 115.315.5. The one-county-per-page / numbered-in-sequence rule grounded verbatim in 115.325.1. Draft correctly separates the elector-nominee district requirement from the (absent) signature distribution quota.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST reading: treat the circulator (affiant who obtains signatures) as required to be a resident of the State of Missouri (the statutory affidavit form in RSMo 115.325 recites 'I, ___, a resident of the state of Missouri'). Use Missouri-resident circulators to avoid any page being rejected. Each SIGNER must be a registered Missouri voter of the county shown on the page (felony to sign if not registered); no voter may sign more than one nomination for one office (RSMo 115.323).","note":"All quotes grounded verbatim in 115.325 (affidavit form) and 115.323. BUT the 'resident of the state of Missouri' language appears in a FORM TEMPLATE recital, not an operative eligibility clause; whether it is an enforceable circulator-residency REQUIREMENT (vs. a recital the affiant happens to make) is a legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle. Added constitutional doubt: circulator-residency requirements have been struck in other states (Buckley v. ACLF line). Strictest defensible posture is to assume MO residency is required and use only MO-resident circulators. Signer requirements (registered MO voter, one-signature-per-office) are clear and grounded.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"BOTH a circulator certification AND notarization are required on EVERY page. Each page carries a CIRCULATOR'S AFFIDAVIT (circulator swears each signer signed in his/her presence and is a registered voter), which must be 'Subscribed and sworn to before me' a Notary Public (notary signature, seal, and commission-expiration appear on the form) — RSMo 115.325.","note":"Grounded verbatim in the 115.325 statutory form: the circulator's-presence/registered-voter recital, 'Subscribed and sworn to before me this ___ day of ___, A.D.___', 'Signature of Notary', and 'Notary Public (Seal)'. Confirms notarized circulator affidavit per page. Substantial-compliance saving clause ('disregarding clerical and merely technical errors') exists but does not eliminate the notarization requirement.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper (wet-ink). Pages of uniform size, signatures from only one county per page, numbered in sequence per county, each page bearing a notarized circulator's affidavit (RSMo 115.325.1 + the statutory form). No Missouri online/digital signature system covers an independent/new-party PRESIDENTIAL nominating petition; collect and submit on paper to the Secretary of State.","note":"RSMo 115.325.1 grounded verbatim (uniform pages, one county per page, numbered in sequence). 115.321 'file a petition with the secretary of state' grounded verbatim. The per-page notarized wet-ink affidavit makes paper the operative and strictest-safe capture mode. The 'no digital system exists' point is a negative assertion, but paper is unambiguously sufficient and required by the form, so reliance carries no ballot-access risk.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing-fee alternative to (or addition to) the signature petition for an independent or new-party presidential candidate; the 10,000-signature petition (RSMo 115.321 / 115.329) is the sole qualification mechanism on this path. Chapter 115 filing fees apply to party-primary declarations of candidacy, not to independent/new-party petitions. STRICTEST operating assumption: do not rely on any fee shortcut — you must complete the petition.","note":"Cited quote (115.321.5, 'placed on the official ballot as an independent candidate') grounds verbatim but speaks to ballot placement rather than fees; the 'None' conclusion is a negative claim derived from the absence of any fee-in-lieu provision in 115.321/115.329. 'None' is itself the conservative posture (assuming no fee shortcut never risks ballot access), so AUTO-LIVE is appropriate. If a campaign wanted to rely on a fee path it does NOT exist — so the value cannot mislead toward under-collecting signatures.","conf":0.82,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Montana","sigs":"5,000 signatures (5% of last governor's vote OR 5,000, whichever is less; 5,000 cap controls — unchanged by 2025 HB 207, which touched only non-presidential)","deadline":"Petition filed with SOS 76 days before general (2024 = Aug 21); signatures to county admins ≥1 week earlier (2024 = Aug 14)","risk":"All 7 citations grounded verbatim (NASS PDF verified via download). Four fields AUTO-LIVE; three on CONSERVATIVE-HOLD for legal-characterization questions (distribution-path separation, circulator residency/eligibility, and whether 13-10-202 fees reach a presidential petitioner) — none should be relied on as \"no requirement\" without SOS confirmation, to avoid ballot-access risk.","sos":["Distribution: For an INDEPENDENT presidential nominating petition under MCA 13-10-504, is there any requirement that signatures be distributed across legislative or other districts, or is the only requirement the statewide total (5% of last governor's vote or 5,000 electors, whichever is less)? Please confirm the 1/3-of-legislative-districts distribution rule applies ONLY to minor-party qualification under 13-10-601 and not to the 13-10-504 candidate petition.","Circulator eligibility: For a 13-10-504 presidential petition, must signature gatherers (circulators) be Montana residents and/or registered Montana electors, or may out-of-state and non-elector circulators gather signatures? Are there any age or registration requirements for circulators beyond the prohibition on per-signature payment in 13-27-102?","Filing fee: Does an independent or non-qualified-party candidate for president/vice president filing a petition under MCA 13-10-504 owe any filing fee (e.g., under 13-10-202), or is the petition the sole condition of access with no fee due and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; initiative pay-per-signature ban is confined to Title 13 ch. 27 (ballot issues) and expressly excludes candidates","note":"For an independent PRESIDENTIAL candidate petition, Montana's election code does NOT address circulator compensation at all — neither permitting nor prohibiting per-signature pay. Montana's only pay-per-signature ban (MCA 13-27-102(2)) sits in Title 13, ch. 27 (\"Statewide Ballot Issues\") and, together with the paid-signature-gatherer scheme in 13-27-112, is by its own definitions limited to initiatives/referenda/constitutional conventions and expressly excludes a \"candidate\"; the presidential-candidate statute (13-10-504(2)) borrows only Chapter 27's affidavit and signature-verification procedures (13-27-302 through 13-27-306), not the compensation ban. No Montana candidate-petition statute imposes a circulator residency requirement (only signers must be Montana electors of the district), so an out-of-state paid pool is legally permissible; per-signature pay is treated as unaddressed and held conservatively.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT PRESIDENTIAL candidate's nominating petition under MCA 13-10-504 (not a ballot issue under Title 13, ch. 27), may a campaign pay circulators on a per-signature basis, or does any provision (e.g., the 13-27-102(2) ban) apply to candidate-petition circulators? Are candidate-petition circulators subject to any residency or registration requirement?","citations":[{"url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0270/part_0010/section_0020/0130-0270-0010-0020.html","quote":"TITLE 13. ELECTIONS / CHAPTER 27. STATEWIDE BALLOT ISSUES / Part 1. General Provisions ... 13-27-102. Who may petition and gather signatures. (1) A petition may be signed only by a qualified elector of the state of Montana. (2) A person gathering signatures for a petition may not be paid anything of value based upon the number of signatures gathered."},{"url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0270/part_0010/section_0120/0130-0270-0010-0120.html","quote":"(5) As used in subsections (2) and (3) ... (c)(i) \"Person\" has the meaning provided in 13-1-101 and includes a political committee. (ii) The term does not include a candidate. (d)(i) \"Person who employs a paid signature gatherer\" means a political party, political committee, or other person seeking to place a ballot issue before the electors. ... (e) \"Signature gatherer\" means an individual who collects signatures on a petition for the purpose of an initiative, a referendum, or the calling of a constitutional convention."},{"url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0040/0130-0100-0050-0040.html","quote":"13-10-504. Independent or minor party candidates for president or vice president. (1) An individual who desires to run for president or vice president as an independent candidate ... shall file a petition for nomination with the secretary of state 76 days prior to the date of the general election. (2) The petition and the affidavits of circulation required by 13-27-302 must first be submitted ... to the election administrator in the county where the signer resides for verification and certification by the procedures provided in 13-27-303 through 13-27-306. (3) The petition must have the signatures of electors equal to 5% or more of the total votes cast for the successful candidate for governor at the last general election or 5,000 electors, whichever is less."},{"url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0010/0130-0100-0050-0010.html","quote":"13-10-501. ... (1) Except as provided in 13-10-504, nominations for public office by an independent candidate or a political party that does not meet the requirements of 13-10-601 may be made by filing a declaration of intent and paying the filing fee in accordance with 13-10-201 and by circulating a petition for nomination. ... (5) Each sheet of a petition must contain signatures of electors residing in only one county."},{"url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0020/0130-0100-0050-0020.html","quote":"13-10-502. Signature requirements for petition. (1) The petition for nomination must be signed by active electors as defined in 13-1-101 residing within the state and district or political subdivision in which the officer or officers are to be elected."},{"url":"https://sosmt.gov/candidate-petition-signatures-submitted-to-montana-counties-election-officials-to-verify-and-certify","quote":"Tuesday evening was the deadline for independent and minor party candidates to submit signed petitions to county election administrators across Montana ... Montana law outlines the signature requirements that each candidate must receive (13-10-502, MCA)."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0270/part_0010/section_0020/0130-0270-0010-0020.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0270/part_0010/section_0120/0130-0270-0010-0120.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0040/0130-0100-0050-0040.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0010/0130-0100-0050-0010.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0100/part_0050/section_0020/0130-0100-0050-0020.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sosmt.gov/candidate-petition-signatures-submitted-to-montana-counties-election-officials-to-verify-and-certify","official":true,"dom":"sosmt.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sosmt.gov/elections/voter-file/","official":true,"dom":"sosmt.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/mca/title_0130/chapter_0020/part_0010/section_0220/0130-0020-0010-0220.html","official":true,"dom":"archive.legmt.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://app.mt.gov/voterfile/","official":true,"dom":"app.mt.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Signatures of electors equal to 5% or more of the total votes cast for the successful candidate for governor at the last general election, OR 5,000 electors, whichever is less. The 5,000 cap controls in practice (5% of the 2020 gubernatorial winner Gianforte's ~328,000 votes is ~16,400, far above 5,000), so the operative requirement for an independent presidential petition is 5,000 signatures. Recomputes each cycle off the most recent governor's race.","note":"All three citations grounded verbatim: MCA 13-10-504(3) (leg.mt.gov), NASS July-2024 PDF (verified via download — quote present p. Montana section), and ballot-access.org ('Presidential independents continue to need 5,000 signatures'). Adversarial: confirmed 2025 HB 207 lowered only NON-presidential petitions (5%->4%); the presidential path under 13-10-504 is unchanged. 5,000 cap independently re-derived from 2020 Gianforte vote (~328k). No interpretation required — statute is explicit.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The nominating petition must be filed with the Secretary of State no later than 76 days before the general election (statutory rule, MCA 13-10-504(1)). Petition signatures must first be submitted to the county election administrator for verification at least 1 week before the SOS filing deadline (13-10-504(2)). For the 2024 cycle (Nov 5, 2024) this computed to an Aug 21, 2024 SOS deadline and an Aug 14, 2024 county-submission deadline. The calendar dates recompute each cycle off the 76-day / 1-week rule.","note":"76-day SOS rule and the '1 week before' county-submission rule both grounded verbatim in MCA 13-10-504(1)-(2). Independently verified the arithmetic: Nov 5 2024 - 76 days = Wed Aug 21 2024; minus 1 week = Wed Aug 14 2024 — both match the draft. Adversarial note: a Ballotpedia 2024 'passed-deadlines' list shows '(August 19)' linked to a 2020 page (appears stale and is NOT relied on); the statutory 76-day rule is authoritative. Both the SOS filing deadline AND the earlier county-verification deadline are binding — captured.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"For the independent / non-qualified-party PRESIDENTIAL petition (MCA 13-10-504), the grounded statutory text imposes only a statewide signature total (5% / 5,000 cap) with no express per-district distribution requirement. STRICTEST reading pending SOS confirmation: do not assume zero distribution requirement — the 1/3-of-legislative-districts distribution rule that appears in the minor-PARTY qualification path (13-10-601, per the NASS summary) must be confirmed by the SOS as NOT applying to a 13-10-504 candidate petition before treating distribution as 'none'.","note":"Citations grounded verbatim (MCA 13-10-504(3) and NASS PDF). Adversarial: the NASS text confirms the 1/3-of-legislative-districts distribution requirement attaches to the PARTY-qualification path, not the individual candidate petition — strongly supporting 'none' for the independent path. But correctness hinges on a legal characterization (which statutory path binds an independent presidential candidate). Per gate rule, grounded + interpretation -> CONSERVATIVE-HOLD; SOS inquiry filed. Getting this wrong (missing a distribution requirement) would risk ballot access, so over-comply.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Grounded facts: (a) a petition may be signed ONLY by a qualified Montana elector, and (b) a circulator may not be paid based on the number of signatures gathered (MCA 13-27-102). STRICTEST reading on circulator residency/eligibility: do NOT assume out-of-state or non-elector circulators are permitted, and do not rely on the 'prior residency rule held unconstitutional' assertion. Ballotpedia only states the statutes 'do not specify circulator requirements' — silence is not affirmative permission. Confirm circulator residency/registration/age rules with the SOS before deploying non-resident or non-elector circulators.","note":"Both citations grounded verbatim: Ballotpedia ('The statutes do not specify circulator requirements (e.g., residency status).') and 13-27-102 (signer must be a qualified MT elector; no per-signature pay). Adversarial: the draft's claims that out-of-state circulators ARE permitted and that a 'prior residency rule was held unconstitutional' are NOT supported by the grounded quotes — they are added legal conclusions from statutory silence. Strictest interpretation treats circulator eligibility as unsettled. CONSERVATIVE-HOLD; SOS inquiry filed. The pay-per-signature ban and elector-signer rule, by themselves, are safe to rely on.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator affidavit required. An affidavit of circulation (in substantially the statutory form) must be attached to each petition sheet/section, in which the gatherer swears the signatures are genuine and signers knew the petition's contents; it must be subscribed and sworn before a person authorized to administer oaths (notarized) and must note the date of the first signature and the circulator's address. MCA 13-10-504(2) expressly requires the 13-27-302 affidavits of circulation.","note":"Both citations grounded verbatim: MCA 13-27-302 affidavit form ('Subscribed and sworn to before me this ___ day of _________, 20__' + '(Person authorized to take oaths)') and Ballotpedia ('The affidavits must also be notarized.'). The notarization requirement is explicit on the face of the statutory form — no interpretation needed. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures are collected on paper petition sheets, each with a notarized circulator affidavit, then submitted to county election administrators for verification before the petition is filed with the Secretary of State. No remote-online or digitized capture exists for an independent presidential nominating petition in Montana.","note":"Both citations grounded verbatim: MCA 13-10-504(2) (county-administrator verification/certification) and 13-27-302 ('An affidavit ... must be attached to each sheet or section submitted to the county official'). The physical-sheet + county-submission model is on the face of the statute; no online capture authorized. No interpretation required. AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option is offered for the presidential petition; the petition is the access mechanism. STRICTEST reading on whether ANY filing fee is owed: do not assume a $0 fee. MCA 13-10-504 itself contains no fee, but MCA 13-10-202 makes independent and non-qualified-party candidates liable for the same filing fees as party candidates; whether that general fee provision reaches a presidential petitioner under 13-10-504 is a legal-characterization question. Confirm with the SOS that no filing fee is due before treating the petition path as fee-free.","note":"Both citations grounded verbatim (MCA 13-10-504(1) and NASS PDF). Adversarial: the draft itself flags MCA 13-10-202, which imposes fees on independent / non-qualified-party candidates equal to party-candidate fees. The draft's conclusion that this does not reach the 13-10-504 presidential petitioner is plausible but is an unsettled legal characterization that retrieval cannot definitively resolve, and wrongly assuming no fee could risk a defective filing. Per gate rule, grounded + interpretation -> CONSERVATIVE-HOLD; SOS inquiry filed. (The narrower claim 'no fee-IN-LIEU-OF-signatures alternative is offered' is safe — there is no such substitution path.)","conf":0.65,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Nebraska","sigs":"2,500 valid signatures (flat statutory) — count grounded; signer-eligibility scope unresolved (HOLD)","deadline":"Petition due Aug 1 of the presidential general-election year (LIVE)","risk":"Core figures (2,500 / Aug 1 / no distribution / no fee / paper / notarized affidavit) are grounded in current statute and consensus-confirmed; the one live risk is signer eligibility — Ballotpedia says signers must not have voted in any party primary, a condition absent from the current grounded statutory petition form (32-620.01), so confirm with the SOS before collecting.","sos":["For an independent/nonpartisan presidential nominating petition under Neb. Rev. Stat. 32-620(3), is a person eligible to sign if they voted in a 2024 party primary, or must signers be registered voters who did NOT vote in any party's primary? (The 32-620.01 form recites only registered-voter qualification; Ballotpedia states a no-primary-vote restriction.)"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; paid circulators permitted, residency not required, per-signature pay only addressed in the initiative context","note":"For an independent/nonpartisan presidential nominating petition, Nebraska's candidate-petition statutes (Neb. Rev. Stat. §§32-628, 32-629, 32-630, applied via §32-617/§32-620.01) clearly PERMIT paid circulators (§32-628(4) requires a red-print \"paid circulator\" disclosure) and impose NO residency/registered-voter requirement on circulators (only age 18+ under §32-629(2)); however, those candidate-petition statutes do NOT address per-signature compensation of circulators at all — the only Nebraska authority on per-signature pay (the 2008 ban and its 2015 repeal by LB 367, plus the struck-down \"hired and salaried\" ban in former §§32-702–32-713) arises in the ballot-initiative context and does not by its terms govern candidate petitions. Per-signature pay for candidate-petition circulators is therefore unaddressed; the §32-630(3)(e)-(f) prohibitions cover paying SIGNERS, not circulators.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/nonpartisan candidate's nominating petition for President (Neb. Rev. Stat. §§32-617, 32-620.01, 32-628 to 32-630), may a campaign lawfully compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and are there any restrictions on how circulators of candidate petitions may be paid or any residency requirement for them?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-628.html","quote":"Each sheet of a petition shall have upon its face and in plain view of persons who sign the petition a statement in letters not smaller than sixteen-point type in red print on the petition. If the petition is circulated by a paid circulator, the statement shall be as follows: This petition is circulated by a paid circulator. If the petition is circulated by a circulator who is not being paid, the statement shall be as follows: This petition is circulated by a volunteer circulator."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-628.html","quote":"Any person who falsely swears to a circulator's affidavit on a petition, who accepts money or other things of value for signing a petition, or who offers money or other things of value in exchange for a signature upon any petition shall be guilty of a Class IV felony."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-629.html","quote":"Only a person who is at least eighteen years of age shall qualify as a valid circulator of a petition and may circulate petitions. Petition circulators shall comply with section 32-630."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-630.html","quote":"No person shall: ... (e) Accept money or other thing of value for signing any petition; or (f) Offer money or other thing of value in exchange for a signature upon any petition."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Nebraska","quote":"To get on the general election ballot, an independent presidential candidate must file with the secretary of state a petition containing the signatures of at least 2,500 registered voters."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_Law_Update:_Nebraska_and_Wyoming_remove_bans_on_pay-per-signature","quote":"On April 7, 2015, Nebraska's unicameral legislature unanimously approved Legislative Bill 367, eliminating the state's seven-year-old ban on paying signature petition circulators based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.nebraska.gov/elections/voter-file-requests","official":true,"dom":"sos.nebraska.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-628.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-629.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ne/chapter-32-elections/ne-rev-st-sect-32-630.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Nebraska","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_Law_Update:_Nebraska_and_Wyoming_remove_bans_on_pay-per-signature","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"2,500 valid signatures (flat statutory number under Neb. Rev. Stat. 32-620(3)(b), not a percentage). STRICT signer-eligibility reading until SOS confirms: each signer must be a registered, qualified Nebraska voter AND (per Ballotpedia's gloss) must not have voted in any party's primary that year. Collect only from voters meeting the stricter condition and over-collect to a healthy cushion.","note":"GROUNDED: 32-620(3)(b) quote 'A petition signed by not less than two thousand five hundred registered voters' verified verbatim on FindLaw (current as of 2024-01-01); 32-620.01 signer-qualification quote verified verbatim. CONSENSUS: Ballotpedia independently confirms 2,500 registered voters for the independent general-election path. ADVERSARIAL: Ballotpedia adds that signers must be voters 'who did not vote in the primary election of any party' — a restriction ABSENT from the grounded current statutory petition form (32-620.01), which recites only registered/qualified-voter status. Could not reach the official Nebraska Legislature site (Cronet failures) or Justia (CAPTCHA) for a third primary-source confirmation, so the signer-eligibility scope is unresolved. The headline count (2,500) and type (flat statutory, not recomputed) are solid; the signer-eligibility discrepancy forces a strict HOLD on collection criteria.","conf":0.72,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"August 1 in the year of the presidential general election (for 2024 this was Thursday, August 1, 2024; no weekend/holiday adjustment). The completed application + petition must be filed with the Secretary of State by that date.","note":"GROUNDED: 32-620 quote 'shall be filed with the Secretary of State by August 1 in the year of the presidential general election' verified verbatim; the 60-day decline-affidavit quote (32-620(4)) also verified verbatim. CONSENSUS: Ballotpedia independently states the petition 'must be filed with the secretary of state by August 1 of the election year.' No statutory ambiguity; the date is fixed and current. Write-in path (second Friday before the election) is correctly flagged as a separate, non-applicable deadline.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 2,500-signature requirement is statewide with no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution/quota for the independent (nonpartisan) presidential petition; the county field on the form is identification only.","note":"GROUNDED: 32-620(3)(b) and the 32-620.01 form county-identification language verified verbatim — neither imposes a distribution quota. CONSENSUS/ADVERSARIAL: Ballotpedia confirms the 100-signatures-per-congressional-district rule applies to the PRIMARY-ballot petition only (party candidates), not the independent general-election petition, exactly as the draft distinguishes. No distribution requirement exists for the independent path.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator must be at least 18 years of age. The statute imposes no Nebraska-residency or registered-voter requirement on the circulator; the circulator must personally witness each signature and disclose paid vs. volunteer status. (Registered-voter/residency requirements apply to signers, not the circulator.)","note":"GROUNDED: 32-628(3) affidavit quote 'he or she is at least eighteen years of age, that each person whose name appears on the petition personally signed the petition in the presence of the affiant' and the 32-628(4) paid/volunteer-circulator statements verified verbatim. The grounded statutory affidavit recites ONLY the 18-years-of-age qualification for the circulator — no residency or registration clause — so the draft's value is a faithful, non-interpretive reading of the current primary text.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"NOTARIZED circulator affidavit required on every sheet bearing signatures (below the signatures), plus the boldface 'WARNING TO PETITION SIGNERS' statement above the signatures. The affidavit must be subscribed and sworn before a notary public.","note":"GROUNDED: 32-628(3) quotes verified verbatim — 'Every sheet of a petition which contains signatures shall have upon it, below the signatures, an affidavit' and 'Subscribed and sworn to before me, a notary public, this ______ day of _________ 20____ at_____________, Nebraska. Notary Public ___________________________'. The boldface WARNING is in 32-628(2). Notarization is unambiguous and current; a witness-only attestation is NOT sufficient.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wet-signature paper process only: statutory sheet layout (>=2.5-inch signature space, <=20 signatures/page, lines >=1/4 inch apart), in-person circulator witnessing each signature, and a notarized per-sheet circulator affidavit. No online/e-signature system covers the Nebraska independent presidential petition; completed petition is returned to the SOS Elections Division by mail or in person.","note":"GROUNDED: 32-628 quotes 'Petitions shall provide for no more than twenty signatures per page' and the in-person witnessing language verified verbatim; SOS candidate page quote 'Return the completed candidate filing forms and fees to the following address: Secretary of State Attn: Elections Division PO Box 94608 Lincoln, NE 68509-4608' verified verbatim. The statutory requirements (physical layout, in-person witnessing, notarized affidavit) are incompatible with a remote-online flow, supporting 'paper' as current and correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for the independent (nonpartisan) presidential petition; the 2,500-signature petition is the sole access mechanism under 32-620(3).","note":"GROUNDED: 32-608(2)(a) fee-bearing-office enumeration verified verbatim — it lists U.S. Senator, state officers, Representatives in Congress, county and city/village officers, etc., and does NOT include President/Vice President; 32-620(3) signature-only requirement verified verbatim. CORROBORATION (32-621, fetched): when a new party forms after the primary, 'all candidates except candidates for President or Vice President of the United States shall pay the filing fee as provided in section 32-608' — independently confirming President/VP are fee-exempt. No fee may be substituted for signatures.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Nevada","sigs":"NV indep pres: 1% of last general's U.S. House vote total (statutory formula); exact 2024 hard number NOT confirmed from primary source — held UNKNOWN","deadline":"NV indep pres petition + declaration due 5 p.m. 2nd Friday in Aug (2024: Aug 9); county-clerk submission due 25 working days prior; copy filed with SOS before circulating","risk":"All 8 fields citation-grounded (4 source URLs verbatim-confirmed). Core deadline/fee/distribution/capture facts AUTO-LIVE off NRS 298.109. Two CONSERVATIVE-HOLDs: signaturesRequired (no confirmed 2024 hard number — must compute from 2022 NV U.S. House total and confirm with SOS before relying) and witnessOrNotary (statute says \"affidavit\"; \"before a notary public\" is from a general-petition secondary source — treat notarization as required). Beware: NRS 298.109 (\"independent\" path) vs NRS 293.1715 (\"minor/new party\" path) are DIFFERENT regimes with different deadlines (Aug vs 3rd Fri June) — do not conflate.","sos":["For an independent presidential candidate filing under NRS 298.109 in 2024, what is the exact number of valid registered-voter signatures required (i.e., 1% of the total votes cast for the offices of Representative in Congress at the 2022 general election), and what is the official certified vote-total figure on which that 1% is based?","Under NRS 298.109(2), must the circulator's affidavit on each petition document be sworn before a notary public specifically, or may it be executed before any officer authorized to administer oaths — and does the Secretary of State's office require a notary acknowledgment block on the presidential petition of candidacy form?","For an independent presidential candidate under NRS 298.109, please confirm the exact 2024 statutory deadlines: (a) the 5 p.m. second-Friday-in-August filing deadline date, and (b) the 25-working-days-before deadline for submitting circulated documents to each county clerk for signature verification."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature pay law is initiative-only, NRS Ch. 295)","note":"The Nevada statute governing an independent presidential candidate's petition of candidacy (NRS 298.109) — and the parallel independent-candidate statute NRS 293.200 — require a circulator's affidavit but are completely SILENT on circulator compensation: they neither permit nor prohibit per-signature pay and do not address paid circulation at all, so candidate-petition compensation is unaddressed. Nevada's \"pay-per-signature permitted\" status is an initiative/ballot-measure fact under NRS Chapter 295 (NRS 295.0575 expressly limits its affidavit/rules to \"a petition for a constitutional amendment or a petition for a statewide measure proposed by an initiative or referendum\") and does NOT automatically carry over to candidate petitions; NRS 298.109/293.200 require only the SIGNERS (not the circulator) to be registered voters of the county, so no circulator residency/registration requirement appears for candidate petitions.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's petition of candidacy under NRS 298.109, does Nevada law permit a campaign to compensate signature circulators on a per-signature basis, and may a non-resident / non-registered-voter serve as the circulator who signs the document's affidavit?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-298-109/","quote":"A person who desires to be an independent candidate for the office of President of the United States must, not later than 5 p.m. on the second Friday in August ... pay a filing fee of $250 and file with the Secretary of State a declaration of candidacy and a petition of candidacy ... Each document of the petition must also contain the affidavit of the person who circulated the document that all signatures thereon are genuine to the best of the person's knowledge and belief and were signed in his or her presence by persons registered to vote in that county."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-295-0575/","quote":"A petition for a constitutional amendment or a petition for a statewide measure proposed by an initiative or referendum may consist of more than one document. Each document of a petition must have attached to it when submitted an affidavit executed by the circulator thereof stating: 1. That the circulator personally circulated the document."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-293-200/","quote":"The person who circulates each document of the petition shall sign an affidavit attesting that the signatures on the document are genuine to the best of his or her knowledge and belief and were signed in his or her presence by persons registered to vote in that county."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_governing_the_initiative_process_in_Nevada","quote":"Nevada allows paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. See law: Nevada Revised Statutes, Chapter 295"},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_governing_the_initiative_process_in_Nevada","quote":"Nevada does not require that petition circulators reside in the state."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Nevada","quote":"To gain access to the general ballot, an independent candidate for president must file a declaration of candidacy with the secretary of state no later than the second Friday in August, pay a $250 filing fee, and file a petition containing the signatures of at least 1 percent of the total number of votes cast for all representatives in Congress in the last election."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.leg.state.nv.us/nrs/nrs-293.html","official":true,"dom":"leg.state.nv.us"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.nvsos.gov/sos/elections/voters/nevvoter-statewide-list","official":true,"dom":"nvsos.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-298-109/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-295-0575/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nv/title-24-elections/nv-rev-st-293-200/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_governing_the_initiative_process_in_Nevada","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Nevada","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Availability_of_state_voter_files","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Signatures of registered voters equal to not less than 1% of the total number of votes cast at the last preceding general election for the offices of Representative in Congress (NRS 298.109(1)). The exact 2024-cycle hard number is treated as UNKNOWN and MUST be computed from the certified 2022 Nevada U.S. House vote total and confirmed with the Secretary of State before relying.","note":"GROUND: Both quotes verbatim-confirmed — NRS 298.109 quote present word-for-word on nevada.public.law/statutes/nrs_298.109; NRS 293.1715(2)(c) quote present word-for-word on nevada.public.law/statutes/nrs_293.1715. JUDGE: The 1% statutory formula is CURRENT and CORRECT for an independent presidential candidate. The draft correctly declines to assert an unverified 2024 hard number and sets it to UNKNOWN — the appropriate conservative move (I could not confirm any specific 2024 count from a primary source; Ballotpedia's 2024 table rendered empty). HOLD (not AUTO-LIVE) solely because the operationally usable value (the actual signature count) is unresolved; the formula itself is sound. Note the draft also correctly distinguishes the 1% basis is shared with the NRS 293.1715(2)(c) minor-party path.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Independent presidential path (NRS 298.109): declaration of candidacy + petition of candidacy filed with the Secretary of State no later than 5 p.m. on the second Friday in August of the presidential-election year (2024: Aug 9, 2024). A copy of the petition must be filed with the SOS before it may be circulated. Documents circulated in a county must be submitted to that county clerk for signature verification no later than 25 working days before the August filing deadline. Minor/new-party path (NRS 293.1715(2)(c)) differs: petition due to SOS no later than the third Friday in June.","note":"GROUND: All three quotes verbatim-confirmed on their cited pages (the 5 p.m. second-Friday-in-August quote and the 25-working-days quote on nrs_298.109; the third-Friday-in-June quote on nrs_293.1715). JUDGE: Independently corroborated — NRS 298.109(1) sets the 5 p.m. second-Friday-in-August deadline and the copy-before-circulation rule; 298.109(2) sets the 25-working-days county-clerk submission. Aug 9, 2024 is the correct second Friday of August 2024. Ballotpedia's 2020 footnote ('Deadline to file petitions with local officials...7/10/2020') is consistent with the 25-working-days-before rule. The draft properly flags the materially different minor-party June deadline so the two paths are not conflated. CURRENT and CORRECT for an independent presidential candidate; no legal interpretation needed.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No statewide-distribution quota for the independent presidential petition (no minimum per congressional district or county). The petition may consist of more than one document; each document must bear the name of a single county and only registered voters of that county may sign it; each county's documents are verified by that county clerk. Signatures are county-segregated but there is no required number per county/district.","note":"GROUND: Quote ('The petition may consist of more than one document. Each document must bear the name of a county and only registered voters of that county may sign the document.') verbatim-confirmed on nrs_298.109. JUDGE: NRS 298.109(2) contains no per-county or per-district minimum for the INDEPENDENT path — confirmed by full read of the section. ADVERSARIAL CHECK: The Justia copy of NRS 293.1715 shows a subsection 5 imposing a per-petition-district apportionment of the 1% — BUT that applies only to the MINOR-PARTY path (293.1715(2)(c)), NOT to the independent presidential petition (298.109) this field is scoped to. The draft is correctly scoped to NRS 298.109 and the no-quota conclusion holds for that path. CURRENT and CORRECT.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"NRS 298.109 imposes no express age, residency, or voter-registration requirement on the circulator; it requires only the circulator's affidavit that signatures are genuine and were signed in the circulator's presence by persons registered to vote in that county. STRICTEST defensible posture for operations: do not assume out-of-state or non-registered circulators are safe statewide — confirm with SOS, since circulator-eligibility rules are an area of active legal change in many states and Ballotpedia's 'no requirements' statement is secondary.","note":"GROUND: Both quotes verbatim-confirmed — the NRS 298.109 affidavit quote on nrs_298.109; the Ballotpedia 'Circulators of petitions are not required to be registered voters in Nevada. The statutes do not stipulate any requirements for circulators in Nevada.' quote confirmed word-for-word at line 370 of the political-candidates page. JUDGE: The statute's silence on circulator eligibility is accurately read. HOLD (interpretationRequired=true) because correctness as an affirmative operational rule ('any circulator is fine') rests on (a) a secondary source (Ballotpedia) generalizing from statutory silence and (b) the open legal question of whether SOS practice or any other NRS provision constrains circulators for a presidential petition. Statutory silence does not equal a guarantee; conservative posture is to verify before relying on out-of-state/non-registered circulators.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat a NOTARIZED circulator affidavit as required: each petition document must contain the circulator's sworn affidavit that all signatures are genuine and were signed in the circulator's presence by persons registered to vote in that county (NRS 298.109(2)). Strictest defensible reading: execute the circulator affidavit before a notary public. No separate notarization of individual voter signatures is required.","note":"GROUND: Both quotes verbatim-confirmed — the NRS 298.109(2) 'affidavit of the person who circulated the document...' quote on nrs_298.109; the Ballotpedia 'The circulator of the petition must sign, before a notary public, an affidavit on the back of the petition verifying that all signatures were recorded in the circulator's presence.' quote confirmed word-for-word at line 366 of the political-candidates page. JUDGE/ADVERSARIAL: NRS 298.109 itself says only 'affidavit' — it does NOT expressly say 'notary public.' The 'before a notary public' language comes from Ballotpedia's GENERAL petition guidance (tied to minor-party/NRS 293.172 petitions), not from NRS 298.109 specifically. An affidavit is by definition sworn before an officer authorized to administer oaths, which conventionally means a notary, so requiring notarization is the SAFE/strictest posture — but whether NRS 298.109 strictly mandates a notary (vs. any oath-administering officer) is a legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle. HOLD at the notarization-required reading.","conf":0.75,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The independent presidential petition is a wet-ink, county-by-county paper document: each signer adds signature, residence address, date, and county of registration; signatures must be in ink; the circulator executes a paper affidavit; documents are physically submitted to each county clerk for verification. No Nevada digital/online signature-collection system covers this petition. (Candidate declaration/filing with the SOS may use the SOS online portal, but signature collection is paper.)","note":"GROUND: Both quotes verbatim-confirmed — the NRS 298.109 signer-information quote ('Each person signing shall add to his or her signature the address...the date...and the name of the county wherein he or she is registered to vote.') on nrs_298.109; the Ballotpedia 'Each signature must be made in ink. Any signature not made in ink will be disregarded.' quote confirmed word-for-word at line 366. JUDGE: The statutory scheme (county-named documents, signer adds handwritten address/date/county, circulator paper affidavit, physical submission to county clerks for NRS 293.1276-293.1279 verification) is inherently wet-ink paper; no e-signature pathway exists for this petition. CURRENT and CORRECT; no interpretation needed. The 'made in ink' requirement is from general petition guidance but is consistent with and reinforces the statutory scheme.","conf":0.88,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"There is NO fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative. The $250 filing fee is required IN ADDITION TO the petition signatures, not as a substitute. An independent presidential candidate must both pay the $250 fee and file the qualifying petition. (The fee is refundable within 10 days if the candidacy is ultimately not qualified, per NRS 293.194, but it cannot replace the signature requirement.)","note":"GROUND: Both quotes verbatim-confirmed — the NRS 298.109(1) 'pay a filing fee of $250 and file...a declaration of candidacy and a petition of candidacy' quote on nrs_298.109; the Ballotpedia presidential-page quote 'must file a declaration of candidacy...pay a $250 filing fee, and file a petition containing the signatures of at least 1 percent...' confirmed word-for-word at line 231 of the presidential-candidates page. JUDGE: 'pay...AND file...a petition' in NRS 298.109(1) is conjunctive — the fee and petition are both mandatory; there is no statutory fee-in-lieu option. The draft's parenthetical refund claim is INDEPENDENTLY corroborated by NRS 293.194 (filing fee 'must be returned to the candidate...within 10 days' after a final determination the petition does not qualify) — a side note that does not affect the central, correct conclusion. CURRENT and CORRECT.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"New Hampshire","sigs":"NH: 3,000 sigs (1,500 per CD, 2 districts) + $250 fee — both required","deadline":"NH: Decl. of Intent Jun 3-12, 2026; papers to SOS by 5pm Wed Sep 2, 2026","risk":"Core numbers/dates verbatim-grounded in RSA 655:42/655:43/655:19-a and confirmed against the SOS 2026 page; only soft spot is circulator eligibility, which rests on statutory silence (no circulator rule exists) rather than an affirmative statement — held conservatively pending SOS confirmation.","sos":["Does New Hampshire impose ANY eligibility requirement (age, NH residency, registered-voter status, or in-state status) on the PERSON who circulates/collects signatures on a presidential candidate's nomination papers under RSA 655:40-45, or is the only personal qualification the one applied to the signer? Please confirm there is no circulator affidavit or circulator-residency rule for the independent/nomination-paper presidential route."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition circulator compensation statute found","note":"New Hampshire's candidate nomination-paper statutes (RSA 655:40–45) and the bribery statute (RSA 659:40) do NOT address compensating circulators of candidate nomination papers — neither permitting nor prohibiting per-signature pay; candidate-petition compensation is unaddressed. NH nomination papers have no statutory \"circulator\" role at all (each registered voter signs and dates an individual paper; certification is by the supervisors of the checklist), so there is no circulator residency requirement on the books, but who may lawfully gather/handle signatures is itself unaddressed.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nomination papers under RSA 655:40–45, does New Hampshire law permit a campaign to compensate the people who gather signatures, and specifically may they be paid on a per-signature basis, or must any such pay be hourly/salaried — and is there any residency or registered-voter requirement for the person collecting signatures?","citations":[{"url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-40.htm","quote":"655:40 General Provisions. – As an alternative to nomination by party primary, a candidate may have his or her name placed on the ballot for the state general election by submitting the requisite number of nomination papers. ... Nomination papers shall be signed by such persons only as are registered to vote at the state general election. No voter shall sign more than one nomination paper for each office to be voted for ... Each voter shall sign and date an individual nomination paper."},{"url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-41.htm","quote":"655:41 Certification. – I. Each nomination paper shall be submitted to the supervisors of the checklist of the town or ward in which the signer is domiciled or is registered, and a majority of the supervisors shall certify whether or not the signer is a registered voter in said town or ward."},{"url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-45.htm","quote":"655:45 Nomination Papers Protected. – No person shall falsely make or file or knowingly deface or destroy any nomination paper, or any part thereof, or sign any nomination paper contrary to the provisions of law knowing the same, or any part thereof, to be falsely made or suppress any nomination paper, or any part thereof, which has been duly filed."},{"url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-42.htm","quote":"655:42 Number. – I. It shall require the names of 3,000 registered voters, 1,500 from each United States congressional district in the state, to nominate by nomination papers a candidate for president, United States senator, or governor."},{"url":"https://gencourt.state.nh.us/rsa/html/LXIII/659/659-40.htm","quote":"659:40 Bribing; Intimidation; Suppression. – I. No person shall directly or indirectly bribe any person not to register to vote or any voter not to vote or to vote for or against any question submitted to voters or to vote for or against any ticket or candidate for office at any election."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-40.htm","official":true,"dom":"gc.nh.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-41.htm","official":true,"dom":"gc.nh.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-45.htm","official":true,"dom":"gc.nh.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/LXIII/655/655-42.htm","official":true,"dom":"gc.nh.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://gencourt.state.nh.us/rsa/html/LXIII/659/659-40.htm","official":true,"dom":"gencourt.state.nh.us"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/lxiii/654/654-31.htm","official":true,"dom":"gc.nh.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.concordmonitor.com/2024/10/15/nh-sells-voter-data-to-political-candidates-here-s-what-they-do-with-it-55945677/","official":false,"dom":"concordmonitor.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"3,000 signatures of registered voters, 1,500 from each of New Hampshire's 2 U.S. congressional districts. Flat statutory number under RSA 655:42, I (which expressly names 'president' alongside U.S. senator and governor); it is not a percentage and does not recompute by cycle. The separate new/minor political-organization path requires signatures equal to 3% of total ballots cast at the previous state general election, computed by the SOS as 18,808 for 2026 (RSA 655:42, III).","note":"RSA 655:42, I quote found verbatim in primary source and expressly lists 'president' at 3,000 / 1,500-per-district. 18,808 political-org figure confirmed verbatim on SOS page. Note: the SOS citation used is the GOVERNOR line ($100 AND 3,000), not a president-specific line (the SOS running-for-office page does not enumerate president), but the statute directly grounds the president figure, so the value is correct.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Two steps for 2026: (1) Declaration of Intent (RSA 655:17-b, presidential) filed with the Secretary of State during the candidate filing window June 3-12, 2026 (RSA 655:14 / 655:14-a: 'first Wednesday in June' = June 3 through 'Friday of the following week' = June 12). (2) Certified nomination papers filed with the Secretary of State no later than 5:00 p.m. Wednesday Sept 2, 2026 (RSA 655:43, I: 'Wednesday one week before the primary'; 2026 primary is Tue Sept 8). Intermediate local deadlines (RSA 655:41): papers to town/ward Supervisors of the Checklist by 5:00 p.m. Aug 5, 2026 (Wed 5 weeks before primary); supervisor certification complete by 5:00 p.m. Aug 26, 2026 (Wed 2 weeks before primary). A filing on the last day must be made in person before the Secretary of State (RSA 655:16 / 655:43, II).","note":"All four dates independently recomputed against a 2026 calendar and confirmed: June 3 is the first Wednesday in June; June 12 is the Friday of the following week; Sept 2 is the Wednesday one week before the Sept 8 (Tue) primary; Aug 5 = 5 weeks before; Aug 26 = 2 weeks before. RSA 655:43, I and 655:14 quotes found verbatim; SOS page lists June 3-12 filing period and the Aug 5 / Aug 26 / Sept 2 deadlines verbatim.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes — geographic distribution by congressional district. Of the 3,000 total, 1,500 must come from each of New Hampshire's 2 U.S. congressional districts, and signers must be registered in the respective district (RSA 655:42, I). Nomination papers must be ordered/grouped by municipality when filed with the Secretary of State (RSA 655:22-a / 655:43, I; SOS page).","note":"RSA 655:42, I quote and SOS '1,500 from each congressional district ... grouped by municipality' quote both found verbatim. Independently corroborated by RSA 655:22-a (petitions ordered alphabetically by municipality) and 655:43, I ('grouped by municipality').","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No circulator-specific eligibility requirement is prescribed by statute, BUT this rests on statutory silence rather than an affirmative authorization. RSA 655:40-45 regulates only SIGNERS: each signer must be registered to vote at the state general election, no voter may sign more than one nomination paper for the same office, and each voter must personally sign and date an individual nomination paper; certification of signers is done by the local Supervisors of the Checklist (RSA 655:41), not by a circulator. Strictest defensible operating posture until SOS confirms: do not assume non-resident or non-voter circulators are unrestricted — treat circulator status as UNCONFIRMED, and where practical have signatures gathered by NH-registered voters and never rely on a circulator-collected sheet as a substitute for the signer's own personal signature and date.","note":"RSA 655:40 signer-rule quote found verbatim. Correctness of 'no circulator requirement' hinges on the inference that statutory silence equals no requirement — retrieval cannot settle whether an unwritten SOS administrative practice or form imposes anything on the collector. Held conservatively and routed to an SOS inquiry; the value itself does not over-promise (it flags UNKNOWN), which is the safe direction.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Petition/nomination-paper sheets are NOT notarized and carry NO circulator affidavit; signer validation is done by the Supervisors of the Checklist of the town/ward where the signer is domiciled or registered, who certify whether the signer is a registered voter there (city clerk may perform this) — RSA 655:41. SEPARATELY, the presidential candidate's own Declaration of Intent MUST be signed by the candidate AND notarized by a notary public — RSA 655:17-b, I. So: notarized candidate Declaration of Intent = YES (required); notarized/witnessed petition sheets or circulator certification = NO (supervisor-of-checklist certification instead).","note":"Both RSA quotes found verbatim — 655:41, I (supervisor certification) and 655:17-b, I ('signed by the candidate, and notarized by a notary public'). The load-bearing, candidate-facing requirement (notarize the Declaration of Intent) is stated expressly in statute and points in the safe/strict direction, so AUTO-LIVE. The 'no petition notarization' element follows from the statutory scheme (certification runs through supervisors, with no circulator oath anywhere in 655:40-45).","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper (wet-ink). RSA 655:40 requires that each voter personally sign and date an individual paper nomination form, dated in the year of the election. Papers are physically submitted to the local Supervisors of the Checklist for certification (RSA 655:41) and the certified papers filed in paper with the Secretary of State, grouped by municipality (RSA 655:43, I). There is no digital/online e-petition system for an independent/nomination-paper presidential nomination in New Hampshire; downloadable PDF forms exist but collection and submission remain paper.","note":"RSA 655:40 quote ('Each voter shall sign and date an individual nomination paper. Nomination papers shall be dated in the year of the election.') found verbatim; SOS 'submit signed nomination papers to Supervisors of the Checklist' quote found verbatim. No statute or SOS material authorizes e-signature for this route; treating capture as paper is the strict/safe reading.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A fee is required IN ADDITION TO signatures, not as an alternative. A presidential candidate seeking nomination by nomination papers pays a single $250 fee to the Secretary of State at the time of filing the Declaration of Intent, covering both the presidential and vice-presidential candidate (RSA 655:19-a). This does NOT substitute for the 3,000 signatures — both the $250 fee and the full signature count are required. There is no signature-for-fee swap and no indigence petition-in-lieu path for the nomination-paper route (the RSA 655:48 indigence/petition option applies only to the separate presidential PRIMARY $1,000 fee, not to nomination papers).","note":"RSA 655:19-a quote found verbatim. Adversarial check confirmed: the only fee-waiver/petition-in-lieu mechanism in Chapter 655 (RSA 655:48, II) is tied to the presidential PRIMARY, not the nomination-paper general-election route, so the draft's 'no swap option' is correct. Both fee and signatures are independently required.","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]},{"state":"New Jersey","sigs":"NJ signatures: HOLD — collect to 2,000 (strict) but the 2,000 figure is documented only for Governor, not President; primary statute still reads 800. Confirm with Division of Elections.","deadline":"NJ deadline: LIVE — 99th day before the general election (N.J.S.A. 19:13-9 presidential-elector carve-out); recompute the calendar date each cycle.","risk":"Only real risk is signaturesRequired: the 2,000 value is an inference (statewide-office aggregate applied to President), but every grounded source ties 2,000 to \"Governor\" and Ballotpedia's presidential page + the cited statute still say 800 — unresolved legal-interpretation question; over-comply to 2,000 and verify. All other fields are grounded and correct.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT candidate for President/Vice President (slate of presidential electors, not nominated at a party convention) filing a direct nomination petition under N.J.S.A. 19:13 for the November general election, how many petition signatures are required after A-5117/S-3994 (P.L. 2025) — is it the 2,000 statewide-office aggregate now applied to Governor, or does the presidential-elector petition retain the prior 800 figure?","Does the NJ-residency requirement for petition circulators in N.J.S.A. 19:13-7 apply to (and is it enforced against) a circulator of an INDEPENDENT general-election presidential-elector petition, in light of Arsenault v. Way and out-of-state-circulator case law?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"New Jersey's independent/direct-nomination petition statutes (Title 19, Chapter 13) and the official Division of Elections petition forms/instructions (N.J.S.A. 19:13-4 and 19:13-7) do NOT address compensation of candidate-petition circulators at all — neither authorizing nor prohibiting per-signature pay, so compensation is UNADDRESSED for candidate petitions. Paying circulators (e.g., hourly) is not prohibited and is implicitly permitted (the recall chapter, 19:27A, expressly contemplates \"paid circulator[s],\" but that is a different petition type); per-signature pay specifically is unaddressed and carries some risk given a separate NJ provision against paying people to sign, so it should not be relied upon. NJ is not a statewide initiative state, so the national pay-per-signature initiative framework does not apply here. Circulators need not be registered voters but must be NJ voter-eligible (18+, U.S. citizen, not otherwise disqualified under NJ election laws), which effectively requires New Jersey residency — a purely out-of-state paid pool would not qualify.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's direct-nomination petition under N.J.S.A. 19:13, may a campaign lawfully pay signature circulators on a per-signature basis; if not, may they be paid hourly/salaried; and must each circulator be a New Jersey resident/NJ-voter-eligible per the 19:13-7 affidavit?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/candidate/2026-general-election-instructions-us-house.pdf","quote":"The person who circulates the petition does not have to be a signer of the petition and shall not be required to be a registered voter, but shall be at least 18 years of age, a citizen of the United States, and not otherwise disqualified from voting under the State Constitution or election laws of New Jersey. ... (N.J.S.A. 19:13-7)"},{"url":"https://www.nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/candidate/2026-general-election-petition-us-house.pdf","quote":"AFFIDAVIT OF PERSON WHO CIRCULATES THIS PETITION AND WITNESSES SIGNATURES (N.J.S.A. 19:13-7) ... I, ____, being duly sworn, upon my oath say that the petition is made in good faith, that I personally circulated the petition and saw all the signatures made thereto and verily believe that the signers are duly qualified voters. I am at least 18 years of age, a citizen of the United States, and not otherwise disqualified from voting under the State Constitution or election laws of New Jersey."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","quote":"There are 26 states that provide for an initiative or referendum process. Sixteen (16) of those states allowed campaigns to make payments to signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected. Ten (10) of those states prohibited campaigns from paying signature gatherers based on the number of signatures collected."},{"url":"https://law.justia.com/codes/new-jersey/title-19/section-19-13-5/","quote":"For an office to be filled by the voters of the entire State, 2,000 signatures in the aggregate for each candidate nominated in the petition shall be sufficient."},{"url":"https://nj.gov/state/dos-statutes-elections-19-20-29.shtml","quote":"i. ... if a recall petition is presented to such a prospective signer by a paid circulator, the solicitation or petition, respectively, shall disclose prominently in a statement printed in at least 10-point type (1) the identity of the person paying for the printed or personal solicitation, and (2) that the circulator is paid."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/candidate/2026-general-election-instructions-us-house.pdf","official":true,"dom":"nj.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/candidate/2026-general-election-petition-us-house.pdf","official":true,"dom":"nj.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://nj.gov/state/dos-statutes-elections-19-20-29.shtml","official":true,"dom":"nj.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://nj.gov/state/dos-statutes-elections-19-31-39.shtml","official":true,"dom":"nj.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://law.justia.com/codes/new-jersey/title-19/section-19-13-5/","official":false,"dom":"law.justia.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 2,000 signatures of qualified registered NJ voters statewide (use the higher figure to over-comply and never fall short). CAUTION: the 2,000 figure (A-5117/S-3994, eff. Feb 3, 2025) is documented in the grounded sources only for GOVERNOR; whether it governs an independent PRESIDENTIAL-elector petition is an unresolved statutory-interpretation question. The cited primary statute (N.J.S.A. 19:13-5) and Ballotpedia's NJ presidential page both still state 800. Confirm the operative number with the NJ Division of Elections before filing.","note":"All citations grounded VERBATIM, but they do not support the draft's value. FindLaw 19:13-5 (current as of Jan 1, 2024) reads 'eight hundred signatures in the aggregate' — the draft cites this to support 2,000, a self-contradiction. NJ Spotlight ('from 800 to 2,000 for governor') and NJ.gov press ('Independent candidates for Governor...2,000 signatures') both tie 2,000 specifically to Governor, NEVER to President. Ballotpedia's presidential page (cited in the deadline field, post-2025) still says 800. NJ nominates a slate of presidential electors under a distinct scheme (the 19:13-9 carve-out), so the draft's inference that the single-statewide-office aggregate automatically applies to President is contestable. Could not retrieve operative amended 19:13-5 text or NJ Div. of Elections presidential guidance (legislature/state pages CAPTCHA/404/unreachable). Disagree + interpretation-required → HOLD; strictest defensible posture is to collect to 2,000.","conf":0.55,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Filed with the Secretary of State before 4:00 p.m. of the 99th day preceding the general election (N.J.S.A. 19:13-9 carve-out for presidential electors not nominated at a party convention). The exact calendar date recomputes each cycle as the 99th day before that cycle's general election.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM: FindLaw 19:13-9 ('...electors of candidates for President and Vice President...not been nominated at a convention...filed with the Secretary of State before 4:00 p.m. of the 99th day preceding the general election') and Ballotpedia presidential page ('no later than 99 days before the general election'). The statute is explicit and the presidential-elector carve-out is correctly identified; no contested interpretation. Note: the 2024 worked example (Aug 1, 2024) is a past-cycle illustration only — the rule is the 99-day formula.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Flat statewide aggregate of signatures of qualified voters of the entire State; no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement. Petition is addressed to (filed with) the Secretary of State.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM: 19:13-5 ('...office to be filled by the voters of the entire State...in the aggregate...') and 19:13-3 ('Petitions naming candidates for office to be filled by voters of the entire State...shall be addressed to the Secretary of State'). NJ imposes no geographic distribution requirement for statewide office; uncontested. (Independent of the 800-vs-2,000 dispute, which is about quantity, not distribution.)","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator need not be a registered voter but must be voter-eligible: at least 18 years of age, a resident of New Jersey, a U.S. citizen, and not otherwise disqualified under the NJ Constitution. The candidate may sign and/or circulate their own petition.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM in 19:13-7 ('shall not be required to be a registered voter, but shall be voter eligible, which means at least 18 years of age, a resident of this State, a citizen of the United States...'); candidate self-circulation confirmed by 19:13-5. Adversarial note flagged in sosInquiries: the NJ-residency bar may be constitutionally vulnerable as applied to an independent general-election presidential circulator (cf. Arsenault v. Way; Buckley v. ACLF), but that doubt cuts toward MORE circulator flexibility, so using only NJ-resident circulators (the value as written) over-complies and cannot threaten ballot access. Value tracks the statute verbatim → LIVE.","conf":0.85,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes — notarized circulator affidavit. Before filing, the circulator (or a candidate who signs/circulates) must make oath by affidavit before a duly qualified officer (notary) that the petition is made in good faith, that the affiant personally circulated it and saw all signatures made, and verily believes the signers are duly qualified voters.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM: 19:13-7 ('...shall make oath by affidavit before a duly qualified officer that the petition is made in good faith, that the affiant personally circulated the petition and saw all the signatures made thereto and verily believes that the signers are duly qualified voters') and Ballotpedia ('Petition circulators must complete and sign an affidavit. The affidavit must also be notarized'). Current and uncontested.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Hand-circulated paper nominating petition, wet-ink voter signatures, notarized circulator affidavit, filed with the Secretary of State. No standing digital/online petition system. The COVID-era EO 216 (Jan 25, 2021) was a temporary emergency order and is not available for current cycles.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM: Ballotpedia quotes EO 216 ('...submitted by hand delivery and electronically'; 'signatures to be collected electronically') and correctly frames it as a one-time 2021 emergency order; 19:13-7's wet-ink affidavit requirement supports paper as the standing default. No permanent e-petition system identified. Current and uncontested.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option; ballot access for an independent presidential candidate is by nominating petition (signatures) only.","note":"Grounded VERBATIM: Ballotpedia ('File a petition with the required number of signatures for the office being sought, including a guarantee that signers are qualified voters...') and 19:13-5 (signatures of qualified voters). No fee or fee-alternative appears in the statutory petition scheme. Uncontested; note this is a negative finding (absence of a fee mechanism) rather than an affirmative 'fee = $0' statement.","conf":0.85,"interp":false}]},{"state":"New Mexico","sigs":"Signature % DISPUTED: statute = 0.5% of gov vote (1-8-51(B)->1-7-2(A)); NASS = 3%. HOLD to 3% until SoS confirms.","deadline":"Deadline DISPUTED: current statute = 23rd day after primary; NASS/Ballotpedia = 21st. HOLD to earlier (21st) date.","risk":"Two unresolved conflicts (signature % and deadline day) both go to ballot-access survival; neither resolvable by retrieval — the SoS per-cycle Nominating Petition Calculations doc and posted filing calendar are the controlling sources and must be obtained before relying on any number/date.","sos":["For the independent presidential nominating petition, what is the EXACT number of valid voter signatures required this cycle, and is the percentage basis one-half of one percent (per 1-8-51(B) cross-referencing 1-7-2(A)) or three percent (as stated in the NASS summary) of the total vote cast for governor at the last preceding general election?","Is the operative filing deadline for the independent presidential declaration and nominating petition the 23rd day following the primary (current 1-8-52(B)) or the 21st day (as listed by NASS and Ballotpedia), and what is the exact posted date and hours for this cycle?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"New Mexico's candidate / independent-presidential nominating-petition law (NMSA 1978 Ch. 1, Arts. 1 & 8) and the official Secretary of State 2026 Candidate Information Guide are entirely SILENT on circulator compensation — they address signature counts, petition form, who may sign, falsification, and challenges, but never per-signature or any other circulator pay. Compensation of candidate-petition circulators is therefore UNADDRESSED (the per-signature bans New Mexico discusses elsewhere are initiative/referendum rules, not candidate-petition rules, and were not carried over). No circulator-residency/registration requirement applies (the registered-voter/resident requirement falls on SIGNERS, not the circulator), and there is no circulator-affidavit requirement, so a non-resident paid pool is not facially barred.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under NMSA 1978 §§ 1-8-3.1, 1-8-51, and 1-8-52, may a campaign compensate petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and must circulators be New Mexico residents or registered voters?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.sos.nm.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/2026-Primary-Candidate-Guide_Final.pdf","quote":"CIRCULATING NOMINATING PETITIONS — Candidates are ultimately responsible for the contents of their petitions and for the actions of the individuals representing them in the public. It is extremely important that individuals assisting candidates with collecting petition signatures are adequately trained and appropriately informed. ... A person knowingly falsifying any information on a nominating petition is guilty of falsifying an election document (see 1-8-32 (A), NMSA 1978). ... It is a misdemeanor to knowingly circulate, present, or offer to present a nominating petition for the signature of a voter that does not contain the information specified under the law (see 1-8-32 (B), NMSA 1978)."},{"url":"https://www.sos.nm.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/2026-Primary-Candidate-Guide_Final.pdf","quote":"Independent and Minor Party candidates: Voters signing petitions for independent and minor party candidates are not required to be registered in the minor candidate's political party. Instead, the voters certify that they are residents of the state, district, county, or area to be represented by the office for which the person seeking nomination is a candidate (see 1-8-2 (B) and 1-8-50, NMSA 1978)."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-8-51/","quote":"B. Nominating petitions for an independent candidate for president of the United States shall be signed by a number of voters equal to the number of signatures required to form a new political party. ... G. A voter shall not sign a petition for an independent candidate as provided in this section if the voter has signed a petition for another independent candidate for the same office."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-8-3-1/","quote":"To qualify as an independent candidate, the candidate must meet all requirements for an independent candidate in Section 1-8-45 NMSA 1978 and submit the required number of petition signatures for an independent candidate as prescribed in Section 1-8-51 NMSA 1978. No candidate may circulate petitions for candidacy for more than one political party in an election cycle."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-1-7-2/","quote":"D. The procedures set forth in this section shall be used to validate signatures on any petition required by the Election Code, except that Paragraph (4) of Subsection C of this section shall not apply to petitions filed by unaffiliated candidates or petitions filed by candidates of minor political parties."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.nm.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/2026-Primary-Candidate-Guide_Final.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.nm.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.nm.gov/voting-and-elections/data-and-maps/voter-data-information/","official":true,"dom":"sos.nm.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-8-51/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-8-3-1/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-1-7-2/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-4-5-5/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nm/chapter-1-elections/nm-st-sect-1-4-5-6/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 3% of the total vote cast for governor at the last preceding general election at which a governor was elected (strictest defensible figure pending SoS confirmation). NOTE: the statutory chain (NMSA 1-8-51(B) -> 1-7-2(A)) reads to only one-half of one percent (0.5%); the 3% comes from the NASS summary and Ballotpedia's overview blurb and is NOT supported by the statutes those sources cite. Because over-collecting never risks the ballot line but under-collecting is fatal, plan to 3% until the SoS per-cycle Nominating Petition Calculations document gives the controlling exact number.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-51(B) ('signed by a number of voters equal to the number of signatures required to form a new political party'), 1-8-51(A) (basis = total vote for governor at last election), and 1-7-2(A) ('one-half of one percent of the total votes cast for the office of governor') all verified verbatim on FindLaw; NASS '3%' quote verified verbatim in the downloaded PDF. ADVERSARIAL: re-deriving from primary law gives 0.5% (1-8-51(B)->1-7-2(A)); Ballotpedia's statute-citing detail section also says 'one-half of one percent.' The 3% appears to be a propagated error — even the NASS entry cites 1-7-2/1-8-51, which yield 0.5%. But correctness hinges on a statutory cross-reference interpretation retrieval cannot settle, and the controlling per-cycle SoS calculation could not be retrieved. HOLD to the higher (3%) figure to never risk the ballot line.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"File the declaration of independent candidacy and nominating petition between 9:00 a.m. and 5:00 p.m. on the 21st day following the primary election (strictest/earliest of the two conflicting dates), pending SoS confirmation. Current NMSA 1-8-52(B) text says the 23rd day, but NASS and Ballotpedia say the 21st; treat the earlier (21st) date as the operative deadline so the filing is never late.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-52(B) 'twenty-third day following the primary election' verified verbatim on FindLaw (current as of Jan 1, 2024); NASS '21st day following the primary election' verified verbatim in the PDF; Ballotpedia detail section independently says '21st day.' ADVERSARIAL: genuine conflict between the current statute (23rd) and two secondary sources (21st) — possibly a recent amendment from 21st to 23rd not yet reflected downstream, or a downstream error. Cannot confirm the operative posted date without the SoS filing calendar. A missed deadline is fatal to ballot access, so HOLD to the earlier 21st-day date.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. New Mexico imposes no congressional-district or county distribution requirement on an independent presidential nominating petition; the requirement is a single statewide number tied to the total vote cast for governor at the last preceding general election.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-51(A) and (B) verified verbatim on FindLaw. ADVERSARIAL: read the full text of 1-8-51 (all subsections A-G) and 1-8-49/1-8-50 — none contains any per-district or per-county allocation for the presidential petition; it is a single statewide figure. Confirmed no distribution rule exists.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No separate statutory circulator qualification. The constraint is on SIGNERS, who must each be a registered voter of New Mexico; a voter may not sign more than one independent-presidential petition. The named presidential electors must be registered NM voters (U.S. senators, U.S. representatives, and persons holding federal offices of trust or profit are ineligible). The Election Code specifies no separate age/residency/voter-status requirement for the person who circulates/collects signatures, as distinct from the signers.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-50(D) presidential petition form ('I, the undersigned, a registered voter of New Mexico...' and the no-double-signing declaration) and 1-8-49(D) (electors must be registered NM voters; federal officeholders ineligible) all verified verbatim on FindLaw. ADVERSARIAL: searched 1-8-49 through 1-8-52 for any circulator affidavit/qualification — none exists for this petition (contrast with states that require a circulator oath). The value's claim of no separate circulator rule is accurate to the statute.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The candidate's declaration of independent candidacy for president (and vice president) must be a sworn statement made under oath and notarized ('Subscribed and sworn to me this ___ day of ___ / notary public'), per NMSA 1-8-49(B)-(C). The signature petition itself carries no circulator affidavit and no notary block; each signer self-certifies as a registered NM voter on the 1-8-50(D) form. So: notarized sworn candidate declaration = YES; circulator/witness certification or notarization of the petition signatures = NONE.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-49 'I make the foregoing affidavit under oath...' and 'Subscribed and sworn to me this ___ day of ___, ... notary public' verified verbatim on FindLaw; 1-8-50(D) petition form (no notary/circulator block) verified verbatim. ADVERSARIAL: the petition form text in 1-8-50(D) contains only signer self-declarations and no notarization line, confirming the petition itself is not notarized while the candidate's declaration is.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The statute prescribes a physical paper petition (approximately 8.5 x 11 inches, numbered lines spaced ~3/8 inch apart, multi-sheet petitions firmly secured by staple/fastening per 1-8-50(D),(F)). No online/remote e-signature or in-person-digitized system covers an independent presidential nominating petition in New Mexico; signatures must be collected on the prescribed paper form.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-50(D) ('on paper approximately eight and one-half inches wide and eleven inches long with numbered lines for signatures spaced approximately three-eighths of an inch apart') and 1-8-50(F) ('firmly secured by a staple or other suitable fastening') verified verbatim on FindLaw. ADVERSARIAL: no statutory authorization for electronic/remote signature capture for this petition exists in 1-8-49 through 1-8-52; paper is correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. New Mexico provides no filing fee in lieu of (or in addition to) the signature petition for an independent presidential candidate. Ballot access is obtained solely by filing the notarized declaration of independent candidacy plus the signed nominating petition (NMSA 1-8-49(A)); the statute specifies no fee and no fee-for-signatures alternative.","note":"GROUNDED: 1-8-49(A) ('Nomination as an independent candidate for president or vice president shall be made by filing a declaration of independent candidacy ... The candidate for president shall also at the same time file a nominating petition with the required number of signatures.') verified verbatim on FindLaw; NASS quote verified verbatim in PDF. ADVERSARIAL: nothing in 1-8-49 through 1-8-52 authorizes a fee alternative for the independent presidential route; the 'None' value is correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"New York","sigs":"45,000 valid signatures (statutory cap; 1% of 2022 gov vote = 59,123, so 45,000 controls). 500 from each of half the CDs. Collect a large buffer.","deadline":"RECOMPUTE PER CYCLE: file 23 weeks before Election Day (was May 28, 2024). 2028 date NOT yet live — do not rely on the 2024 date.","risk":"3 of 7 fields on CONSERVATIVE-HOLD: deadline is a stale 2024 date that must be recomputed for the live cycle; circulator eligibility relies on a court injunction (use NY-registered witnesses to be safe); fee-alternative is an unverified absence claim. Core signature/distribution/capture/witness rules are AUTO-LIVE.","sos":["For an independent presidential nominating petition in the upcoming presidential cycle, what is the exact first and last day to file the petition with the State Board of Elections (the 24-week / 23-week window dates), and the exact deadline for each candidate's certificate of acceptance?","Is there any filing fee, bond, or other alternative to the 45,000-signature independent nominating petition for a presidential candidate, or is ballot access for an independent presidential candidate available by petition only?","Is the Schmidt v. Kosinski permanent injunction (allowing non-registered/non-resident U.S.-citizen petition witnesses to sign the appended statement) still in full effect for the upcoming cycle, and will signatures witnessed under it be accepted without challenge?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","perSignatureAllowed":"no","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"hourly-only","operatingStance":"NO per-signature (prohibited) — pay hourly/bonus; advocate to legalize","model":"per-signature prohibited (candidate/independent petitions) — hourly/salary OK; circulator must be NY voter","note":"Candidate-petition compensation IS specifically addressed. NY Election Law 17-122(4) makes it a misdemeanor to pay circulators for procuring signatures on \"an independent nominating petition for public office\" on a per-name basis or at a fixed amount per name, and 17-122(5) criminalizes even representing such per-name pay; paying circulators by hourly/salary/flat fee is not prohibited. Separately, 6-140(1)(b) requires each petition sheet to be witnessed by \"a duly qualified voter of the State of New York\" (or a NY notary/commissioner of deeds), so circulators must be NY voters and a non-resident national paid pool could not validly witness presidential independent petitions.","sosInquiry":"For an independent (unaffiliated) candidate's nominating petition for President of the United States in New York, does Election Law 17-122 prohibit paying petition circulators per signature, and is paying circulators on an hourly or salaried basis (with non-per-name bonuses) permitted? Also, must the subscribing witness/circulator be a duly qualified New York voter under 6-140?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/laws/ELN/17-122","quote":"Any person who: ... 4. Pays or agrees to pay money or other valuable consideration, to any person for his services in canvassing for or otherwise procuring the signatures of voters to a petition for the designation of a candidate or candidates for party nomination or for election to a party position to be voted for at a primary election, or to a petition for opportunity to ballot at a primary election, or to an independent nominating petition for public office, upon the basis of the number of names to such petition procured by such person, or at a fixed amount per name; or, 5. Represents to any person as an inducement for signing ... an independent nominating petition for public office, that the person soliciting such signature is to be compensated upon the basis of the number of names procured by such a person, or at a fixed amount per name; ... is guilty of a misdemeanor."},{"url":"https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/laws/ELN/6-140","quote":"There shall be appended at the bottom of each sheet a signed statement of a witness who is a duly qualified voter of the state and who has not previously signed a petition for another candidate for the same office. ... I, ...... (name of witness) state: I am a duly qualified voter of the State of New York and now reside at ......... (residence address). Each of the individuals whose names are subscribed to this petition sheet ... subscribed the same in my presence on the dates above indicated"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/laws/ELN/17-122","official":true,"dom":"nysenate.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/laws/ELN/6-140","official":true,"dom":"nysenate.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://elections.ny.gov/freedom-information-law-foil-requests","official":true,"dom":"elections.ny.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://newyork.public.law/laws/n.y._election_law_section_3-103","official":false,"dom":"newyork.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://newyork.public.law/laws/n.y._election_law_section_5-602","official":false,"dom":"newyork.public.law"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"45,000 valid signatures, OR 1% of the total votes (excluding blank/void) cast for Governor at the last gubernatorial election, whichever is less. 45,000 is the operative cap: 1% of the 2022 gubernatorial vote (5,912,286 total) = 59,123, which exceeds 45,000, so 45,000 controls for the 2024 cycle. Collected by an independent body on a single statewide independent nominating petition naming the presidential/VP candidates and the slate of electors. Recomputes each cycle.","note":"Citations verbatim at ELN 6-142, SBOE running-president, and ballot-access.org. Independently re-derived: 1% of 5,912,286 (2022 NY gov total, Hochul 3,140,415 + Zeldin 2,762,581 + minor) = 59,122.86 > 45,000, so the 'whichever is less' clause yields 45,000. Confirmed correct and current for 2024; will remain 45,000 unless gubernatorial turnout falls below ~4.5M. Strict guidance: collect a wide buffer (Diane Sare filed 70,000 for the 45,000 requirement).","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Statutory rule (ELN 6-158(9)): an independent nominating petition for an office filled at the general election must be filed not earlier than 24 weeks and not later than 23 weeks preceding the election. STRICTEST READING: treat the 23-weeks-before-Election-Day Tuesday as the hard filing deadline. For 2024 that was May 28, 2024; for any future presidential cycle this MUST be recomputed and confirmed with the SBOE before relying on it. Each named candidate (incl. president/VP) must file an acknowledged certificate of acceptance no later than the 3rd day after the last day to file the petition. EL 1-106 weekend/holiday rollover may apply.","note":"All citations verbatim (ELN 6-158(9), SBOE running-president acceptance rule, ballot-access.org May 28 corroboration). Date arithmetic independently confirmed: Nov 5, 2024 minus 23 weeks = Tue May 28, 2024 (= 23rd Tuesday preceding); minus 24 weeks = May 21, 2024. HOLD because the value is a PAST 2024-cycle date and the rule recomputes each cycle — the live actionable deadline for the next presidential election is not yet established and must be recomputed/confirmed. Over-comply: do not let a candidate rely on the stale 2024 date.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes - a congressional-district distribution requirement applies. At least 500 signatures, OR 1% of enrolled voters (whichever is less), must come from each of one-half of the state's congressional districts (i.e., from at least half of NY's congressional districts). In practice 500 per district controls, since 1% of enrolled voters in any CD far exceeds 500.","note":"Verbatim at ELN 6-142(1) and SBOE running-president. Independently confirmed: 1% of enrolled voters per CD vastly exceeds 500, so 500 is the binding per-district minimum across at least half the CDs. Current and correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST DEFENSIBLE: use witnesses who are duly qualified (registered) New York voters who have not previously signed a petition for another candidate for the same office. (Signers must themselves be NY registered voters qualified to vote for the office who have not signed a designating petition for it.) The Schmidt v. Kosinski permanent injunction (EDNY) expands eligibility to non-registered/non-resident U.S. citizens who sign the special appended statement, and the SBOE currently publishes this expansion - but a campaign should NOT bet ballot access on the injunction; default to registered-NY-voter witnesses.","note":"Base rule grounded verbatim at ELN 6-140(1)(b); the Schmidt expansion grounded verbatim at SBOE petition-information and running-president pages (SBOE itself states the witness requirements 'have changed' pursuant to the injunction). HOLD because correctness of the EXPANDED rule hinges on the continued force of a court injunction that retrieval cannot guarantee for a future cycle; the over-comply posture for ballot access is to rely only on the base statutory witness rule. SOS inquiry added to confirm the injunction's continued effect.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Each petition sheet requires a signed Statement of Witness by a qualified witness, accepted for all purposes as the equivalent of an affidavit and carrying perjury penalties (ELN 6-140(1)(b)). In lieu of the witness statement, the sheet may instead bear a notarial acknowledgment signed by a notary public or commissioner of deeds who swore each signer (ELN 6-140(2)). A non-resident/non-registered witness (per Schmidt v. Kosinski) uses a special appended statement instead. No separate notarization is required when a qualified witness signs.","note":"Both quotes verbatim in ELN 6-140 (the witness-affidavit-equivalent clause and the 'In lieu of the signed statement of a witness... notary public or commissioner of deeds shall be accepted' clause). Stable statutory text; current and correct. The witness-OR-notary alternative is squarely on the face of the statute.","conf":0.94,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Petitions must be on paper, signed in ink, and circulated by hand; the State Board of Elections expressly states electronic signatures are not acceptable. No digital/online petition system covers an independent presidential nominating petition in New York.","note":"Verbatim at SBOE petition-information ('These forms can be printed and filled out by hand. Electronic signatures are not acceptable.') and ELN 6-140(1)(a) ('Each sheet... shall be signed in ink'). Current and correct; no e-signature path exists.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat ballot access as petition-only. Assume NO filing-fee, bond, or other alternative to the 45,000-signature independent nominating petition exists for an independent presidential candidate; do not rely on any fee shortcut. (Confirm absence directly with the SBOE.)","note":"The cited running-president quote describes petition CONTENTS, not fees - it does not state 'no fee alternative,' so the value's core assertion ('None') is NOT grounded by the quote provided; it is an absence/negative inference. The conclusion is very likely correct (NY independent presidential access is petition-only with no statutory fee-in-lieu), but a negative cannot be verified verbatim from the supplied citation. HOLD and confirm with SBOE. The strict posture (petition-only) is conservative regardless.","conf":0.7,"interp":true}]},{"state":"North Carolina","sigs":"NC: 1.5% of last gubernatorial turnout = 83,874 (2024 cycle, NCSBE-confirmed) + 200 from each of 3 districts. AUTO-LIVE.","deadline":"NC deadline DISPUTED: statute+NCSBE say noon, day of primary (Mar 2024/2026); Ballotpedia says last Fri June. HOLD on earliest.","risk":"Two unresolved legal-interpretation conflicts (presidential petition deadline; whether any filing fee applies to an independent presidential candidate) force CONSERVATIVE-HOLD on deadline and feeAlternative; treat the earliest deadline (noon, day of primary) and a possible fee as binding until NCSBE confirms. All citations grounded verbatim; nothing BLOCKED.","sos":["For an unaffiliated/independent candidate for President of the United States under G.S. 163-122, is the petition-filing deadline noon on the day of the primary election (per the NCSBE petitions table and G.S. 163-122(a)(1)), or is there a separate presidential-specific deadline (e.g., the last Friday in June, with presidential-elector certification by the first Friday in August)? Please confirm the controlling date for the current cycle.","Does an unaffiliated/independent candidate for President of the United States owe any filing fee under G.S. 163-122(e)/G.S. 163-107 given that the G.S. 163-107 fee schedule lists no line item for President or presidential electors, or is the office fee-free? If a fee applies, what is the amount and does the G.S. 163-107.1 petition-in-lieu-of-fee alternative apply?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (general secondary indication the practice is currently legal, but not enacted/candidate-specific)","note":"The controlling unaffiliated-candidate-petition statute (N.C.G.S. 163-122, which governs independent presidential petitions) is entirely SILENT on circulator compensation: it does not authorize, prohibit, or mention paying circulators per signature or otherwise, and it imposes NO residency or voter-registration requirement on who may circulate/collect the signatures (only the signers must be qualified registered NC voters). NCSBE confirms \"State law provides minimal guidelines for conducting petitions,\" and the proposed 2025 Chapter 22 petition rules (Sections .0100/.0300/.0400) contain no compensation provision at all. So candidate-petition compensation is UNADDRESSED in primary NC authority. A WRAL news report indicates per-signature pay for ballot-access petitions is currently legal in NC and that the Board is only \"expected to recommend that lawmakers outlaw\" it — but that is a legislative recommendation, not enacted law, and is not candidate-petition-specific primary authority, so this stays CONSERVATIVE-HOLD.","sosInquiry":"For an UNAFFILIATED presidential candidate's nominating petition under N.C.G.S. 163-122, does any North Carolina statute or rule (a) permit or prohibit paying signature circulators per signature, (b) restrict paying circulators at all (e.g., hourly/salary), or (c) require circulators to be North Carolina residents or registered voters?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nc/chapter-163-elections-and-election-laws/nc-gen-st-sect-163-122/","quote":"(a) Procedure for Having Name Printed on Ballot as Unaffiliated Candidate.--Any qualified voter who seeks to have the voter's name printed on the general election ballot as an unaffiliated candidate shall: (1) If the office is a statewide office, file written petitions with the State Board of Elections supporting the voter's candidacy for a specified office. These petitions must be filed with the State Board of Elections on or before 12:00 noon on the day of the primary election and must be signed by qualified voters of the State equal in number to one and a half percent (1.5%) of the total number of voters who voted in the most recent general election for Governor."},{"url":"https://www.ncsbe.gov/news/press-releases/2025/03/17/public-comment-period-opens-proposed-rules-about-petitions-campaign-finance-disclosure","quote":"State law provides minimal guidelines for conducting petitions. The State Board has proposed rules for petitions that are designed to ensure consistency and transparency in the process for petitioners conducting petition drives and election officials tasked with reviewing and certifying petitions."},{"url":"https://wral.com/amp/political-long-shots-pay-per-signature-for-ballot-access-why-state-officials-want-to-end-the-practice/20385914","quote":"Like a majority of states, North Carolina allows political parties to pay collectors by the signature... The practice is legal, but critics say it raises the risk of fraud. Before the next legislative session, the board is expected to recommend that lawmakers outlaw the practice of paying collectors by the signature."},{"url":"https://www.ncsbe.gov/candidates/petitions/unaffiliated-candidate-petitions","quote":"...in the contest for President of the U.S. | 1.5% of all registered N.C. voters who voted in the most recent election for N.C. Governor. | Noon on the day of the primary election to CBE. | N.C.G.S. §163-122(a)(1), N.C.G.S. §163-209"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.ncsbe.gov/news/press-releases/2025/03/17/public-comment-period-opens-proposed-rules-about-petitions-campaign-finance-disclosure","official":true,"dom":"ncsbe.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.ncsbe.gov/candidates/petitions/unaffiliated-candidate-petitions","official":true,"dom":"ncsbe.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.ncsbe.gov/results-data/voter-registration-data","official":true,"dom":"ncsbe.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/dl.ncsbe.gov/data/layout_ncvoter.txt","official":true,"dom":"s3.amazonaws.com"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/dl.ncsbe.gov/data/ncvoter_Statewide.zip","official":true,"dom":"s3.amazonaws.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nc/chapter-163-elections-and-election-laws/nc-gen-st-sect-163-122/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://wral.com/amp/political-long-shots-pay-per-signature-for-ballot-access-why-state-officials-want-to-end-the-practice/20385914","official":false,"dom":"wral.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Formula-based: signatures equal to 1.5% of the total number of voters who voted in the most recent general election for Governor, plus at least 200 registered voters from each of three different NC congressional districts. For the 2024 gubernatorial base this equals 83,874 (per NCSBE 2026 Unaffiliated Candidate Fact Sheet). Statewide/presidential path runs through G.S. 163-122(a)(1), with G.S. 163-1(c) confirming an unaffiliated presidential candidate qualifies under 163-122 and nominates electors.","note":"All three citations ground verbatim (FindLaw 163-122, NCSBE unaffiliated-petitions table, FindLaw 163-1(c)). Formula is current and correct. Adversarial note: the draft labels the 2024 integer UNKNOWN, but the NCSBE 2026 official fact sheet explicitly states 83,874 (1.5% of 2024 gubernatorial turnout) for the statewide path — the figure IS confirmable from a primary source, so I relied on it. Minor wording variance (statute 'voters who voted' vs NCSBE 'registered voters who voted'; Ballotpedia 'votes cast for governor') is immaterial in practice. Value recomputes each cycle.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST: petition signature pages due to the county board of elections by 12:00 noon on the DAY OF THE PRIMARY ELECTION (e.g., noon March 5, 2024; noon March 3, 2026 per NCSBE fact sheet) — the earliest of the conflicting candidate deadlines. County-board verification no later than 15 business days after canvass of the primary. Do NOT rely on any later 'last Friday in June' date until NCSBE confirms in writing.","note":"Both citations ground verbatim. UNRESOLVED CONFLICT for the PRESIDENTIAL contest: statute 163-122(a)(1) + NCSBE petitions table + NCSBE 2026 fact sheet all say 'noon on the day of the primary'; Ballotpedia (citing FEC) says the independent-presidential petition is due 'no later than the last Friday in June' with electors certified by 'the first Friday in August.' Reconciling these requires legal interpretation retrieval cannot settle (whether a presidential-specific timeline supersedes 163-122). Strictest = earliest deadline (day of primary), which is what the draft adopts; held rather than auto-lived because missing the true deadline is catastrophic. Note the draft omits the possible first-Friday-in-August presidential-elector certification step.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Geographic distribution required: at least 200 registered voters from EACH of three NC congressional districts (minimum 200 from each of three different districts). Petition pages must additionally be divided into sections by the county in which signatures were obtained, for county-level verification.","note":"Citation grounds verbatim in 163-122(a)(1): 'the petition must be signed by at least 200 registered voters from each of three congressional districts in North Carolina. The petitions shall be divided into sections based on the county in which the signatures were obtained.' NCSBE 2026 fact sheet independently confirms '200 registered voters from three different congressional districts.' Adversarial check cleared a stale Ballotpedia phrase ('each of the state's congressional districts') — the statute and the fact sheet both say THREE, so the draft is correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"NC law regulates SIGNERS, not circulators: each signer must be a qualified registered NC voter residing in the applicable county, and no one may sign on behalf of another. No separate statutory circulator (age/residency/voter-status) requirement found for the unaffiliated petition; circulator-specific eligibility is UNKNOWN (no primary source establishes one).","note":"All three citations ground verbatim (NCSBE petitions page signer language; 'No one may sign a petition on behalf of another person'; statute signer requirement). The value is itself conservative — it asserts the signer rules and explicitly marks circulator eligibility UNKNOWN rather than claiming none exists. That is the strict posture, so no stricter reading is needed. Field rests on absence of a circulator statute, which is consistent with the primary sources reviewed.","conf":0.78,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None / not required. Verification is performed by election officials (Executive Director for statewide petitions, or the county board chair), who check signatures against registration records and attach a signed certificate. No notarized affidavit or circulator certification by the petition gatherer is required by G.S. 163-122 or NCSBE petition instructions.","note":"Citation grounds verbatim in 163-122(a)(1)(a): the Executive Director examines names, check-marks qualified/registered signers, and attaches a signed certificate stating signatures were checked against registration records. No circulator affidavit/notary appears anywhere in 163-122, the NCSBE petitions page, or the 2026 fact sheet. Correct and not interpretation-dependent.","conf":0.85,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper only. Signatures must be collected on official paper petition sheets, in ink, with original (wet) signatures; electronic signatures are not counted and signatures cannot be collected electronically. No digital/remote-online capture exists for the NC unaffiliated presidential petition.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim on the NCSBE petitions page: 'Signatures cannot be collected electronically.' and 'Signatures must be originals (please use INK); no electronic signatures will be counted. (Photocopies of signed forms are not accepted by county or state elections offices.)' Paper-only is correct and unambiguous.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST: do NOT assume the office is fee-free. G.S. 163-122(e) requires an unaffiliated candidate to pay the G.S. 163-107 filing fee for the office OR use the G.S. 163-107.1 petition-in-lieu-of-fee alternative; the NCSBE 2026 fact sheet answers 'Is there a filing fee to run as an unaffiliated candidate? Yes.' Treat a filing fee as potentially due for an independent presidential candidate and budget for the G.S. 163-107.1 fee-waiver petition as a hedge until NCSBE confirms in writing whether President carries a $0 fee.","note":"Both citations ground verbatim (163-122(e) fee-or-alternative language; 163-107 fee-schedule preamble). BUT the draft's CONCLUSION ('no fee for President') is an inference — the 163-107 table lists no 'President/presidential electors' line, so the draft reasons the fee is $0. This conflicts with the NCSBE fact sheet's plain 'Yes' that unaffiliated candidates owe a filing fee, and resolving it requires legal interpretation (does the missing line mean $0, or does the Board apply another basis?). Underpaying a required fee can void the filing, so strict posture = assume a fee may apply and confirm. Held, not auto-lived.","conf":0.55,"interp":true}]},{"state":"North Dakota","sigs":"4,000 signatures (flat statutory number; no distribution)","deadline":"4:00 p.m. on the 64th day before the general election","risk":"7 of 8 fields AUTO-LIVE and grounded against the SOS guide, NASS summary, and primary statute NDCC 16.1-12-02; only witnessOrNotary is on CONSERVATIVE-HOLD because the exact on-form certification block of SFN 58578 is unverifiable (sos.nd.gov form server returns HTTP 522, reproduced independently).","sos":["Does the Petition/Certificate of Nomination form (SFN 58578) for a non-established-party / independent presidential candidate require a circulator certification or notarized circulator affidavit, or is the candidate Affidavit of Candidacy (SFN 52500) the only sworn document in a complete filing? Please confirm the exact certification block printed on SFN 58578."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"North Dakota's candidate-petition statutes (NDCC 16.1-11-16 \"Form of nominating petitions\" and 16.1-12-02, which sets the 4,000-signature presidential petition) regulate only the petition's contents and require signers to be qualified ND electors; they are SILENT on who may circulate, circulator residency, and circulator compensation. The state's per-signature pay ban and circulator residency/affidavit/age rules sit only in the initiative/referendum framework (NDCC 16.1-01-09, titled \"Initiative or referendum petitions\" and tied to Article III of the ND Constitution) and the SoS \"Petition Signature Gathering Guidance FOR CIRCULATORS OF INITIATED AND REFERENDUM PETITIONS\" — neither applies to candidate petitions. So candidate-petition compensation is unaddressed, not permitted or prohibited; hold conservatively rather than carrying over the initiative rule.","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition under NDCC 16.1-12-02 (the 4,000-signature petition), may a campaign pay circulators per signature, and must those circulators be North Dakota residents or qualified electors — or do the per-signature ban and circulator residency rules in NDCC 16.1-01-09 apply only to initiative/referendum petitions?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-11-16/","quote":"1. Each nominating petition circulated by candidates for any state, district, county, or other political subdivision office must include or have attached the following information... 2. Only qualified electors of the state, district, county, or other political subdivision, as the case may be, may sign nominating petitions."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-12-02/","quote":"3. If the nomination is for the office of president, there must be no fewer than four thousand signatures and the petition must contain the names of the presidential and vice presidential candidates along with the names of the elector nominees and alternate elector nominees for the office of the North Dakota presidential electors. The elector nominees and alternate elector nominees must be qualified electors of North Dakota."},{"url":"https://www.sos.nd.gov/sites/www/files/documents/elections/petition-signature-gathering-guidance.pdf","quote":"PETITION SIGNATURE GATHERING GUIDANCE FOR CIRCULATORS OF INITIATED AND REFERENDUM PETITIONS ... Any person gathering signatures for a statewide petition may not be paid anything of value based on the number of signatures gathered."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-01-09/","quote":"§ 16.1-01-09. Initiative or referendum petitions--Signature--Form--Circulation ... No petition may be circulated under the authority of article III of the Constitution of North Dakota by an individual who is less than eighteen years of age ... The chairperson also shall submit a complete list of petition circulators which must include each circulator's full name and residential address. The residential address must be in this state and identify the circulator's street address, city, and zip code."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_North_Dakota","quote":"The relevant statutes do not stipulate any requirements (such as residency or pay status) that petition circulators must meet."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.nd.gov/sites/www/files/documents/elections/petition-signature-gathering-guidance.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.nd.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.nd.gov/elections/voter/voting-north-dakota/forms-voter-id","official":true,"dom":"sos.nd.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.nd.gov/elections/election-official","official":true,"dom":"sos.nd.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.nd.gov/elections/voter/ballot-measures","official":true,"dom":"sos.nd.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-11-16/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-12-02/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/nd/title-16-1-elections/nd-cent-code-sect-16-1-01-09/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_North_Dakota","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"4,000 qualified North Dakota electors (flat statutory number, not a percentage; does not recompute per cycle). Independent and non-established-party presidential candidates use the same form (SFN 58578), checking the 'independent candidate' box for the independent path. Authority: NDCC 16.1-12-02(3).","note":"SOS-guide quote and NASS quote both ground verbatim (SOS running-president.pdf lines 50-53; NASS report lines 803-806). Independently confirmed against primary statute NDCC 16.1-12-02 subsection 3 (FindLaw, current as of Jan 1 2024): 'If the nomination is for the office of president, there must be no fewer than four thousand signatures.' Flat number, current and correct for an independent presidential candidate.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"4:00 p.m. on the 64th day before the November general election (statutory rule, NDCC 16.1-12-02). The complete filing (petition + affidavit of candidacy + statement of interests + certificate(s) of nomination of presidential electors) must be in the physical possession of the Secretary of State's office by that deadline. The 2024 instance of this rule was September 3, 2024; the date shifts each cycle to the 64th day before that November election.","note":"SOS-guide quote (lines 85-93) and NASS quote (lines 803-806) ground verbatim. Primary statute confirms: petition 'shall submit ... before four p.m. on the sixty-fourth day before the general election.' Relied value is the recurring 64th-day rule, not the one-cycle Sept 3 2024 date. Physical-possession requirement confirmed in SOS guide.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. A single statewide total of 4,000 qualified-elector signatures; no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement (ND has one at-large U.S. House district). NDCC 16.1-12-02(3).","note":"NASS quote grounds verbatim (lines 805-806). Adversarially checked the statute: subsection 3 (president) sets only the flat 4,000 figure with no geographic distribution. The 2%-of-district rule in subsection 2 applies to sub-state district offices, NOT to president. No distribution rule appears in SOS guide, NASS summary, or the statute. None confirmed.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulators of this presidential nominating petition are NOT required to be ND qualified electors (no age/residency/voter-status requirement on circulators). The petition may not be circulated or signed before January 1 of the presidential election year. Signers must be qualified ND electors (U.S. citizen, 18+, 30 days' ND residency). Note: ND initiative/ballot-measure petitions under ch. 16.1-01 are different (resident circulators + notarized affidavits) and must not be conflated.","note":"SOS-guide quote grounds verbatim (lines 74-77): 'Petition circulators do not need to be ND qualified electors.' Statute confirms the Jan-1 signing window and exempts presidential petitions from the general form spec (16.1-11-16). Adversarial nuance: statute 16.1-12-02(3) requires the elector NOMINEES to be qualified ND electors, but that is a requirement on the presidential electors named on the petition, not on circulators or signers, so it does not contradict this field.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Strictest posture: ASSUME the SFN 58578 petition may carry a circulator certification or affidavit block that must be completed (and possibly notarized) before filing, and prepare to satisfy it; do NOT assume the signatures need no certification. The candidate Affidavit of Candidacy (SFN 52500) is independently required in any case. Cited sources (SOS guide, NASS, statute 16.1-12-02/16.1-11-16) describe no notary requirement on the signatures, but the exact on-form certification wording is UNCONFIRMED.","note":"Cited quotes ground verbatim (SOS guide line 59-61; NASS lines 803-806). Statute exempts presidential petitions from 16.1-11-16, and 16.1-11-16 itself contains no notary/circulator-affidavit clause, which supports the draft's reading. HOWEVER the precise certification block printed on form SFN 58578 could not be retrieved: the nd.gov/sos.nd.gov form server returns HTTP 522, which I reproduced independently via both curl and wick. Because the form's actual certification wording could change the answer and cannot be settled by retrieval, held conservatively and an SOS inquiry is filed.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures are collected on the paper Petition/Certificate of Nomination (SFN 58578); the complete filing must be in the physical possession of the Secretary of State's office by the deadline. ND has no remote/online or in-person-digitized signature-capture system for this presidential nominating petition.","note":"Both SOS-guide quotes ground verbatim (lines 91-93 and 50-53). Physical-possession requirement plus paper SFN 58578 confirmed by statute (petition 'submitted' to SOS). No online-capture path exists for this petition.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No state filing fee for the independent/non-established-party presidential nominating petition and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative; the 4,000-signature petition is the sole ballot-access mechanism. The $5,000 figure in the SOS guide is the federal FECA registration trigger (a campaign-finance obligation), NOT a state ballot-access fee.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim (SOS guide lines 89-92; NASS lines 803-806). No filing fee appears in the SOS complete-filing checklist, the NASS summary, or statute 16.1-12-02. The $5,000 FECA figure is correctly characterized as federal, not a state fee. Adversarially: statute lists petition contents only, no fee.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Ohio","sigs":"5,000 valid (max 15,000); fixed number, no per-district minimum","deadline":"90th day before general (Aug 7, 2024); recomputes each cycle","risk":"Core petition rule (5,000 sigs, 90-day, paper wet-ink, no notary) is grounded and AUTO-LIVE; two CONSERVATIVE-HOLDs: circulator residency depends on current injunction status, and the \"no fee alternative\" rests on a statutory gap (president absent from the 3513.10 fee schedule) that needs SOS confirmation.","sos":["For an independent presidential (president/vice-president) nominating petition filed under R.C. 3513.257, is a petition circulator currently required to be an Ohio resident, or does R.C. 3503.06(C)(1)(b) (age 18 only) plus the Citizens in Charge v. Husted injunction mean no residency requirement is enforced for the 2024/2028 cycle?","For an independent candidate for president/vice-president, is any filing fee owed at the time of filing the nominating petition under R.C. 3513.261? The 3513.10(A)/(B) fee schedule and the 3513.10(G) 'statewide office' definition do not list president/vice-president — please confirm the fee amount (if any) and that there is no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"no","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"hourly-only","operatingStance":"NO per-signature (prohibited) — pay hourly/bonus; advocate to legalize","model":"per-signature prohibited by statute (ORC 3599.111, expressly covers candidate/nominating petitions) but that statute was struck down for initiatives in Citizens for Tax Reform v. Deters; status as applied to candidate petitions is unsettled","note":"Ohio's per-signature ban (ORC 3599.111) is candidate-petition-specific: it expressly names \"any declaration of candidacy, nominating petition\" and makes per-signature/per-volume pay a 5th-degree felony, requiring payment \"except on the basis of time worked.\" However, the Sixth Circuit struck that statute as unconstitutional in Citizens for Tax Reform v. Deters, 518 F.3d 375 (6th Cir. 2008) (cert. denied) — but in an INITIATIVE-petition posture, so its reach to a candidate-petition prosecution is an extrapolation, not a clean authorization; the statute is still on the books. Paying circulators by time worked is clearly lawful, and circulators need not be Ohio residents/electors (residency requirement enjoined in Citizens in Charge v. Husted).","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition, does the Ohio Secretary of State / Elections Division consider ORC 3599.111's per-signature/per-volume compensation prohibition enforceable against candidate-petition circulators after Citizens for Tax Reform v. Deters, 518 F.3d 375 (6th Cir. 2008), or may circulators be compensated on a per-signature basis?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-revised-code/section-3599.111","quote":"No person shall receive compensation on a fee per signature or fee per volume basis for circulating any declaration of candidacy, nominating petition, initiative petition, referendum petition, recall petition, or any other election-related petition that is filed with or transmitted to a board of elections, the office of the secretary of state, or other appropriate public office. No person shall pay any other person for collecting signatures on election-related petitions or for registering voters except on the basis of time worked."},{"url":"https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-revised-code/section-3599.111","quote":"Whoever violates division (B) of this section is guilty of receiving improper compensation for circulating a petition, a felony of the fifth degree."},{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizens_for_Tax_Reform_v._Deters","quote":"Citizens for Tax Reform v. Deters, 518 F.3d 375 (6th Cir. 2008), was a decision that overturned an Ohio statute that made it a felony to pay petitioners by the signature."},{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizens_for_Tax_Reform_v._Deters","quote":"On March 5, 2008, a three judge panel of the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously upheld the district court ruling to strike Ohio's law banning per-signature payments.... On November 17, 2008, the United States Supreme Court announced that it was declining to hear Ohio's appeal."},{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizens_for_Tax_Reform_v._Deters","quote":"The case arose out of an attempt of Citizens for Tax Reform (CTR), an Ohio political advocacy group, to quality a citizen initiative for the 2005 general election ballot in that state."},{"url":"https://www.sos.state.oh.us/globalassets/publications/election/2025_crg.pdf","quote":"the Ohio residency requirement is not currently in place based on the preliminary injunction in Citizens in Charge v. Husted, Case: 2:13-CV-00935 (S.D. Ohio 11/13/13); See also, Citizens in Charge v. Husted, 810 F. 3d 437 (6th Cir 2016). ... a circulator does not have to be an Ohio elector or Ohio resident."}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-revised-code/section-3599.111","official":true,"dom":"codes.ohio.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.state.oh.us/globalassets/publications/election/2025_crg.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.state.oh.us"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://data.ohiosos.gov/portal/voter-registration","official":true,"dom":"data.ohiosos.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www6.ohiosos.gov/ords/f?p=VOTERFTP:STWD:::#stwdVtrFiles","official":true,"dom":"ohiosos.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizens_for_Tax_Reform_v._Deters","official":false,"dom":"en.wikipedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 valid signatures of qualified electors (statewide minimum), with petitions rejected if they purport to contain more than 15,000 signatures. Fixed statutory number, not a percentage; does not recompute by cycle.","note":"R.C. 3513.257(A) quote confirmed verbatim on FindLaw ('no less than five thousand qualified electors ... no petition shall be accepted ... more than fifteen thousand signatures'). Ballotpedia quote confirmed verbatim (line 234: 'at least 5,000 qualified voters'). NASS report independently corroborates 'at least 5,000 qualified electors.' Independently re-derived and correct for an independent presidential candidate. Minor caveat: the parenthetical extending the same 5,000 threshold to a 'new/minor-party presidential candidate' is loose (minor-party ballot status runs through a separate party-formation/petition mechanism), but it does not affect the independent-candidate value relied upon.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Not later than 4 p.m. of the 90th day before the general election. For 2024 (general election Nov. 5, 2024) this was August 7, 2024. Statement of candidacy + nominating petition + a sufficient slate of presidential electors must be filed with the Secretary of State by that time. The 90-day rule recomputes each cycle. HB2 (2024 special session) moved only the major-party certification deadline to the 65th day; it did not change the independent-candidate petition deadline.","note":"R.C. 3513.257 quote confirmed verbatim ('not later than four p.m. of the ninetieth day before the day of the general election'). NASS report quote confirmed verbatim (lines 846-848) and independently corroborates the 90th-day independent-candidate deadline AND the HB2 note that the 65th-day change applies only to MAJOR-PARTY certification (NASS lines 835-839), exactly as the draft claims. Date arithmetic independently verified: 90 days before Nov 5, 2024 = Aug 7, 2024 (Wednesday). Statute also confirms the presidential-elector slate must be submitted at filing. Value is current and correct; the specific date is cycle-specific and recomputes.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. The 5,000-signature requirement is a single statewide total; no minimum number of signatures per congressional district or per county. Mechanically, each petition paper must contain signatures of electors of only one county and separate papers are used per county, but no geographic distribution minimum is imposed.","note":"R.C. 3513.257(A) and R.C. 3513.261 quotes both confirmed verbatim on FindLaw. Independently re-derived: 3513.257 sets one statewide aggregate (5,000) with no district/county allocation; 3513.261's one-county-per-paper rule is a sorting/validity mechanic, not a distribution quota. Adversarial note worth flagging to staff (does not change the gate): 3513.261 further provides that if a single petition paper mixes counties, the board counts only signatures from the majority county and invalidates the rest — a paper-integrity rule, still not a geographic distribution minimum.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"A circulator of a nominating petition for presidential electors must be at least 18 years of age (R.C. 3503.06(C)(1)(b)). STRICTEST POSTURE: also assume the circulator may need to be an Ohio resident — the general residency requirement in R.C. 3503.06(C)(1)(a) is on the books and is reported as non-enforced only by virtue of the Citizens in Charge v. Husted injunction, an enforcement-status fact that retrieval cannot durably confirm as current. Plan for resident, 18+ circulators. Circulators need not be registered voters. Signers must be registered Ohio electors qualified to vote on the candidacy (R.C. 3501.38(A)).","note":"R.C. 3503.06(C)(1)(b) quote (age 18, presidential-elector petition) confirmed verbatim; Hamilton County 2024 guide quote confirmed verbatim (lines 47-50, including the Citizens in Charge v. Husted citations); R.C. 3501.38(A) signer-qualification quote confirmed verbatim. The age-18 and signer requirements are AUTO-LIVE-grade. HOLD is driven solely by the residency claim: whether the statutory Ohio-residency requirement is currently unenforced depends on the live status of a federal injunction, which is a currency/legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle to the strict standard. Defaulting to the over-comply posture (assume residency may apply) avoids any ballot-access risk.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization required. Each petition paper requires a circulator statement made UNDER PENALTY OF ELECTION FALSIFICATION (not before a notary) attesting to the number of signatures, that the circulator witnessed the affixing of every signature, that all signers were to the best of the circulator's knowledge and belief qualified to sign, and that every signature is genuine. Each petition must also carry the boldface warning that election falsification is a fifth-degree felony.","note":"R.C. 3501.38(E)(1) circulator-statement quote and 3501.38(J) boldface-felony-warning quote both confirmed verbatim on FindLaw. R.C. 3513.261's prescribed petition form independently shows the same circulator declaration ('under penalty of election falsification ... witnessed the affixing of every signature') with no notary jurat. Statute uses 'penalty of election falsification' rather than notarization throughout. Value is current and correct; no notary/witness requirement exists.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be collected on the official paper nominating petition with signatures affixed in ink or indelible pencil. Ohio provides no remote-online or in-person digital signature system for an independent presidential nominating petition; the petition is wet-ink paper filed with the Secretary of State.","note":"R.C. 3513.261 quote ('All signatures on nominating petitions shall be written in ink or indelible pencil') and R.C. 3501.38(B) quote ('Signatures shall be affixed in ink') both confirmed verbatim on FindLaw. Independently re-derived: ink/indelible-pencil wet-signature paper petition, no statutory e-signature alternative for nominating petitions. The specific form name 'Form 3-O' is non-load-bearing color not appearing in the cited statutory quotes, but the substantive paper/wet-ink mode is fully grounded and correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Treat ballot access as obtainable only via the 5,000-signature nominating petition; there is no money-payment alternative to gathering signatures for an independent presidential candidate. STRICTEST POSTURE: do not assume a fee can substitute for signatures, and confirm with the SOS whether any nominal filing fee is nonetheless owed at filing under R.C. 3513.261. The 3513.10(A)/(B) fee tables and the 3513.10(G) 'statewide office' definition do not list president/vice-president, creating an interpretive gap as to what (if any) fee 3513.261's cross-reference produces.","note":"R.C. 3513.261 fee-cross-reference quote and R.C. 3513.10(G) 'statewide office' definition quote both confirmed verbatim on FindLaw. Adversarial finding: the draft's CONCLUSION (no fee alternative; president absent from the fee schedule) is correct as far as the texts go, but bridging '3513.261 says pay the 3513.10(A)/(B) fee for the office' with '3513.10 lists no fee for president' requires a legal interpretation (does the office owe $0, or is the fee provision simply inapplicable?) that retrieval cannot definitively settle. Because the load-bearing point for ballot access is that signatures are the route (which is safe regardless), HOLD with the over-comply posture and route the fee-amount question to the SOS.","conf":0.68,"interp":true}]},{"state":"Oklahoma","sigs":"3% of last gubernatorial vote (34,599 for 2024); recomputes each cycle — HOLD on the stale number","deadline":"July 15 of presidential election year (fixed statutory date) — LIVE","risk":"All 7 citations grounded verbatim in primary sources. Hard mechanics (deadline, notary, paper-only capture, $35,000 fee) are AUTO-LIVE. Holds are on the cycle-stale signature number and three negative-inference claims (no distribution quota, circulator residency) that retrieval cannot settle — over-comply by treating the formula (not 34,599) as live and assuming no distribution/residency relief beyond what the form states.","sos":["For an independent presidential petition, is there any per-county or per-district minimum-signature distribution requirement, or is the only county rule that each petition page list voters from a single county?","Must a petition circulator for an independent presidential candidate be a registered Oklahoma voter (or Oklahoma resident), or is the only circulator requirement that they be at least 18 years old?","For the 2028 presidential cycle, what is the exact signature count equal to 3% of the total votes cast in the most recent (November 2026) general election for Governor, and the current per-elector filing-fee amount under 26 O.S. Section 20-102?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature ban is initiative-only under SB 1027)","note":"For Oklahoma CANDIDATE / independent-presidential petitions, compensation of circulators is UNADDRESSED: the election code and State Election Board guidance describe circulator duties but contain no per-signature or paid-circulator rule, and Oklahoma's 2025 pay-per-signature ban plus registered-Oklahoma-voter requirement (SB 1027) apply only to INITIATIVE/REFERENDUM petitions, not candidate petitions. The candidate-petition code imposes no circulator residency/registered-voter requirement, so a national paid pool is not statutorily barred — but because per-signature pay is unaddressed (neither permitted nor prohibited) for candidate petitions, hold conservatively and do not pay per signature.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition (not an initiative/referendum): does Oklahoma law permit paying circulators per signature, and must candidate-petition circulators be Oklahoma residents or registered voters?","citations":[{"url":"https://news.ballotpedia.org/2025/05/28/oklahoma-enacts-pay-per-signature-ban-residency-requirement-signature-distribution-requirement-and-funding-disclosure-rules-for-ballot-initiative-petitions/","quote":"Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt (R) signed Senate Bill 1027 (SB 1027) on May 27, enacting changes to the state's initiative and referendum processes."},{"url":"https://news.ballotpedia.org/2025/05/28/oklahoma-enacts-pay-per-signature-ban-residency-requirement-signature-distribution-requirement-and-funding-disclosure-rules-for-ballot-initiative-petitions/","quote":"Senate Bill 1027 also prohibits signature gatherers from being paid per signature, making Oklahoma the 10th state to enact such a ban."},{"url":"https://news.ballotpedia.org/2025/05/28/oklahoma-enacts-pay-per-signature-ban-residency-requirement-signature-distribution-requirement-and-funding-disclosure-rules-for-ballot-initiative-petitions/","quote":"The bill also made Oklahoma the ninth state with an initiative process to enact a residency requirement for signature gatherers, requiring signature gatherers to be registered voters in the state."},{"url":"https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/candidate-filing-archives/2026-candidate-filing-archives/2026-petition-info/2026-candidate-petition-instructions.pdf","quote":"It shall be the responsibility of the circulator to ensure that voters sign the petition page for the correct county. (See OKLA. ADMIN. CODE 230:20-9-2)."},{"url":"https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/candidate-filing-archives/2026-candidate-filing-archives/2026-petition-info/2026-candidate-petition-instructions.pdf","quote":"A signature on a petition in support of a Declaration of Candidacy filed by a candidate for a federal, state, or county office shall be the original, personally handwritten signature of a registered voter eligible to vote for the candidate and office."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Oklahoma","quote":"In order to qualify for placement on the general election ballot, an independent candidate must submit a petition containing signatures equaling at least 3 percent of the total votes cast in the last general election for governor."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Oklahoma","quote":"The Oklahoma Code did not stipulate any requirements for circulators of petitions, specifically with no residency requirements for circulators."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/candidate-filing-archives/2026-candidate-filing-archives/2026-petition-info/2026-candidate-petition-instructions.pdf","official":true,"dom":"oklahoma.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/ok-election-data-warehouse/edw-form-vrlist.pdf","official":true,"dom":"oklahoma.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/ok-election-data-warehouse/readme-vrlist.pdf","official":true,"dom":"oklahoma.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://oklahoma.gov/elections/candidates/voter-registration-list.html","official":true,"dom":"oklahoma.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://news.ballotpedia.org/2025/05/28/oklahoma-enacts-pay-per-signature-ban-residency-requirement-signature-distribution-requirement-and-funding-disclosure-rules-for-ballot-initiative-petitions/","official":false,"dom":"news.ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Oklahoma","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Oklahoma","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"At least 3% of the total votes cast in the last General Election for Governor. The signature count recomputes each presidential cycle off the most recent gubernatorial general election; rely on this formula, not a fixed number. (For the 2024 cycle the figure was 34,599 = 3% of 1,153,284, but that is a prior-cycle number and the 2028 figure depends on the Nov. 2026 gubernatorial vote, not yet held as of 2026-06-07.)","note":"GROUNDED: packet lines 101-111 (3% language + Total Votes 1,153,284 / 34,599) and NASS lines 867-868 confirmed verbatim. Independently re-derived: 1,153,284 x 3% = 34,598.52 -> 34,599, and 2022 gubernatorial total of 1,153,284 confirmed against Ballotpedia citing OK SEB certified results. The 3% RULE is correct and current. HOLD reason is temporal currency, not citation failure: 34,599 is the 2024-cycle figure; the live number for the next cycle is not yet determinable. Strictest treatment is to rely on the formula and avoid presenting the stale count as the current requirement.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"July 15 of the presidential election year. An independent presidential candidate must file the Statement of Candidacy (with petition or filing fee) with the Secretary of the State Election Board no later than July 15 of a presidential election year (26 O.S. Sec. 10-101.1(A)(1)). For 2024 the last day was Monday, July 15, 2024.","note":"GROUNDED: packet line 144 (statute: 'no later than July 15 of a presidential election year'), line 35 ('Monday, July 15, 2024'), and NASS line 869 confirmed verbatim. Fixed statutory date, not a cycle-variable number, so it remains live. The draft's '30 days' detail is correctly the Secretary's petition-sufficiency determination window (packet lines 38, 166), not a separate candidate deadline; it does not affect the July 15 filing deadline.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Strictest defensible: treat the single-county-per-page rule as a binding mandatory format requirement — each petition page must contain only registered voters from one Oklahoma county; do not mix counties on a sheet. Do NOT assume any relief beyond this: presence/absence of a per-county or per-district signature-distribution quota is not established by the form and should be confirmed with the Election Board before relying on 'no quota.'","note":"GROUNDED: packet lines 113 and 163 ('Each page... shall contain the names of registered voters from a single county') confirmed verbatim. But the draft's headline conclusion ('no geographic distribution quota') is a NEGATIVE INFERENCE (proving absence of a requirement) that retrieval cannot settle. The single-county-per-page rule IS confirmed; whether a distribution minimum exists elsewhere in 26 O.S. is not. Hold and over-comply by treating the per-page county rule as strict and not assuming quota relief.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Confirmed: circulator must be at least 18 years old and attest all signatures were signed in their presence; signers must be registered Oklahoma voters of the county listed on the page (packet lines 358, 373). STRICTEST treatment of the unconfirmed part: assume the circulator may also need to be a registered Oklahoma voter/resident — do NOT rely on the claim that there is 'no residency requirement beyond age 18' until confirmed with the Election Board.","note":"GROUNDED: packet line 373 ('at least eighteen (18) years old and that all signatures... were signed in my presence') and line 358 (signer voter-certification) confirmed verbatim. The age-18 and in-presence requirements are solid. But the draft's assertion that the packet imposes 'no separate Oklahoma-residency requirement on the circulator' is a NEGATIVE INFERENCE; circulator residency/voter-registration status is genuinely ambiguous from the form. Hold and assume the stricter requirement pending office confirmation.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarization required in two places: (1) the candidate's Statement of Candidacy oath must be witnessed by a notary public; and (2) each petition page's circulator affidavit ('TO BE COMPLETED BY PERSON CIRCULATING PETITION') must be signed and sworn before a notary public.","note":"GROUNDED: packet line 152 ('the candidate's signature shall be witnessed by a notary public'), line 372 ('TO BE COMPLETED BY PERSON CIRCULATING PETITION'), and line 379 ('Signed and sworn to before me on') all confirmed verbatim. Both notarization points are directly stated in the statute text and the prescribed form. No interpretation needed.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Oklahoma uses a paper petition on the form prescribed by the Secretary of the State Election Board (packet Page 10), circulated and signed in wet ink, organized by county, with a notarized circulator affidavit. There is no online/remote or digitized-signature system for an independent presidential petition; the only non-petition alternative is the paper filing fee. Submission is by mail, private delivery service, or in person.","note":"GROUNDED: packet line 114 ('Candidates must use the provided petition form (Page 10)') and lines 58-60 ('may be submitted by mail, private delivery service or in person') confirmed verbatim. No evidence of any electronic/online signature path; paper-only is the correct and current capture mode.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes — a filing fee may be submitted in lieu of the petition. For the current/2024 cycle the fee is $5,000 per Presidential Elector; Oklahoma has 7 electors, so the total is $35,000, payable by cashier's check or certified check to the Secretary of the State Election Board (campaign checks, personal checks, and cash are not accepted). Statutory per-elector basis: 26 O.S. Sec. 10-101.1 referencing the fee in Sec. 20-102.","note":"GROUNDED: packet lines 90-96 ('thirty-five thousand dollars ($35,000.00)... five thousand dollars ($5,000.00) for each Presidential Elector... seven (7) Presidential Electors... Campaign checks, personal checks, and cash cannot be accepted') and line 168 ('in lieu of the petition... a filing fee... may be submitted') confirmed verbatim. Minor currency caveat: the per-elector fee is statutorily tied to 26 O.S. Sec. 20-102; the $5,000/$35,000 figures are the packet's stated amounts for the current cycle, so they are grounded for now but worth reconfirming each cycle (captured in the SOS inquiry).","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Oregon","sigs":"~23,744 valid signatures (1% of 2020 presidential vote, 2,374,321); confirm SOS-certified count","deadline":"Filing deadline Aug 25, 2026 (70th day before 11/3 election); submit by ~Aug 11 for guaranteed verification","risk":"Core ballot-access rule is solid and grounded; treat the precise signature count and circulator eligibility details as unconfirmed (over-collect signatures; do not assume any circulator-eligibility leniency) until SOS confirms.","sos":["For an independent presidential candidate filing by Individual Electors for the November 3, 2026 general election, what is the exact SOS-certified number of valid signatures required (1% of the 2020 presidential vote), and what is the 2026 guaranteed-verification submission deadline?","For a candidate Individual Electors nominating petition (not an initiative), does Oregon impose any eligibility requirement on signature circulators as to minimum age, Oregon residency, or voter registration, and must paid circulators register with the Secretary of State before circulating?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","perSignatureAllowed":"no","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"hourly-only","operatingStance":"NO per-signature (prohibited) — pay hourly/bonus; advocate to legalize","model":"per-signature prohibited (candidate petitions expressly covered)","note":"Candidate-petition compensation IS expressly addressed in Oregon. ORS 260.569 and OAR 165-014-0260 specifically prohibit paying or receiving money based on the number of \"signatures a person obtains for purposes of nominating a candidate for elective public office\" — i.e., per-signature pay is illegal for candidate (including independent presidential) nominating petitions. Circulators may still be paid hourly/salary/bonus, and there is no Oregon residency or voter-registration requirement for circulators (paid circulators must instead register with the SoS and complete training per ORS 250.048).","sosInquiry":"For an independent (unaffiliated) presidential candidate's nominating petition under ORS 249.740, may circulators be paid by hourly wage, salary, or discretionary bonus (not per signature), and what registration/training and residency requirements apply to those paid circulators?","citations":[{"url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_260.569","quote":"A person may not pay or receive money or another thing of value based on the number of: (1) Signatures a person obtains for purposes of nominating a candidate for elective public office; or (2) Signed voter registration cards a person collects."},{"url":"https://oregon.public.law/rules/oar_165-014-0260","quote":"Prohibition on Paying or Receipt of Payment based on the Number of Signatures Obtained on an Initiative, Referendum, Candidate Nominating Petition or Voter Registration Cards ... A person may not pay or receive money or another thing of value based on the number of: signatures a person obtains for purposes of nominating a candidate for elective public office"},{"url":"https://oregon.public.law/rules/oar_165-014-0260","quote":"paying an hourly wage or salary, using express minimum signature requirements (quota), terminating those who do not meet the productivity requirements, adjusting salaries prospectively relative to productivity, and paying discretionary bonuses based on reliability, longevity and productivity, provided no payments are made on a per signature basis."},{"url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_249.740","quote":"whether one or more persons will be paid money or other valuable consideration for obtaining signatures"},{"url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_250.048","quote":"A person may not pay money or other valuable consideration to another person for obtaining signatures...unless the person obtaining the signatures: (a) Registers with the Secretary of State...and (b) Completes the training program"}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Pages/request-for-voter-list.aspx","official":true,"dom":"sos.oregon.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_260.569","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://oregon.public.law/rules/oar_165-014-0260","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_249.740","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_250.048","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_247.945","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_247.955","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://oregon.public.law/statutes/ors_247.948","official":false,"dom":"oregon.public.law"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Petition path (Individual Electors): valid signatures of active registered Oregon electors equal to not less than 1% of the total votes cast for all candidates for presidential electors at the last general election (ORS 249.735). For the 2024/2026 baseline (2020 Oregon presidential total = 2,374,321) that is approximately 23,744 (1% rounded up), but the operative requirement is the EXACT figure certified by the Secretary of State for the cycle; collect a comfortable cushion above 23,744. Names of the presidential electors must be filed with the petition. Alternative: nomination by an Assembly of at least 1,000 electors gathered in one place for no longer than 12 hours.","note":"All three citations confirmed verbatim: NASS PDF (lines 902-905: '...signatures of individual electors equal to not less than 1% of the total votes cast for all candidates for presidential electors...names of the presidential electors must be filed with the petition'), Ballotpedia ('...at least 1 percent of the total votes cast for presidential electors...'), Wikipedia total 2,374,321 (the official Total row). Independent re-derivation: 1% of 2,374,321 = 23,743.21, rounds up to 23,744 -> draft's ~23,744 is correct. CONSERVATIVE-HOLD because the precise operative count is set/certified by the SOS each cycle (draft itself flags this); the '~23,744' is a derived estimate, not the certified figure. The 1% legal rule itself is unambiguous; only the exact number needs SOS confirmation. Strictest defensible stance: treat 23,744 as a floor, over-collect, and verify the certified number before relying on it.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"70th day before the general election (ORS 249.722). For the November 3, 2026 general election that date is August 25, 2026. The certificate of nomination / petition signatures and the names of presidential electors must be filed by this deadline. SOS strongly advises submitting signatures earlier for verification time (the 2024 advice was 8/13/24); the 2026 guaranteed-verification signature submission date is on or about August 11, 2026 (signatures must be received at least 10 business days before the filing deadline).","note":"Independently verified the date math: Election Day 2026 = Tuesday Nov 3, 2026; 70 days before = Tuesday Aug 25, 2026 (exact match). SOS 2026 calendar row confirmed: 'August 25, 2026 / Last day for nonaffiliated or minor political party candidate, other than elected incumbent...to file certificate of nomination / 249.722 / -70' (calendar lines 1514-1558; reassembled across the PDF table columns, every token verbatim). NASS 70th-day quote verbatim (PDF lines 902-905). Ballotpedia 8/13/24 advice verbatim (line 592). The Aug 11, 2026 guaranteed-verification date is corroborated in the SOS calendar (lines 1398-1400) and the manual's 10-business-day rule (lines 1066-1067). Statutory date, no interpretation.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for a nonaffiliated/independent presidential candidate. The 1%-of-presidential-vote petition is a single statewide total with no per-county or per-congressional-district distribution quota. Signers should sign a petition sheet designated for their county of residence for sorting/verification only, which is not a distribution requirement. The 100-signatures-per-congressional-district rule applies to major-party statewide partisan petitions-in-lieu-of-fee and to nonpartisan statewide offices (Labor Commissioner, appellate judges), NOT to the nonaffiliated presidential petition.","note":"Both citations confirmed. NASS quote verbatim (flat statewide 1%, no distribution language). SOS manual county-sheet quote is verbatim but split across the PDF two-column break: 'Sign a petition sheet that is designated for' (line 1903) + 'their county of residence, if applicable.' (line 1932) form one continuous bullet. Independently confirmed the draft's congressional-district caveat is correct: the 100-per-CD rule appears at manual lines 740-742 (major-party statewide partisan petition) and lines 1384-1401 (nonpartisan statewide: Labor Commissioner, appellate judges), and is absent from the Individual Electors presidential petition definition. Line 1796 confirms county sorting is a verification convenience ('sheets are sorted by county if required'), not a quota. No real interpretation needed; primary sources are unambiguous.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Do NOT assume any circulator-eligibility leniency. Confirmed by the manual: every circulator must personally witness each signature and complete the circulator certification with a legal signature and date; an insufficient certification rejects the sheet; circulator pay status must be designated on the SEL 114 prospective-petition form. The candidate must be registered to vote as a nonaffiliated voter at least 180 days before the filing deadline (deadline to register nonaffiliated = February 26, 2026). UNVERIFIED and treated strictly: the manual does NOT affirmatively state there is no circulator age/residency/voter-registration requirement (the draft infers this from silence), and it does NOT affirmatively state that paid circulators must register with the SOS for candidate petitions. Pending SOS confirmation, assume circulators may need to meet eligibility requirements and that paid circulators may need to register.","note":"All three citations confirmed verbatim (manual lines 1816-1819 circulator definition; lines 917-918 prospective petition / pay status; lines 904-906 180-day nonaffiliated registration; cross-confirmed Feb 26, 2026 at quick-guide line 8 and manual line 907). 'Personally witness each signature' also verbatim (lines 1826/1830). DISAGREE / interpretationRequired because the VALUE makes two claims weaker than the sources support: (1) 'no age/residency/voter-registration requirement' is inferred from ABSENCE of a stated rule -- absence is not proof none exists (the draft openly flags this), and (2) 'Paid circulators must be registered with the SOS' is NOT affirmatively stated in the manual (the manual only references 'a paid circulator's registration' in the legal-signature definition, lines 1842/1979). Strictest defensible interpretation: do not rely on circulator leniency; assume eligibility limits and paid-circulator registration may apply until SOS confirms. Routed to sosInquiries.","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Individual Electors petition path: NO notarization. The circulator must personally witness each signature and complete a circulator certification (legal signature + date) on each signature sheet; an incomplete/insufficient certification rejects the sheet. Notarization is required only for the alternative Assembly of Electors path (SEL 115 certificate of nomination executed and notarized by the assembly's presiding officer and secretary) and for the minor-party SEL 110 form.","note":"All three citations confirmed verbatim: certification-by-signing quote (manual lines 1977-1978), 'Personally witness each signature collected' (lines 1826/1830, split across columns), and 'Notarized form SEL 115...executed by the presiding officer and secretary of the assembly' (lines 1056-1057). Independently confirmed the SEL 110 minor-party notarization claim (manual lines 296, 893-894, 2257). The Individual Electors path nowhere requires notarization. Correct and current; no interpretation.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The candidate files the prospective petition / certificate of nomination and gathers wet-ink signatures on Elections Division-issued paper signature-sheet templates; circulators must personally witness and certify each sheet. The manual states minor party and nonaffiliated candidates in the general election must file paper forms. ORESTAR is used only for the separate Voters' Pamphlet statement and fee-based primary/nonpartisan filings, not for collecting the nonaffiliated presidential nominating-petition signatures. No remote-online or digitized signature system covers an independent presidential petition.","note":"Both citations confirmed verbatim: 'Minor party or nonaffiliated candidates in the general election must file paper forms.' (manual line 379) and 'The Elections Division will provide signature sheet templates for candidates filing by individual electors' process.' (lines 920-921). Quick guide independently confirms ORESTAR is used only for the Voters' Pamphlet statement (lines 35-39), not for nominating-petition signatures. Correct; no interpretation.","conf":0.94,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"There is NO filing-fee alternative to the signature requirement for a nonaffiliated presidential candidate. Ballot access at the general election is obtained ONLY by (1) the Individual Electors petition (1% of presidential vote) or (2) an Assembly of at least 1,000 electors. No fee-in-lieu path exists. A separate optional Voters' Pamphlet filing fee exists solely to appear in the pamphlet (payable or substitutable with a separate pamphlet petition) and is not a route onto the ballot.","note":"All three citations confirmed: quick-guide Individual Electors quote verbatim incl. source typo 'By submit' (lines 10-12); NASS Assembly-of-1,000 quote verbatim (PDF lines 907-908); Voters'-Pamphlet pay-or-petition quote verbatim (quick-guide lines 35-39). Independently confirmed the two-and-only-two ballot routes for nonaffiliated candidates (quick-guide lines 9-13; manual Individual Electors / Assembly sections) with no fee-in-lieu option onto the ballot. The Voters' Pamphlet fee is explicitly a separate publication matter, not ballot access. Correct; no interpretation.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Pennsylvania","sigs":"President: 5,000 valid signatures (court-fixed) + $200 fee — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"Deadline HOLD: not a fixed Aug 1 — first day of Aug, rolled to next business day (Aug 3 in 2026); confirm per cycle","risk":"All 8 fields grounded verbatim, but every citation is the 2024 (presidential-cycle) DOS instructions; today is 2026 (a midterm with no presidential race) so the next live cycle is 2028. Substantive rules (5,000 sigs, no distribution, paper-only, fee-plus-sigs, circulator no-residency/no-affidavit) re-confirmed unchanged in the 2026 instructions, but the date-specific deadline is stale and the circulator age/registration qualification is unknown — these two are held.","sos":["For an independent/political-body candidate for President of the United States, what is the exact last day to file statewide nomination papers in the next presidential cycle (2028), given that the deadline is administered as the first day of August rolled to the next business day (e.g., Aug 1 in 2024 but Aug 3 in 2026)?","Other than the eliminated in-state residency and affidavit requirements, does Pennsylvania impose any minimum-age or voter-registration qualification on a circulator of political-body nomination papers?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Pennsylvania's Election Code provisions governing independent/political-body PRESIDENTIAL nomination papers (25 P.S. § 2911) and the Department of State's 2025 nomination-paper instructions are silent on circulator compensation: they do NOT permit or prohibit paying circulators, and say nothing about per-signature pay — so candidate-petition compensation is genuinely unaddressed, not carried over from initiative law (PA has no statewide initiative process and is not on Ballotpedia/NCSL's per-signature ban/permit lists). Circulator RESIDENCY, however, is clearly addressed: 2019 Act 77 amended § 2911(d) to eliminate the in-state residency requirement for circulators of nomination papers, and the statement may be made by \"some person, not necessarily a signer,\" so a national paid pool is not barred by a residency rule on these papers.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/political-body candidate for President filing nomination papers under 25 P.S. § 2911, may the campaign compensate circulators on a per-signature basis, or is only hourly/salary/flat-fee compensation permitted?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/pa/title-25-ps-elections-electoral-districts/pa-st-sect-25-2911/","quote":"Each sheet shall have appended thereto the statement of some person, not necessarily a signer, and not necessarily the same person on each sheet, setting forth, subject to the penalties of 18 Pa.C.S. § 4904 (relating to unsworn falsification to authorities)--(1) Deleted by 2019, Oct. 31, P.L. 552, No. 77, § 3, imd. effective;"},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/pa/title-25-ps-elections-electoral-districts/pa-st-sect-25-2911/","quote":"In addition to the party nominations made at primaries, nomination of candidates for any public office may also be made by nomination papers signed by qualified electors of the State, or of the electoral district for which the nomination is made, and filed in the manner herein provided."},{"url":"https://www.pa.gov/content/dam/copapwp-pagov/en/dos/programs/voting-and-elections/running-for-office/2025/nomination-papers-2025/pb%20nomination%20paper%20instructions%20final%202025.pdf","quote":"Statement of Circulator - Every nomination paper page must have the \"Statement of Circulator\" filled in and signed after all signatures have been obtained. Recent amendments to section 951(d) of the Pennsylvania Election Code, 25 P.S. § 2911(d), have eliminated the in-state residency requirement and the affidavit requirement for circulators of nomination papers for all political bodies."},{"url":"https://www.pa.gov/content/dam/copapwp-pagov/en/dos/programs/voting-and-elections/running-for-office/2025/nomination-papers-2025/pb%20nomination%20paper%20instructions%20final%202025.pdf","quote":"Rather, candidates for all statewide offices must gather 2,500 signatures, except for the offices of President of the United States, United States Senator, or Governor, which require 5,000 signatures."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","quote":"Pay-per-signature is a method of compensating signature gatherers, also known as circulators, who collect signatures for ballot initiatives and veto referendums, involving paying signature gatherers at a rate based on the number of signatures collected."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.pa.gov/content/dam/copapwp-pagov/en/dos/programs/voting-and-elections/running-for-office/2025/nomination-papers-2025/pb%20nomination%20paper%20instructions%20final%202025.pdf","official":true,"dom":"pa.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.pavoterservices.pa.gov/Pages/PurchasePAFullVoterExport.aspx?Langcode=en-US","official":true,"dom":"pavoterservices.pa.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.pavoterservices.pa.gov/Pages/PurchasePAFullVoterExport.aspx","official":true,"dom":"pavoterservices.pa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/pa/title-25-ps-elections-electoral-districts/pa-st-sect-25-2911/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Pay-per-signature_for_ballot_initiative_signature_gatherers","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.bedfordcountypa.org/document_center/Elections/requestvoterlists.pdf","official":false,"dom":"bedfordcountypa.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.reddit.com/r/Pennsylvania/comments/ti9278/did_you_know_you_can_download_the_entire_state/","official":false,"dom":"reddit.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 valid signatures of qualified registered electors of Pennsylvania for President (statewide nomination papers under 25 P.S. § 2911 et seq.). The 2% statutory calculation in § 2911(b) is not enforced per Constitution Party of Pa. v. Cortés (E.D. Pa. Feb. 1, 2018); DOS applies a fixed 5,000 for President, U.S. Senator, and Governor, and 2,500 for all other statewide offices.","note":"Quote verbatim in NASS PDF (PA section) and in the PB 2024 instructions both narratively (\"...except for the offices of President of the United States, United States Senator, or Governor, which require 5,000 signatures\") and in the signature table (\"President of the United States 5,000\"). Re-confirmed UNCHANGED in the active 2026 DOS instructions (same 5,000 language) and independently corroborated by Ballotpedia. Court-order basis stated correctly.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Do NOT treat the deadline as a fixed \"August 1.\" The statutory/consent-decree deadline is the first day of August, administered by DOS and rolled to the next business day when Aug 1 falls on a weekend/holiday: it was August 1, 2024 (Thu) for the 2024 presidential cycle but August 3, 2026 (Mon, because Aug 1, 2026 is a Saturday) for the 2026 cycle. For the next presidential cycle (2028), Aug 1 is a Tuesday, so the operative date is likely Aug 1, 2028 — but this MUST be confirmed against DOS's published 2028 calendar before relied upon. Filing is with the Bureau of Elections / Secretary of the Commonwealth, Room 201 North Office Building, Harrisburg, by 5:00 P.M. on that date. Strictest posture: assume the earliest plausible date (first business day of August), never assume any date later than the first of August is safe.","note":"Quotes are grounded verbatim in PB 2024 instructions, but they are 2024-specific (circulation Feb 14–Aug 1, 2024). The draft generalizes this to \"August 1 of the election year,\" which is FALSE: the active 2026 DOS instructions set the deadline to August 3, 2026 (Aug 1 is a Saturday). The deadline recomputes per cycle and is calendar-dependent; correctness for a current/2028 independent presidential candidate cannot be settled by retrieving the 2024 document. Held to strictest interpretation.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for President. There is no per-congressional-district or per-county minimum for a statewide presidential nomination paper — only the single statewide total of 5,000. Signers are organized by county solely as a clerical matter (each two-sided sheet must contain signers from one county, with that county noted); there is no per-county/per-district minimum. The historical \"severe distribution requirement\" applied only to statewide STATE offices, not to President.","note":"\"County of Signers\" quote and the 5,000 table entry are verbatim in PB 2024. The 2026 instructions confirm the same county-per-page clerical rule with no per-county minimum for statewide. Ballotpedia citation note 19 independently confirms the distribution requirement attaches to statewide STATE office, not President. No distribution minimum for President is correct and current.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"No in-state residency requirement and no circulator affidavit requirement for political-body nomination papers (covers independent/minor-party presidential papers) — both eliminated by amendment to 25 P.S. § 2911(d); the circulator need not be a PA resident. UNKNOWN whether any minimum-age or voter-registration qualification applies to the circulator: DOS instructions specify only that residency and the affidavit were removed and are silent on circulator age/registration. Strictest posture: do not assume any person may circulate; treat circulator age/registration as an open question pending DOS confirmation.","note":"\"...eliminated the in-state residency requirement and the affidavit requirement for circulators of nomination papers for all political bodies\" is verbatim in PB 2024 and re-confirmed verbatim in the 2026 instructions. The grounded claim is correct and current. Held only because the draft itself flags an UNKNOWN (circulator age/registration) that retrieval cannot resolve; an SOS inquiry is added rather than asserting \"anyone may circulate.\"","conf":0.85,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator: a \"Statement of Circulator\" must be filled in and signed on every sheet after all signatures are obtained, but the notarized circulator affidavit was eliminated (no notarization of the circulator statement). Candidate: must file a Candidate's Affidavit, normally notarized; under Act 2020-15 (signed Apr 20, 2020) the candidate may instead submit an unsworn Candidate's Declaration along with the affidavit in lieu of notarization.","note":"\"Every sheet... Statement of Circulator filled in and signed\" and the Act 2020-15 unsworn-statement language are verbatim in PB 2024; the candidate notarization/declaration language is verbatim on the live DOS third-party page. All re-confirmed UNCHANGED in the active 2026 instructions. Correct and current.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be collected on the official two-sided printed nomination paper (legal-size 8.5 x 14, printed 2-sided head-to-head); each signer personally signs with printed name, residence, and date (wet ink). Filing is in person or by mail; no online/digital signature-collection system exists for political-body/presidential nomination papers — DOS provides only blank printable forms.","note":"\"Nomination papers must be printed 2-sided on 8 1/2 x 14\\\" paper, head to head\" verbatim on the live DOS third-party page; \"Each signer must personally sign... printed name, place of residence and the date of signing\" verbatim in PB 2024. The 2026 instructions confirm \"Pages are double-sided.\" Paper-only with no e-signature option is correct and current.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"$200.00 filing fee for President, required IN ADDITION TO (not in lieu of) the 5,000 signatures — there is no signature-vs-fee alternative; both are required. The fee must accompany the nomination papers, paid by certified check or money order payable to the \"Commonwealth of Pennsylvania\" (no personal checks or cash).","note":"\"For Statewide offices (President of the United States...) — $200.00\" and the CERTIFIED CHECK/MONEY ORDER payment language are verbatim in PB 2024; NASS confirms \"a $200 fee, and nomination papers containing the signatures of 5000 qualified electors.\" The 2026 instructions and the live DOS page confirm the certified-check/money-order requirement. PA has no fee-vs-signature substitution; fee is additive. Correct and current.","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Rhode Island","sigs":"1,000 signatures (flat statewide aggregate) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"File w/ local board 60 days before general (Sep 6 in 2024) — HOLD: date recomputes each cycle","risk":"7 of 8 fields grounded and AUTO-LIVE; only the deadline is held because the specific calendar date is cycle-specific and one cited URL (justia §17-14-12) was unreachable, though the operative 60-day statutory rule is grounded verbatim elsewhere.","sos":["For an independent presidential candidate in the [next] general election, please confirm the exact date by which signed nomination papers must be returned to the local Board of Canvassers (the 60-days-before-general date) and the separate date by which local boards must file certified papers with the Secretary of State (54 days before), so we can verify both against the official election calendar."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; collectors need only be 18+ (no residency requirement)","note":"For Rhode Island candidate/independent-presidential nomination papers, circulator COMPENSATION is unaddressed: neither the candidate-petition statute (RIGL 17-14-10, the affidavit of person obtaining signatures), the controlling Board of Elections regulation (410-RICR-20-00-10), nor the official SOS candidate guide says anything about paying collectors per signature, hourly, or at all — so per-signature pay is neither expressly permitted nor prohibited. Residency is clearly NOT required: a collector need only be \"any person 18 years of age or older\" (the statutory qualification in RIGL 17-23-12 applies only to home-rule charter petitions, not ordinary candidate petitions), so a national paid pool could legally collect.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nomination papers under R.I. Gen. Laws ch. 17-14, may a campaign compensate signature collectors on a per-signature basis (and is paying collectors hourly/salary otherwise permitted), or does any RI statute, regulation, or Board of Elections policy restrict paying nomination-paper collectors?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ri/title-17-elections/ri-gen-laws-sect-17-14-10.html","quote":"Every person who obtains signatures of voters upon nomination papers shall under oath sign the following statement: \"I, __________, of the city/town of __________, under oath, make affidavit and say that the signers of the within nomination paper did so sign the paper in my presence.\""},{"url":"https://rules.sos.ri.gov/regulations/part/410-20-00-10","quote":"\"Collector\" means any individual who gathers the signatures and addresses of eligible voters upon nomination papers."},{"url":"https://rules.sos.ri.gov/regulations/part/410-20-00-10","quote":"A collector, who may be any person 18 years of age or older, must personally witness the signature of each person and shall sign and attest before a notary public that each person who signed the nomination papers appeared personally before him or her and signed the nomination papers in the presence of the. Said collector must have personal knowledge that each person actually signed the document and must provide on the nomination paper form the collector's printed name, residence address, and telephone number."},{"url":"https://vote.sos.ri.gov/Forms/Elections/Guides/NomPapers24Eng.pdf","quote":"Any individual over the age of 18 can collect signatures. ... The candidate does not need to be the one to collect the signatures."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ri/title-17-elections/ri-gen-laws-sect-17-23-12.html","quote":"No person, except one qualified to sign a petition for the adoption of a home rule charter as provided in § 6 of article XIII of the Constitution of this state, shall circulate any petition, or obtain signatures on any petition ... Nor shall any person not qualified as provided in subsection (a) of this section, obtain signatures on nomination papers of any elector seeking to be a candidate at any election held for the purpose of selecting the members of a charter commission"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://rules.sos.ri.gov/regulations/part/410-20-00-10","official":true,"dom":"rules.sos.ri.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://vote.sos.ri.gov/Forms/Elections/Guides/NomPapers24Eng.pdf","official":true,"dom":"vote.sos.ri.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://vote.sos.ri.gov/Forms/elections/Forms/VoterListOrderForm.pdf","official":true,"dom":"vote.sos.ri.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ri/title-17-elections/ri-gen-laws-sect-17-14-10.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ri/title-17-elections/ri-gen-laws-sect-17-23-12.html","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/ri/title-17-elections/ri-gen-laws-sect-17-6-9/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 signatures of registered voters, in the aggregate (a flat statewide number, not a percentage). Per RI Gen. Laws § 17-14-7(a), nomination papers of an independent candidate for presidential elector must be signed, in the aggregate, by at least 1,000 voters. Fixed statutory figure; does not recompute per cycle.","note":"All three citations ground VERBATIM: findlaw §17-14-7(a) ('signed, in the aggregate, by at least one thousand (1,000) voters'); SOS Nominations page table ('President of the United States | 1000'); Ballotpedia presidential page ('This petition must contain 1,000 signatures'). Adversarial check: the §17-14-7 'for the 2020 election only' reduction to 500 applied ONLY to US Senator and Representative in Congress, NOT to presidential elector, and has expired — so president remains at 1,000. Current and correct.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Operative candidate deadline: signed nomination papers must be returned to the local Board of Canvassers no later than 60 days before the general election (RI Gen. Laws § 17-14-11(a)). For Nov 5, 2024 that date was September 6, 2024 (matching the SOS official calendar). Separately, local boards must file certified papers with the Secretary of State no later than 54 days before the election (§ 17-14-12; Sept 12, 2024). STRICT reliance: treat the 60-day-before-general local-board filing as binding and RECONFIRM the exact calendar date against the SOS election calendar for each cycle — the specific date recomputes annually.","note":"Facts grounded: findlaw §17-14-11(a) ('shall be filed not later than sixty (60) days prior to the general election') VERBATIM; SOS page ('Presidential Electors | September 6') VERBATIM; §17-14-12 54-day boards-to-SOS deadline VERBATIM on findlaw. Date math confirms Nov 5 2024 −60d = Sep 6, −54d = Sep 12. Held (not AUTO-LIVE) for two reasons: (1) the cited justia URL for §17-14-12 returned a CAPTCHA and could not be grounded at the cited URL (the fact is grounded on findlaw instead) — citation-integrity gap; (2) 'September 6' is cycle-specific and recomputes, and two distinct deadlines exist (60-day candidate→local board vs 54-day local board→SOS) — relying on a stale calendar date could risk ballot access, so the durable statutory rule plus a per-cycle reconfirmation is the strictest defensible posture.","conf":0.82,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No per-congressional-district or per-county signature quota; the requirement is a single statewide aggregate of 1,000 voters (RI Gen. Laws § 17-14-7(a)). A procedural per-sheet organization rule applies (not a distribution quota): each nomination-paper sheet lists one city/town at the top and may carry only signatures of voters registered in that city/town, because that sheet is verified by that locality's Board of Canvassers.","note":"Both citations ground VERBATIM: findlaw §17-14-7(a) (aggregate 1,000); SOS page ('Signers on a nomination paper must be from the city or town listed at the top of the nomination paper'). Adversarial check confirmed the city/town rule is an organizational/verification mechanism, not a geographic distribution minimum — there is no minimum-per-locality quota. Characterization is accurate.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The signature collector (circulator) may be any person 18 years of age or older (410-RICR-20-00-10 §10.4(A)). No circulator residency requirement, no requirement that the circulator be a registered voter, and no restriction on paid circulators. Signers must be RI registered voters eligible to vote for the office and need not be members of the candidate's party.","note":"Both citations ground VERBATIM against the CURRENT regulation (amendment effective 07/22/2024): reg §10.4(A) ('A collector, who may be any person 18 years of age or older, must personally witness...'); Ballotpedia political-candidates page ('The relevant statutes do not specify any additional circulator requirements (such as residency or pay status)'). Note for downstream use: this same regulation requires the collector to execute a NOTARIZED affidavit (see witnessOrNotary). Current and correct.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator affidavit required. The collector must personally witness each signature and must sign and attest BEFORE A NOTARY PUBLIC that each signer appeared personally and signed in the collector's presence; the collector must also provide their printed name, residence address, and telephone number on the nomination paper (410-RICR-20-00-10 §10.4(A), adopted under RI Gen. Laws § 17-14-10).","note":"Citation grounds VERBATIM in the current 07/22/2024 regulation, including the (sic) truncated phrase 'in the presence of the.' which appears in the source itself. 'shall sign and attest before a notary public' confirms notarization is mandatory, not optional witnessing. Current and correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. In-person, paper-based process: the candidate (or authorized designee for federal/presidential papers) obtains physical nomination papers from the Department of State's Elections Division (148 W. River Street, Providence); signers sign in person with name and residence as on the voting list; the collector witnesses each signature in close physical proximity and executes a notarized affidavit; signed papers are returned to local Boards of Canvassers for manual verification. No online/remote-digital or digitized petition system exists for a presidential petition in RI.","note":"All three citations ground VERBATIM: SOS page ('Federal offices: You must obtain your nomination papers from the Department of State's Elections Division, 148 W. River Street, Providence, RI.'); reg ('Every voter signing a nomination paper shall sign in person with his or her name, place of residence, and street number, as it appears on the voting list.'); reg definition of 'Presence' ('close physical proximity coupled with awareness sufficient...'). No evidence of any electronic petition pathway. Correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Rhode Island has no filing fee for ballot access and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option; qualification is by nomination papers (signatures) only.","note":"SOS quote grounds VERBATIM ('In order to be on the ballot, you will need to obtain a specified number of valid signatures on your nomination papers. All candidates for federal, state and local public office need nomination papers.'). Adversarial check: searched the SOS Nominations page and both Ballotpedia pages for any filing-fee or fee-in-lieu provision — none found; RI ballot access is signature-only. This is an absence-of-evidence finding but is consistent across all sources, hence AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"South Carolina","sigs":"10,000 valid signatures (statewide cap; 5% of registered electors but capped at 10k, which always controls)","deadline":"Noon, July 15 of general-election year (next Monday if July 15 is Sat/Sun)","risk":"All seven fields grounded against primary sources (verbatim) and corroborated by Ballotpedia; six AUTO-LIVE. Only captureMode held: digitized signatures are permitted but the SEC explicitly warns they may be unverifiable, so rely on paper to avoid any ballot-access risk.","sos":["For an independent presidential petition (10,000 signatures), will the State Election Commission accept digitized (touchscreen/stylus + DocuSign Certificate of Completion) signatures on the same footing as pen-and-ink for the full 10,000, and are there any volume, format, or assembly conditions that affect how digitized signatures are counted toward the 10,000-signature requirement?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"South Carolina's candidate-petition statutes (Title 7, Chapter 11) and the election-offenses chapter (Title 7, Chapter 25) are entirely silent on petition circulators: they neither define a circulator role nor impose any residency/voter-registration requirement, and they neither authorize nor prohibit paying circulators (per signature or otherwise). Candidate-petition circulator compensation is therefore unaddressed by any primary source found; SC also has no statewide initiative/referendum process, so there is no initiative pay-per-signature law to carry over. A widely-repeated secondary claim that SC \"prohibits paid circulators\" and requires county residency could not be corroborated in the actual statutes and should not be relied upon.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under S.C. Code Title 7, Chapter 11, does South Carolina law restrict compensating petition circulators — specifically, may a campaign pay circulators per signature, and must a circulator be a South Carolina resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t07c011.php","quote":"SECTION 7-11-70. Nomination by petition. A candidate's nominating petition for any office in this State shall contain the signatures of at least five percent of the qualified registered electors of the geographical area of the office for which he offers as a candidate; provided, that no petition candidate is required to furnish the signatures of more than ten thousand qualified registered electors for any office."},{"url":"https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t07c011.php","quote":"SECTION 7-11-80. Form of nominating petition. All nominating petitions for any political office or petition of any political party seeking certification as such in the State of South Carolina shall be standardized as follows: (1) Shall be on good quality original bond paper sized 8 1/2 '' X 14''. (2) Shall contain a concise statement of purpose; in the case of nomination of candidates, the name of the candidate, the office for which he offers and the date of the election for such office shall be contained in such petition. (3) Shall contain in separate columns from left to right the following: (a) Signature of voter and printed name of voter; (b) Address of residence where registered; and (c) Precinct of voter."},{"url":"https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t07c025.php","quote":"SECTION 7-25-50. Bribery at elections; unlawful to accept bribery. It is unlawful for a person to procure, by the payment, delivery, or promise of money or other article of value, another to vote for or against any particular candidate or measure at any election held within this State..."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/States_without_initiative_or_referendum","quote":"South Carolina is one of the 24 states that do not have initiative and referendum. ... citizens do not have the power to initiate ballot measures at the state level."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t07c011.php","official":true,"dom":"scstatehouse.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t07c025.php","official":true,"dom":"scstatehouse.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://scvotes.gov/resources/sale-of-voter-registration-lists/","official":true,"dom":"scvotes.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/States_without_initiative_or_referendum","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"10,000 valid signatures of active, registered South Carolina voters (statewide cap). Statutory basis: 5% of qualified registered electors of the office's geographic area, capped at 10,000 for any office (S.C. Code 7-11-70). For statewide President, 5% of ~3.39M registered voters (~170k) far exceeds the cap, so 10,000 always controls. Electorate baseline = registrations 120 days before the election.","note":"Both citations verbatim in sources (7-11-70 statute; scvotes.gov 'valid signatures of 10,000 active, registered'). Independently corroborated by Ballotpedia (5% / max 10,000) and by the SEC page's live registered-voter count of 3,392,645, confirming the cap controls. The cap is a fixed hard number; it could only stop controlling if SC registration fell below 200,000, which is impossible.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Noon (12:00 p.m.) on July 15 of the general-election year, filed with the State Election Commission. If July 15 falls on a Saturday or Sunday, the deadline is noon the following Monday (S.C. Code 7-13-351). For Nov 2024 this was Monday, July 15, 2024.","note":"7-13-351 quote verbatim in fetched statute; scvotes.gov presidential-section quote verbatim. Ballotpedia corroborates July 15. Draft correctly tracks the statute's 'Saturday or Sunday' rule (the SEC general petition section drops 'Saturday', but the statute and the presidential-specific section both include it). July 15, 2024 was indeed a Monday. Note: a Governor-declared emergency grants +5 days (7-13-351), an omitted contingency, not a defect in the standard deadline.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No geographic distribution requirement. For statewide President the petition is a single statewide aggregate with no per-county or per-district minimum. Administrative formatting only: no single petition page may contain signatures of voters from different counties (S.C. Code 7-11-80(4)) — a per-page sorting rule, not a distribution quota.","note":"7-11-80(4) and scvotes.gov 5% quotes both verbatim. Statute imposes no geographic spread requirement; the one-county-per-page rule is correctly characterized as formatting, not a quota.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None specified. S.C. petition statutes (7-11-70, 7-11-80, 7-11-85) impose no circulator/collector requirements (no oath, age, residency, or voter-status). The petition form collects only signer information; there is no circulator role. Validity rests on matching each signer against county registration records.","note":"7-11-80(3) quote verbatim. Confirmed no circulator role exists anywhere in 7-11-70/80/85. 'None specified' is the correct, accurate statement of SC law.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No circulator affidavit, witness, or notarization requirement for the petition pages. The 7-11-80 form has only the statement of purpose and voter-signature columns. Validity is determined by county boards matching signatures against original registration applications (S.C. Code 7-11-85). (Separately the candidate self-certifies qualifications and files a Statement of Economic Interests, but the petition pages need no notary/witness.)","note":"7-11-85 verification quote verbatim. No notary/witness/affidavit block exists on the petition form per 7-11-80. Accurate.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"paper (original pen-and-ink petition pages on 8.5 x 14 bond paper, filed with the State Election Commission). Photocopies are NOT accepted. The SEC permits 'digitized signatures' (human-readable, drawn on touchscreen/stylus, with an accompanying Certificate of Completion) as an OPTIONAL add-on, but expressly warns the petitioner 'assumes the risk that such differences may render the signature unverifiable,' and there is no dedicated e-petition portal. Cryptographic 'digital signatures' are NOT accepted. To never risk ballot access, treat capture as paper-primary and do not rely on digitized signatures for the bulk of the 10,000.","note":"All three digitized/digital quotes verbatim on scvotes.gov, so the field is fully grounded. Held because the draft's 'hybrid' label is an operational interpretation that retrieval cannot settle: the SEC explicitly disclaims reliability of digitized signatures and provides no e-petition system, so leaning on the digital path could jeopardize the ballot line. Strictest defensible mode = paper; digitized signatures are permitted-but-risky, not a true digital capture channel.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee for petition candidates and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for an independent presidential petition. Filing fees apply only to candidates seeking a party nomination by primary. (A local jurisdiction could require a fee in addition to a petition, but that does not apply to a statewide presidential petition filed with the SEC.)","note":"Both scvotes.gov quotes verbatim ('candidates filing by petition do not pay a filing fee'; the local-jurisdiction caveat). No fee-in-lieu path exists for the petition route; accurate.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"South Dakota","sigs":"3,502 valid sigs (1% of combined 2022 gov vote, 350,166) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"First Tue in Aug, 5:00 PM CT (Aug 6, 2024) — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"6 of 7 fields AUTO-LIVE on grounded primary statute + SOS sources; only circulatorEligibility is CONSERVATIVE-HOLD because SD's resident-circulator rule is constitutionally contested and 12-1-4 was amended (SL 2025, partly eff. 1/1/2026) so the 2024-cycle residency text is uncertain — strictest path (SD-resident, 18+ circulators) does not risk ballot access.","sos":["For the 2024 general election cycle, did South Dakota enforce the SDCL 12-1-3(12)/12-1-4 requirement that a nominating-petition circulator be a South Dakota resident (and what residency definition, e.g. the 30-consecutive-day standard, applied), given federal litigation over resident-circulator requirements? Please confirm whether a non-resident circulator's signatures would be rejected for an independent presidential petition."],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature ban SDCL 12-13-28 applies only to ballot measures); circulator must be a SD resident","note":"For CANDIDATE/independent nominating petitions, South Dakota law does NOT address circulator compensation at all — there is no candidate-petition per-signature statute and the Secretary of State's candidate-circulation guide is silent on pay. The only per-signature prohibition, SDCL 12-13-28, applies expressly and solely to ballot measures (initiated measures, referred laws, constitutional amendments), so it does NOT control candidate petitions; per-signature pay for candidate circulators is therefore unaddressed (not affirmatively permitted). Residency IS clearly required for candidate-petition circulators: they must be SD residents and 18+ (registration not required).","sosInquiry":"For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's nominating petition (not a ballot measure), may a campaign pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, or is per-signature pay limited to hourly/salary/bonus, and does any compensation restriction in Title 12 apply to candidate petitions as opposed to initiated measures under SDCL 12-13-28?","citations":[{"url":"https://sdlegislature.gov/api/Statutes/12-13-28.html?all=true","quote":"No person may employ, reward, or compensate any person to circulate a petition for an initiated measure, referred law, or proposed amendment to the South Dakota Constitution based on the number of registered voters who signed the petition. Nothing in this section prohibits any person from employing a petition circulator based on one of the following practices: (1) Paying an hourly wage or salary; ... (4) Paying discretionary bonuses based on reliability, longevity, and productivity. Any violation of this section is a Class 2 misdemeanor."},{"url":"https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/assets/2026%20Documents/2026HowtoCirculateNomPetitionStateLegCountyCandidates.pdf","quote":"A petition circulator must be a resident of the state of South Dakota who is at least eighteen years of age. They are not required to be a registered voter."},{"url":"https://sdlegislature.gov/api/Statutes/12-1-3.html?all=true","quote":"\"Petition circulator,\" a resident of the State of South Dakota as defined under § 12-1-4, who is at least eighteen years of age who circulates nominating petitions or other petitions for the purpose of placing candidates or issues on any election ballot"}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sdlegislature.gov/api/Statutes/12-13-28.html?all=true","official":true,"dom":"sdlegislature.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/assets/2026%20Documents/2026HowtoCirculateNomPetitionStateLegCountyCandidates.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sdsos.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sdlegislature.gov/api/Statutes/12-1-3.html?all=true","official":true,"dom":"sdlegislature.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/upcoming-elections/voter-registration-totals/default.aspx","official":true,"dom":"sdsos.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/assets/VoterFileRequestForm.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sdsos.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"3,502 valid signatures for the 2024 cycle (1% of the 350,166 total combined vote cast for Governor at the 2022 election). Recomputes each cycle off the most recent certified gubernatorial total. SDCL 12-7-7.","note":"Both citations grounded verbatim: SDCL 12-7-7 ('not less than one percent of the total combined vote cast for Governor at the last certified gubernatorial election') and the SOS 2024 page ('Independent: 3,502 signatures (1% of the total vote for governor in 2022 - 350,166)'). Re-derived: 1% of 350,166 = 3,501.66 -> 3,502. Ballotpedia's dedicated presidential page independently confirms the same combined-gubernatorial-vote basis (distinct from the per-party 1% basis used for partisan candidates). Operative SOS figure is correct and current.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Certificate of nomination with nominating petitions, declaration of candidacy, and VP certification must be filed with the Secretary of State by the first Tuesday in August at 5:00 p.m. central time before the election (August 6, 2024 for the 2024 general). Mailing by registered mail by the deadline is timely. Petitions may not be circulated before January 1 of the election year. SDCL 12-7-7; 12-6-4.1.","note":"SDCL 12-7-7 grounded verbatim ('after December thirty-first and by the first Tuesday in August at 5:00 p.m. central time before the election ... If the certificate of nomination is mailed by registered mail ... it is timely submitted'). SDCL 12-6-4.1 grounded verbatim at its section URL ('No petition or certificate of nomination ... may be circulated prior to the first day of January'). First Tuesday in August 2024 = Aug 6, 2024 (Aug 1, 2024 was a Thursday). Confirmed by Ballotpedia ('filed by 5:00 p.m. on the first Tuesday in August'). Note: the draft cites the chapter URL /Statute/12-6 for the 12-6-4.1 quote; the text lives at section 12-6-4.1, which I fetched and confirmed verbatim.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Single statewide total (1% of the statewide combined gubernatorial vote); no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement for a statewide independent presidential candidate. Filed with the Secretary of State because the office is voted on in more than one county.","note":"SDCL 12-7-7 grounded verbatim; the statute imposes only a single statewide 1%-of-combined-gubernatorial-vote total with no geographic distribution. Reviewed full chapter 12-6 (incl. 12-6-7) and found per-county/per-district splits only for legislative/county offices and vote-center counties, not for statewide/presidential petitions. No distribution requirement applies.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST: Use only circulators who are South Dakota residents (actual fixed permanent dwelling, lives/usually sleeps there for the requisite consecutive days per SDCL 12-1-4) and at least 18 years old (SDCL 12-1-3(12)). Signers must be registered voters entitled to vote for the office; a party-affiliated voter may sign an independent's petition only if they have not previously signed another petition for that office (SDCL 12-6-8). Do NOT rely on non-resident circulators.","note":"All quoted text grounded verbatim: SDCL 12-1-3(12) ('a resident of the State of South Dakota as defined under 12-1-4, who is at least eighteen years of age'), 12-1-4 residency definition, and 12-6-8 signer-eligibility/cross-party provision. HOLD for two reasons: (1) SD's resident-circulator requirement has a known constitutional vulnerability (federal courts have enjoined SD resident-circulator requirements in the ballot-measure context), so whether a non-resident circulator's signatures can lawfully be rejected is a legal-interpretation question retrieval cannot settle; (2) SDCL 12-1-4 was amended by SL 2025 ch 57 and ch 58 (the latter eff. Jan 1, 2026), so the current 'thirty consecutive days' text may not be the exact version in force for the 2024 cycle the draft labels it for. The over-comply path (SD-resident, 18+ circulators) never risks ballot access, so it is the relied value; sent an SOS inquiry to confirm enforcement and the applicable residency standard.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator certification under oath (verification by the circulator on each self-contained sheet), not a per-signer notarized affidavit. The circulator's verification may NOT be notarized by the candidate the petition nominates. Falsely attesting is a Class 6 felony. SDCL 12-6-8; 12-1-3(11).","note":"Grounded verbatim at SDCL 12-6-8 ('The petition must be verified under oath by the persons circulating the petition. The verification ... may not be notarized by the candidate whom the petition is nominating. Any person ... who falsely attests to the verification is guilty of a Class 6 felony') and SDCL 12-1-3(11) (form contains 'the verification of the circulator'; multi-sheet petitions each separately verified). Correct and current. (Draft cites chapter URL /Statute/12-6; the operative text is at section 12-6-8, fetched and confirmed verbatim.)","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Physical paper nominating petitions, wet-ink signatures by registered voters, verified under oath by a resident circulator on each self-contained sheet. No remote/online or in-person-digitized e-signature system exists for SD candidate petitions. SDCL 12-1-3(11); 12-6-8.","note":"Grounded verbatim: SDCL 12-6-8 ('The circulator or the individual who signs the petition shall add the address at which the individual is currently registered to vote, the county ..., and the date of signing'; 'A nominating petition for any election shall be a self-contained sheet of paper') and 12-1-3(11) (each sheet self-contained and separately verified). The self-contained-paper-sheet + handwritten signer info + circulator oath structure confirms paper-only; no statutory e-signature petition portal for SD candidate petitions. Correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee in lieu of or in addition to the signature requirement for an independent presidential candidate. Ballot access is obtained solely by filing the certificate of nomination with the required petition signatures. SDCL 12-7-7; chapter 12-6.","note":"SDCL 12-7-7 grounded verbatim; it conditions nomination only on filing the certificate with the required petition signatures and prescribes no fee alternative. Reviewed full chapter 12-6 and found no filing-fee-in-lieu provision for nominating petitions. Absence-of-fee-alternative independently confirmed; no contrary provision located.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Tennessee","sigs":"275 signatures (25 × 11 electors), statewide, no distribution — VERIFIED","deadline":"Noon CT, 3rd Thursday in August (Aug 15, 2024) — physical receipt, no postmark — VERIFIED","risk":"Core ballot-access facts (275 sigs, Aug deadline, paper, no fee) are grounded and independently corroborated; two negative-fact fields (circulator eligibility, no notary) rest on statutory silence — circulator field has zero citations (BLOCKED) and notary held conservative; confirm both with TN SOS before relying on unrestricted circulators or unwitnessed pages.","sos":["Does Tennessee impose any age, residency, or voter-registration requirement on a person who circulates or collects signatures for an independent presidential nominating petition under TCA 2-5-101, or may a non-resident/paid circulator collect signatures?","Does an independent presidential nominating petition under TCA 2-5-101 require any circulator affidavit, oath, witness, or notarization on each petition sheet, or is the signer's residence address the only verification requirement?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Tennessee's candidate-petition statute (TCA § 2-5-101) sets only the signature counts (an independent presidential candidate's petition needs the candidate plus 25 registered voters per allocated elector — 275 total) and its sole \"prohibited acts\" subsection (f) addresses dual qualification, not paying signature gatherers; nothing in the candidate election code, the Secretary of State / CTAS guidance, or Ballotpedia addresses whether candidate-petition circulators may be paid, paid per signature, or must be Tennessee residents. Ballotpedia states verbatim that \"The relevant statutes do not address petition circulator requirements,\" so candidate-petition compensation is genuinely UNADDRESSED — do not carry over any initiative/ballot-measure per-signature rule, and treat per-signature pay as not-clearly-permitted pending confirmation.","sosInquiry":"For an independent candidate for President, does Tennessee law permit a campaign to pay people who circulate the nominating petition on a per-signature basis (versus hourly/salary), and must a paid petition circulator be a Tennessee resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/tn/title-2-elections/tn-code-sect-2-5-101/","quote":"(b)(1) Nominating petitions shall be signed by the candidate and twenty-five (25) or more registered voters who are eligible to vote to fill the office. Nominating petitions for independent presidential candidates shall be signed by the candidate and twenty-five (25) or more registered voters for each elector allocated to the state. Each independent candidate must designate the full number of electors allocated to the state."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/tn/title-2-elections/tn-code-sect-2-5-101/","quote":"(f)(1) It is unlawful for any person to qualify as a candidate in a primary election with more than one (1) political party in which such person seeks the same office. (2) It is unlawful for any person to qualify as an independent candidate and as a primary candidate for the same office in the same year."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Tennessee","quote":"The relevant statutes do not address petition circulator requirements."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Tennessee","quote":"An independent presidential candidate must petition for placement on the general election ballot. This petition must contain 275 signatures."},{"url":"https://www.ctas.tennessee.edu/eli/nominating-petitions","quote":"the nominating petition must be signed by the candidate as well as a minimum of 25 or more registered voters who are eligible to fill the office."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.nashville.gov/departments/elections/candidates/order-voter-list","official":true,"dom":"nashville.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://ovr.govote.tn.gov/","official":true,"dom":"ovr.govote.tn.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.tn.gov/elections","official":true,"dom":"sos.tn.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/tn/title-2-elections/tn-code-sect-2-5-101/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Tennessee","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_presidential_candidates_in_Tennessee","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.ctas.tennessee.edu/eli/nominating-petitions","official":false,"dom":"ctas.tennessee.edu"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/tn/title-2-elections/tn-code-sect-2-2-138/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"275 signatures (25 registered voters per elector × 11 electors). Signers must be registered voters anywhere in Tennessee; no per-county or per-district distribution. Candidate must also sign. Recomputes after each census-driven reapportionment of TN's electoral votes.","note":"Both citations verbatim: FindLaw TCA 2-5-101(b)(1) ('twenty-five (25) or more registered voters for each elector allocated to the state'; 'must designate the full number of electors') and SOS guide ('at least two hundred seventy-five (275) voters registered anywhere within the State'). Independently corroborated by Ballotpedia (lines 98, 229: '25 voters per state elector (275 total)') and that TN was allocated 11 electoral votes in 2012/2016/2020/2024. Math 25×11=275 is current through 2030 census cycle. Per-elector formula recompute claim is correct.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"12:00 noon Central time on the third Thursday in August of the election year (Aug 15, 2024 for that cycle). Original petition plus one certified duplicate must be physically received by the deadline; a postmark does not suffice. If the deadline falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or state holiday it moves to noon on the previous business day (TCA 2-5-101(g)(2)). Recomputes each cycle.","note":"SOS quotes verbatim ('third Thursday in August'; 'A postmark will not suffice'). TCA 2-5-101(g)(2) text confirmed verbatim on FindLaw: deadline on Sat/Sun/state holiday moves to noon previous business day. Ballot Access News (2024-08-13) and Ballotpedia independently confirm Aug 15, 2024 and the third-Thursday rule (changed from third Tuesday in 2021). Third-Thursday-in-August derives from the general (a)(1) rule (third Thursday of third calendar month before a November election) and is stated explicitly in the SOS guide.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No distribution requirement on petition signatures — the 275 signers may be registered voters anywhere in Tennessee. A separate distribution rule applies only to the elector slate: 11 electors total, 1 resident from each of the 9 congressional districts plus 2 at-large electors who may reside anywhere in the state.","note":"Both SOS quotes verbatim ('voters registered anywhere within the State'; '1 elector from each of Tennessee's 9 congressional districts, and 2 additional electors who may be residents of any part of the state'). The signer-vs-elector distinction is explicit in the guide, not an inference. Ballotpedia corroborates 9 congressional districts and 11 electors. Structural fact, not a contested legal interpretation.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"BLOCKED","val":"none","note":"Field has ZERO citations, so it cannot be grounded per gate rules. The assertion (statute/guide silent on circulator qualifications) is consistent with the full TCA 2-5-101 text I read and with the SOS guide — no circulator provision appears — but a negative claim with no supporting citation is unverifiable as drafted. Strictest posture: do NOT assume circulators are unrestricted; confirm with TN SOS before using non-resident or paid circulators. SOS inquiry added.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"As read, TCA 2-5-101 and the SOS guide impose no per-sheet witness/notary/circulator-affidavit requirement; the only signer-verification rule is that each signer include the residence address shown on the signer's voter registration card (TCA 2-5-101(b)(2)). TREAT AS UNCONFIRMED until the TN SOS confirms no notarization/oath is required, since this rests on statutory silence.","note":"Cited quote is verbatim from TCA 2-5-101(b)(2) ('must include the address of the signer's residence as shown on the signer's voter registration card in order for that person's signature to be counted'). I confirmed the full statute text contains no witness/notary/affidavit provision. BUT the cited quote only establishes the signer-address rule; the 'no notary required' conclusion is an inference from statutory silence that retrieval cannot fully settle — hence held conservatively. SOS inquiry added.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Physical paper petition only: candidate picks up the petition from the Division of Elections (in person or by mail) and files the wet-ink original plus one certified duplicate by the deadline; a postmark does not suffice and faxed/emailed documents are not accepted. No remote-online or in-person-digitized e-signature system exists for this petition.","note":"Both SOS quotes verbatim (90-day pick-up window, in person or mailed; 'A postmark will not suffice'; certified-duplicate photocopy definition). Physical-receipt requirement plus the write-in section's 'No faxed or emailed documents will be accepted' support paper-only. No e-signature pathway found in any source. Current factual matter.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee for an independent presidential nominating petition, and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option. The petition signatures are the sole path to the general-election ballot.","note":"SOS quote 'There are no filing fees.' is verbatim; filing-location quote (note the source's own 'with with' typo) is verbatim. No fee-in-lieu provision appears in TCA 2-5-101 or the SOS guide. The 'no fee-in-lieu' claim is supported by the affirmative 'no filing fees' statement plus absence of any alternative path; uncontested.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Texas","sigs":"TX independent pres: 113,151 valid sigs for 2024 (1% of prior presidential total); non-primary voters only — number confirmed, but verify cycle recompute","deadline":"TX deadline: 2nd Monday in May = May 13, 2024; circulate only after March 5 primary — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"Grounding clean on all 8 fields (every quote verbatim; 113,151 = round-up of 1% of 11,315,056 2020 TX total). Two holds: signatures (mixes the minor-party gubernatorial base into the independent rule) and circulatorEligibility (self-flagged UNKNOWN, an unprovable absence claim). Default strict pending SOS confirmation.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT presidential candidate's petition under Tex. Elec. Code 192.032, are there any statutory or administrative qualifications on who may circulate the petition (e.g., must the circulator be a registered Texas voter, of a minimum age, or a U.S. resident), or may any person circulate it?","Does the independent presidential candidate's signature requirement of 1% of the most recent presidential vote recompute each presidential cycle off the prior presidential general election total (i.e., for 2028 it will be 1% of the 2024 Texas presidential vote), and is the 113,151 figure specific to the 2024 cycle only?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition, Texas Election Code §192.032 incorporates the candidate-petition rules of §141.062–.065; none of those sections — nor the SOS candidate-guide FAQs or the SOS petitions page — addresses compensating circulators in any way, so per-signature pay for CANDIDATE petitions is genuinely unaddressed (not authorized and not prohibited). Circulator residency is NOT required: §141.065 imposes no residency/registration requirement on the circulator and the SOS FAQ states verbatim that the Election Code defines no eligibility requirements for circulators, so a national paid pool could legally circulate in Texas.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under Texas Election Code §§192.032 and 141.062–.065, may the campaign pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and are there any restrictions on paying circulators (e.g., hourly vs. per-signature) or any circulator residency/registration requirement?","citations":[{"url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_192.032","quote":"(b) An application must: (1) comply with Section 141.031 ... and (3) be accompanied by: (A) a petition that satisfies the requirements prescribed by Section 141.062 (Validity of Petition) ... (e) A petition signer's voter registration is not required to be in any particular territory."},{"url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_141.065","quote":"(a) Each part of a petition must include an affidavit of the person who circulated it, executed before a person authorized to administer oaths in this state, stating that the person: (1) pointed out and read to each signer, before the petition was signed, each statement pertaining to the signer that appears on the petition; (2) witnessed each signature; (3) verified each signer's registration status; and (4) believes each signature to be genuine and the corresponding information to be correct."},{"url":"https://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/candidates/guide/2026/faqs.shtml","quote":"The Election Code does not define any eligibility requirements for service as a circulator. For example, a person may circulate a petition even if the circulator is not a registered voter of the area."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/candidates/guide/2026/faqs.shtml","official":true,"dom":"sos.state.tx.us"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/pi.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.state.tx.us"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_192.032","official":false,"dom":"texas.public.law"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_141.065","official":false,"dom":"texas.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_18.066","official":false,"dom":"texas.public.law"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://texas.public.law/statutes/tex._election_code_section_18.067","official":false,"dom":"texas.public.law"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"For the independent presidential path only: at least 1% of the total vote received in Texas by all candidates for president in the most recent presidential general election. For the 2024 cycle this equaled 113,151 valid signatures of registered voters who did NOT vote in either party's presidential primary that year (recomputes each cycle off the prior presidential vote; 1% of the 2020 total of 11,315,056 rounds up to 113,151). No geographic/territory requirement on signers. (Strict scope: the minor/convention-party qualification — 5% statewide nominee threshold or 1% of the most recent gubernatorial vote — is a DIFFERENT path with a DIFFERENT base and does not apply to an independent candidate; do not conflate.)","note":"All quotes verbatim. 192.032(d)=1%; SOS=113,151; 192.032(e)=no territory; 192.032(f)/(g)=non-primary voters/invalid if signed on or before primary. Math checks: 1% of 11,315,056 (2020 TX total, confirmed via Wikipedia) = 113,150.56 -> 113,151. HOLD because the draft value bundles the convention/minor-party path (gubernatorial-vote base) into the independent rule, which is out-of-scope for accessPath=independent and could mislead; the 'recomputes each cycle' framing is also a derived gloss not stated verbatim in a citation. Independent number itself is correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":true},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The application and accompanying petition must be filed with the Secretary of State no later than the second Monday in May of the presidential election year — May 13, 2024 for the 2024 cycle. The petition may not be circulated until after the March 5, 2024 presidential primary; a signature is invalid if signed on or before the date of the primary or by anyone who voted in a presidential primary that year.","note":"192.032(c) 'second Monday in May' verbatim; SOS 'no later than May 13, 2024' and 'circulated beginning after March 5, 2024' verbatim. May 2024 Mondays = 6th, 13th, so 2nd Monday = May 13 (date arithmetic confirmed). 192.032(g) invalidity quote present. Correct and self-executing, no legal interpretation needed.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no per-congressional-district or per-county distribution requirement for the independent presidential petition; the statute expressly provides that a signer's voter registration need not be in any particular territory, so signatures may be gathered statewide with no geographic spread.","note":"192.032(e) quote 'A petition signer's voter registration is not required to be in any particular territory.' verbatim. Independently confirmed against NASS (no distribution language for the TX independent presidential petition, unlike states such as Virginia which NASS lists with a 400-per-district requirement). Negative claim but directly supported by the express statutory text.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"UNKNOWN / not established by retrieval. Secs. 141.064-141.065 prescribe the circulator's DUTIES (point out and read each statement, witness each signature, ascertain dates, verify each signer's registration, and execute a notarized affidavit) but do not by themselves establish that there are NO eligibility limits. Do not represent that 'any person' may circulate; treat circulator qualifications as unconfirmed and assume the petition must be circulated by a competent adult able to witness signatures and swear the notarized affidavit, pending SOS confirmation.","note":"Both cited section headers/quotes are verbatim (141.064 'A person circulating a petition must:'; 141.065(a) affidavit clause). But the field's substantive claim is a NEGATIVE/absence assertion ('no statutory provision restricts circulator eligibility') that two cited duty-sections cannot prove — the value even self-flags UNKNOWN. Cannot ground the non-existence of a restriction from these sources; strictest stance is to hold and ask the SOS rather than assert open eligibility.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Notarized circulator affidavit required. Each part of the petition must include an affidavit of the circulator, executed before a person authorized to administer oaths (notarized), stating the circulator pointed out and read each required statement to each signer, witnessed each signature, verified each signer's registration status, and believes each signature genuine. A single notarized affidavit covers all signatures gathered by that circulator if notarization is on or after the date of the last signature obtained.","note":"141.065(a) 'executed before a person authorized to administer oaths in this state' and 141.065(c) single-notarized-affidavit quote both verbatim. Directly on point and applies to the independent presidential petition via 192.032(b)(3)(A)->141.062. No interpretation needed.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper (wet-signature). Signers must sign in their own handwriting; the circulator must witness each signature in person and a notarized circulator affidavit is required per part. No online/remote or digitized-signature system exists for an independent presidential petition in Texas — the SOS publishes only PDF forms (Application 2-38f, Petition 2-39f).","note":"141.063(b) 'The signature is the only information that is required to appear on the petition in the signer's own handwriting.' verbatim; 141.064(1) read-each-statement quote verbatim; SOS 'Independent Candidate's Petition for President (PDF)' verbatim. Wet-ink/witnessed paper process follows directly from witnessing + per-part notarized affidavit. Correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Ballot access for an independent presidential candidate is by petition only — there is no filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option for this office. Sec. 192.032 requires the application to be accompanied by a qualifying petition and the consent statements, and lists no filing-fee alternative. (The fee-or-petition election available to Texas primary/partisan candidates does not apply to this independent presidential path.)","note":"192.032(b)(3) 'be accompanied by:' quote verbatim — the statutory list of what accompanies the application is exhaustive and contains only the petition and written consents, no fee or fee-in-lieu. SOS independent section (quote verbatim) describes application+petition with no fee. The absence is supported by an exhaustive statutory enumeration rather than mere silence, so 'no fee alternative' is reliable without legal interpretation.","conf":0.85,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Utah","sigs":"1,000 valid registered-voter signatures statewide (flat statutory number) + $500 fee","deadline":"DISPUTED: signatures due June 15 (20A-9-502(5)(a)); Aug 15 only for running-mate/VP filing — treat June 15 as binding for signatures","risk":"Only real exposure is the deadline: statute sets June 15 for signature submission while 504 sets Aug 15 for the running-mate/VP step; collect and submit signatures by June 15 to never risk the ballot line. Circulator non-residency relied on a 2015 snapshot; current statute dropped the residency clause but confirm before staffing non-resident circulators.","sos":["For an unaffiliated/independent candidate for President of the United States, what is the firm deadline to SUBMIT the 1,000 signatures / certificate-of-nomination petition to the county clerks and to FILE the certificate with the Lieutenant Governor — is it the June 15 deadline in Utah Code 20A-9-502(5)(a)/20A-9-503(1), or the August 15 date in 20A-9-504(2), which on its face governs only selection of a running mate and the VP's 20A-9-202(7) filing?","Under the current (post-2024) version of Utah Code 20A-9-502, is there any residency requirement for the person who circulates and signs the verification on an unaffiliated U.S. President certificate-of-nomination petition, or may a non-resident circulate and verify?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found (per-signature ban in 20A-7-104 is limited to initiatives/referenda)","note":"Utah's candidate-petition statute for unaffiliated candidates (20A-9-502, which expressly covers president of the United States) sets out circulation/verification mechanics — circulator must be 18+, need not be a Utah resident for a presidential petition — but is SILENT on compensating circulators; it neither permits nor prohibits per-signature pay. Utah's per-signature ban (20A-7-104) applies only \"under this chapter,\" i.e., to initiative/referendum petitions in Title 20A, Chapter 7, and does NOT reach candidate petitions in Chapter 9. Because no candidate-petition-specific compensation rule exists, per-signature pay is unaddressed, not clearly authorized — so CONSERVATIVE-HOLD applies.","sosInquiry":"For an independent/unaffiliated candidate for President of the United States gathering nominating-petition signatures under Utah Code 20A-9-501 to -503, may the campaign pay circulators on a per-signature basis, or does any statute, rule, or office policy require hourly/salaried compensation (as 20A-7-104 does for initiatives/referenda)? Also, must petition circulators be Utah residents or registered voters?","citations":[{"url":"https://le.utah.gov/xcode/Title20A/Chapter9/C20A-9-S502_2025050720250507.pdf","quote":"20A-9-502 Certificate of nomination -- Contents -- Circulation -- Verification -- Criminal penalty -- Removal of petition signature. (3)(a) The candidate shall circulate the nomination petition and ensure that the person in whose presence each signature sheet is signed: (i) is at least 18 years old; and (ii) verifies each signature sheet by completing the verification bound to one or more signature sheets that are bound together."},{"url":"https://le.utah.gov/xcode/Title20A/Chapter9/C20A-9-S502_2025050720250507.pdf","quote":"I will be out of the state of Utah during the entire candidate filing period [applies if filing via a designated agent for an office other than president of the United States] ... at least 1,000 registered voters residing within the state when the nomination is for an office to be filled by the voters of the entire state"},{"url":"https://le.utah.gov/xcode/Title20A/Chapter7/C20A-7-S104_2024050120240501.pdf","quote":"20A-7-104 Signature gatherers -- Payments -- Badges ... (1) A person may not pay a person to gather signatures under this chapter based on a rate per signature, on a rate per verified signature, or on the initiative or referendum qualifying for the ballot. (2) A person that pays a person to gather signatures under this section shall base the payment solely on an hourly rate."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://le.utah.gov/xcode/Title20A/Chapter9/C20A-9-S502_2025050720250507.pdf","official":true,"dom":"le.utah.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://le.utah.gov/xcode/Title20A/Chapter7/C20A-7-S104_2024050120240501.pdf","official":true,"dom":"le.utah.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://vote.utah.gov/obtain-voter-registration-or-election-data/","official":true,"dom":"vote.utah.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://vote.utah.gov/voter-privacy-information/","official":true,"dom":"vote.utah.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://cs.utah.gov/s/elections-request","official":true,"dom":"cs.utah.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 signatures of registered voters statewide — a flat statutory number set by Utah Code 20A-9-502(5)(a)(ii)(A) for an office filled by the voters of the entire state (President); not a percentage and does not recompute by cycle. Each must be a VALID signature certified by the county clerks.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim. FindLaw 20A-9-502(5)(a)(ii)(A) (current as of Jan 1, 2025) sets 'at least 1,000 registered voters residing within the state' for statewide offices; Ballotpedia independently confirms 1,000 for an independent presidential candidate. President is an office filled by Utah voters statewide. Note clerks count/certify only valid holographic signatures of registered voters (502(5)(b)-(c)), so collect a cushion above 1,000.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST READING: submit the 1,000 signatures to the county clerks AND file the certificate of nomination + $500 fee with the Lieutenant Governor no later than 5 p.m. on JUNE 15 of the general election year. The August 15 date in 20A-9-504(2) on its face governs only (a) selection of the unaffiliated running mate and (b) the VP candidate's compliance with 20A-9-202(7) — NOT the signature/petition submission. Operate to the earlier June 15 date to avoid any risk to ballot access; confirm with the Lt. Governor's office before relying on August 15 for signatures.","note":"DISAGREE with the draft's headline that Aug 15 is the presidential SIGNATURE/petition deadline. Primary text conflicts: 20A-9-502(5)(a) sets the signature-submission deadline at 'no later than 5 p.m. on June 15,' and 20A-9-503(1) ties certificate filing + fee to that same 502(5)(a) deadline (June 15). 20A-9-504(2)(a) only requires the presidential candidate to 'select a running mate' by Aug 15, and 504(2)(b) requires the VP to satisfy 20A-9-202(7) by Aug 15 — neither sets the signature deadline. Ballotpedia (secondary) says petition filed 'no later than August 15,' contradicting the plain June 15 statutory text. The draft itself flags the June 15 vs Aug 15 tension and that the Lt. Gov used discretion amid 2024 litigation. Correctness hinges on a legal interpretation retrieval cannot settle; strictest defensible posture is the earlier June 15 for signatures. Aug 15 grounds verbatim but the VALUE's interpretation (Aug 15 = signature deadline) is not supported by the statute it cites.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No geographic distribution requirement — a single flat statewide total of 1,000 valid registered-voter signatures, with no minimum per congressional district or county. Packets are submitted to the county clerk where the majority of that packet's signatures were collected, but that is an administrative routing rule, not a distribution quota; the 1,000 total is statewide.","note":"Quote grounds verbatim in current 20A-9-502(5)(a)(ii). The statute imposes only a single statewide 1,000 threshold for a statewide office; the per-political-division minimums in (5)(a)(ii)(B) apply only to sub-state offices, not President. The 'county clerk where the majority of signatures were collected' language is a submission-routing rule, correctly characterized as not a distribution requirement.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Circulator (the person who witnesses each signature and signs the verification) must be at least 18 years old; need NOT be a registered voter. Residency: the CURRENT statute (FindLaw, current to Jan 1, 2025) requires only age 18 in 20A-9-502(3)(a)(i) and contains no circulator residency requirement, so a non-resident may circulate. CAUTION: the draft's basis for non-residency is the superseded 2015 ut.elaws.us snapshot (which had a presidential-specific residency waiver against a now-removed general residency rule). Confirm current residency rules with the Lt. Governor before staffing non-resident circulators; using Utah-resident circulators is the zero-risk posture. Signers must be registered to vote in Utah (or intend to register before certification) and may sign for only one candidate for the office.","note":"Age-18 and not-required-to-be-a-registered-voter sub-claims ground in current 20A-9-502(3)(a) and are correct. The non-residency conclusion is also TRUE under current law, but the CITED basis is stale: the ut.elaws.us quote ('A person who is not a resident may sign the verification...for president') is from a January 2015 snapshot whose structure (general residency requirement under 20A-2-105 + presidential carve-out in 502(3)(b)) no longer matches the current statute, which dropped the residency clause entirely (now no residency requirement for any office). So the draft reaches a right answer via outdated authority and a presidential-specific rationale that no longer exists. Because the current contours rest on confirming that no residency requirement survives, treat as CONSERVATIVE-HOLD; strictest safe posture is to not depend on non-resident circulators without office confirmation.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Both required: (1) the candidate's certificate of nomination is a sworn statement that must be NOTARIZED ('Subscribed and sworn to before me... Notary Public (or other officer qualified to administer oaths)'); and (2) each signature packet must include a circulator VERIFICATION attesting that each signer signed in the circulator's presence — signed by the circulator (with residence address and date) but not separately notarized. False verification is a class A misdemeanor.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim in current 20A-9-502: 502(1)(a) ends with the notary jurat (notarized candidate certificate), and 502(1)(c) sets out the circulator 'Verification' signed by the circulator. 502(4) makes false signing/verification a class A misdemeanor. The notarized-affidavit-plus-non-notarized-circulator-verification structure is correctly stated for the current statute.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper / wet-ink. The statute mandates handwritten 'holographic' signatures on printed 8-1/2 x 11 signature sheets, each signed in the circulator's physical presence; the county clerk counts/certifies only persons who signed 'with a holographic signature' (20A-9-502(1)(b)(viii)(C), (5)(c)). Treat digital/online capture as NOT available for the unaffiliated presidential certificate-of-nomination petition.","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim in current 20A-9-502 (the 'Holographic Signature of Registered Voter' column heading and the clerk counting 'only those persons who signed with a holographic signature'). The holographic mandate makes wet-ink/paper the legally safe answer, and the draft's conclusion is already the strictest posture. Caveat retained: the draft could not confirm from a primary source that any Utah state-approved signature app covers this specific path, so reliance on digital capture is unverified and should be avoided — which the relied value reflects.","conf":0.88,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A $500 filing fee is required IN ADDITION TO the 1,000-signature petition — it is NOT an alternative that can substitute for collecting signatures. An individual filing a certificate of nomination for President pays the $500 fee at filing alongside the petition (20A-9-503(4)(a)); filing and fee are due with the certificate per 20A-9-503(1).","note":"Both quotes ground verbatim. 20A-9-503(4)(a) requires a $500 filing fee for a presidential certificate of nomination; nothing in 502/503 lets the fee substitute for the 1,000 signatures (503(1) requires the candidate to file the certificate, file the declaration, AND pay the fee, on top of the 502 signature requirement). The fee is additive, not a fee-in-lieu alternative — correctly stated. Ballotpedia independently confirms both the $500 fee and the 1,000 signatures.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Vermont","sigs":"VT: 1,000 valid signatures, flat statewide, no distribution — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"VT deadline CONFLICT: statute/SoS say Aug 1; NASS says June — HOLD to earlier June deadline for planning","risk":"Signature count and capture mode are firm; the only material ballot-access risk is the deadline (two authoritative sources conflict — plan to the earlier June date) and unverified-by-omission claims (circulator eligibility) that should be confirmed with the VT SoS before relying on them.","sos":["For an INDEPENDENT presidential/VP candidate filing under 17 V.S.A. 2402(d)(1)(A), is the 2028 filing deadline 5:00 p.m. on August 1 (per 2402 and your 2024 candidate form), and NOT the 'second Thursday after the first Monday in June' deadline that the NASS July-2024 summary lists for Vermont? Please confirm the controlling deadline and statute.","Does Vermont impose ANY eligibility requirement (age, in-state residency, voter registration) on the PERSON who circulates an independent presidential nomination petition, or may a non-resident / non-registered person circulate so long as every SIGNER is a registered Vermont voter? Is there any circulator affidavit, oath, or registration step?","Is there any approved electronic or remote method to collect or submit signatures for an independent presidential nomination petition, or must all signatures be wet-ink on paper, certified by each town clerk, and physically filed at the SoS office before the deadline?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"Vermont's candidate-petition statutes (17 V.S.A. §§ 2402, 2353, 2354) regulate only the signers (registered/qualified voters, town of residence) and impose NO requirements on petition circulators — there is no circulator-affirmation, no residency requirement, and crucially NO statute addressing whether circulators on an independent/presidential nominating petition may be compensated or paid per signature. Compensation of candidate-petition circulators is therefore unaddressed (not affirmatively permitted), so per-signature pay is NOT clearly authorized and falls under CONSERVATIVE-HOLD; this is distinct from any initiative/ballot-measure rule, which does not apply to candidate petitions.","sosInquiry":"For an independent candidate's presidential nominating petition (17 V.S.A. § 2402), does Vermont law permit a campaign to pay petition circulators on a per-signature basis, and are there any restrictions on paying circulators (hourly/salary) or any residency/registered-voter requirement for who may circulate the statement of nomination?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2402/","quote":"(b)(1) To constitute a valid nomination, a statement shall contain signatures of voters qualified to vote in an election for the office in question, equal in number to at least: (A) for presidential and vice presidential offices, 1,000... (c) A statement shall state that each signer is qualified to vote in an election for the office in question and that the voter's residence is as set forth next to the voter's name."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2354/","quote":"(a) Any number of voters may sign the same petition. (b)(1) A voter's signature shall not be valid unless at the time he or she signs, the voter is registered and qualified to vote for the candidate whose petition he or she signs. (2) Each voter shall indicate his or her town of residence next to his or her signature."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2353/","quote":"The name of any person shall be printed upon the primary ballot as a candidate for nomination by any major political party for the office indicated, if a petition containing the requisite number of signatures made by registered voters, in substantially the following form, is filed with the proper official... and I certify that I am at the present time a registered voter and am qualified to vote for a candidate for this office."},{"url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Vermont","quote":"The relevant statutes do not stipulate any particular requirements on petition circulators."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"voter file","url":"https://sos.vermont.gov/elections/voters/voter-faqs/voter-registration-faqs","official":true,"dom":"sos.vermont.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.eac.gov/sites/default/files/voters/Available_Voter_File_Information.pdf","official":true,"dom":"eac.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://outside.vermont.gov/dept/sos/Elections_Division/voters/faq/request_electronic_copy_vermont_statewide_checklist.pdf","official":true,"dom":"outside.vermont.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2402/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2354/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2353/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_requirements_for_political_candidates_in_Vermont","official":false,"dom":"ballotpedia.org"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/vt/title-17-elections/vt-st-tit-17-sect-2154/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 valid signatures (flat statewide number, not a percentage), per 17 V.S.A. 2402(b)(1)(A). Only signatures certified by a town clerk as belonging to registered voters count toward the 1,000.","note":"GROUNDED: 2402(b)(1)(A) '...for presidential and vice presidential offices, 1,000' verified verbatim on FindLaw; SoS 2024 form 'For President - 1,000' verified verbatim in extracted PDF text. Independently re-derived: flat statutory number, no percentage, does not recompute per cycle. Town-clerk-certification-only counting confirmed by 2402(a)(4)(B)(ii). Correct and current.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"PLAN to the EARLIER of the two conflicting authorities: file no later than the second Thursday after the first Monday in June of the election year (the NASS-stated date), even though the controlling presidential-specific statute 17 V.S.A. 2402(d)(1)(A) and the VT SoS form both state 5:00 p.m. on August 1. Filing window opens the fourth Monday in April. All signatures must be town-clerk-certified BEFORE filing, so begin certification weeks earlier. Treat August 1 as the statutory backstop but do not rely on it without SoS confirmation given the documented NASS conflict.","note":"GROUNDED: statute quote (2402(d)(1)(A) 'not earlier than the fourth Monday in April and not later than 5:00 p.m. on the August 1...') verified verbatim on FindLaw; SoS form 'between Monday, April 22 and 5:00 p.m. on Thursday, August 1, 2024' verified verbatim; NASS quote (June deadline) verified verbatim in NASS PDF. ADVERSARIAL: the draft correctly diagnoses that NASS conflated the independent-presidential path with the 2356/2381 minor-party/general-independent June path (NASS's own citation list is 2103,2319,2356,2381,2382,2385 — it does NOT cite 2402). Ballotpedia INDEPENDENTLY corroborates 'fourth Monday in April...no later than August 1.' So August 1 is almost certainly correct. BUT: a national SoS-association source conflicts on a deadline, no human counsel is available, and missing the true deadline forfeits ballot access while filing early costs nothing — strictest defensible posture is to plan to the earlier June date and confirm with the SoS. Note 2103(13): if the deadline falls on a weekend/holiday it extends to the next business day (Aug 1 2024 was a Thursday, so no shift that cycle); the deadline is date-defined, not a fixed weekday, so re-check the actual calendar date each cycle.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Vermont requires a flat statewide total of 1,000 signatures for President/VP with no geographic distribution requirement (no per-district or per-county minimums). Signatures may be collected anywhere in the state and need not all be on one paper (17 V.S.A. 2402(b)(2)); the only locality dimension is administrative town-clerk certification.","note":"GROUNDED: '(2) Signatures need not all be contained on one paper' and the flat 1,000 figure both verified verbatim on FindLaw. ADVERSARIAL: re-read all of 2402 — no subsection imposes any geographic/county/district distribution; the per-town element is purely the clerk-certification mechanism, not a distribution minimum. Correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Strictest posture: use only circulators who are themselves Vermont-resident REGISTERED VOTERS until the SoS confirms no circulator restriction. The grounded SIGNER rule is firm: each signer must, at the time of signing, be registered and qualified to vote for the candidate and must indicate their town of residence next to the signature (17 V.S.A. 2354(b)); any number of voters may sign and there is no limit on petitions a voter may sign (2354(a), SoS form). The draft's claim of 'no circulator-eligibility requirement' is an inference from statutory silence, not an affirmative grant, so do not rely on out-of-state or unregistered circulators without confirmation.","note":"GROUNDED: 2354(b)(1)-(2) signer/town-of-residence quote verified verbatim on FindLaw; SoS form 'no restrictions on the number of petitions a voter may sign. 17 V.S.A. 2354' verified verbatim. ADVERSARIAL: the SIGNER requirements are explicit and correct. The 'no circulator requirement' conclusion rests on ABSENCE of statutory text — retrieval cannot prove a negative, and a restriction could live elsewhere in Title 17 ch. 49 or in SoS administrative guidance. Because mis-assuming out-of-state circulators are permissible could taint signatures and risk ballot access, hold to the strict interpretation and confirm with SoS.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarized affidavit and no circulator oath. The operative requirement is TOWN-CLERK certification: before filing, the town clerk of each town where signers appear to be voters must certify on the statement of nomination that the named signers are registered voters in that town and the total number of valid signers; only so-certified signatures count (17 V.S.A. 2402(a)(4)(B)(i)-(ii)). The candidate's statement also attests each signer is qualified and the residence shown is correct (2402(c)). Comply by routing every petition page through the relevant town clerk for certification BEFORE filing.","note":"GROUNDED: 2402(a)(4)(B)(i)-(ii) town-clerk-certification quote verified verbatim on FindLaw; SoS form certification-before-filing language verified verbatim. ADVERSARIAL: the AFFIRMATIVE compliance mechanism (town-clerk pre-certification) is explicit and is itself the strict/verification-heavy posture, so the actionable requirement is firm. The 'no notary' element is an absence inference, but nothing in 2402, 2354, or the SoS form suggests an additional notary/oath; the compliance action (get town-clerk certification) is unchanged regardless. Treated as AUTO-LIVE on the affirmative requirement.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The statement of nomination is a paper form circulated for wet-ink signatures, taken to each town clerk for certification against the voter checklist, then physically filed with the Secretary of State in Montpelier ('filed' = 'deposited in the regularly maintained office of the official', 17 V.S.A. 2103(13); a document is not filed until received at the office). No remote/online digital signature-collection system exists for an independent presidential petition; forms are print-sign-file PDFs.","note":"GROUNDED: SoS form certify-before-file and 'deposited in the regularly maintained office...' (2103(13)) quotes verified verbatim; 2103(13) full text independently confirmed on FindLaw (also adds the not-filed-until-received and weekend-extension rules). ADVERSARIAL: the 'no online system' element is an absence inference, but the strict/safe posture is identical to the stated value (assume paper, wet-ink, physical filing). Aligned with strict interpretation; AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. No filing fee for an independent presidential candidate and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures option — the 1,000-signature petition (plus consent forms and three electors) is the sole ballot-access path. The $2,000 fee applies only to MAJOR-PARTY candidates seeking the presidential PRIMARY ballot, not to independent general-election candidates.","note":"GROUNDED: Ballotpedia quote ('...A primary candidate must also pay a $2,000 filing fee. An independent candidate...must file a petition containing the signatures of 1,000 registered voters.') verified verbatim; SoS form '1,000' requirement verified verbatim and contains no fee reference. ADVERSARIAL: 2402 imposes no fee on independents; the strict compliance action is to collect 1,000 certified signatures, which holds whether or not a fee theoretically existed, so no ballot-access risk arises from the 'no fee' conclusion. Correct; AUTO-LIVE.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Virginia","sigs":"VA: 5,000 sigs total, ≥200 per congressional district (11 districts) — AUTO-LIVE","deadline":"VA: noon of 74th day before election (2024 cycle = Aug 23, 2024) — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"7 of 9 fields AUTO-LIVE on grounded primary statute (Va. Code 24.2-543). Two HOLDs: captureMode (operative value \"paper\" confirmed, but draft's form ID ELECT-543(P) is WRONG — current 2024 indep/3rd-party petition is ELECT-242(P); HB89 source CAPTCHA-blocked) and feeAlternative (negative/absence claim not provable from a single quote). No field BLOCKED; all relied values are ballot-access-safe.","sos":["For an independent/third-party presidential elector petition under Va. Code 24.2-543, is there any filing fee or fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative to the 5,000-signature petition, or is petition the sole ballot-access path? (Confirming no fee provision exists anywhere in Title 24.2 for this petition.)","For the 2024+ cycle, what is the correct current Department of Elections form number for the independent/third-party Petition of Qualified Voters for Electors for President and Vice President — is it ELECT-242(P)? And is any online/electronic filing path available, or is original wet-signature paper still required?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; per-signature neither authorized nor prohibited","note":"Virginia's controlling statute for an independent/non-party presidential petition is Va. Code § 24.2-242 (enacted 2024 c. 801, which repealed the former § 24.2-543/§ 24.2-542); it, the general independent-candidate petition statute § 24.2-506, and the election-offenses chapter (§§ 24.2-1000 to 24.2-1019) are silent on circulator compensation — paying candidate-petition circulators (per signature or at all) is neither expressly authorized nor prohibited, so compensation is UNADDRESSED. Circulator residency is NOT required: both § 24.2-242 and § 24.2-506 expressly allow nonresident petition circulators (who must sign a consent-to-jurisdiction statement and remain subject to subpoena), and the witness need only be a non-minor and not a disqualified felon, so a national paid pool could legally circulate there.","sosInquiry":"For an independent (non-party) presidential candidate's petition under Va. Code § 24.2-242, may the campaign pay petition circulators per signature collected, and are there any restrictions on compensating circulators (e.g., per-signature bans, registration, or disclosure requirements)?","citations":[{"url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter2.1/section24.2-242/","quote":"The petition shall be signed by at least 5,000 qualified voters and include signatures of at least 200 qualified voters from each congressional district. The petition shall be signed by petitioners on and after January 1 of the year of the presidential election and contain the residence address of each petitioner. The signature of each petitioner shall be witnessed either by an individual who is a constitutionally qualified candidate for President, who may witness his own petition, or by an individual who is not a minor or a felon whose voting rights have not been restored and whose affidavit to that effect appears on each page of the petition. Each individual circulating a petition who is not a legal resident of the Commonwealth shall sign a statement on the affidavit that he consents to the jurisdiction of the courts of Virginia in resolving any disputes concerning the circulation of petitions, or signatures contained therein, by that individual."},{"url":"https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?241+ful+CHAP0801","quote":"That §§ 24.2-202 through 24.2-205 and Article 6 (§§ 24.2-542, 24.2-542.1, and 24.2-543) of Chapter 5 of Title 24.2 of the Code of Virginia are repealed."},{"url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter5/section24.2-506/","quote":"Each signature on the petition shall have been witnessed by a person who is not a minor or a felon whose voting rights have not been restored and whose affidavit to that effect appears on each page of the petition. Each such person circulating a petition who is not a legal resident of the Commonwealth shall sign a statement on the affidavit that he consents to the jurisdiction of the courts of Virginia in resolving any disputes concerning the circulation of petitions, or signatures contained therein, by that person."},{"url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter10/","quote":"§ 24.2-1007 Soliciting or accepting bribe to influence or procure vote"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter2.1/section24.2-242/","official":true,"dom":"law.lis.virginia.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?241+ful+CHAP0801","official":true,"dom":"lis.virginia.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter5/section24.2-506/","official":true,"dom":"law.lis.virginia.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter10/","official":true,"dom":"law.lis.virginia.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title24.2/chapter4/section24.2-405/","official":true,"dom":"law.lis.virginia.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.elections.virginia.gov/candidatepac-info/client-services/","official":true,"dom":"elections.virginia.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://virginiamercury.com/2025/06/24/virginia-slashes-voter-data-costs-ahead-of-2025-elections/","official":false,"dom":"virginiamercury.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"5,000 signatures of Virginia qualified voters total, with at least 200 from each of Virginia's 11 congressional districts. The 5,000 total is the binding figure (11 x 200 = 2,200 < 5,000). Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Statute quote verbatim at vacode.org/24.2-543.txt: 'signed by at least 5,000 qualified voters and include signatures of at least 200 qualified voters from each congressional district.' Ballotpedia quote verbatim. Independently confirmed VA has 11 congressional districts (in effect since 2022 elections; 118th/119th Congress). Binding-total reasoning correct.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Noon of the 74th day before the presidential election (statutory, recomputes each cycle). For the Nov 5, 2024 general election that date was August 23, 2024. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Statute quote verbatim: 'filed with the State Board by noon of the seventy-fourth day before the presidential election.' Independently computed: 74 days before 2024-11-05 = 2024-08-23 (Friday) — matches draft. Forward-looking operative rule is the 74th-day formula, not the fixed 2024 date.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Yes — distribution requirement: at least 200 qualified-voter signatures from each of Virginia's 11 congressional districts (within the 5,000 total). Elector slate must also include one elector residing in each congressional district plus two at-large. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Both quotes verbatim at vacode.org/24.2-543.txt ('include signatures of at least 200 qualified voters from each congressional district' and 'including one elector residing in each congressional district and two from the Commonwealth at large'). Correct.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Each signature must be witnessed by either (a) a constitutionally qualified candidate for President (who may witness his own petition), or (b) a Virginia resident who is not a minor and not a felon whose voting rights have not been restored. The witness need not be a registered voter. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Statute quote verbatim. The 'need not be a registered voter' gloss is well-supported by plain text (statute requires only residency + non-minor + non-disqualified-felon, not registration). Minor reading, but settled by the text itself.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Two layers: (1) per-page circulator/witness affidavit (VA residency, not a minor, not a disqualified felon) on EACH petition page; (2) a subscribed and notarized oath by each selected elector, filed with the petition. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Both quotes verbatim ('whose affidavit to that effect appears on each page of the petition' and 'a subscribed and notarized oath by each elector'). Corroborated by the official VA elector oath form ELECT-242(C) for independent/third-party electors.","conf":0.94,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"paper. The independent/third-party Petition of Qualified Voters for Electors for President and Vice President is collected on the Department of Elections' prescribed paper form with original wet signatures and per-page witness affidavits; no online/remote filing path was available for the 2024 cycle. NOTE: the operative form number is ELECT-242(P), NOT 'ELECT-543(P)' as the draft stated. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A) + VA Dept. of Elections candidate forms page.","note":"HOLD for a factual defect, not a legal interpretation. Core value 'paper' is independently grounded by the statute (wet signatures + per-page affidavits) AND the official VA forms page (which lists only paper letter/legal petition forms for the 2024 indep/3rd-party general path). BUT (1) the draft's form ID 'ELECT-543(P)' is WRONG — the current 2024 form is ELECT-242(P); ELECT-543(P) survives only in stale 2020 Korean-language filenames; (2) the HB89/TrackBill citation is CAPTCHA-blocked and could not be grounded, so the prospective-online-system claim is unverified. Relying on 'paper' is the strictest/safest posture for ballot access.","conf":0.8,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"None (treat as petition-only). Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543 contains no filing fee and no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative for the independent/non-party presidential elector petition; verify with the state before relying on any fee path. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"HOLD because this is a negative/absence claim. The grounded statute quote shows the petition path but does not affirmatively state 'no fee'; proving the absence of any fee-in-lieu alternative anywhere in Title 24.2 from a single quote is an inference retrieval did not fully settle. The value is very likely correct (VA presidential ballot access is petition-only), so the strictest defensible posture (assume no fee escape, plan for full petition) is also the safe one. SOS inquiry added.","conf":0.78,"interp":true},{"f":"minorPartyPathNote","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The new/minor-party (party-name) path uses the SAME statute (Sec. 24.2-543) and SAME numeric requirements (5,000 signatures, 200 per congressional district, noon of the 74th day, same witness/notary rules). The only material difference is the ballot LABEL: to appear under a chosen party name the group must additionally have had, for at least six months before filing, a state central committee of registered voters from each congressional district, a party plan and bylaws, and a designated chairman and secretary; otherwise the candidate and electors are designated 'Independent'. Basis: Va. Code Sec. 24.2-543(A).","note":"Both quotes verbatim at vacode.org/24.2-543.txt (six-month organizational requirement for party name; 'Independent' designation fallback). The same-statute/same-numeric-requirements claim is directly correct — there is no separate numeric scheme for the party-name path.","conf":0.93,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Washington","sigs":"1,000 registered WA voters (flat; conv. attendees)","deadline":"Cert+petition to SOS by 1st Fri of Aug (2028: Aug 4)","risk":"7 fields grounded; 6 AUTO-LIVE, 1 CONSERVATIVE-HOLD (circulator eligibility — absence-of-rule cannot be retrieval-confirmed). Watch SOS \"last Saturday in July\" vs statutory \"fourth Saturday\" convention-window discrepancy (differs in 2028: Jul 29 vs Jul 22).","sos":["Beyond requiring that each petition signer be a registered Washington voter who attends a qualifying state convention, does Washington impose any separate qualification (age, residency, voter-registration, or affidavit) on the person who circulates/collects an independent or minor-party presidential nominating petition?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found; WA per-signature ban is initiative/referendum-only","note":"Washington's candidate (minor party/independent presidential) nominating-petition statutes (RCW 29A.56.630 and 29A.56.640) and the candidate-petition crime statute (RCW 29A.84.311) are SILENT on circulator compensation — they regulate signers (must be registered WA voters), not circulators, and impose no circulator residency or pay rules. Washington's pay-per-signature ban (RCW 29A.84.250(2), with the 29A.84.280 finding) applies by its express terms ONLY to \"initiative or referendum petitions,\" so it does not automatically reach candidate petitions; candidate-petition compensation is therefore unaddressed rather than clearly permitted or prohibited.","sosInquiry":"For a minor-party/independent presidential candidate's nominating petitions under RCW 29A.56.630/.640, may the campaign compensate signature gatherers on a per-signature basis, and is there any circulator residency or registered-voter requirement — given that RCW 29A.84.250(2)'s per-signature ban is written only for initiative/referendum petitions?","citations":[{"url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.250","quote":"(2) Provides or receives consideration for soliciting or procuring signatures on an initiative or referendum petition if any part of the consideration is based upon the number of signatures solicited or procured, or offers to provide or agrees to receive such consideration any of which is based on the number of signatures solicited or procured"},{"url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.280","quote":"The legislature finds that paying a worker, whose task it is to secure the signatures of voters on initiative or referendum petitions, on the basis of the number of signatures the worker secures on the petitions encourages the introduction of fraud in the signature gathering process."},{"url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.311","quote":"Every person who: (1) Knowingly provides false information on his or her declaration of candidacy or petition of nomination; or (2) Conceals or fraudulently defaces or destroys a certificate that has been filed with an elections officer under chapter 29A.20 RCW or a declaration of candidacy or petition of nomination that has been filed with an elections officer ... is guilty of a class C felony"},{"url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.56.630","quote":"The petition shall also contain a statement that the person signing the petition is a registered voter of the state of Washington and shall have a space for the voter to sign his or her name and to print his or her name and address. No person may sign more than one nominating petition under this chapter for an office for an election."},{"url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.56.640","quote":"(5) Be accompanied by a nominating petition or petitions bearing the signatures and addresses of at least one thousand registered voters of the state of Washington"}],"initiativePrior":"permitted"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.250","official":true,"dom":"app.leg.wa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.280","official":true,"dom":"app.leg.wa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.84.311","official":true,"dom":"app.leg.wa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.56.630","official":true,"dom":"app.leg.wa.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=29A.56.640","official":true,"dom":"app.leg.wa.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://www.sos.wa.gov/elections/data-research/reports-data-and-statistics/washington-state-voter-registration-database-vrdb","official":true,"dom":"sos.wa.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://www.sos.wa.gov/washington-voter-registration-database-extract","official":true,"dom":"sos.wa.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"1,000 signatures of registered Washington voters (flat statewide number; not a percentage). An independent (or minor-party) presidential candidate is nominated by convention, and the certificate of nomination must be accompanied by nominating petition(s) bearing the signatures of at least 1,000 registered Washington voters. These voters must attend a state convention held in support of the candidate; a candidate holding multiple conventions may aggregate signatures across conventions to reach 1,000.","note":"All 3 citations grounded verbatim. RCW 29A.56.640(5): 'at least one thousand registered voters of the state of Washington'; RCW 29A.56.610 confirms multi-convention aggregation and 100-attendee minimum; SOS page confirms 1,000 signatures. Statute last amended 2013, no newer amendment found; SOS 2028 page still describes same process. Flat number, no interpretation needed.","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"First Friday of August of the presidential election year (for 2028 = August 4, 2028). The certificate of nomination (with the petition(s)) must be submitted to the Secretary of State not later than the first Friday of August. Conventions must be held no earlier than the first Saturday in May and no later than the fourth Saturday in July per RCW 29A.56.610 (for 2028: May 6 to July 22). Date recomputes each cycle.","note":"RCW 29A.56.640(7) 'not later than the first Friday of August' and RCW 29A.56.610 convention-window quote grounded verbatim; SOS quote grounded. Submission deadline value is correct and verified. NOTE discrepancy: SOS website says conventions run to the 'last Saturday in July' while the controlling statute (RCW 29A.56.610) says 'fourth Saturday in July' — these differ in years with five July Saturdays (2028: 4th=Jul 22 vs last=Jul 29). The draft value correctly uses the stricter statutory 'fourth Saturday'. Updated illustrative date from 2024 (Aug 2) to 2028 cycle (Aug 4).","conf":null,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Washington requires a flat statewide total of 1,000 registered-voter signatures with no geographic distribution requirement across congressional districts or counties.","note":"RCW 29A.56.640(5) grounded verbatim; statute requires only a statewide total of 1,000 'registered voters of the state of Washington' with no district/county distribution language anywhere in RCW 29A.56.610-.640. Correct.","conf":null,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"Each person who signs the nominating petition must be a registered Washington voter and must attend a qualifying state convention (the convention must be attended by at least 100 registered voters), and no person may sign more than one nominating petition for an office for an election. Treat any circulator as needing to be a registered Washington voter unless the SOS confirms otherwise. UNKNOWN whether a distinct circulator-qualification rule (age/residency/voter-status of the petition collector, as opposed to the signer) exists beyond these signer/attendee requirements.","note":"RCW 29A.56.630 and 29A.56.610 grounded verbatim (signer must be registered WA voter; no person signs more than one petition; convention needs 100 registered voters). However the field's core claim is an absence-of-law assertion ('no separate statutory circulator qualification') which retrieval cannot affirmatively confirm; the draft itself marks this UNKNOWN. Per strict-interpretation rule, hold and adopt the strictest defensible reading (circulator treated as needing registered-WA-voter status) pending SOS confirmation.","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarized circulator affidavit is required on the petition itself. Verification attaches to the certificate of nomination: it must be verified by the oath of the convention's presiding officer and secretary, and must contain a sworn statement from both nominees consenting to the nomination. The certificate must also contain proof of publication of the convention notice (published in a newspaper of general circulation at least ten days before the convention).","note":"RCW 29A.56.640(2) (sworn consent of nominees) and (4) (verified by oath of presiding officer and secretary) grounded verbatim; RCW 29A.56.620 (newspaper notice at least ten days before convention) grounded verbatim. No petition-level notarized circulator affidavit appears in statute. Correct.","conf":null,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. The petition is gathered on paper from registered voters who physically attend the state convention, and the certificate of nomination plus petitions are submitted to the Secretary of State by mail or by in-person appointment. There is no remote-online or digitized signature system covering an independent presidential nominating petition in Washington (Washington is not among the jurisdictions that allow electronic signing of candidate nominating petitions).","note":"SOS quote (voters must attend a state convention) grounded verbatim; 2024 candidate guide PDF grounded verbatim ('Call (360) 902-4180 to schedule an in-person appointment, or submit by mail to:' — split across PDF lines 102-103 but exact). Ballotpedia electronic-signing list grounded (Arizona/New Mexico online, Denver/DC eSign) and does NOT include Washington, confirming no e-signature path. Guide's 'online' references are voters' pamphlet only, not petition signing. Correct.","conf":null,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. There is no filing fee for a presidential candidate in Washington, and there is no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative; the signature/convention requirement is the sole path.","note":"SOS quote 'There is no filing fee' grounded verbatim; 2024 guide independently confirms 'Washington state does not collect filing fees for the offices of President and Vice President.' No fee-in-lieu provision exists in RCW 29A.56.610-.640. Correct.","conf":null,"interp":false}]},{"state":"West Virginia","sigs":"7,947 sigs (1% of 2020 WV presidential vote; min 25) — recomputes each cycle","deadline":"Aug 1 — nomination certificate + $2,500 fee to Secretary of State","risk":"7 of 8 fields AUTO-LIVE on strong primary+consensus grounding; only circulatorEligibility is CONSERVATIVE-HOLD (statute is silent on whether a non-resident/non-registered person may circulate beyond the county-clerk credential requirement — an interpretation gap). No field is BLOCKED. Note the credentials doc is officially \"Form P-1,\" not \"P-3\" as the captureMode/witness fields imply for the credential.","sos":["West Virginia SOS Elections Division: Beyond obtaining county-clerk credentials under W. Va. Code §3-5-23(b), is a petition circulator for an independent presidential nomination certificate required to be (a) a West Virginia resident, (b) a registered voter, and/or (c) at least 18 years old, or may an out-of-state/non-registered person circulate so long as they hold valid county credentials?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"unknown","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute found","note":"West Virginia's candidate-petition statute for independent/group (\"certificate\") nominations, including president (W.Va. Code §3-5-23, with §3-5-24 on filing), is SILENT on compensating circulators: it does not permit, prohibit, or otherwise address per-signature pay or paid circulation at all. Circulator compensation for candidate petitions is therefore unaddressed by any primary source (and WV has no statewide initiative process to even arguably borrow a pay-per-signature rule from); §3-5-23(b) does require circulators to obtain credentials from the county commission clerk but does not expressly impose a circulator residency/registration requirement.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nomination certificate under W.Va. Code §3-5-23, may the campaign compensate signature gatherers (a) per valid signature and (b) by hourly wage or salary, and must a credentialed circulator be a West Virginia resident or registered voter?","citations":[{"url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-23/","quote":"(b) The person or persons soliciting or canvassing signatures of duly qualified voters on the certificate or certificates, may solicit or canvass duly registered voters residing within the county, district, or other political division represented by the office sought, but must first obtain from the clerk of the county commission credentials which must be exhibited to each voter canvassed or solicited"},{"url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-23/","quote":"(c) The certificate shall be personally signed by duly registered voters, in their own proper handwriting or by their marks duly witnessed, who must be residents within the county, district, or other political division represented by the office sought wherein the canvass or solicitation is made by the person or persons duly authorized."},{"url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-23/","quote":"(h) In addition to penalties prescribed elsewhere for violation of this chapter, any person violating the provisions of this section is guilty of a misdemeanor and, upon conviction, shall be fined not more than $1,000, or confined in jail not more than one year, or both fined and confined: Provided, That a criminal penalty may not be imposed upon anyone who signs a nomination certificate and votes in the primary election held after the date the certificate was signed."},{"url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-24/","quote":"(a) All certificates nominating candidates for office under section twenty-three of this article shall be filed not later than August 1 preceding the November general election"}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-23/","official":true,"dom":"code.wvlegislature.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-5-24/","official":true,"dom":"code.wvlegislature.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/59-1-2B/","official":true,"dom":"code.wvlegislature.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://code.wvlegislature.gov/3-2-30/","official":true,"dom":"code.wvlegislature.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.wv.gov/media/656/download?inline=","official":true,"dom":"sos.wv.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Signatures equal to at least 1% of the entire vote cast for president in the last preceding presidential election (statewide), but in no event fewer than 25. For the 2024 cycle the threshold was 7,947 (1% of West Virginia's 2020 presidential vote of 794,731). Recomputes each presidential cycle.","note":"All three citations verified verbatim: §3-5-23 ('not less than one percent... but in no event... less than 25'; also a second sentence keyed to 'any statewide, congressional, or presidential candidate'), NASS report ('equal to at least 1% of the entire vote cast for president in the last preceding presidential election'), and WV Watch ('Kennedy... needed 7,947 signatures'). Independently re-derived: 1% of WV 2020 presidential total (794,731) = 7,947 exactly. Cross-confirmed by Ballotpedia ('1 percent of the total votes cast in the state for president in the most recent election'). The 25 floor is statutory.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"August 1 preceding the November general election. The nomination certificate (petition) and filing fee must be filed with the Secretary of State no later than August 1 (e.g., August 1, 2024 for the 2024 cycle).","note":"§3-5-24(a) verbatim: 'All certificates nominating candidates for office under section twenty-three... shall be filed not later than August 1 preceding the November general election.' NASS report verbatim ('no later than August 1st preceding the general election'). Cross-confirmed by Ballotpedia ('by August 1 in the year of the election').","conf":0.97,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for a presidential (statewide) candidate. The 1% threshold is a single statewide total against the entire presidential vote; there is no per-congressional-district or per-county minimum. Separate petition forms per county exist solely for county-clerk verification, with no minimum-per-county quota.","note":"§3-5-23 quote verified verbatim. Statute measures 1% against the statewide vote with no geographic-distribution language; 'Offices to be filled by the voters of more than one county shall use separate petition forms... for each county' is administrative (verification), not a quota. Ballotpedia describes only a flat statewide 1% with no district distribution (the only 'distribution' reference is to Electoral College apportionment). No source found imposing a per-county/per-district signature minimum.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICT: The circulator must obtain Official Credentials (Form P-1) from the clerk of the county commission for EACH county in which they canvass and must exhibit those credentials to every voter solicited. Until the SOS confirms otherwise, assume the strictest reading — that a circulator should be a West Virginia resident and a registered voter (matching the residency framing of the credential and the signer requirements) — rather than relying on the absence of an explicit circulator age/residency rule.","note":"Credentialing requirement verified verbatim in §3-5-23(b) and on the credentials form (extracted from media/413). The statute imposes residency/registration on SIGNERS, not expressly on circulators, and the draft honestly flags this as UNKNOWN. But the credential authorizes soliciting 'voters residing in [county],' leaving genuinely unsettled whether a non-resident/non-registered person may circulate — an interpretation retrieval cannot resolve. Per over-comply mandate, HOLD and query the SOS. (Also: the credentials doc is officially 'Official Form P-1,' which the draft's P-3-centric framing conflates.)","conf":0.6,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarized circulator affidavit is required. Each signer personally signs in their own handwriting (or by a duly witnessed mark). The official paper petition (Form P-3) contains only signer rows plus a 'County Use' VLD/INV validity column; county-commission clerks verify signatures against county voter-registration records. There is no sworn circulator certification.","note":"Both §3-5-23 quotes verified verbatim ('personally signed by duly registered voters, in their own proper handwriting or by their marks duly witnessed' and the clerk-comparison-to-registration-records provision in subsection (e)). P-3 form text extracted directly confirms only signer fields plus a 'County Use / VLD INV' column and no notary/circulator-oath block. Statute imposes no circulator oath or notarization.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures are collected on the Secretary of State's paper 'Minor Party or Independent Candidate Nomination Petition' (Official Form P-3), with separate forms per county, and verified by county clerks. There is NO digital/remote-online or in-person-digitized petition system for an independent presidential candidate in West Virginia.","note":"Form P-3 PDF (media/414) text extracted and matches the quote verbatim: 'MINOR PARTY OR INDEPENDENT CANDIDATE NOMINATION PETITION... we, the undersigned, are registered voters of ____ County... Official form P-3/Issued by the Office of the Secretary of State (WV Code §3-5-23).' §3-5-23 verbatim: 'Offices to be filled by the voters of more than one county shall use separate petition forms... for each county.' No statute, form, or SOS source indicates any electronic/online signature option; paper is the only mode.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"A filing fee is required IN ADDITION to (not in lieu of) the signature petition. The fee equals 1% of the annual salary of the office, capped at $2,500; for president/vice president the fee is $2,500, paid when the nomination certificate is filed. A separate impecuniosity path (§3-5-8a) lets a candidate unable to pay petition in lieu of the fee (four signatures per dollar of fee), but the standard independent-presidential path is petition PLUS the $2,500 fee.","note":"NASS quote verbatim ('must also pay a fee equivalent to 1% of the annual salary... must not exceed $2500'). §3-5-24(c) verbatim ('Each candidate shall pay the filing fee required by section eight... at the time of the filing of the nomination certificate'). §3-5-8(a)(1) independently confirms the $2,500 cap for president/VP. Ballotpedia confirms the fee is additive ('In addition, the candidate must pay a $2,500 filing fee') and the §3-5-8a waiver ('four signatures for each dollar of the filing fee'). The draft's framing of the waiver as 'additional signatures' is slightly loose (it substitutes for the FEE, not the nomination petition) but does not affect the relied value for the standard path.","conf":0.9,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Wisconsin","sigs":"2,000–4,000 valid elector signatures (flat statutory band; AUTO-LIVE)","deadline":"5 p.m. first Tuesday in August of the presidential year (Aug 6 in 2024); circulate from July 1; file with WEC — AUTO-LIVE","risk":"All fields grounded; one HOLD — 2025 Act 126 (eff. 2026-03-30) made circulators be qualified WI-resident electors, with a presidential-papers carve-out the stale eLaws citation does not surface, so circulatorEligibility is held to the strictest (WI-resident) reading pending WEC confirmation.","sos":["Confirm in writing: for INDEPENDENT PRESIDENTIAL nomination papers (EL-167) filed for the 2028 general election, does the 2025 Act 126 presidential carve-out still allow a circulator who is an adult U.S. citizen, 18+, not a Wisconsin resident, but who would be qualified to vote under Wis. law — or must all circulators now be qualified Wisconsin-resident electors?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"yes","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute; per-unit pay banned only for voter-registration forms (s. 12.13(3)(ze)), not nomination papers","note":"Wisconsin's candidate/independent-presidential petition statutes (Wis. Stat. ss. 8.20 and 8.15) are SILENT on circulator compensation — they neither authorize nor prohibit paying circulators, per signature or otherwise. Notably, Wisconsin's election-fraud statute s. 12.13(3)(ze) DOES ban variable/per-unit compensation, but ONLY for collectors of VOTER REGISTRATION forms, not for nomination-paper signatures; the legislature did not extend that ban to candidate petitions, so per-signature candidate-petition pay is unaddressed (not clearly prohibited, but not affirmatively permitted by any primary source). For PRESIDENT specifically, circulator residency is NOT required: s. 8.15(4)(a) lets the circulator be \"a qualified elector of this state, or if not a qualified elector of this state, ... a U.S. citizen age 18 or older who, if he or she were a resident of this state, would not be disqualified from voting,\" and 2025 Wisconsin Act 126 (signed March 30, 2026) — which newly requires circulators to be Wisconsin qualified electors — expressly EXEMPTS U.S. president, so a national/out-of-state paid circulator pool remains legal for the presidential petition. Caveat: the circulator certification still requires the circulator to attest \"that he or she intends to support the candidate,\" which is an operational constraint on any paid pool.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nomination papers (Wis. Stat. ss. 8.20/8.15), may a campaign compensate circulators on a per-signature basis, given that the variable-rate compensation ban in s. 12.13(3)(ze) by its terms applies only to voter-registration forms and not to nomination papers?","citations":[{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-12-13/","quote":"(ze) Compensate a person who obtains voter registration forms from other persons at a rate that varies in relation to the number of voter registrations obtained by the person."},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-8-15/","quote":"that he or she, the circulator, is a qualified elector of this state, or if not a qualified elector of this state, is a U.S. citizen age 18 or older who, if he or she were a resident of this state, would not be disqualified from voting under s. 6.03; that he or she intends to support the candidate"},{"url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-8-20/","quote":"The certification of a qualified circulator under s. 8.15(4)(a) shall be appended to each nomination paper."},{"url":"https://www.kenoshacountywi.gov/m/newsflash/Home/Detail/3525","quote":"Act 126, which was signed into law last month, amends statutes to require a circulator of nomination papers for all offices other than U.S. president to be a “qualified elector of the state.” Previously, circulators could be residents of other states who would have otherwise been eligible to vote in Wisconsin if they lived in the state."}],"initiativePrior":"n/a — no statewide initiative process"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://www.kenoshacountywi.gov/m/newsflash/Home/Detail/3525","official":true,"dom":"kenoshacountywi.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://badgervoters.wi.gov/faq","official":true,"dom":"badgervoters.wi.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/code/admin_code/el/3/50","official":true,"dom":"docs.legis.wisconsin.gov"},{"label":"voter file","url":"https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/statutes/statutes/6/ii/36","official":true,"dom":"docs.legis.wisconsin.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://badgervoters.wi.gov/","official":true,"dom":"badgervoters.wi.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-12-13/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-8-15/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://codes.findlaw.com/wi/elections-ch-5-to-12/wi-st-8-20/","official":false,"dom":"codes.findlaw.com"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Not less than 2,000 nor more than 4,000 valid signatures of electors — a flat statutory band specific to independent presidential electors voting for the same president/VP candidates (Wis. Stat. 8.20(4)). It is NOT a percentage of votes cast and does not recompute by cycle. Collect a cushion above 2,000 to survive challenges, but do not file more than 4,000.","note":"Both citations verified VERBATIM. eLaws 8.20(4): 'For independent presidential electors intending to vote for the same candidates for president and vice president, the number of required signatures shall be not less than 2,000 nor more than 4,000 electors.' NASS July-2024 report (downloaded, pdftotext): 'nomination papers containing between 2,000 and 4,000 signatures.' Adversarial check: 2025 Act 126 amended 8.20 but only as to circulator qualifications, not signature counts; no later act changes the band. Value current and correct.","conf":0.96,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Nomination papers may be circulated no sooner than July 1 and must be filed no later than 5:00 p.m. on the first Tuesday in August preceding the presidential election (Wis. Stat. 8.20(8)(am)), filed with the Wisconsin Elections Commission. For 2024 this was 5:00 p.m. on August 6, 2024. The date recomputes each presidential cycle.","note":"Both citations verified VERBATIM. eLaws 8.20(8)(am): 'may be circulated no sooner than July 1 and may be filed not later than 5 p.m. on the first Tuesday in August preceding a presidential election.' Lisbon WI Type-A notice (downloaded, pdftotext, line 12-14): 'Independent candidates for President or Vice President may circulate nomination papers beginning July 1, 2024, and must file nomination papers with the Wisconsin Elections Commission no later than 5:00 p.m. on August 6, 2024.' NASS corroborates filing 'no later than the first Tuesday in August.' Current and correct.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None for the independent presidential petition. The 2,000–4,000 signatures may be gathered anywhere in Wisconsin (signers must be electors eligible to vote in the state) with no per-congressional-district or per-county minimum. (Separate, materially different path: forming a recognized political party requires 10,000 electors including at least 1,000 in each of at least 3 congressional districts — this is NOT the independent path.)","note":"Both citations verified VERBATIM. eLaws 8.20(5): 'Signers of each nomination paper shall reside in the same jurisdiction or district which the candidate named therein will represent, if elected.' NASS report: 'A political organization may also become a recognized political party by filing... a petition containing the signatures of at least 10,000 electors, including at least 1,000 electors residing in each of at least 3 separate congressional districts.' Adversarial check: statute imposes only a same-jurisdiction (statewide, for president) residency requirement and no district/county allocation for the independent petition; the distribution rule applies only to the distinct party-formation path. Correct; the contrast is properly flagged.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"STRICTEST: treat every circulator as required to be a QUALIFIED ELECTOR OF WISCONSIN — i.e., a U.S. citizen, age 18+, a Wisconsin resident at their residence for 28+ days, not serving a felony sentence, not adjudicated incompetent to vote, who intends to support the candidate and signs the s.8.15(4)(a) circulator certification (no notarization). A non-resident-circulator allowance MAY exist for presidential papers, but do not rely on it without written WEC confirmation. If a circulator lists an out-of-state address, WEC strikes the entire page.","note":"The eLaws quotes (8.15(4)(a) non-resident allowance; 8.20(3) certification-appended) match VERBATIM — but eLaws is a JAN-2017 snapshot and is STALE. 2025 Wisconsin Act 126 (signed/effective 2026-03-30) AMENDED 8.10, 8.15, 8.20, 8.40, 9.10 to require circulators be a 'qualified elector of this state,' removing the old non-resident allowance. WEC's official 2026-04-08 Act 126 memo (fetched) says the change applies 'except Presidential nomination papers,' and notes presidential circulators 'may still be adult U.S. citizens who are not Wisconsin residents but who would be qualified to vote under Wisconsin law.' So the draft's bottom-line outcome is likely correct FOR THE PRESIDENTIAL PATH — but it now hinges entirely on a non-obvious statutory carve-out the stale citation never surfaces, and the general headline is now 'must reside in Wisconsin.' Per over-comply mandate (never risk ballot access), HOLD to the strict WI-resident reading and confirm the carve-out with WEC in writing.","conf":0.8,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"No notarization required. Each nomination paper requires a circulator certification (signed and dated by the circulator at the bottom of the sheet under s.8.15(4)(a)) attesting that the circulator personally circulated the paper and personally obtained each signature, knows the signers are electors of the required jurisdiction, knows they signed knowingly on the stated dates, and that falsifying the certification is punishable under Wis. Stat. 12.13(3)(a). The certification may be made by the candidate or any qualified circulator.","note":"eLaws 8.15(4)(a) quote verified VERBATIM, incl. 'personally circulated the nomination paper and personally obtained each of the signatures... aware that falsifying the certification is punishable under s. 12.13 (3) (a)... may be made by the candidate or any qualified circulator.' Adversarial check: Wisconsin uses circulator certification, not a notary/witness; Act 126 changes WHO may certify (qualifications) but does not add a notarization requirement. The no-notary conclusion is unaffected and correct. (Note the linked qualified-circulator definition is the field handled under circulatorEligibility.)","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Wisconsin requires physical paper nomination papers (EL-167 for independent president/VP) with wet-ink signatures: each signer must legibly print name, list municipality of residence, street and number, and date of signing next to their signature, and a circulator must physically circulate each sheet and sign the certification. There is NO official online/remote-electronic petition for an independent presidential petition; the official filing is paper, delivered to the Wisconsin Elections Commission.","note":"Both citations verified VERBATIM. eLaws 8.20(5): 'each signer shall legibly print his or her name in a space provided next to his or her signature and shall list his or her municipality of residence for voting purposes, the street and number, if any, on which the signer resides, and the date of signing.' eLaws 8.15(4)(a): 'personally circulated the nomination paper and personally obtained each of the signatures.' WEC pages confirm paper EL-167 forms and in-person filing. No e-signature path exists. Correct.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. Wisconsin imposes no filing fee for ballot access and provides no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures alternative for independent presidential candidates — qualification is by nomination-paper signatures only (2,000–4,000) plus a declaration of candidacy under s.8.21. (Separately, 2025 Act 43 imposes a fee only to WITHDRAW a name from the ballot — that is not a ballot-access fee and does not create a fee path.)","note":"Both citations verified VERBATIM. eLaws 8.20(6): 'Nomination papers shall be accompanied by a declaration of candidacy under s. 8.21.' NASS report lists qualification by signatures only with no fee. Adversarial check: I checked for any fee path. The only fee found (WEC FAQ, 2025 Act 43) is for REMOVING a name from the ballot via sworn statement — a withdrawal fee, not an access fee or fee-in-lieu of signatures. No fee-in-lieu exists. Correct.","conf":0.88,"interp":false}]},{"state":"Wyoming","sigs":"3,891 valid sigs (2% of 2022 U.S. House vote); recomputed each cycle","deadline":"File with SOS no later than 70 days before general (2024: Aug 26, 2024)","risk":"All 8 fields grounded; statute and SOS form agree. Only open item: circulator qualifications are unstated in primary sources (held conservative). Fee conflict ($200 NASS vs $750) resolved to $750 by W.S. 22-5-208(a)(iii)+22-5-306(b).","sos":["Wyoming independent presidential nominating petition: are there any qualifications for a petition CIRCULATOR (minimum age, Wyoming residency, or voter registration), or may any person circulate, given the form only requires the circulator to certify personal circulation and give a residence address?"],"comp":{"verified":true,"verifiedBy":"machine (single-pass, candidate-petition); confirm with SoS / counsel before paying real money","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","perSignatureAllowed":"unaddressed","paidCirculatorsAllowed":"unknown","circulatorResidency":"not_required","payMethod":"per-signature","operatingStance":"PAY PER SIGNATURE — not prohibited; verification is the safeguard; confirm w/ SoS before a large spend","model":"unaddressed — no candidate-petition compensation statute; only initiative/referendum payment bans exist, plus a general bribery ban on paying a person \"to sign a petition\"","note":"Wyoming's candidate/independent-presidential petition statutes (W.S. 22-5-301 through 22-5-308) are silent on circulator compensation — they neither permit nor prohibit paying circulators (per signature or otherwise), so candidate-petition comp is UNADDRESSED. The only \"payment for signatures\" bans in the Election Code (W.S. 22-24-323 initiative; 22-24-420 referendum) are by their own text confined to initiative/referendum petitions and prohibit paying the SIGNER, not paying circulators; they do not reach candidate petitions. However, the general election-bribery felony, W.S. 22-26-109(a)(i), broadly prohibits paying \"any money or other valuable thing to a person ... to ... sign or not sign a petition,\" which covers candidate petitions and makes per-signature pay legally risky. No Wyoming residency or voter-registration requirement is imposed on candidate-petition circulators (only the signers must be Wyoming registered electors); the analogous initiative-circulator rule, W.S. 22-24-306(a), requires only U.S. citizenship and age 18.","sosInquiry":"For an independent presidential candidate's nominating petition under W.S. 22-5-301 to 22-5-308, may the campaign pay circulators on a per-signature basis, and does Wyoming impose any residency or voter-registration requirement on those circulators?","citations":[{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"22-5-304. Qualifications and number of signers required. (a) For a statewide partisan office, a petition shall be signed by registered electors, resident in the state and eligible to vote for the petitioner, numbering not less than two percent (2%) of the total number of votes cast for representative in congress in the last general election for the entire state."},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"22-5-305. When petitions may be circulated; use of copies; requirements. (a) A petition shall be circulated for signatures only during the calendar year in which the election for the office sought is to be held. (b) Copies of the petition may be circulated for signatures, but each separate page shall contain the information required to be contained in the original petition for nomination."},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"VERIFICATION BY CIRCULATORS  I, ...., do hereby certify that I am a circulator of this petition, and I solely and personally circulated this petition, that all the signatures appearing herein were made in my presence ... and to the best of my knowledge and belief such signatures are those of the persons whose names they purport to be."},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"22-24-323. Petitions; payment for signatures; misrepresentation of petition; prohibition; penalty. (a) A circulator of an initiative petition or a person who causes the circulation of an initiative petition may not pay or offer to pay any compensation to another person for that person's signature on the initiative petition."},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"22-26-109. Offering bribe. (a) Offering bribe consists of willfully advancing, paying, offering to pay or causing to be paid, or promising, directly or indirectly, any money or other valuable thing to a person, for any of the following purposes: (i) To induce a person to vote or refrain from voting for or against a candidate or ballot proposition or to sign or not sign a petition;"},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","quote":"22-24-306. Sponsors and circulators. (a) ... An individual shall not be qualified to act as a circulator unless he is a citizen of the United States and is at least eighteen (18) years of age."},{"url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Elections/Apps/Independent_Presidential_petition_WY.pdf","quote":"Wyoming Statutes 22-5-301 through 22-5-308 are controlling legislation. The petition shall be approved by the appropriate filing office prior to circulation. ... A petition for a statewide office shall be signed by registered electors, resident in the jurisdiction and eligible to vote for the petitioner, numbering not less than two percent (2%) of the total number of votes cast in the state for U.S. Representative in the last general election."}],"initiativePrior":"banned"},"sources":[{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Publications/ElectionCode.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.wyo.gov"},{"label":"circulator pay rules","url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Elections/Apps/Independent_Presidential_petition_WY.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.wyo.gov"},{"label":"voter file — download / request","url":"https://sos.wyo.gov/Forms/Elections/General/VoterProductOrderForm.pdf","official":true,"dom":"sos.wyo.gov"}],"fields":[{"f":"signaturesRequired","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"2% of the total number of votes cast in Wyoming for U.S. Representative in the last general election. For the 2024 cycle this equaled 3,891 valid signatures. (Statewide flat figure; recomputed each cycle from the most recent U.S. House vote total.) Statutory basis: W.S. 22-5-304(a).","note":"Quotes verified verbatim: SOS form (downloaded+text-extracted, lines 12-16: 'numbering not less than two percent (2%)... 3,891 for the upcoming 2024 General Election (W.S. 22-5-304(a))') and FindLaw W.S. 22-5-304(a). Independently re-derived: 2022 WY U.S. House total = 193,902 votes; 2% = ~3,878, within source-variance of the official 3,891 (corroborates, does not refute). Caveat: statute text reads 'statewide PARTISAN office', but the SOS office-issued independent-presidential form authoritatively applies the same 2% figure and cites 304(a), so this is office-settled, not an open interpretation.","conf":0.93,"interp":false},{"f":"deadline","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"The petition must be filed with the Secretary of State not less than 70 days before the general election. For the 2024 cycle the filing deadline was August 26, 2024. A petition may be circulated for signatures only during the election year (W.S. 22-5-305(a)). Recomputes each cycle (70 days before the November general election date).","note":"Verified verbatim: SOS form line 22-24 ('Filing Deadline: August 26, 2024. You must file not less than seventy (70) days prior...') and Ballotpedia ('no later than 70 days prior to the general election'). W.S. 22-5-305(a) circulation-window quote verified verbatim on FindLaw. Date is cycle-specific; the 70-day formula is the durable rule, correctly stated.","conf":0.95,"interp":false},{"f":"distributionRule","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"None. For president (a statewide office) the requirement is a single statewide total of 2% of the last U.S. House vote; signatures are not allocated per congressional district or county. (W.S. 22-5-304(a) governs statewide office; the per-county/per-district formulas in 22-5-304(b)-(c) apply only to countywide and district offices.)","note":"Verified verbatim: W.S. 22-5-304(a) on FindLaw and SOS form lines 37-38. Confirmed adversarially that 304(b) is countywide and 304(c) is district — neither applies to a statewide/presidential petition. No geographic distribution requirement exists. WY has a single at-large U.S. House district, so no district split is even possible.","conf":0.92,"interp":false},{"f":"circulatorEligibility","gate":"CONSERVATIVE-HOLD","val":"UNRESOLVED / verify with SOS. Wyoming's petition statutes (W.S. 22-5-304/305/306) and the SOS petition form impose eligibility only on SIGNERS (registered elector, resident in the jurisdiction, eligible to vote for the petitioner). No age, residency, or registration qualification for the CIRCULATOR is stated in any primary source; the form requires only that the circulator certify they personally circulated the petition and give a name and residence address. Treat circulator qualifications as unconfirmed until the SOS verifies; do not assume non-residents may circulate.","note":"Citations grounded: SOS form circulator verification (lines 66-67) and W.S. 22-5-305(c) signer requirements, both verbatim. The draft's factual reading (no stated circulator requirement) is correct, BUT absence of a stated requirement is not proof none exists in rule/practice; strictest posture holds it open. Hold + SOS inquiry filed.","conf":0.7,"interp":true},{"f":"witnessOrNotary","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"Circulator certification (NOT notarized). The petition carries a 'VERIFICATION BY CIRCULATOR' in which the circulator certifies personal circulation and that signatures were made in their presence; there is no notarization requirement on the form. Separately, the presidential and vice-presidential candidates must file sworn statements naming the three presidential electors.","note":"Verified verbatim against the extracted SOS form: VERIFICATION BY CIRCULATOR block (lines 65-68) and Sworn Statements paragraph (lines 18-20). Confirmed zero occurrences of 'notary'/'notariz' anywhere in the extracted form text. Circulator attestation, not notarization, is correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"captureMode","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"paper. Signatures must be collected on the printed SOS petition form (which must be approved by the filing office before circulation), and each signer must hand-print name, date of signing, and physical residential address. No online/remote or digitized e-signature system exists for an independent presidential petition in Wyoming; collection and filing are paper-only.","note":"Verified verbatim: W.S. 22-5-305(b)-(c) on FindLaw and the SOS form's 'The petition shall be approved by the appropriate filing office prior to circulation' (form lines 5-6). Form requires handwritten signer fields and prohibits P.O. boxes. No statutory or SOS e-signature pathway found; paper-only is correct.","conf":0.9,"interp":false},{"f":"feeAlternative","gate":"AUTO-LIVE","val":"$750 filing fee REQUIRED (in addition to, NOT in lieu of, the signatures). The petition is invalid if not accompanied by the fee. Statutory chain: W.S. 22-5-306(b) ties the independent-petition fee to the same fee a primary candidate pays for the same office, and W.S. 22-5-208(a)(iii) sets $750 for any federal office voted on statewide. The NASS July-2024 summary's $200 figure is incorrect and should be disregarded.","note":"Conflict RESOLVED in verification. SOS form ('Filing Fee: $750 – Candidates for federal offices', line 26) and Ballotpedia ($750) verified verbatim; NASS PDF ($200, line 1178 of extract) verified verbatim as the conflicting source. Decisive primary source: W.S. 22-5-208(a)(iii) = '$750.00 for any federal office voted for by electors of the entire state', combined with 22-5-306(b) (fee = same as primary). $750 is statutorily controlling; NASS $200 is simply wrong/stale. Note this is a mandatory fee in addition to signatures, despite the field name 'feeAlternative' — there is no fee-in-lieu-of-signatures path in Wyoming.","conf":0.92,"interp":false}]}];
